<title>Mar_1993: Why go to the seminary</title>
<h1>Why go to the seminary</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 1 Mar 1993 15:39:50 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#4">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#4">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#4">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#4">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0005.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Under Law"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0003.html">CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Shootout in Texas"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Some time ago Lola asked why individuals go to the seminary when they<br>
don't want to.  I asked several seminary students who work in my<br>
department, and this is some of what I heard.  There are several aspects<br>
to this situation, and these are some of them.<br>
<p>
The first is, Is the ministry a calling or a profession?  If it is only<br>
a calling, and professional training is not necessary (and this is the<br>
position of some individuals and even of some conferences--obviously<br>
including Kentucky)--then why go to the seminary.  However, I believe<br>
there are good reasons to consider the ministry both a calling and a<br>
profession.  A person can feel called to work in the legal field, but<br>
certainly won't become a lawyer without a degree and passing the bar.<br>
We've tried to have it both ways in the church, but the trend has been<br>
toward requiring professional training--you can't become a doctor<br>
without an M.D. and you can't become a minister without an M.Div.  This<br>
is not to say that these degrees guarantee adequate professional<br>
practice, but they should guarantee that an individual has learned the<br>
basics of the profession.  This is also not to say that an individual<br>
can't "minister" without a professional degree, what it does say is that<br>
they aren't a "professional clergyperson" with a "union card."  Of<br>
course this gets further confused when ordination (which is what really<br>
matters) can be gotten without the professional degree, and unlike in<br>
many professions, hiring organizations don't require it.  There has been<br>
some attempt by the seminary to give a degree "in the field" to those<br>
without it.<br>
<p>
I'm not sure I'm qualified to comment on whether or not what they learn<br>
in their academic program is worth learning.  However, I can state that<br>
being a minister in these days is a very complex job, and it would<br>
appear to be very useful to have a working knowledge of a number of<br>
branches of knowledge (including psychology and management) in addition<br>
to the more "theological" disciplines.  In recent years greater<br>
attention has been paid to trying to integrate the curricula of the<br>
college religion programs with that of the seminary so that there is<br>
less duplication, that students are adequately prepared for the<br>
seminary, and that the whole thing is more like one seamless program.<br>
But the basic question remains:  Is there a basic core of knowledge that<br>
all clergy should know? and of course the related, Are they getting it<br>
with the current program.<br>
<p>
My personal observation is that many seminary students don't seem<br>
grateful that the church (at great expense) has given them this<br>
opportunity at a bargain-basement cost (very low tuition/costs, and<br>
often living expenses).  Those of us who have had to pay for our own<br>
advanced education find this hard to understand.  Some really don't seem<br>
to have the ability and/or desire to learn.  Others find it inconvenient<br>
to move to a distant location for their education.  Others have what I<br>
call "center of the universe" mentality--I already live at the center of<br>
universe, why should I spend 2 years in that snowbank?  Yet others for<br>
whatever reason don't find the content/quality of the education to their<br>
liking.  So you can see, it leaves lots of room for bitching!<br>
<p>
Well, this has been more of a stream of consciousness monologue, but<br>
those are a few of my thoughts.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
Internet: brneise@andrews.edu<br>
<p>
w<br>
the universe, why should I have to spend 2 years in that snowbank?<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
