<title>Mar_1993: Under Law</title>
<h1>Under Law</h1>
<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i><br>
<i>Mon, 01 Mar 93 07:45:08 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#5">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#5">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#5">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#5">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0006.html">bluejay@dcs.qmw.ac.uk: "FTP and Mail Server List"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0004.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Why go to the seminary"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;All this talk about laws I find interesting!  I am currently doing resurch</i><br>
<i>&gt;to write a 7 to 10 page paper on Romans 6:12-14.  The vs. 14 states that</i><br>
<i>&gt;we are no longer under law [at all] but under grace.  I have been stuck on</i><br>
<i>&gt;that more than any other part of the verses.  I'm not sure how to take</i><br>
<i>&gt;that.  Reference to Ex. 20? or all of the OT laws  or what?  (at all was</i><br>
<i>&gt;added for my emphases)</i><br>
<p>
What would happen if we asked a well studied orthodox Jew to set asside<br>
his Jewish biases against Christian and then to take Paul's Greek and<br>
translate this passage of scripture into English.<br>
<p>
The Greek used is Nomos, which our hypothetical Orthodox Jew would<br>
translate into Torah.  "We are not under the Torah . . . ."  Consider<br>
Paul's audiance and Jewish custom and we see that Paul is saying that<br>
"we are not under the system of Jewish Torah", that is, as Christians<br>
we are not under the entire system of Jewish law.  Torah/Nomos does<br>
not mean Ten Commandments.  Torah translates "revelation".  It has an<br>
entirely different meaning than "law" means to modern Christians.  It<br>
means the entire system of Jewish practice.<br>
<p>
For example:  On one hand the Sadducees insisted that Torah was nothing<br>
more nor less than the books of Moses taken at face value.  On the other<br>
hand the Pharisees insisted insisted on far more, even to the point<br>
that a Rabinical student could come up with something profound that<br>
would be accepted as something that God had said to Moses at Mt. Sinaii.<br>
This was the oral law.  Torah = law of Moses + the traditions past<br>
and future of the Oral law.  Part of this oral law included over 1000<br>
statements on how the Sabbath was to be kept.<br>
<p>
Here is a passage of scripture that shows that Paul taught a distinction<br>
between Jewish Torah and God's Torah:<br>
<p>
     "and to the Jews I became as a Jew, that I might win Jews; to those who<br>
     are  under  the law [nomos], as under the law [nomos], that I might win<br>
     those who are under the law [nomos]; "to  those  who  are  without  law<br>
     [anomos],  as  without  law  [anomos]  (not  being without law [anomos]<br>
     toward God, but under law [ennomos] toward Christ), that  I  might  win<br>
     those  who  are without law [anomos]; "  --  1 Cor 9:20, 21  (NKJ) (NIV<br>
     similar)<br>
<p>
To me it is clear that Paul is saying that we are not under the  Torah/Nomos<br>
of Judaism and yet we are under the Torah/Nomos of God.  To insist that Paul<br>
tosses out the baby with the bath water is  to  insist  that  this  text  in<br>
Corinthians  is incomprehensible, or at least contradictory.  Is Paul speak-<br>
ing nonsense, or does this text make clear that Paul  does  not  dispose  of<br>
God's  law as some would have us believe.  Note again 1 Cor 7:19 -- "Circum-<br>
cision is nothing and uncircumcision is nothing. Keeping of the commandments<br>
of  God is what counts."  Also --  "What shall we say, then?  Shall we go on<br>
sinning so that grace may increase?  By no means!  We died to sin;  how  can<br>
we  live  in  it  any longer?"  (Rom. 6:1,2)  Paul and other NT writers make<br>
clear that sin is the transgression of God's law (Rom. 4:15;  1  John  3:4).<br>
And  so  we  must search out what is the Torah law of God as being something<br>
quite apart from the Torah law of the Pharisees.  Certainly, we would<br>
agree that the Ten Commandments is part of God's law.  And we would agree<br>
that the majority of Jewish traditional practice (Torah/Nomos/Law) is not<br>
part of "God's Law".  The fullness of God's law, found in the Bible, is for<br>
each of us to search out.<br>
<p>
     "They worship me in vain; their teachings are but the  commandments  of<br>
     men.   You have let go of the commandments of God and are holding on to<br>
     the traditions of men.  And he said to them: traditions!"  (Mark 7:7-9)<br>
<p>
Jesus also said He did not come to change even the punctuation of  the  law.<br>
He kept God's law perfectly and yet did not subscribe to the traditions.  "I<br>
know that his commandments lead to everlasting life.  Whatever I say is what<br>
the Father has told me to say."  (John 12:50)  His coming here to this earth<br>
did not change even the punctuation of  [God's]  law.<br>
<p>
The baby must not go out with<br>
the bathwater and Paul does not do so.  This becomes clear  if  we  discover<br>
Paul's enthusiasm for God's law (Rom 7:12, 22, etc).<br>
<p>
At the same time, it is not law keeping, even of God's Law, by which we earn<br>
salvation  but rather because we Love Him who died while we were yet sinners<br>
with rags for righteousness.  To make light of that in disobedience of  what<br>
He would have us to do is to assume our salvation presumptuously.<br>
<p>
     "If you keep my commandments, you will abide in my love; even as I have<br>
     kept my Father's commandments, and abide in his love.  (John 15:10)<br>
<p>
Let Him be our perfect example, even in how He kept the Law of God.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
