<title>Mar_1993: Making the record stand</title>
<h1>Making the record stand</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  1 Mar 1993 22:43:40 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#7">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#7">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#7">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#7">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0008.html">sdanet@peter.cs.andrews.edu: "Re: FTP and Mail Server List"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0006.html">bluejay@dcs.qmw.ac.uk: "FTP and Mail Server List"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In the month of February we put 254 messages through SDAnet, an all-time<br>
record.  We lost several subscribers in the process who couldn't take the<br>
traffic.  I don't plan to have that much traffic every month.<br>
You may notice that several times in the past few days I've skipped <br>
the morning mailing.  This saves time for me and traffic for you,<br>
because the more messages arrive the more people respond to.  Traffic <br>
breeds traffic.<br>
<p>
Those who are still digging out from the backlog of last month's messages,<br>
there is still the weekly digest which gives the traffic to you in four<br>
humungous weekly chunks rather than 254 separate messages.  Bear this in<br>
mind.  And for the creative and fertile who want less traffic, SDA-L<br>
is a blank slate waiting for someone to do something with it.<br>
<p>
But I hope all of you stay on, and join us in the next exciting chapters<br>
of SDAnet.  The board is working hard on technical issues, and we hope<br>
to have a bunch of improvements soon, perhaps even shorter opening headers!<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
