<!-- body="start" -->
When I contacted the General Conference Communications Dept. early<br>
Monday morning, they had already sent notices to the press disclaiming<br>
any relationship between the SDA Church and the Davidians. If you notice<br>
statements appearing in the New York Times, AP, USA Today and other<br>
media, the disclaimer reached the media in time to be included in the<br>
early reports. The Communication Dept. had contacted all major media<br>
outlets, including print and electronic. They should be commended.<br>
<p>
However, it remains to be seen if the official church will suffer<br>
by being connected in name with the story. This, of course, is of great<br>
interest to those of us in professional public relations. The church has<br>
a good name (as revealed in various national polling organizations) and<br>
I'm sure we are all jealous that it be guarded carefully. <br>
<p>
Although it is unfortunate to be connected with this story, undoubtedly<br>
most of the public see this group as a fanatical, extreme group. But <br>
isn't this the impressional of Adventism the was painted by the<br>
Australian press during the Lindy Chamberlain story? <br>
<p>
Pam Harris<br>
Harrisp@utkvx.utk.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
