<title>Mar_1993: Matthew 24</title>
<h1>Matthew 24</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 2 Mar 93 14:26:08 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#12">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#12">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#12">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#12">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0013.html">David Plaisted: "Shootout in WACO, Texas"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0011.html">Steven Timm: "church image"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi people,<br>
<p>
     since there is so much interest in the shootout in Texas,<br>
i thought you would be interested in this article, which was<br>
on the front page of today's Straits Times, the main English<br>
Newspaper here in Singapore. It was also the biggest article<br>
on the front page (because of photos).<br>
________________________________________________________________________<br>
The Straits Times Tuesday March 2, 1993<br>
<p>
4 FEDERAL AGENTS KILLED IN SHOOTOUT WITH CULT<br>
---------------------------------------------<br>
Waco (Texas) - A raid on the compound of a religious cult to arrest its<br>
leader erupted into a bloody gun battle here on Sunday, leaving 4 federal<br>
agents dead and at least 15 injured.<br>
     The cult's 33-year old leader, who claims that he is the biblical<br>
Messiah, told a local radio station that one child inside the walled<br>
compound had been killed in the shootout and that several other people were<br>
hurt. But a standoff prevented any independent confirmation of his account.<br>
     The battle erupted after more than 100 agents, seeking to arrest the<br>
leader on a weapons charge, emerged from hiding in livestock trailers at<br>
about 9:30am on Sunday and entered the fortified 31-hectare compound, 16km<br>
outside Waco. The agents, caught off-guard by a hail of gunfire, retreated<br>
after 45 minutes of shooting and called for a truce to carry their dead and<br>
wounded away by ambulance and helicopter. They then negotiated with the<br>
group by phone.<br>
     Hours after nightfall, the standoff continued. David Koresh, the<br>
group's leader, said in a rambling interview with Cable News Network that<br>
he would release children in the group two by two if radio stations played<br>
his religious messages. There was no immediate response from the<br>
authorities, but federal officials said late on Sunday night that two<br>
children had left the compound.<br>
     But at 7pm, three members of the sect came out of the compound and<br>
began shooting at agents, said a spokesman for the federal Bureau of<br>
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms in Washington, which conducted the raid. One<br>
was killed and one captured.<br>
     Koresh told CNN that he himself had been "shot through the guts".<br>
     The bureau had been planning the raid for months and had rehearsed it<br>
several times, said Mr Ted Royster, special agent for its Dallas field<br>
office, at a news conference here on Sunday afternoon. But members of the<br>
sect, the Branch Davidians, had clearly learned of the raid in advance.<br>
     Mr Royster said "I cannot tell you what went wrong. It appeared as<br>
though they were waiting for us." He did not elaborate.<br>
     It was one of the largest operations ever mounted by the bureau, a<br>
Treasury Department agency that enforces federal law on trafficking in<br>
illegal weapons, alcohol and tobacco. And it was "the greatest loss of life<br>
ever suffered by the bureau", Mr Royster said, his voice breaking.<br>
     The battle came a day after the local newspaper, The Waco Tribune-<br>
Herald, carried a long report on the sect, calling attention to the weapons<br>
and discussing accusations by former members that Koresh sexually abused<br>
girls in the compound. Mr Royster said the timing of the raid on Sunday was<br>
not related to that report. The bureau had been investigating the cult for<br>
nearly eight months.<br>
     The federal agents had warrants to search the Davidians' compound for<br>
guns and explosives and to arrest Koresh, a musician whose followers<br>
believe that he is Jesus Christ. - NYT,UPI<br>
<p>
------------------------End of article-------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Well, i'm glad the article didn't mention the words "Seventh-day Adventist."<br>
Anyway, since there was so much violence and loss of life, a film will<br>
probably be made about it. <br>
     As for me, it is just another of many signs of the times about which<br>
our Lord spoke, the news is full of them, and it just means that we'd<br>
better get our act together, get cracking and let people know about God and<br>
the gospel, because there isn't much time left.<br>
<p>
Mt 24:4-14<br>
 4 And Jesus answered and said unto them, Take heed that no man deceive<br>
you.  5 For many shall come in my name, saying, I am Christ; and shall<br>
deceive many.  6 And ye shall hear of wars and rumours of wars: see that<br>
ye be not troubled: for all these things must come to pass, but the end is<br>
not yet.  7 For nation shall rise against nation, and kingdom against<br>
kingdom: and there shall be famines, and pestilences, and earthquakes, in<br>
divers places.  8 All these are the beginning of sorrows.  9 Then shall<br>
they deliver you up to be afflicted, and shall kill you: and ye shall be<br>
hated of all nations for my name's sake. 10 And then shall many be<br>
offended, and shall betray one another, and shall hate one another. 11 And<br>
many false prophets shall rise, and shall deceive many. 12 And because<br>
iniquity shall abound, the love of many shall wax cold. 13 But he that<br>
shall endure unto the end, the same shall be saved. 14 And this gospel of<br>
the kingdom shall be preached in all the world for a witness unto all<br>
nations; and then shall the end come. (KJV) <br>
<p>
Mt 24:21-30<br>
21 For then shall be great tribulation, such as was not since the beginning<br>
of the world to this time, no, nor ever shall be. 22 And except those days<br>
should be shortened, there should no flesh be saved: but for the elect's<br>
sake those days shall be shortened. 23 Then if any man shall say unto you,<br>
Lo, here is Christ, or there; believe it not. 24 For there shall arise<br>
false Christs, and false prophets, and shall shew great signs and wonders;<br>
insomuch that, if it were possible, they shall deceive the very elect. 25<br>
Behold, I have told you before. 26 Wherefore if they shall say unto you,<br>
Behold, he is in the desert; go not forth: behold, he is in the secret<br>
chambers; believe it not. 27 For as the lightning cometh out of the east,<br>
and shineth even unto the west; so shall also the coming of the Son of man<br>
be. 28 For wheresoever the carcase is, there will the eagles be gathered<br>
together. 29 Immediately after the tribulation of those days shall the sun<br>
be darkened, and the moon shall not give her light, and the stars shall<br>
fall from heaven, and the powers of the heavens shall be shaken: 30 And<br>
then shall appear the sign of the Son of man in heaven: and then shall all<br>
the tribes of the earth mourn, and they shall see the Son of man coming in<br>
the clouds of heaven with power and great glory. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Luke 21:28 And when these things begin to come to pass, then look up, and<br>
lift up your heads; for your redemption draweth nigh. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Matt 28:19-20 19 Go ye therefore, and teach all nations, baptizing them in<br>
the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Ghost: 20 Teaching<br>
them to observe all things whatsoever I have commanded you: and, lo, I am<br>
with you alway, even unto the end of the world. Amen. (KJV)<br>
<p>
- Beng<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
