<title>Mar_1993: More about Texan happenings.</title>
<h1>More about Texan happenings.</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 2 Mar 93 17:57:21 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#15">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#15">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#15">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#15">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Steven Timm: "Under Law"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Service and degrees"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi people,<br>
<p>
     I sent in a front page article from today's Straits Times<br>
about the Texan happenings. Apparently there's more stuff about it<br>
on page 8, which i didn't notice earlier. Here it is:<br>
     There are 2 articles in a big box occupying most of the page,<br>
the box is labelled "Shootout in Texas".<br>
<p>
NO WAY IN: Federal agent retreats in face of fire<br>
(some sequential pictures of an armed man on a roof failing to get<br>
in through a window and being shot at instead)<br>
<p>
CULT WELL-ARMED TO DEAL WITH ATTACK BY OUTSIDERS<br>
------------------------------------------------<br>
WACO (Texas) - Members of the apocalyptic Branch Davidians cult<br>
were well-prepared for any assault by outsiders, a local newspaper<br>
which had been investigating the group said. The Waco Herald-<br>
Tribune discovered that the cult's followers had a large arsenal of<br>
high-powered weapons.<br>
     And they routinely held paramilitary exercises at their<br>
heavily fortified 31-ha Mount Carmel farm which even had a watch<br>
tower.<br>
     On sunday, about 100 federal agents found out just how well-<br>
prepared the cult was. When the officers, who were wearing bullet-<br>
proof vests, tried to storm the cult's buildings, they were beaten<br>
back by a hail of gunfire which killed four agents and wounded at<br>
least 15 others.<br>
     And later, a spokesman from the bureau of Alcohol Tobacco and<br>
Firearms (ATF), which organised the raid, confirmed that at least<br>
one agent had been hit by gunfire from a 50-calibre machine gun<br>
normally used against tanks and aircraft.<br>
     Two of the three helicopters used during the raid were also<br>
hit by gunfire, apparently from a semi-automatic AR-15 rifle.    <br>
The cult is also believed to have explosives on the farm.<br>
     The branch Davidians has its origins in Los Angeles, where<br>
founder Victor Houteff split from the Seventh-day Adventist church<br>
in 1933.<br>
     Mr Houteff, a Bulgarian immigrant, left a teaching position<br>
with the church because of conflicts over his theological views,<br>
notably his interpretation of the Book of Revelation.<br>
     In Waco, he established the original Mount Carmel Centre and<br>
preached that the second coming of Christ was only a year away,<br>
according to Baylor University religion professor Bill Pitts, who<br>
has written several papers on the cult.<br>
     Even though the years passed without incident, Mr Houteff's<br>
following totalled more than 1000 by the time he died in 1955.<br>
     His wife, Florence, took over the leadership, predicting that<br>
April 22, 1959 would mark the end of the world.<br>
     When the date came and went, the group split, with most<br>
choosing to follow rival prophet Ben Roden and his new<br>
organisation, the Branch Davidians.<br>
     History repeated itself when Mr Roden died in 1978. His wife,<br>
Lois, took over the leadership of the group, which split again in<br>
1984.<br>
     Mr Vernon Howell, who now goes by the name David Koresh, took<br>
most of the members with him and has led the cult since then.<br>
     It is now estimated at 75 members male and female.<br>
     Former members of the cult told the Tribune-Herald that Mr<br>
Koresh abused both adult and child members of the cult and claimed<br>
at least 15 wives.<br>
     Meanwhile, the Seventh-day Adventist church denied strongly<br>
any connection with Mr Koresh's group and deplored what happened<br>
near Waco. - Reuter,UPI,NYT.<br>
<p>
CULT LEADER SAYS HE IS THE LAMB IN THE BIBLE<br>
--------------------------------------------<br>
WACO (Texas) - Vernon Howell, leader of the Branch Davidian cult,<br>
believes he is the lamb referred to in the Bible's Book of<br>
Revelation, according to the Waco Herald-Tribune.<br>
     Howell, now known as David Koresh, and his followers say he<br>
alone can open the so-called seven seals, setting loose events<br>
which they believe will end mankind and propel Koresh and his<br>
followers into heaven.<br>
     Koresh, 33, told the newspaper over the weekend in a copyright<br>
series: "If the Bible is true, then I'm Christ."<br>
     He also believes in free love.<br>
     The firefight on Sunday was the second at the farm. Koresh and<br>
seven other cult members were accused of attempted murder after a<br>
1987 gun battle with a former leader.<br>
     The seven followers were acquitted, and charges against Koresh<br>
were dismissed after his trial ended with a mistrial. - UPI,NYT.<br>
<p>
--------------------------End of article---------------------------<br>
<p>
Well, the GC comms department did well in getting the disclaimer<br>
into the press so fast. The thing that puzzels me is why it took 2<br>
days for the news to be printed here. I also wonder why they give<br>
so much space in the papers, to an event which, nowadays, is<br>
relatively insignificant(to us here in Singapore) compared to other<br>
happenings in the wider world. Anyway, it still isn't a good thing<br>
for the SDA church.<br>
     I am quite sure that some people will come and ask me about it<br>
and i will have to explain to them that SDAs don't even use guns in<br>
the army. And i wouldn't be surprised if our church is going to be<br>
put under surveillance by agents of the authorities.<br>
     A lot of people, especially other Christians, think we are a<br>
"cult" and this prejudice will not be lessened even though it was<br>
a splinter of a split off from the SDA church which behaved like<br>
that. I think it is quite unfair to think bad of SDAs just because<br>
of the Lindy Chamberlain case (which itself reeks of religious<br>
prejudice) or because of some wacky terrorist splinter group, and<br>
take little notice of the organised terrorist tactics of the IRA and<br>
other so-called Christian groups, for instance.<br>
     Speaking of prejudice, i think it is largely based on<br>
ignorance, because our church is so little-known. The obscure<br>
Branch Davidians have got more published about them, their origins<br>
and so on, in today's papers than the SDA church has had as far<br>
back as i can remember.<br>
<p>
- Beng<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
