<title>Mar_1993: Positive PR in Indianapolis</title>
<h1>Positive PR in Indianapolis</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  3 Mar 1993 18:27:13 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#26">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#26">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#26">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#26">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Serving without a degree"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Lisa Parry: "Re: AZ Republic/AP on Howell/Koresh"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Prior to General Conference in Indianapolis, the SDA General Conference<br>
Communications team carried out a successful publicity campaign  to<br>
prepare a city not acquainted with SDAs for the major onslaught of SDAs<br>
from around the globe.<br>
<p>
As I recall, they ran a series of announcements/ads on local television,<br>
professionally produced, about who SDAs are, why they are coming to the city,<br>
when they are coming, etc. They met with print press officials and supplied<br>
information about eh organization and created a laison. When GC happened, I<br>
followed the press coverage carefully. There were articles on everything from<br>
SDAs from the Soviet Union, Pitcarin (and stamps from there), fruit stands<br>
running out of fruits and vegetables, vegetarianism, the technoguts of<br>
feeding thousands of vegetarian meals in just a short time, etc. etc.<br>
<p>
Stories (negative) which otherwise could have receive high play didn't.<br>
For example, there were groups demonstrating there from other organizations<br>
such as the Indiana Athiests, etc. etc. Now, most people in Indianapolis<br>
who attend to the media probably know who SDAs are. The church owes a<br>
great deal to the quiet, behind-the-scenes operation of the Communication<br>
Dept., which spent money wisely on a tight budget and worked closely with<br>
the media in advance. <br>
<p>
This is an example of good public relations. In many cities across America,<br>
communications secretaries are doing the same thing when a church holds a<br>
stop-smoing clinic, sends relief to Hurricane Andrew victims. etc. The<br>
Knoxville News-Sentinel ran a full-color 8 X 10 photo above the fold on<br>
the front page on the church's relief efforts. Of course, the local news-<br>
paper has also run front-page stories this year on the babies that got<br>
switched in the Adventist hospital at Greenville and the resulting <br>
lawsuit. <br>
<p>
Pam Harris<br>
<p>
[Unfortunately, as I understand it, within a few months after GC<br>
there was a giant brouhaha in the Indianapolis churches, leaving them<br>
unable to capitalize on this good PR.  R. Helzerman is from there<br>
and is a member of SDAnet, he has given some details to SDAnet before <br>
on this situation.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
