<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Tony writes:</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I would like to see some of those who feel called to be leaders</i><br>
<i>&gt;take on that responsibility as best they can in their current state,</i><br>
<i>&gt;whether they're plumbers or professors.  A call to minister</i><br>
<i>&gt;doesn't equate with a call to the seminary.</i><br>
<p>
	I couldn't agree with you more Tony.  While I do believe that if<br>
	we lift seminary completion to high status, then discriminatory practices<br>
	during or after enrollment, based solely on a persons' skin color, age,<br>
	or gender, strikes me as AntiCHRIST-like.<br>
<p>
	Isn't it interesting that Jesus faced the same thing for not being formally<br>
	educated in the schools of the prophets?  Are we better than our Master?<br>
	Can we expect the human heart, that worships human achievements,<br>
	fame, to treat the children better than our Lord was treated?<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
