<title>Mar_1993: Re: Silence and Sainthood</title>
<h1>Re: Silence and Sainthood</h1>
patricio d navia (<i>pdnavia@midway.uchicago.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 3 Mar 93 22:07:51 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#42">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#42">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#42">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#42">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Fred Christiansen: "re: Branch Davidians"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0041.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: advice"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I don't think that a stand with regard to the Holocaust is a criteria<br>
the Catholic church uses to decide whether someone 'deserves' to become<br>
(or be declared) a saint.<br>
<p>
The last cannonization of the founder of the Opus Dei movement (a native<br>
Spanish) is perhaps a clear indication that the church is rapidly<br>
moving towards the 'political right' and abandoning its short-lived<br>
'compromised with the poor'.<br>
<p>
Patricio Navia.<br>
<p>
(the canonization of people has become a more common practice during<br>
the past few years, in October 1992, the Pope while visiting the<br>
Domincan Republic cannonized several latin American bishops, nouns<br>
and laymen.  In fact, and just as a 'trivial note' a Chilean noun<br>
will soon be cannonized in the Vatican and in Chile there are several<br>
travel agencies offering plans to attend the ceremony andtake the<br>
opportunity to travel around Europe).<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
