<title>Mar_1993: re: Branch Davidians</title>
<h1>re: Branch Davidians</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Mar 93 10:27:34 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Fred Christiansen: "the EGW CD-ROM:  price? performance?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">patricio d navia: "Re: Silence and Sainthood"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0084.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Branch Davidians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0052.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: Branch Davidians"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Lenson Wong writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Last night on the MacNeil-Lehrer News Hour, a Professor at UC Santa</i><br>
<i>&gt; Barbara who is an expert on cults was interviewed concerning the origin</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the Branch Davidians and specifically concerning their relationship</i><br>
<i>&gt; to the SDA Church. He said that in 1942 a group of SDA's objected</i><br>
<i>&gt; to the Church's relaxing of their pacifist stand toward WWII. This </i><br>
<i>&gt; group felt that the Church should hold a stronger pacifist stand (I assume</i><br>
<i>&gt; tis relates to participation in the military.). They then broke off</i><br>
<i>&gt; from the Church and formed the Branch Davidians. This is the first</i><br>
<i>&gt; that I've heards this story. Does anyone know if this is true?</i><br>
<p>
Sounds majorly confused.  The facts that have come to SDAnet so far<br>
show that Houteff et al split off prior to WWII.  I had not understood<br>
that his group was named Shepherd's Rod at one point (I even got<br>
something from them, unsolicited of course 8-), a few months back) before<br>
switching to Davidians.<br>
<p>
As for the pacifist item:  During WWI, Germans SDA young men were being<br>
conscripted into the Kaiser's army.  Given that conscientious objectors were<br>
not given any quarter, an appeal was made to the GC to opine whether SDA<br>
young men should refuse to serve (no option to just not bear arms) or to<br>
serve it whatever capacity they were assigned.  The GC evidently said<br>
it was OK to serve, given the tough situation.  Numerous Germans disagreed<br>
with this "relaxing of the pacifist stand" and felt that the church<br>
should hold "a stronger pacifist stand".  This group split off to become<br>
the Reformed Seventh-day Adventist Church in protest over the compromise.<br>
I have no idea what their attitudes and positions are at this time.<br>
<p>
The background for my info is this:  In 1987, a family moved to this<br>
area and started attending our church.  They were members of the Reformed<br>
SDA church.  During an elders meeting, the pastor discussed with us re<br>
how to handle the application for membership in our church.  We moved<br>
to Oregon before they were brought into membership, so I don't know the<br>
rest of the details, but I distinctly recall our pastor, Bill Bassham,<br>
preaching a sermon on the fallout that results from compromise, in which<br>
he specifically touched on the events surrounding the split off of the<br>
Reformed SDA church.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
