<title>Mar_1993: Thoughts on the Waco standoff</title>
<h1>Thoughts on the Waco standoff</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu,  4 Mar 1993 20:52:19 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#46">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#46">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#46">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#46">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Tony L. Donley: "Adventist Review"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: Branch SDA's"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0050.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It's been interesting to read the conversation on the Unix nets<br>
about the shootout in Waco.  Most of it is actually supportive<br>
of the Branch Davidians, asking what business did the government have<br>
going in shooting, especially since they had no proof that any illegal<br>
weapons were at the compound.  Koresh evidently has a license to own most <br>
if not all of the weapons he does.  <br>
<p>
Others have focused on the religious liberty issues this raises,<br>
wondering who will be next with such a raid.<br>
<p>
Marcus Stringer asks, why is our church so little known?  I think it <br>
is because our church has developed an inferiority complex about being <br>
different from the world, while at the same time we have assimilated to it.<br>
If our churches were all places where people could know the love <br>
of Jesus Christ  (some are now, but not enough), we wouldn't have to do <br>
PR or have parades or bake sales or whatever.  People would be breaking <br>
down the doors.  (For that matter, if we could hold half of the visitors<br>
we already get, our churches would soon be too small.)  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
