<title>Mar_1993: Battle Creek Adventist Hospital in Trouble</title>
<h1>Battle Creek Adventist Hospital in Trouble</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu,  4 Mar 1993 23:53:08 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#49">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#49">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#49">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#49">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0050.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Woody Baker: "Re: AZ Republic/AP on Howell/Koresh"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0061.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Battle Creek Adventist Hospital in Trouble"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[From Ron Vyhmeister]<br>
Following is the text of a copyrighted article on the situation of the<br>
Battle Creek Adventist Hospital.  It seems a real possibility that we<br>
may lose this historical institution.  I'm curious about people's<br>
feelings on the subject.  Taken from Battle Creek Enquirer, Feb. 6.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ailing Adventist Hospital exploring link with BCHS<br>
By Mark Mayes<br>
<p>
Rocked by millions of dollars in losses the last two years, Battle Creek<br>
Adventist Hospital is looking for help.<br>
<p>
The hospital's president, Ronald Brown, has approached Battle Creek<br>
Health System (Sisters of Mercy) officials about combining efforts to<br>
keep local psychiatric services going.<br>
<p>
"Over the last couple of years, the hospital has not operated<br>
profitably," Brown said, "The hospital doesn't really have a financial<br>
safety net as some organizations do."<br>
<p>
A logical place to turn was BCHS, the area's largest health-care<br>
provider, Brown said.<br>
<p>
BCHS has never been in the psychiatry business but got involved to<br>
make sure psychiatric services are available in Battle Creek, BCHS<br>
President Stephen Abbott said.<br>
<p>
"We're concerned about maintaining psychiatric services in this<br>
community," Abbott said, "How that is done could take many forms."<br>
<p>
Before talks between the hospitals began, Adventist tried to deal with<br>
its financial crisis from within, making major restructuring changes<br>
and cutting workers from about 320 to 210 since the end of 1991. More<br>
layoffs are possible.<br>
<p>
Officials from Adventist and BCHS have been talking for two months.<br>
But decisions on whether the organizations will merge are up in the<br>
air, Brown said.<br>
<p>
Brown said Adventist Hospital, is not for sale and a decision has<br>
not been made about the building's future.<br>
<p>
"We're looking to find the best way to integrate some of our programs<br>
or services into their delivery system," Brown said, "We really don't<br>
have all the answers because we really don't know what all the options<br>
are at this point."<br>
<p>
But a decision will have to be made soon, Brown said.<br>
<p>
"We're talking months, not years, at this point," he said.<br>
<p>
The major problem for Adventist Hospital, the largest regional<br>
mental health and addicion-treatment center in Southwest Michigan,<br>
is a loss of patinets.<br>
<p>
The hospital is providing more treatment on an outpatient basis than<br>
ever before and patients are not staying in the hospital as long as<br>
they used to.<br>
<p>
The length of the average hospital stay was down neraly 50 percent<br>
last year alone.  Adventist hospital uses about half of its 155 beds<br>
on a regular basis, Brown said.<br>
<p>
In recent years, the hospital began to branch out from its traditional<br>
role of providing inpatient care.<br>
<p>
In 1991, while celebrating its 125th anniversary, the hospital built a<br>
rehabilitation center and gymnasium to provide facilities for<br>
occupational therapy.<br>
<p>
It also began an organized effort to expand its outpatient programs.<br>
It moved the New Day Center Addiction and Treatment Passages and<br>
psychological services from the hospital to 333 E. Columbia Ave.<br>
<p>
Abbott said some of the facilities at the Adventist Hosptial would<br>
be critical to providing psychiatric care.<br>
<p>
"But we, as hospitals, don't need all the space that we used to,"<br>
he said.<br>
<p>
Combining the efforts of BSHS and Adventist follow a health-care trend<br>
forced by rising health-care costs and pressure from business and<br>
insurance companies.<br>
<p>
"Twelve years ago, Battle Creek was a four-hospital town," Brown said.<br>
"Essentially, with the way health care has moved, Battle Creek is the<br>
size town that needs one integrated health-care delivery system.<br>
<p>
"And I think that's the way it's coming together."<br>
<p>
--------------------------<br>
This has been updated to mean that the hospital is either merging or<br>
closing. Either way, the Battle Creek Adventist Hospital will cease<br>
to exist. Any comments, what do you think?<br>
<p>
[It wouldn't be the first time the church has lost Battle Creek<br>
Adventist Hospital (formerly Sanitarium).  It was out of denominational<br>
hands from 1907 through the late 1960's.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
