<title>Mar_1993: Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff</title>
<h1>Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 5 Mar 93 23:02:46 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#50">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#50">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#50">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#50">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0051.html">Ralf Simonsson: "I am Back"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0049.html">Steven Timm: "Battle Creek Adventist Hospital in Trouble"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Steven Timm: "Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0056.html">Bruce Holm: "Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<i>&gt;It's been interesting to read the conversation on the Unix nets</i><br>
<i>&gt;about the shootout in Waco.  Most of it is actually supportive</i><br>
<i>&gt;of the Branch Davidians, asking what business did the government have</i><br>
<i>&gt;going in shooting, especially since they had no proof that any illegal</i><br>
<i>&gt;weapons were at the compound.  Koresh evidently has a license to own most </i><br>
<i>&gt;if not all of the weapons he does.</i><br>
<p>
Well, the newspaper said that an ATF agent was hit by a round from a<br>
50-calibre machine gun. I may be wrong, but I doubt you can get a licence<br>
for that, even in Texas.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Others have focused on the religious liberty issues this raises,</i><br>
<i>&gt;wondering who will be next with such a raid.</i><br>
<p>
Well, it appears to me, that they got raided not because of their religion,<br>
but because they broke the law. This of course, raises the question of<br>
where to draw the line between religious liberty and the law of the land.<br>
Should religious liberty include being allowed to own an arsenal of<br>
dangerous weapons and using them to shoot at people?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Marcus Stringer asks, why is our church so little known?  I think it </i><br>
<i>&gt;is because our church has developed an inferiority complex about being </i><br>
<i>&gt;different from the world, while at the same time we have assimilated to it.</i><br>
<i>&gt;If our churches were all places where people could know the love </i><br>
<i>&gt;of Jesus Christ  (some are now, but not enough), we wouldn't have to do </i><br>
<i>&gt;PR or have parades or bake sales or whatever.  People would be breaking </i><br>
<i>&gt;down the doors.  (For that matter, if we could hold half of the visitors</i><br>
<i>&gt;we already get, our churches would soon be too small.)  </i><br>
<p>
Actually, that is very true. If we have not the love of Jesus, then we<br>
are nothing. All our truths and so on are good and necessary, but without<br>
love, it'll all amount to nothing. Our job, first and foremost, is to<br>
show people what God is like, to lift Christ up before mankind, that He<br>
may draw all men to himself, and to help them get to know Jesus personally.<br>
If the world only knew the love of God, i'm sure most of them would be<br>
attracted by it. Once a person really knows Christ, is really convicted<br>
and converted, i'm sure God will be able to lead them to His true church.<br>
	Having said that, i think PR is still necessary for the church,<br>
to let people know more about what the church stands for and of its<br>
character and activities, because there are still a lot of people who<br>
don't know very much about SDAs and they hear all sorts of funny ideas<br>
about us and this might make them harder for us to reach later on. And<br>
PR is not only about dispelling prejudice, it is about letting people<br>
know about the gospel we have and about the love of God.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
