<title>Mar_1993: Re: Under Law</title>
<h1>Re: Under Law</h1>
<i>ronswen@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 05 Mar 93 03:28:22 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#53">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#53">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#53">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#53">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0054.html">Tim Swensen: "Battle Creek Aventist Hospital"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0052.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: Branch Davidians"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0016.html">Steven Timm: "Under Law"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0058.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Re: Under Law"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Thanks Dave for your thoughtful comments about the law.  I am not capable of<br>
reading the Greek in context and appreciate your  interpretation.  Your post<br>
raises some thoughts in my mind.<br>
<p>
You suggest that we can use this interpretation of the law (nomos) to split<br>
out a core of the law that is divine and leave behind the baggage of human<br>
tradition.  The divine component of the Law is to be followed whereas the<br>
human tradition is of no value.  The grace of Christ is the source of<br>
salvation however.<br>
<p>
I would like to suggest a more radical interpretation.  Paul seems to suggest<br>
in Romans 6 that the Law (nomos, however it may be interpreted) is not<br>
relevant to my salvation.  My salvation is "in Christ".  Jesus Christ saves<br>
me because of his freely offered grace which is given to me if I accept it. <br>
The Law is now obsolete because Christ paid whatever penalty the Law was to<br>
exact.  It's main purpose now is as a schoolmaster to point me to Christ.  <br>
My keeping of the law, while a necessary component of behavior for a follower<br>
of Christ, is not the source of my salvation.  Put another way, even if a<br>
human could live his/her own life completely free from transgressing the law<br>
eternal life would not be obtained.  Just think about it; we Adventists do<br>
not believe in an immortal soul, we believe that death is the end of us until<br>
God calls us back to life.  A perfect life, lived without sin is still<br>
subject to death (for example, Christ).  Once we are dead only an act of God<br>
can recreate us, so regardless of perfect adherence to the law we still are<br>
saved by GRACE.<br>
<p>
This leaves us with what I like to think of as the "Boarding Academy<br>
problem", that being " How are we going to get Christians to follow the rules<br>
if they are no longer required to?"  To solve this problem we need to<br>
reconsider what Grace is and what it's action is on the person who accepts<br>
it.  Accepting God's Grace is not a glib trite experience but rather is a<br>
life changing event that reorients the whole direction of ones life.  When I<br>
realized the enormous meaning of Christ's sacrifice, and what risks He took,<br>
and what love He demonstrated I was awestruck.   Gone were trivia such as<br>
whether it is o.k. to go out to eat on Sabbath and in its place was a desire<br>
to know who Christ really is and to be like Him.  Don't misunderstand me,<br>
behaving like Christ is a constant challenge, but the focus is on Christ,<br>
rather than the law.<br>
<p>
These posts never seem to be short!!!  I am curious what the rest of you<br>
think regarding all of this.<br>
<p>
Thanks for reading,<br>
Ron Swensen<br>
ron swen@aol.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
