<title>Mar_1993: Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff</title>
<h1>Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 5 Mar 93 11:28:34 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#56">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#56">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#56">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#56">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Cam Litvin: "the EGW CD-ROM: price? performance?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Dan Gill: "EGW CD-ROM"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Steven Timm: "Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0064.html">Trevor Tompkins: "Re: Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu Fri Mar  5 08:56:58 1993</i><br>
<i>&gt; Date: Fri, 5 Mar 93 23:02:46 +0800</i><br>
<i>&gt; From: med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg (TANG BENG YONG)</i><br>
<i>&gt; To: +dist+/afs/andrew.cmu.edu/usr4/st0o/sdanet.dl@andrew.cmu.edu,</i><br>
<i>&gt;         st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff</i><br>
<i>&gt; Content-Length: 2657</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Tang Beng Yong writes:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Well, it appears to me, that they got raided not because of their religion,</i><br>
<i>&gt; but because they broke the law. This of course, raises the question of</i><br>
<i>&gt; where to draw the line between religious liberty and the law of the land.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Should religious liberty include being allowed to own an arsenal of</i><br>
<i>&gt; dangerous weapons and using them to shoot at people?</i><br>
<p>
Weapons, dangerous or not, are not bad in and of themselves.  It's the people<br>
who use them and how they use them that can be bad.<br>
<p>
Why shouldn't religious liberty be extended to those with guns?  As long as<br>
no illegal activity is performed with them, and as long as no laws of the land<br>
are broken, then they should be entitled to the freedom of religion.  Our<br>
constitution guarantees it.<br>
<p>
Just because someone has dangerous weapons in their posession is no offense.<br>
It is possible to get licenses for fully automatic weapons (at least it used to<br>
be possible a few years ago).  I don't know if this includes 50-cal machine guns<br>
or not.<br>
<p>
As for using them for shooting at people, I would say that Koresh and company were <br>
shooting out of self defense.  They were not shooting at innocent people.  The <br>
laws of this land do allow shooting people out of self defense if the persons <br>
attacking you are doing so illegally...such as someone trying to murder or rape <br>
you, etc.  I don't believe this applies in Koresh's situation since he was firing<br>
on law enforcement officers (although he obviously would have a different opinion <br>
on this).<br>
<p>
I am not condoning Koresh's actions in any way, simply trying to address the comment <br>
that just because you own/possess dangerous weapons and/or shoot at people means <br>
you should have your religious liberty deprived.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
