<title>Mar_1993: Re: Battle Creek Adventist Hospital in Trouble</title>
<h1>Re: Battle Creek Adventist Hospital in Trouble</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 5 Mar 93 12:09:19 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#61">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#61">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#61">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#61">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0062.html">Fred Christiansen: "wisdom from a youth"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Marcus Stringer: "Church vs. State News"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0049.html">Steven Timm: "Battle Creek Adventist Hospital in Trouble"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ron V. writes:<br>
<i>&gt; This has been updated to mean that the hospital is either merging or</i><br>
<i>&gt; closing. Either way, the Battle Creek Adventist Hospital will cease</i><br>
<i>&gt; to exist. Any comments, what do you think?</i><br>
<p>
Has anyone ever heard the story of the Bangkok, Thailand SDA hospital?<br>
If you haven't, I can get you a copy of it (its pretty long...20-30 pgs)<br>
to you.  It is pretty amazing.  We picked it up when my wife and I visited <br>
there back in 1987.  It is an amazing story of how they were in financial <br>
struggles and being threatened to close down.  They took a long hard look <br>
at their situation and decided that maybe they were not following God's <br>
plan and counsel as provided by EGW writings.  So they decided to put God <br>
to the test and try implementing changes that were found in EGW's writings.  <br>
Most all the changes centered around what they did on the Sabbath.  They <br>
realized that the Sabbath was not being differentiated from any other day <br>
of the week (sound familiar...in reference to other SDA hospitals around <br>
the US?).<br>
<p>
So they mades changes, such as not charging patients who came in on Sabbath,<br>
they scheduled no surgury for Saturday unless absolutely necessary for life.<br>
There were other changes, which I can't recall right now.  But within a year<br>
or two they had turned their financial picture around so dramatically that<br>
they are now expanding their services and adding rooms, etc.  They definately<br>
feel that it was a result of the changes they made in their attitude about<br>
Sabbath observance.<br>
<p>
I think alot of the SDA hosipitals have totally lost the vision of what they<br>
should be doing as a witness to the community.  They treat health care as<br>
simply a business, not a witnessing tool.  They don`t rely enough on natural<br>
remedies instead of on man made remedies.  Why do they serve meat in some of<br>
the institutions?  Why do they charge for meals on Sabbath in the cafeteria?  <br>
<p>
When I hear of hospitals in financial trouble, I usually like to take a look<br>
at their observance of Sabbath.  How can God bless an institution when they<br>
don't follow His counsel and distinguish themselves from other medical<br>
institutions in the area?  <br>
<p>
I have no idea what the BC hospital does on Sabbath or if they serve meat or <br>
disregard other counsel or not, but I am simply raising the question since I <br>
don't live out there or have not visited it.<br>
<p>
Just my thoughts...<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
