<title>Mar_1993: wisdom from a youth</title>
<h1>wisdom from a youth</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 5 Mar 93 13:08:21 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Fred Christiansen: "re: Reformed SDA members and my local church (more detail)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Battle Creek Adventist Hospital in Trouble"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
February's Focus on the Family contained this gem, from its inteview with<br>
Bob Vernon, former LAPD asst chief:<br>
<p>
   I like the way my son put it during his senior year in college.  That<br>
Christmas he said, "Dad, it's like this," stretching his hands out flat in<br>
front of him.  Then he put one about eight inches below the other and slowly<br>
moved both of them down toward his right leg.<br>
   "This is how it is with a lot of Christians," he told me.  "Every day,<br>
we're keeping our eye on the guys in the world, and we figure as long as<br>
we're a cut above them we're okay.  But guess what?  They're going<br>
downhill, so if we keep our eyes on them, we're coming down several<br>
notches, too, as far as our morality is concerned.  We have unwittingly<br>
taken a position of comparing ourselves with the rest of the world.<br>
And as long as we're a little better than they are, we figure we're okay --<br>
but we're really not," said my son.<br>
   I thought, That's really wise for a college kid.  We need a plumb line<br>
to let us know when we're wrong, or else we'll slip into the behavior<br>
of the rest of our culture and not even be cognizant of it.<br>
-- EOQ --<br>
<pre>
-- 
