<title>Mar_1993: Re: Thoughts on the Waco standoff</title>
<h1>Re: Thoughts on the Waco standoff</h1>
Trevor Tompkins (<i>tt17+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri,  5 Mar 1993 15:59:43 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Steven Timm: "SDA-L:  Michael Card"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Fred Christiansen: "re: Reformed SDA members and my local church (more detail)"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Steven Timm: "Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0068.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>|It's been interesting to read the conversation on the Unix nets</i><br>
<i>|about the shootout in Waco.  Most of it is actually supportive</i><br>
<i>|of the Branch Davidians, asking what business did the government have</i><br>
<i>|going in shooting, especially since they had no proof that any illegal</i><br>
<i>|weapons were at the compound.  Koresh evidently has a license to own |most </i><br>
<i>|if not all of the weapons he does.  </i><br>
<p>
Where do these people get there news?!!  The raid was not because Koresh<br>
illegally owned guns, but to arrest him for various other illegal<br>
activities, some of which was his marrying many different wives, and<br>
child abuse.  The reason they needed guns was a result of the Branch<br>
Davidians' violent nature.  They had an ATF agent infiltrate the group<br>
for four months.  He reproted on the incredible number of guns, the<br>
militaristic style, and the survivalist attitude of the Branch<br>
Davidians.  They didn't go in shooting, but went in with guns because<br>
they didn't want to get shot back at.  They had to shoot because they<br>
were shot at (the news tape is pretty clear about this). Obviously the<br>
ATF underestimated the Branch Davidians (although the ATF is saying that<br>
the Branch Davidians must have been tipped off). <br>
<p>
<i>|Others have focused on the religious liberty issues this raises,</i><br>
<i>|wondering who will be next with such a raid.</i><br>
<p>
The raid was not religiously motivated.  It has religious overtones<br>
because David Koresh is trying to make it that way.  It should be noted<br>
that Koresh has been in trouble with the law before.  He took over that<br>
compound with weapons from another fanatical religious nutcase who now<br>
sits in prison.  Koresh was charged with assault, but the charges were<br>
not pursued because the government was after the guy who is now<br>
currently in prison.   Branch Davidians are the equivalent in<br>
Christianity that radical Moslem factions are in the Moslem Religion.<br>
<p>
<i>|Marcus Stringer asks, why is our church so little known?  I think it </i><br>
<i>|is because our church has developed an inferiority complex about being </i><br>
<i>|different from the world, while at the same time we have assimilated to it.</i><br>
<i>|If our churches were all places where people could know the love </i><br>
<i>|of Jesus Christ  (some are now, but not enough), we wouldn't have to do </i><br>
<i>|PR or have parades or bake sales or whatever.  People would be breaking </i><br>
<i>|down the doors.  (For that matter, if we could hold half of the visitors</i><br>
<i>|we already get, our churches would soon be too small.)  </i><br>
<p>
Why is our church so little known?  Read Nietzsche.  "God is dead" in<br>
our society.  For most people God is not needed.  The Idea that God's<br>
love will win them over has been used over and over yet we have few<br>
results.  Our problem is that we have no clear definition of what "God's<br>
love" is.  We use examples that describe it, but this never entails a<br>
complete definition.  When the love doesn't work then it must not have<br>
been "God's love" right.  I think this becomes a useless phrase that we<br>
fall back on.  If you look at the well known religions of the world,<br>
they are moslty due to political history (i.e. they control governments,<br>
or did at one time).  Since we advocate separation of church and state,<br>
we will never have the same impact.  <br>
<p>
	Further, I'm not convinced that we need be concerned about getting such<br>
large numbers in our church, or be so well known.  I think it is better<br>
that we concern ourselves with how we, as a church, can be beneficial to<br>
 society.  This will do much more than any PR campaign.  When we get off<br>
our pedestal of "we need to convert the world because only we know how<br>
to worship God," then we will have a church that people see as being<br>
"hey aren't they a neat group, look at what they are doing."  <br>
<p>
	The University Church in Loma Linda California is now involved with<br>
helping the police combat gang influence (no they are not spying and<br>
then turning them in).  They meet gang members to better understand why<br>
they join gangs, they go on activities with gang members such as<br>
camping, and they have the opportunity to teach them social, and<br>
cognitive skills to help them assimilate.  Never, do they go in to teach<br>
them about the SDA religion;That is not the reason for their project. <br>
This is just one activity that the church is involved with.  The church<br>
actually has many projects that they devote to helping the community.  <br>
Bill Lovless, head minister, actually has a section of the church<br>
service discussing their progress, and it is never "how many new members<br>
have we enrolled." The surrounding community knows the SDA church, the<br>
newspaper writes about them with all of their projects, and people don't<br>
feel that they have to watch out for the "sales pitch."  Is this God's<br>
love?  Maybe, but there is no reason why anyone has to be an SDA, or<br>
even Christian to do these things.  The church does them because they<br>
feel that they should provide a benefit to society, not suck people out<br>
of society.   Sometimes it is better to just do what is "human" than<br>
what is "Christian."<br>
<p>
<p>
--Trevor Tompkins<br>
_________________<br>
<p>
Logic and Computation<br>
Carnegie Mellon University<br>
tt17@andrew.cmu.edu<br>
