Bruce Holm writes:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; Tang Beng Yong writes:</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; Well, it appears to me, that they got raided not because of their religion,</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; but because they broke the law. This of course, raises the question of</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; where to draw the line between religious liberty and the law of the land.</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; Should religious liberty include being allowed to own an arsenal of</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; dangerous weapons and using them to shoot at people?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Weapons, dangerous or not, are not bad in and of themselves. It's the people</i><br>
<i>&gt;who use them and how they use them that can be bad.</i><br>
<p>
I am one who is interested in guns and shooting things. I also agree that<br>
weapons are not bad in themselves, even if they were invented to be used<br>
as weapons.   However, i think that if dangerous weapons are readily<br>
available in abundance, the likelihood of their being used on people<br>
increases, because people who want to use them for bad purposes or who<br>
use them carelessly are unfortunately in abundance too. I guess i am not<br>
used to the idea of weapons being so freely available as they are in<br>
the USA. Where i come from, gun control is very strict and i think even<br>
those who can get a licence for a gun are not allowed to store their<br>
weapons at home, in case they get stolen; they keep them at police stations<br>
or gun clubs i think. The local gangsters usually have to make do with<br>
knives, bottles, and other home-made weapons for their turf wars. Gunshot<br>
wounds are rare in Singapore. Here, catapults are banned and one can be<br>
arrested for carrying around a hunting knife and gun-running is a<br>
capital offense.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Why shouldn't religious liberty be extended to those with guns?  As long as</i><br>
<i>&gt;no illegal activity is performed with them, and as long as no laws of the land</i><br>
<i>&gt;are broken, then they should be entitled to the freedom of religion. Our</i><br>
<i>&gt;constitution guarantees it.</i><br>
<p>
I think that guns and religious liberty are usually seperate issues, unless<br>
the religion has something to do with guns. As far as i know, guns do not<br>
form part of most people's religions. There are a few survivalist groups<br>
like the Branch Davidians, i suppose, whose religion calls for them to be<br>
armed for the end of the world or whatever. I suppose if they are legally<br>
owning and using guns, the law should leave them alone. Conflict would arise<br>
only if they illegally own guns or use them illegally and then claim that<br>
they should be allowed to do so because of religious liberty.<br>
	Speaking about constitutions, i know more about yours than i do<br>
about mine. Yours is old and established but mine is changing all the time.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Just because someone has dangerous weapons in their posession is no offense.</i><br>
<i>&gt;It is possible to get licenses for fully automatic weapons (at least it</i><br>
<i>&gt;used to be possible a few years ago).  I don't know if this includes 50-cal</i><br>
<i>&gt;machine guns or not.</i><br>
<p>
Well, Woody Knapper informs me that you can indeed legally procure a 50-cal<br>
MG and even a fully operational battle tank. I used to think that full-auto<br>
weapons couldn't be gotten legally because i read somewhere that some people<br>
buy semi-auto Uzi SMGs or Colt AR-15s and illegally modify them to fire<br>
full-auto.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;As for using them for shooting at people, I would say that Koresh and company</i><br>
<i>&gt;were shooting out of self defense.  They were not shooting at innocent</i><br>
<i>&gt;people.  The laws of this land do allow shooting people out of self defense</i><br>
<i>&gt;if the persons attacking you are doing so illegally...such as someone</i><br>
<i>&gt;trying to murder or rape you, etc.  I don't believe this applies in Koresh's</i><br>
<i>&gt;situation since he was firing on law enforcement officers (although he</i><br>
<i>&gt;obviously would have a different opinion on this).</i><br>
<p>
They would be shooting out of self-defense if the ATF men were going to<br>
shoot at them first, which i think unlikely.<br>
	As for shooting in self-defense, is it still legal if the person<br>
attacking you is not going to kill you but perhaps rob or rape you?<br>
 - just curious.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I am not condoning Koresh's actions in any way, simply trying to address</i><br>
<i>&gt;the comment that just because you own/possess dangerous weapons and/or</i><br>
<i>&gt;shoot at people means you should have your religious liberty deprived.</i><br>
<p>
Actually, that was not the meaning of what i said. I was asking where to<br>
draw the line when religious liberty conflicts with the law of the land.<br>
When i made that statement(refer to the top of this article for the quote)<br>
i had assumed that owning arsenals and shooting people were illegal.<br>
<p>
For example, if it was part of somebody's religion to take cocaine or to<br>
conduct human sacrifices, and if these activities are illegal, should the<br>
adherents of that religion be allowed to do these things on the grounds of<br>
religious liberty or arrested for breaking the laws of the land?<br>
<p>
regards,<br>
	beng<br>
<p>
[Well, the Smith decision in the US in 1989 made it illegal to take peyote<br>
as part of one's religion.  And the Supreme Court will soon rule on if <br>
animal sacrifice ought to be banned.  Stay tuned.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
