<title>Mar_1993: Re Pacifism</title>
<h1>Re Pacifism</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix3.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 6 Mar 93 21:17:42 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#69">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#69">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#69">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#69">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0070.html">Steven Timm: "White flight from SDA schools"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0087.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Re Pacifism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Fred Christiansen writes:<br>
<i>&gt;As for the pacifist item:  During WWI, Germans SDA young men were being</i><br>
<i>&gt;conscripted into the Kaiser's army.  Given that conscientious objectors were</i><br>
<i>&gt;not given any quarter, an appeal was made to the GC to opine whether SDA</i><br>
<i>&gt;young men should refuse to serve (no option to just not bear arms) or to</i><br>
<i>&gt;serve it whatever capacity they were assigned.  The GC evidently said</i><br>
<i>&gt;it was OK to serve, given the tough situation.  Numerous Germans disagreed</i><br>
<i>&gt;with this "relaxing of the pacifist stand" and felt that the church</i><br>
<i>&gt;should hold "a stronger pacifist stand".  This group split off to become</i><br>
<i>&gt;the Reformed Seventh-day Adventist Church in protest over the compromise.</i><br>
<i>&gt;I have no idea what their attitudes and positions are at this time.</i><br>
<p>
I've been told that SDAs aresupposed to be conscientous objectors, but not<br>
necessarily pacifists. They help with the war effort in non-combattent<br>
vocations. I am still trying to make sense of this. While one may not do<br>
the actual squeezing of the trigger, one may be the clerk who types the<br>
order to kill or be the driver who drives the ammunition to the front.<br>
<p>
Ideally, SDAs should serve as medics or perhaps do bomb disposal, or<br>
something which actually helps save lives, but nowadays, even medics are<br>
required to be armed, because they are prime targets for enemy snipers;<br>
now not many people bother about the Geneva convention.<br>
<p>
Here in Singapore, we are fortunate in that the SDA church has a certain<br>
level of understanding with the ministry of defense in that they post our<br>
young men to non-combattent vocations and do not require them to use<br>
weapons. In some other countries the SDAs have to choose to serve in the<br>
armed forces with no regard to their religious scruples of face lengthy<br>
prison terms or other punishments, and some really get a lot of<br>
persecuition.<br>
<p>
I have also herd that up in Myanmar, some of the Karens have converted to<br>
Adventism, but some of these still fight for their lives, against the<br>
Yangon regieme, whith whom they are in the midst of a war. I am not judging<br>
them or anything, i just want to note that the churches' stand on this<br>
issue doesn't seem to be a hard and fast rule everywhere.<br>
<p>
I wonder what Mrs White had to say about wars and fighting and SDAs.<br>
I only remember that she said something about the American civil war.<br>
If anyone has any thoughts about all this, i'd be glad to hear them.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
