<title>Mar_1993: EGW-CD ROM</title>
<h1>EGW-CD ROM</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun,  7 Mar 1993 14:23:32 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#73">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#73">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#73">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#73">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0074.html">Steven Timm: "E.B.White ??"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0072.html">Lisa Parry: "Re: White flight from SDA schools"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I would again like to address the issue of making the Ellen White<br>
database available via the Internet.  It is my understanding that many<br>
of the original writings are now in the public domain (no longer<br>
protected by copyright); however, this does not apply to the<br>
compilations done after her death (copyrights held by the publishing<br>
houses).  I expect that the machine-readable database itself is also<br>
copyrighted.  The purpose of copyright is to protect the investment of<br>
the originators of intellectual property.  I think we have a legal and<br>
moral obligation to respect copyright and abide by provisions for fair<br>
use.  In general I see the next few years as being years of conflict<br>
between that is technically feasible and legal and financial restraints<br>
placed by producers of information.  In this case, we need to recognize<br>
the investment made by the publishers, and by the White Estate (i.e. in<br>
having all the keyboarding done).  It is unfortunate that at least one<br>
Adventist-related organization has already stolen at least part of the<br>
database and is marketing it themselves.  I do not believe the White<br>
Estate is trying to protect sensitive information or to "make a bundle."<br>
Nor do I believe that they want to enter into litigation.<br>
<p>
However, even if they don't want to "make a bundle," they do want to<br>
recoup their original investment and to have funds to improve the<br>
product.  I think they should be commended for making this a<br>
self-supporting project rather than looking for a church handout.  They<br>
money has to come from somewhere.  At present, I believe they have just<br>
about amortized their original investment.  However, they would like to<br>
produce a new edition (with corrections to mistakes found) as well as to<br>
eventually produce a disc that also includes the unpublished writings.<br>
                                                        ^^^^^^^^<br>
[WHOA!!!  When the volumes of "Manuscript Releases" came out a couple years<br>
ago, there was quite a bit of noise that this was the last of the unpublished<br>
writings and that everything was now in print.  Just what unpublished<br>
writings are you referring to, Harvey?   SCT]<br>
<p>
<p>
I hope we can find a win/win situation where the White Estate's needs<br>
can be met, as well as our interest in making the database available<br>
over the Internet.<br>
<p>
While it might be technically possible to do this without their cooperation<br>
(even I suppose from a country that does not honor US copyright) I do<br>
not believe that would be the right thing to do, and I would urge that<br>
it not be done.  They are understandably cautious in their approach to<br>
this.  Just on Friday, I was writing a belated followup letter to Tim<br>
Poirier at the Washington office (after a visit I had with him in<br>
November).  They want to know more about the Internet (so far the only<br>
Internet connection to the GC is at the GC library).  I hope in the next<br>
few weeks to get Bill Fagal of the White Estate branch office here going<br>
with the Internet (between my online catalog and his dissertation this<br>
hasn't happened yet even though his computers are on the campus fiber<br>
optic network through the library system, and could certainly access the<br>
Internet).  Bill is quite interested in computer technology and would be<br>
a good ally.<br>
<p>
Some questions have been raised about the software for this product.<br>
Because the White Estate has a branch office on our campus (in fact, it<br>
is located in the basement of the library), the James White Library<br>
itself has not felt a need to duplicate what's already available in this<br>
building, therefore I have no personal experience with the software.<br>
However, my library colleages from other institutions feel that the software<br>
itself is not very user-friendly.  That, combined with the purchase of<br>
this product by many novice computer users, led the White Estate to<br>
conclude early on that they were not capable of providing personal<br>
assistance in software support.  They therefore contracted with the<br>
software company to provide this support.  As a result, a substantial<br>
portion of the purchase price goes to that company for software use and<br>
support.  One of the options I will be exploring with the White Estate<br>
is to make their database available using some other software engine so<br>
that we would not have to make arrangements for use of this particular<br>
3rd party software.  <br>
<p>
Several entities (including the publishers) would be involved in this<br>
negotiation, and I continue to urge patience.  In addition, I would note<br>
that purchasers of the product read the license agreement very carefully.<br>
My own experience with such products is that they are usually licensed<br>
for one user, with multi-user licenses sometimes available, but for an<br>
additional fee.  Again, this is usually software-related.<br>
<p>
In conclusion, I hope to be able to spend more time on this project in<br>
the next few months (I will be visiting Washington later this month and<br>
hope to visit the GC at that time).  I believe patience will pay off.<br>
<p>
On another topic, I understand that several other schools in the DC area<br>
have seen large reductions in Anglo students (Sligo School and J. N.<br>
Andrews School come to mind).  I believe something similar has happened<br>
at Atlantic Union College.  However, whether this means that white students<br>
drive by that school (so to speak) to go elsewhere or whether this is<br>
due to chaning demographics in particular areas or regions is hard to<br>
say.  That church demographics show increasing presence of non-Anglos is<br>
beyond dispute.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(Internet: brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
