<title>Mar_1993: Re: Shootout in Texas</title>
<h1>Re: Shootout in Texas</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 08 Mar 1993 08:53:51 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#85">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#85">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#85">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#85">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0086.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Perfecting Character, NT texts"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0084.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Branch Davidians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think we need to start concentrating on the positive aspects of this.<br>
It seems funny, but this week kicks off the largest evangalistic effort<br>
in the history of the Texas conference.  It has been in the planning for a year.<br>
It involves 20-30 crusades to be held in Houston Texas.  The SS superintendant<br>
called me friday evening about 7 p.m. and asked me to substitute for him, as<br>
well as to teach the main ss class.  Said Mission Spotlight would take llmost<br>
of the time.  Well, it did not come.  In a conversaion with our pastor, he<br>
related the events of the past week, so I got him up front to tell about them.<br>
I spent a good deal of time talking about SDA-NET, and how it was providing<br>
a good clearing house for information dealing with the waco thing, and <br>
presented our efforts.  Beng should know that I specificaly mentioned his<br>
continual updating of the Singapore coverage.  Any way, our pastor was<br>
watching the news when the initial announcment came over the air last<br>
<p>
Sunday.  He immediatly called the station, and requested that they take the<br>
words "Seventh-day Adventist background" off the screen in conjunction with<br>
the story, which they did.  The station called him up for an interview, but<br>
he declined because he did not want to as a representative of the SDA church,<br>
promote the connection, which he felt that he would be doing.  Later another<br>
station called him up, and he gave them the same response.<br>
<p>
The local newspaper called him up, and told him that they wanted to do a<br>
complete in-depth coverage of the Seventh-day Adventist church, and would<br>
he be willing to give an interview.  After assuring him that they would not<br>
bring the branch davaidians into the article, he spent an hour and a half<br>
talking with the reporter, detailing adventist history.  The reporter asked<br>
him if there were any contridictions in the bible, whereupon he said that there<br>
were some apparent contradictions, and gave him the example in revalation<br>
where it says that the wicked are completely burned up, and then says that<br>
they burn for ever and ever.  He then proceeded to reconcile those with each<br>
other, explained how they were NOT a real contridiction, and wound up involved<br>
in a bible study with the guy.  I have not seen the article, but I am going<br>
to try to find a copy of it.  If we are careful, we as a church may be able<br>
to take advantage of the publicity surrounding this event, to show our unique<br>
point of view.  There has been a decidedly increased awareness of the <br>
Adventist church, with our offical disclaimers and all, and if we seize the<br>
moment, we should be able to turn some of the publicity to our advantage.<br>
especially, by contrasting our beliefs with those of the Davidains.<br>
<p>
It turns out that there are 8 people in waco who are ORIGIANL Davadian<br>
association of Seventh-day Adventist.  Apparently the waco group split<br>
and part of them moved off to this 77 acres outside of waco, that they are<br>
now calling Ranch Apocolypse.  the origianl Davidians apparently still attend<br>
the waco church, and have regained control over the remaining 7 acres of the<br>
origianal Mt. Carmel site, where they carry on thier publishing activities.<br>
<p>
The fact that they meet with the local adventists should be some cause for<br>
alarm I would think.<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
