<title>Mar_1993: Re: Re Pacifism</title>
<h1>Re: Re Pacifism</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 8 Mar 93 09:47:55 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#87">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#87">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#87">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#87">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0088.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Law, Parable of two Husbands"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0086.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Perfecting Character, NT texts"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0069.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re Pacifism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From: med10014@nusunix3.nus.sg (TANG BENG YONG)</i><br>
<i>&gt; To: st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re Pacifism</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I've been told that SDAs aresupposed to be conscientous objectors, but not</i><br>
<i>&gt; necessarily pacifists. </i><br>
<p>
Here in the U.S. we've made an even finer distinction, mostly because of<br>
the way terminology is (was) used for draft classifications.<br>
<p>
Conscientous objectors (classification 1-O) are people who refuse to have<br>
anything at all to do military duty.  In the past, they used to go straight<br>
to jail, do not collect $200.  Later they were offered, and usually accepted,<br>
non-military service of some sort.<br>
<p>
One level away from this was the 1-AO ("conscientious cooperator"), those<br>
who would accept military service, but no combat position.  SDA's in the<br>
U.S. seem to moslty have gone that way (with a minority either taking 1-O<br>
or 1-A on either side).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; They help with the war effort in non-combattent</i><br>
<i>&gt; vocations. I am still trying to make sense of this. While one may not do</i><br>
<i>&gt; the actual squeezing of the trigger, one may be the clerk who types the</i><br>
<i>&gt; order to kill or be the driver who drives the ammunition to the front.</i><br>
<p>
In most cases this would not be correct: a truck driver, engineer, typist,<br>
etc., would be at least possibly combat-related: they all receive weapons<br>
training.  (And in the Marines, for example, *everyone* is a rifleman first,<br>
and whatever second.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Ideally, SDAs should serve as medics or perhaps do bomb disposal, or</i><br>
<i>&gt; something which actually helps save lives, but nowadays, even medics are</i><br>
<i>&gt; required to be armed, because they are prime targets for enemy snipers;</i><br>
<i>&gt; now not many people bother about the Geneva convention.</i><br>
<p>
Which must explain why most of my friends from academy and college who saw<br>
service in Viet Nam (or, previously in WW2 or Korea who were SDA at that<br>
time) who were medics on the front line didn't carry a weapon.  (There were<br>
some advantages here: without the normal weapon/ammo load, they could carry<br>
more medical supplies, and they weren't distracted by having to think about<br>
trying to defend themselves.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Here in Singapore, we are fortunate in that the SDA church has a certain</i><br>
<i>&gt; level of understanding with the ministry of defense in that they post our</i><br>
<i>&gt; young men to non-combattent vocations and do not require them to use</i><br>
<i>&gt; weapons. </i><br>
<p>
Works here, too.  But it isn't automatic, you would have to request non-combat<br>
positions.<br>
<p>
Actually, now that the military is all-volunteer now, you won't have the<br>
option.  It's one thing to be drafted, it's something else entirely to volunteer.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; In some other countries the SDAs have to choose to serve in the</i><br>
<i>&gt; armed forces with no regard to their religious scruples of face lengthy</i><br>
<i>&gt; prison terms or other punishments, and some really get a lot of</i><br>
<i>&gt; persecuition.</i><br>
<p>
Up until WW1, this was the situation in the U.S.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I have also herd that up in Myanmar, some of the Karens have converted to</i><br>
<i>&gt; Adventism, but some of these still fight for their lives, against the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Yangon regieme, whith whom they are in the midst of a war. I am not judging</i><br>
<i>&gt; them or anything, i just want to note that the churches' stand on this</i><br>
<i>&gt; issue doesn't seem to be a hard and fast rule everywhere.</i><br>
<p>
The Bible itself makes a clear distinction between offensive and defensive<br>
use of force.  (Ought to be good for a healthy discussion... :} )<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
