<title>Mar_1993: Law, Parable of two Husbands</title>
<h1>Law, Parable of two Husbands</h1>
<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i><br>
<i>Mon, 08 Mar 93 09:32:54 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#88">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#88">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#88">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#88">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Wong Kwai Ying, Library, X6725: "Re:  Texas shootout"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Re Pacifism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A few years ago I posted a sort of parable about two husbands, this was<br>
posted to s.r.c.<br>
<p>
The first husband was meticulous about the birthdays of family members<br>
and their wedding anniversary.  Full blown celebration for each event.<br>
But the rest of the year he was not a very attentive husband, being more<br>
of a workaholic with his job.  His marriage eventually failed.<br>
<p>
The other husband, by way of illustration, was watching TV and the talk<br>
show host was interviewing the author of a new book.  The book documented<br>
the results of a questionaire in which one of the questions was -- would<br>
you divorce your husband because he never bothered with birthdays and<br>
anniversaries.  The unanimous answer from the wives was that they would<br>
not divorce their husbands over that.  And so the 2nd husband resolved<br>
immediately that he would make himself completely aloof from these<br>
events in the lives of his family -- reasoning that -- why bother if<br>
its not going to cost me my marriage.  That attitude led to the neglect<br>
of other things and . . . . . .   If it seemed that something would<br>
not cost him his marriage he couldn't be bothered.   His marriage ended<br>
in divorce.  Not because his wife dumped him, in fact she tried<br>
desperately to energize the marriage.  Rather, the husband simply<br>
became increasingly aloof from his marriage and family.  The time<br>
came when his interrests were caught up with another woman, in fact<br>
he came to celebrate her birdays, and . . . . .<br>
<p>
These two husbands illustrate two forms of legalism.  The first husband<br>
kept the law as if it would preserve his marriage.  But the day by<br>
relationships throughout the year meant nothing to him.  His marriage<br>
failed.<br>
<p>
The second husband was also a legalist in that he could not be bothered<br>
with anything that would not immediately cost him his marriage.  The<br>
second husband started out as an attentive husband and father.  But<br>
his attitude of getting by on the minimums led to his eventual divorce.<br>
<p>
Both kinds of legalism can cost us our salvation.  Certainly Jesus<br>
would have us married to him.  But too often we let the marriage fail.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
