<title>Mar_1993: Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff</title>
<h1>Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 8 Mar 93 10:26:42 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#91">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#91">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#91">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#91">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0092.html">Trevor Tompkins: "Re: Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0090.html">Scott Hinks: "Re: SDA Doctrinal Distinctives"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Steven Timm: "Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0092.html">Trevor Tompkins: "Re: Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Steve Timm writes:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Well, the newspaper said that an ATF agent was hit by a round from a</i><br>
<i>&gt; 50-calibre machine gun.</i><br>
<p>
There's been no followup on that report.  On the other hand, since the<br>
media were there filming the initial assault, it's been possible to<br>
review the video.  The .50 BMG has a *very* distinctive sound...and that<br>
sound is nowhere evident.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I may be wrong, but I doubt you can get a licence</i><br>
<i>&gt; for that, even in Texas.</i><br>
<p>
The National Firearms Act of 1934 set out the rules for legal ownership<br>
of full-auto firearms.  You *can*, except in a couple of states like<br>
California and New Jersey, get a permit to purchase and own full-auto<br>
firearms.  It costs a lot, requires an extended permit process including<br>
an extensive background check.<br>
<p>
Oh yes, since 1934 there have been all of three occurances of legally-owned<br>
(as per NFA-34) full-auto firearms involved in criminal use.  Or so I<br>
understand...I've only been able to find real references for two.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; Well, it appears to me, that they got raided not because of their religion,</i><br>
<i>&gt; but because they broke the law. </i><br>
<p>
But what law?<br>
<p>
The BATF (Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms) deals only in those<br>
items.  They're part of the Treasury department, and are basically tax<br>
collectors.<br>
<p>
Initially, they reported that they (BATF) reported that they were serving<br>
a warrant issued to *search* the compound for reported firearms violations.<br>
<p>
Rather an energetic search, it seems to me.  Oh yes, the BATF issues those<br>
Class III (full-auto) permits and collects the taxes on them.  If, as has<br>
been said, the .50 was owned by Koresh, and if Koresh does really have a<br>
Class III firearms permit...the BATF would have issued the permit.<br>
<p>
Allegations of child abuse and polygamy were brought up later to justify<br>
the raid.  (Don't ask *me* why...these aren't crimes under the BATF's<br>
jurisdiction.)  Don't forget, the local sheriff investigated the child<br>
abuse allegations a while back.  Drove over to the farm, asked to look<br>
around to see if there was any evidence that they might be true.  No<br>
shooting either way, no violence, ...<br>
<p>
I am beginning to fear that the BATF has been other than perfectly frank<br>
with us regarding their motives and goals.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; This of course, raises the question of</i><br>
<i>&gt; where to draw the line between religious liberty and the law of the land.</i><br>
<p>
Yes.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Should religious liberty include being allowed to own an arsenal of</i><br>
<i>&gt; dangerous weapons and using them to shoot at people?</i><br>
<p>
Don't mix the two.  Ownership is one thing.  Harming others is something<br>
else entirely.<br>
<p>
We don't punish people (*God* doesn't punish us) because they might<br>
possibly hurt someone, but punishment is supposed to result from the<br>
*act* of harming another.  Otherwise, we'd *all* be in jail, or be<br>
lost forever.<br>
<p>
regards,<br>
<p>
	steve hix<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
