<title>Mar_1993: Re: Thoughts on the Waco standoff</title>
<h1>Re: Thoughts on the Waco standoff</h1>
Trevor Tompkins (<i>tt17+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  8 Mar 1993 21:22:48 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#92">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#92">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#92">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#92">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0093.html">Danny Kumamoto: "news coverage of Waco, TX (San Jose and Japan)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Steve Hix: "Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Steven Timm: "Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0100.html">Woody Baker: "Re:  Thoughts on the Waco standoff"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>|&gt; Where do these people get there news?!!  The raid was not because Koresh</i><br>
<i>|&gt; illegally owned guns, but to arrest him for various other illegal</i><br>
<i>|&gt; activities, some of which was his marrying many different wives, and</i><br>
<i>|&gt; child abuse.</i><br>
<i>|</i><br>
<i>|It's interesting that the child abuse/polygamy didn't come up until after</i><br>
<i>|the BATF's initial assault failed.</i><br>
<p>
Would you expect them to announce a raid?  Contrary to the first<br>
posting, the ATF stated that they did have reason to believe that there<br>
were illegal firearms and explosives.  So I was wrong,  the other<br>
allegations were another side story about the so called messiah.<br>
<p>
<i>|It's also interesting that they occurred *at all*, since the BATF's</i><br>
<i>|jurisdiction extends only to "Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms".</i><br>
<p>
Right!<br>
<p>
<i>|The child-abuse allegations, btw, were investigated a while back by the</i><br>
<i>|local sheriff.  He drove over to the farm, told them that there were such</i><br>
<i>|allegations and asked to be allowed in to look for evidence.</i><br>
<p>
<i>|No violence, they cooperated, no evidence found.</i><br>
<p>
Of course there is no evidence, the witnesses believe he is the son of God.<br>
  <br>
<i>|&gt; The reason they needed guns was a result of the Branch</i><br>
<i>|&gt; Davidians' violent nature.</i><br>
<p>
<i>|Other than the "civil war" among the BD factions in 1987, what violent</i><br>
<i>|nature.  (Their neighbors don't seem to be worried about the threat that</i><br>
<i>|they pose to the community.)</i><br>
<p>
And apparently the civil war in 1989, according to "A current affair" (I<br>
know there not the most reliable).  However, do you need more than a<br>
civil war that involved military styled shootings?  Also, if you see the<br>
pictures on the news, the neighbors are nowhere in sight. I live closer<br>
to violent areas than the BD's neighbors.<br>
<p>
<i>|&gt; |Others have focused on the religious liberty issues this raises,</i><br>
<i>|&gt; |wondering who will be next with such a raid.</i><br>
<i>|&gt; </i><br>
<i>|&gt; The raid was not religiously motivated.  It has religious overtones</i><br>
<i>|&gt; because David Koresh is trying to make it that way.</i><br>
<p>
<i>|The media, if not the BATF (although they, too, are working that angle)</i><br>
<i>|are using their religious differences from the mainstream to justify the</i><br>
<i>|operation.</i><br>
<p>
When a religion not only advocates violence against others, but also<br>
uses it, I think that is a religious difference from the mainstream to<br>
justify such an operation.  The rest, such as Koresh preying on<br>
psychologically weak, His unjustified claims of being the Messiah, and<br>
telling his followers that God wants the women of the church to be his,<br>
just adds to incredibleness of it all.<br>
<p>
<i>|Here in the U.S., such deviation has often been enough justification for</i><br>
<i>|local, state, and federal governments to do things that would not otherwise </i><br>
<i>|be tolerated.</i><br>
<p>
In this case the deviations match what we often call organized crime,<br>
but in this case they are called, Branch Davidian.  There are all kinds<br>
of organizations in the U.S.  The one's that should be shut down are the<br>
one's that break the laws set up in our society (like organized crime). <br>
 Just because an organization is "religious," doesn't mean can it break<br>
these laws.  Religious organizations can believe what they want to, but<br>
if these beliefs turn into actions that break laws, then they need to<br>
taken to task just like any other organization.  If the Branch Davidians<br>
were a telemarketing firm (and I don't see much difference beside the<br>
violence) they would have the same action taken against them.  In fact,<br>
there was a raid recently that did, just that.  And the telemarketers<br>
didn't even shoot anyone.  They did prey on innocent people for their<br>
own benefit however.<br>
<p>
I certainly don't think the government always acts correctly (not even<br>
half the time).  But so far, this particular case reveals a group of<br>
people who do not think that they need to follow the same laws as we do<br>
(they probably also don't mind the attention either).<br>
<p>
--Trevor<br>
_________________<br>
Logic and Computation<br>
Carnegie Mellon University<br>
tt17@andrew.cmu.edu<br>
