<title>Mar_1993: Re: Pacifisim and the Church (2 more anecdotes)</title>
<h1>Re: Pacifisim and the Church (2 more anecdotes)</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Mar 93 16:44:19 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#102">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#102">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#102">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#102">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0103.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Pacifism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0101.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "pacifist != won't fight"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[fredch writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Perhaps our stance was not brought up to you for two reasons:</i><br>
<i>&gt; 1) Whether or not one bears arms in private or in the military is not a</i><br>
<i>&gt; test of fellowship, to the best of my knowledge.  Re the first case:</i><br>
<i>&gt; for example, many pioneer missionaries needed guns to protect against</i><br>
<i>&gt; marauding animals.  [..]</i><br>
<p>
Two anecdotes re private bearing of arms:<br>
The head deacon of the church I attended in Oregon runs an auto body shop.<br>
He has a good size shop, with many specialized, expensive tools.  A few<br>
years back, his shop was broken into and several thousands of dollars<br>
worth of tools were stolen.  He started sleeping over in his shop.  One<br>
night, an intruder cut through an aluminum garage door and entered.  He<br>
was challenged by my friend to drop his knife and spread-eagle.  Instead,<br>
the intruder charged my friend, to attack him.  My friend pulled out his<br>
pistol and shot the intruder in the leg, disabling him; clear self-defense.<br>
My friend offered to resign his position as head deacon, but the church<br>
board felt that was not necessary.<br>
<p>
Re arms and sports:  A friend of mine in Southern Ontario, Canada, has<br>
been Canadian National Champion several times in his marksmanship specialty,<br>
distinguished himself at the Olympics, and was World Champion during a<br>
non-Olympics year.  He gives a powerful testimony on God's leading in his<br>
life, and draws parallels between the disciplines required to become a<br>
champion and the disciplines of the Christian life.  Mature youth have<br>
appreciated his testimony; unfortunately, others feel talking about discipline<br>
and self-denial is a drag.  Since hanging up his rifles, my friend has<br>
switched from being a medal winner to being a soul winner.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
