<title>Mar_1993: Re: Pacifism</title>
<h1>Re: Pacifism</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Mar 93 17:10:43 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#103">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#103">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#103">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#103">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0104.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Pacifisim and the Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0102.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Pacifisim and the Church (2 more anecdotes)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; This is not at all a simple issue.</i><br>
<p>
Not at all.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Take a medic who repairs combat troops. Those troops whose lives have been</i><br>
<i>&gt; saved then go back to fight some more. </i><br>
<p>
Well...<br>
<p>
Troops lightly wounded enough to be sent back into fighting soon often<br>
don't need the medic much at all.<br>
<p>
The ones that really need the medic's services are more likely to<br>
be people who won't be coming back for quite a while, if at all.<br>
<p>
People who would otherwise have died.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; So the medic is doing just as much to aid the killing as "the</i><br>
<i>&gt; clerk who types the order to kill" or the truck driver carting</i><br>
<i>&gt; the ammunition.</i><br>
<p>
I would disagree, at least partly: the medic isn't normally doing<br>
anything to supply the tools of war to the troops who have to do<br>
the killing. You might argue that it just frees up another man to<br>
take weapons and fight...except that it's very seldom the case that<br>
the government's resources are so constrained that they can't just<br>
conscript a few more to make up the difference.  Your choosing to<br>
not serve is unlikely to result in any fewer, or any more, troops<br>
being eventually sent into combat.<br>
<p>
Looks to me like a juggling match.  If I refuse to serve when called<br>
up, most likely I'll be put in a small room for the duration (in<br>
earlier times I'd just be shot, as happened in U.S. during the Civil<br>
War), and they'll just select another hapless sort, who, if not<br>
choosing to forego weapons training, might well turn out to be a<br>
poorer medic, being distracted with the competing urges to do his job<br>
and provide a measure of his own self defense.<br>
<p>
My choice was to try to reduce the sum total of suffering, if called<br>
up.  Most of my friends called up made the same choice, a few didn't.<br>
<p>
My father served during WW2 as a navy medical corpsman, basically taking<br>
the same choice.<br>
<p>
It's something that should be left up to the choice of the individual,<br>
and respected either way.<br>
<p>
	seh<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
