<title>Mar_1993: Re: Pacifisim and the Church</title>
<h1>Re: Pacifisim and the Church</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Mar 93 16:21:10 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#104">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#104">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#104">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#104">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0105.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Pacifism and the church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0103.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Pacifism"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0097.html">Russell Yonkers: "Pacifisim and the Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Russell Yonkers writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; The church that my wife and I attended when we became</i><br>
<i>&gt; Adventists was located outside of an Air Force base on which I was</i><br>
<i>&gt; stationed.  They never mentioned the fact that the church took a </i><br>
<i>&gt; pacifistic stance.</i><br>
<p>
I'm not an etymologist (is that the right word?), but, given the denotation<br>
of pacifist, I think pacifist may not be an entirely correct characterization,<br>
even tho we may speak of the SDA church as being pacifist.  As they used to<br>
say in English class, compare &amp; contrast our stance vs Mennonites &amp; Quakers.<br>
<p>
Perhaps our stance was not brought up to you for two reasons:<br>
1) Whether or not one bears arms in private or in the military is not a<br>
test of fellowship, to the best of my knowledge.  Re the first case:<br>
for example, many pioneer missionaries needed guns to protect against<br>
marauding animals.  However, as to military service, the historical stand,<br>
in my experience, is to strongly recommend serving in a non-combatant role (the rationale has been worked out over many years).  In your case, your<br>
role was chosen before you became an SDA, so there was no need to press<br>
the issue, but leave it up to you.  Some SDAs have, I believe, bore arms<br>
during wartime.  It is my understanding that one of the main Pathfinder<br>
leaders in Yuma, Arizona, has been a gunnery training officer for the Marines<br>
(just recently retired).  I also recall Guide magazine, back in the 60s,<br>
publishing a story about an SDA youth in South America who had no choice<br>
but to bear arms, did so while praying not to have to go into combat,<br>
and how the Lord used him to protect the general's family, etc.<br>
Of course, there are also stories about those who served as non-combatants.<br>
2) Since it is a personal decision, your pastor decided to let you grow<br>
in Christian maturity and make the decision in your/God's own time.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I was upset that people took</i><br>
<i>&gt; such a strong stance on it and that I had never heard about it before</i><br>
<p>
Perhaps because of the non-combatant recommendation and whereas the vast<br>
majority of SDA young men choose not to bear arms, many suffering persecution<br>
on many occasion as result, some folk may feel that those who chose<br>
otherwise betray the faith; thus they speak out strongly.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Is the church </i><br>
<i>&gt; really such a strong "peace" church or is the tone of the conversation</i><br>
<i>&gt; just much stronger then the actual beliefs?</i><br>
<p>
I would suggest the latter is closer, given my comments above.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I feel strongly</i><br>
<i>&gt; about my rights to bear arms and have recently been shopping for firearms.</i><br>
<p>
Final comment:  When my wife and I were overseas as missionaries, there was<br>
a riot at our school, stemming in part over tribal rivalries but directed<br>
at the missionaries over alleged preferential treatment.  Several of the<br>
missionaries came very close to being killed, and there was great damage<br>
to property.  Some of the missionaries took up machetes and lead pipes.<br>
My wife and I did neither, prefering "feathers" (see Ruth 2:12, Ps 36:7;<br>
57:1; 61:4; 91:4).<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
