<title>Mar_1993: Re: Pacifism and the church</title>
<h1>Re: Pacifism and the church</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  9 Mar 1993 23:21:30 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#105">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#105">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#105">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#105">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0106.html">Steven Timm: "Album Review:  Rachel Rachel  "You Oughta Know By Now""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0104.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Pacifisim and the Church"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0125.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Pacifism and the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0164.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Pacifism and the church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
If any pacifists there be in the SDA church, they certainly don't go<br>
to my local church in Illinois.  One of the leading families in the church<br>
had a grandson in the Gulf war, and another had a son in the National Guard<br>
that almost got sent.  The first Sabbath during the gulf war was marked <br>
by marked and long prayers for our troops and none for the Iraqi civilians.<br>
A yellow candle was conspicuously burning on the communion table.<br>
<p>
After the Desert Storm operation was over and this soldier returned to <br>
visit the church that had written him many letters and prayed many prayers,<br>
there was quite the celebration in church, the pastor doing everything <br>
but wrapping himself in the American flag.  God help me, I felt like<br>
going on stage and burning the American flag.  (I didn't.)  <br>
<p>
The media such as the Adventist Review was not immune to cheerleading<br>
during the gulf war, either.  The Adventists in the war that were<br>
casualties<br>
got newsbreak mention, even press releases from the GC communication<br>
department.  We've still never heard what happened to the SDA church <br>
in Baghdad (there was one, I understand).  Nobody mentioned that Iraq<br>
was one of the few countries in the Gulf that allows some measure of <br>
religious freedom.<br>
<p>
People will not believe that our church recommends against combatancy<br>
if we continue to lionize the soldiers who shoot.  The Review coverage<br>
plus the four-part feature on Ronald Tull which appeared in Insight magazine <br>
tell the real story of where we stand.  Not to mention that many SDA pastors<br>
are chaplains in the National Guard and Army Reserves in addition to their <br>
regular duties.  Too often Adventism and Americanism are combined,<br>
with disastrous results to both.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
