<title>Mar_1993: Album Review:  Rachel Rachel  "You Oughta Know By Now"</title>
<h1>Album Review:  Rachel Rachel  "You Oughta Know By Now"</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  9 Mar 1993 23:42:23 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#106">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#106">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#106">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#106">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0107.html">Steven Timm: "bit.listserv.christia"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0105.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Pacifism and the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Having overcome the ugly picture on the front of their first album to<br>
continue on a successful tour, they are now ready to put out a second<br>
album, this one makes them look almost as good as they do in real life.<br>
Again this album is produced by Billy Smiley.  The influences from <br>
White Heart, being both their producer and touring partner, are obvious.<br>
However, there are some important differences.<br>
<p>
For those who have been hiding for the last two years, Rachel Rachel<br>
is an all-female Christian rock band, comprised of Brynn Beltran (keyboards)<br>
Cheryl Jewel (lead vocals), Jennifer Sparks (Sparky) drums, <br>
Heli Sterner (guitars+vocals) and Jennifer York (bass).  Their music<br>
is straight-up rock and roll with well-harmonized three and four part vocals.<br>
<p>
Highlights from this album are "In Your Arms" and "You Are Always There".<br>
It's well-produced, well-written (they write most of their own stuff)<br>
and well-performed.  If you liked their previous album, you'll like this <br>
one better.  If you liked anything that White Heart or early Margaret Becker<br>
has done, you'll like this, too.  Although I must say I have heard <br>
this album four times now and still none of the songs have stuck with me.<br>
<p>
Steve's rating  2.5 thistles on a scale of -5 to 5<br>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
