<title>Mar_1993: Pacifism and the church</title>
<h1>Pacifism and the church</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Mar 1993 20:28:36 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#112">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#112">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#112">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#112">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0113.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Pacifism and the church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0111.html">Russell Yonkers: "Des Ford writings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0118.html">Terry L Anderson: "Pacifism and the church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm sure that research has been done on the relationship of the SDA<br>
church and the military.  In the U.S. this history goes back to the<br>
Civil War, when church authorities tried to prevent Adventist young men<br>
from being drafted.  I don't remember, but this may have had to do as<br>
much with Sabbath problems than it did with a real pacifist belief.<br>
Most Adventists, including Ellen White, had been real abolitionists<br>
(to the point that Ellen White said that the Civil War was a punishment<br>
to the North for having tolerated slavery for so long).  These were New<br>
England reformers after all.  While SDAs have never been as strictly<br>
pacifist as the Amish (many of whom live not far from here in Northern<br>
Indiana), there certainly is a long history of at least a modified<br>
version of it.  To deny this or try to cover it up is not a credit to<br>
our history.  I believe Seminary professor George Knight recently gave a<br>
paper on this topic at a conference at Goshen (Ind.) College.<br>
<p>
By the time of World War II (the war of my father's generation), the<br>
church had made an accomodation with the military/government complex in<br>
the form of serving as I-AO (non-combatants in the military),<br>
particularly as medics.  This was promoted by the Medical Cadet Corps,<br>
which was an organization where old and young Adventists could play at<br>
being soldiers and also learn something about what lay ahead of them (at<br>
least the young men).  I believe this organization lasted into the late<br>
'60s or early '70s.  The '60s generation was not prepared for this type<br>
of lockstep approach, and it was really at that time that I believe the<br>
church really began to support the concept of supporting individual<br>
choice.  For some, this meant becoming true conscientious objectors and<br>
doing alternate service.  If I had been older or had a lower lottery<br>
number, that is the route that I would have taken.  But it also opened<br>
the door wider for SDAs to take combatant roles.<br>
<p>
This became much more widespread after the reinstitution of the<br>
volunteer army after Vietnam.  Economic incentives may have played a<br>
part in some of these individuals' decision to enlist.  Many no doubt<br>
experiences Sabbath problems.  I am one of Maxwell's reprobates who<br>
writes for Spectrum (though Mervyn and I get along just fine on a<br>
personal basis), and in my survey of SDA colleges newspapers at the time<br>
of the Gulf War, I found the same thing as Steve did--far more overt<br>
support for the war and the warriors than one would expect, given the<br>
church's historic position.  On the campus here at Andrews there was a<br>
fascinating response from many of the foreign students (who in the past<br>
have been shocked by the patriotic activities and "showing the flag"<br>
during Pathfinder Sabbath).  These students were truly shocked that the<br>
American church was taking such a pro-military stand (and Pioneer<br>
Memorial Church also glorified its heroes).  Some, like the Germans,<br>
knew that historically their church had been split over this issue (and<br>
the Seventh-day Adventist Reform Movement begun).  Given their history,<br>
it was not surprising that the Germans were pacifistic, but many other<br>
nationalities supported this, indicating to me that this is something<br>
that our missionaries had probably originally taken to these lands as<br>
part of our beliefs and practices.<br>
<p>
In this country, I wonder how much this pro-military stance is related<br>
to the drift toward fundamentalism found in some segments of the church.<br>
A few years ago I was in Huntsville for the 4th of July and went to a<br>
performace at a Baptist Church--a patriotic extravaganza including<br>
fireworks--in the church!  I don't know of any Adventist churches that<br>
would do this (though a local black SDA church participated in the<br>
Baptist performance), but I'm sure there are many sympathizers.  In<br>
North America, we sometimes forget that we are a minority in a world<br>
church, and that Adventism and America are not the same.  Sometimes I<br>
wonder if our practice has as much to do with avoiding Sabbath problems<br>
in the military as it does with actual belief that serving in the<br>
military is wrong, in much the same way as it is easier to be an<br>
Adventist in the medical professions (where almost by definition there<br>
are no Sabbath problems) than in other professions.  I would like to<br>
think that Adventists are less violent than the general public, and I<br>
suspect that far fewer of us own guns than do our neighbors.  If for<br>
nothing else, this would distance us from such kooks as Koresh.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(Internet:  brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
