<title>Mar_1993: &gt; Pacifism and the church</title>
<h1>&gt; Pacifism and the church</h1>
Ralf Simonsson (<i>/G=Ralf/S=Simonsson/O=Fimnet/@elisa.fi</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 1993 05:58:49 +0200</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#113">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#113">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#113">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#113">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0114.html">Malachi Robertson: "Donahue and Waco stuff"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0112.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Pacifism and the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have followed with some interest the "American" discussion about non-combatancy<br>
I am also a little surprised - for me adventism has always meant not bearing <br>
guns (well maybe hunting). When I made my military service in the<br>
60's (in Finland), I applied for a service not wearing guns. That was granted<br>
very easily - the service time was some 13 moths instead for normal 8. I <br>
counted that as a sacrifice for my beliefs. I declared that I will not do any service<br>
service on Sabbaths either and that was also granted; provided that i dissappeared<br>
from the garrisons during Saturdays.<br>
<p>
In my unit with som 800 men there was  som 20 who were conscientius; SDAs, Baptists<br>
Pentecostals etc. Today here in Finland altogether some 6000 men decline<br>
to go to military service, mainly because of ethical reasons (or as some militar<br>
people think because of comfort).<br>
<p>
Wel we have to accept that the Adventist culture is different in different parts<br>
of the world (Here in Finland we go swimming on Sabbath! 8-) )<br>
<p>
RSi<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
