<title>Mar_1993: Pacifism and the church</title>
<h1>Pacifism and the church</h1>
Terry L Anderson (<i>tla@mozart.att.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 93 10:59:21 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#118">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#118">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#118">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#118">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0119.html">Michael Merginio: "Re: Donahue and Waco stuff"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0117.html">Steven Timm: "Unclean meats and Genesis 9"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0112.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Pacifism and the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Harvey Brenneise writes:<br>
    I'm sure that research has been done on the relationship of the SDA<br>
    church and the military...  <br>
<p>
I recently joined this net so have not seen the earlier messages in<br>
this thread, but ...<br>
<p>
Ron Lawson, an SDA sociologist at Queens College, NYC, has done<br>
research on SDA and its relationship to the military (both official<br>
and practice).  He is "chaplain" of our Assoc of Adv Forum chapter in<br>
Greater NY (meets weekly on the campus of Columbia University,<br>
Manhattan, St Paul's Chapel, Sat 10:00-12:00).  Ron has done a lot of<br>
sociological work on the SDA church around the world and is working on<br>
a book about the church.  He has interviewed officials from every<br>
division and every union in the world and many local conferences,<br>
missions and other institutions over the last several years.<br>
<p>
In a recent meeting Ron described some of his work on SDAs and<br>
military and we had a response from Elder Tull (I believe that is the<br>
right spelling, he was Ministerial Secr of NJ Conf but has since taken<br>
a Pastorship in Paradise Valley, CA).  Elder Tull's son was the sole<br>
survivor of an attach on his Marine tank during Desert Storm and he<br>
talked about his attitudes concerning his son's service (he supported<br>
his son and saw God's protection in his survival).<br>
<p>
Ron's findings were very interesting.  The US history is reasonably<br>
well known but he has collected a lot of data on the relationship in<br>
other parts of the world -- which has varied enormously.  Ron recently<br>
published his work but I do not have the reference.  I could get the<br>
citation if this would be of interest to the group.<br>
<p>
The non-combatant option is nearly unique to the US.  Elsewhere, the<br>
variation runs from cases in which nearly every Adventist serves <br>
as combatants to countries where the Church insists on conscientious<br>
objection and nearly every Adventist (at least male) serves time in<br>
prison for it.  Sometimes the position changes very quickly such as in<br>
Korea, where until recently many SDAs served time in prison for<br>
refusing to serve and then, in a very abrupt reversal, we now provide<br>
military training with weapons on the campus of our college (we would<br>
have lost government approval of the college if we refused to provide<br>
training).<br>
<p>
It seems that our position has often had less to do with any<br>
principles and more to do with public acceptance/image and the<br>
advantages vs disadvantages of government cooperation.  As the church<br>
(in many countries) has become more mainstream, there has developed a<br>
pressure to perserve (or create) a positive image and acceptance by<br>
the public.  Where cooperation with the government has brought better<br>
acceptance and sometimes other accommodations and where there has not<br>
been a firm position based on universally accepted principles we seem<br>
to have moved toward cooperation (on this as well as other issues).  <br>
<p>
Since I do not look to my church to determine my position for me, such<br>
changes don't bother me deeply, but I feel badly for others who have<br>
felt compelled to pay a high personal price (prison, ...) for<br>
maintaining the church's position and then have that abruptly change.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
			     --	Terry L Anderson<br>
				AT&amp;T Bell Laboratories, RM 3D-481<br>
				600 Mountain Av, Murray Hill, NJ 07974<br>
				UUCP:	...!att!mozart!tla<br>
				NET:	tla@mozart.att.com<br>
				ATTMAIL: mozart!tla<br>
				VOICE: 908 582-7013<br>
				FAX:   908 582-7988<br>
