<title>Mar_1993: Re: Unclean meats and Genesis 9</title>
<h1>Re: Unclean meats and Genesis 9</h1>
<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 93 13:13:18 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#121">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#121">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#121">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#121">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0122.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Reformers and the Antichrist"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Unclean meats and Genesis 9"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0117.html">Steven Timm: "Unclean meats and Genesis 9"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0138.html">Bill Nickless: "Re: Unclean meats and Genesis 9"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Regarding eating any moving thing right after the flood.<br>
<p>
  * Vegetarian seems to be all thats promoted before the flood.<br>
<p>
  * Right after the flood, with a totally baren landscape, there<br>
    would be little to eat.<br>
<p>
  * God said meats were made available to shorten their lifespans.<br>
<p>
  * After that we see the unclean meats clearly defined.<br>
<p>
So, at best the Noah and flood argument applys to the desert island<br>
scenario where starvation is the other alternative.<br>
<p>
On the other hand, the Bible stories of God providing.  And of course<br>
Daniel and his friends did so much better without the kings food.<br>
Was the king serving pork?  Of course we cannot say for sure.  Was<br>
it simply rich sweet/fat vege foods?  Again, we cannot say for sure.<br>
But I think its very likely that foods forbidden to Israelites was<br>
the issue and so very probably unclean meats.  So Daniel and his<br>
friends resorted to a vegetarian diet and did incredibly well compared<br>
to those eating what the king ate.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
