<title>Mar_1993: Wedding rings</title>
<h1>Wedding rings</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 1993 13:17:05 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#123">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#123">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#123">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#123">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0124.html">Richard Behrens: "Australlian elections on Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0122.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Reformers and the Antichrist"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In the U.S., the wedding ring is usually worn on the fourth finger of<br>
the left hand.  [That's where I wore mine until I lost it in the garden<br>
about a year ago.  I still hope to find it before we move to a new house<br>
later this year.]  Many, if not most, Europeans wear theirs on the fouth<br>
finger of the right hand (and don't understand why Americans use the<br>
left--or gauche/sinister--hand for this--sorry southpaws!).  Some<br>
people, mostly female, also wear an engagement ring (usually with a<br>
stone).  I believe in the past that the custom in some areas was for the<br>
wife to wear a wedding ring but not the husband.  This may have grown<br>
out of the concept of the wedding ring as a token of ownership.  In<br>
recent years I think there has been a growing trend for both husband and<br>
wife to wear wedding rings.<br>
<p>
I don't know where Steve's statistics come from about the incidence of<br>
wedding ring wearing.  Many of our married students at Andrews (and most<br>
of the European ones) wear wedding rings.  When I meet people<br>
professionally, they are often wearing a wedding ring (including the<br>
men).  There are lots of cultural differences in the world at large, in<br>
the church at large, and in the church in North America on this.  I have<br>
heard that there are still churches where this is a no-no.  Yet others<br>
feel very strongly about its symbolism.  I remember when I was in<br>
library school at Chapel Hill just before I came up here, I put my ring<br>
away (figuring it would not be the thing to do).  It was surprising how<br>
many people noticed and concluded that Coral and I had split up.  We<br>
need to be tolerant of other people's convictions.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
