<title>Mar_1993: Pacifism and the church</title>
<h1>Pacifism and the church</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix3.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 13 Mar 93 00:59:27 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#125">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#125">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#125">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#125">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0126.html">Marcus Stringer: "Religion as Minority status"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0124.html">Richard Behrens: "Australlian elections on Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0105.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Pacifism and the church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ralf Simonsson writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I have followed with some interest the "American" discussion about</i><br>
<i>&gt;non-combatancy I am also a little surprised - for me adventism has always</i><br>
<i>&gt;meant not bearing guns (well maybe hunting).</i><br>
<p>
Yes i am a bit surprised too. The national media here sometimes publishes<br>
views that the west, and especially America, is decadent, unruly, and given<br>
to much crime, violence, drugs and moral peversion, and therefore urge<br>
this as a warning against copying all the values and customs of the west,<br>
like human rights and so on. Of course, i know that views of this sort are<br>
biased, hypocritical, and usually politically motivated; but (and no offense<br>
meant to anyone) from all the _bad_ news, America does appear to be a violent<br>
war-like society, with people getting shot at for sounding a car horn and<br>
all that, although i still think and hope that violence there is localised<br>
and still rather the exception than the rule. Of course, there is more<br>
violence all over the world nowadays, Singapore is no exception, but somehow,<br>
i always expected, at the back of my mind, that America was founded by<br>
Christian people, on Christian principles, and so would be more peaceful<br>
and civilised than some other places, although i probably saw that this was<br>
not the case.<br>
	Well, America has been styled the policeman of the new world order,<br>
since it is the only superpower left, and nowadays, policemen need guns i<br>
suppose. Still, imagine what it will be like when the lamb-like beast<br>
speaks like the dragon.<br>
	And serving with guns, it is seldom a black-and-white clear cut<br>
issue, i suppose, and has to do a lot with individual beliefs, after all<br>
each must live with their own conscience. That it is not a test of<br>
fellowship in the SDA church shows, i suppose, that it is not a hard and<br>
fast rule everywhere and there is considerable variance in views about<br>
bearing arms in the armed services. And in actual combat, it gets even harder,<br>
because the situation is so extreme and so unnatural that many moral issues<br>
become hard to decide. Is there such a thing as a "just" war?  Or is it just<br>
a war. What does it justify? Does the ends justify the means?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;When I made my military service</i><br>
<i>&gt;in the 60's (in Finland), I applied for a service not wearing guns. That</i><br>
<i>&gt;was granted very easily - the service time was some 13 moths instead for</i><br>
<i>&gt;normal 8. I counted that as a sacrifice for my beliefs.</i><br>
<p>
Here, the length of service varies according to educational qualifications.<br>
The higher qualified people serve 2 1/2 years and the others 2 years. I just<br>
finished my full-time servie in June last year and am now a reservist, a<br>
part-time soldier, till i'm 40 years old.<br>
	Well, it must have meant quite a lot to you to have to serve 1 1/2<br>
times as long as other people because of your beliefs. Here we are quite<br>
fortunate in that there is no official penalty for SDAs who choose not to<br>
bear weapons and not to work on Sabbath, although we sometimes still get<br>
Sabbath problems and harrassment of various sorts from some superiors. In<br>
the early days in the 60s, it was a lot worse for SDAs, who were subjected<br>
to detention and other punishments because of Sabbath and bearing arms.<br>
	In some other countries, Korea for example, not bearing arms means<br>
a lengthy jail term or other penalties. I heard that in the US up until<br>
world war 1, some of them were even execuited because of this.<br>
	Presently in Singapore, there is relative tolerance of SDA practices<br>
in the armed forces. Interestingly it is the Jehovah's Witnesses, who are<br>
banned in Singapore and considered a subversive cult, that are imprisoned.<br>
	I quite admire their faith and determination in willing to undergo<br>
that. Well, they believe in totally not doing National Service at all and<br>
refuse to take the oath of allegiance to the Republic or the Armed Forces<br>
and so end up in detention barracks for 3 years i think. But i understand<br>
that they are considered prisoners of conscience and kept appart from the<br>
other inmates and treated relatively humanely.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I declared that I will not do any service service on Sabbaths either and</i><br>
<i>&gt;that was also granted; provided that i dissappeared from the garrisons</i><br>
<i>&gt;during Saturdays.</i><br>
<p>
Wow! i wish they had such a proviso here! My superiors were kind enough to<br>
let me _not_ stay in camp on most Saturdays and so i could attend church<br>
almost every week. My friend who is still serving NS is not so fortunate.<br>
He never comes to church nowadays because he is not allowed out on Sabbath,<br>
although he is excused from working on that day.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;In my unit with som 800 men there was some 20 who were conscientius; SDAs,</i><br>
<i>&gt;Baptists Pentecostals etc. Today here in Finland altogether some 6000 men</i><br>
<i>&gt;decline to go to military service, mainly because of ethical reasons</i><br>
<i>&gt;(or as some militar people think because of comfort).</i><br>
<p>
Well, in my unit there were 2 other SDAs (i can't tell you how many men<br>
were in my unit because that would be considered a breach of security).<br>
As far as i know, SDAs are the only conscientious objectors serving here.<br>
Here, no one is allowed to decline millitary service. We have to produce<br>
a letter from the church to certify that we are practising SDAs (there<br>
is a list of definitions such as non-smoking, tithe paying etc.) before<br>
they will make provisions for us to serve without weapons etc, to reduce<br>
the chance of people using religion as an excuse to avoid combat vocations<br>
or work on Saturdays. Anyway, when i enlisted, i didn't want to avoid<br>
National Service at all, and was actually quite enthusiastic about it,<br>
but when i got in, it wasn't much like what i expected.<br>
	Well, perhaps i'll write about the time i was threatened with a<br>
court-marshall because i refused to do a physical fitness test on Sabbath.<br>
Somebody on SDAnet asked me to tell about it to encourage people with<br>
Sabbath problems, and all this talk about the army reminded me of it.<br>
Well, that will be another story.<br>
	<br>
<i>&gt;Wel we have to accept that the Adventist culture is different in different</i><br>
<i>&gt;parts of the world (Here in Finland we go swimming on Sabbath! 8-) )</i><br>
<p>
And i hear that in India, they play drums for worship service music! And<br>
my local church doesn't allow any flesh food, even "clean meat" on the<br>
premises! And somebody told me that some tribes people in a remote part of<br>
the world, go to church practically naked! Yes, culture does vary a lot.<br>
What is considered proper in one culture might not be viewed as such in<br>
another, but God understands all cultures and all languages so i don't<br>
suppose He minds it.<br>
<p>
-Beng Tang, Singapore<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
