<title>Mar_1993: Religion as Minority status</title>
<h1>Religion as Minority status</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 93 15:32:58 -0800 </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#126">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#126">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#126">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#126">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0127.html">Tim Swensen: "Reformers and statements about RCC"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0125.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Pacifism and the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It seems like the world's questioning eye is focusing<br>
more intensely on religion...<br>
<p>
"Should 'religion' remain a part off federal civil rights?"<br>
I've been asked this pointed question, and would like<br>
to hear some responses.  Actually I need help.<br>
The argument is quite cutting because one's "religion"<br>
per se, is not like race, or gender.  We who are "born"<br>
into families which practice certain beliefs, "choose"<br>
our religion.<br>
<p>
Also, it is pointed out that religious groups have<br>
extra-ordinary financial recourses, and political clout.<br>
Thus, they should be considered as non-minority, and<br>
should not receive the same protection.<br>
<p>
Any comments would be appreciated.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
