<title>Mar_1993: Relevance of Prophecy</title>
<h1>Relevance of Prophecy</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 93 12:54:07 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#129">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#129">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#129">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#129">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0130.html">Steven Timm: "Religion as Minority status"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0128.html">Ron Vyhmeister: "Fire in Frederick, Maryland"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0168.html">Russell Grau: "Re: Relevance of Prophecy"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
I would appreciate it if some of you folks would answer these questions.  I<br>
am formulating a sermon on the topic "The Relevance of Prophecy" and would <br>
like to gauge the importance of prophecy to contemporary Seventh-day <br>
Adventists.<br>
<p>
Questions:<br>
<p>
  To what degree is a correct understanding of Biblical prophecy important to<br>
  your daily experience as a Seventh-day Adventist Christian? <br>
<p>
  What about prophecy makes it this important?<br>
<p>
You relatively brief answers would be very much appreciated.<br>
<p>
<p>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
