<title>Mar_1993: Religion as Minority status</title>
<h1>Religion as Minority status</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 1993 20:00:41 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#130">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#130">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#130">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#130">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0131.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Maxwell's letter"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0129.html">Tim Swensen: "Relevance of Prophecy"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;"Should 'religion' remain a part off federal civil rights?"</i><br>
<i>&gt;I've been asked this pointed question, and would like</i><br>
<i>&gt;to hear some responses.  Actually I need help.</i><br>
<i>&gt;The argument is quite cutting because one's "religion"</i><br>
<i>&gt;per se, is not like race, or gender.  We who are "born"</i><br>
<i>&gt;into families which practice certain beliefs, "choose"</i><br>
<i>&gt;our religion.</i><br>
<p>
In fact, the position of freedom of religion in law  has been gradually <br>
eroded by the Supreme court over the last couple of years.  But I was not<br>
aware that we had the protection of Civil Rights law to start with.<br>
The First Amendment rights of free exercise of religion are different from<br>
the civil rights afforded to minority groups.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;Also, it is pointed out that religious groups have</i><br>
<i>&gt;extra-ordinary financial recourses, and political clout.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Thus, they should be considered as non-minority, and</i><br>
<i>&gt;should not receive the same protection.</i><br>
<p>
Civil rights are not only to protect minorities.  Witness women, who <br>
are a majority, still needing civil protection.  What these people <br>
may be trying to suggest is "Churches are not victims of society."<br>
For that I would say that civil rights should not be limited to victims.<br>
<p>
There were enough religious killings in the early history of USA,<br>
and are still enough going on elsewhere (Bosnia) to justify protection<br>
against what might happen.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
