<!-- received="Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Fri, 12 Mar 1993 17:16:35 -0500 (EST)" -->
<!-- name="Harvey Brenneise" -->
<!-- email="brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Maxwell's letter" -->
<!-- id="9303122216.AA13678@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Mar_1993: Maxwell's letter</title>
<h1>Maxwell's letter</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 1993 17:16:35 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#131">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#131">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#131">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#131">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0132.html">Malachi Robertson: "Unclean meats and Gen. 9"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0130.html">Steven Timm: "Religion as Minority status"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm surprised that there hasn't been any reaction on the list yet to<br>
Maxwell's letter given the number of topics he covered.  I'll take a<br>
crack at a few of them.  In general, I believe in the legal concept of<br>
race ipsit loquiter (the thing speaks for itself).  I think it is safe<br>
to report that all seminary faculty do not share his views (although a<br>
former dean did his best to fill the seminary with this type of<br>
conservative, and they still have a hammer-lock on two of the seminary<br>
departments).  I wonder at the ethics of distributing another's<br>
correspondence without his permission (by paper or in machine-readable<br>
form).  Perhaps by the time it reached the net, it was considered to<br>
already be in the public domain (Mervyn tells me that Pilgrim's Rest<br>
published it).  Actually, he may rather enjoy the notoriety.  However, I<br>
think care should be taken to preserve privacy.  I too called Mervyn to<br>
verify its authenticity (although internal evidence did not suggest that<br>
it was not authentic), and he seemed somewhat surprised that it had been<br>
distributed on the net.<br>
<p>
While I disagree with him on many issues, and agree on a few, I think<br>
some larger issues are raised, most importantly the same question that<br>
currently faces the Republican Party (similarly being held hostage by<br>
conservatives):  How large is the tent?  Like Mervyn, many old time GOPers<br>
don't recognize the party of the 1992 convention.  Our Anabaptist<br>
friends in Northern Indiana and elsewhere ask the same question:  Where<br>
should the fences be?  At the excellent Menno-Hof visitor's center in<br>
Shipsewana, IN, there is a slide presentation with this very theme<br>
discussing beliefs and practices of Amish, Hutterite and Mennonite.  All<br>
three answer the question somewhat differently.  Apparently, Maxwell<br>
wants a small tent/close fences.  In fact, fellow travelers have found<br>
it so distasteful to meet and fellowship with the "liberal" academic<br>
religion scholars in the professional society Andrews Society of<br>
Religious Studies (for many years the SDA professional society in<br>
religion) that they formed their own Adventist Theological Society,<br>
underwritten generously by outside funding.  They have a separate<br>
meeting from ASRS, but often in a nearby location and at the same time.<br>
This last fall, ATS even declined to have a joint church service with<br>
ASRS in a Seventh-day Adventist church in San Francisco.  Little wonder<br>
that some fear schism.<br>
<p>
Maxwell's call appears to be a demand that the church give in to the<br>
conservatives because some of them have always believed that way and<br>
because they are loyal and tithe-paying.  I expect that many others who<br>
do not agree with them also fit these categories.  It is interesting<br>
that in the book "Issues," which the church published to explain its<br>
position about these ministries, the church made a strong plea for<br>
toleration.  I was surprised and pleased.  I do not believe the church<br>
has "defrocked" anyone except in the most extreme circumstances.  If<br>
anything, they have bent over backwards to be tolerant, especially<br>
toward the conservatives.  Maxwell would like to equate Spectrum with<br>
Our Firm Foundation.  As a regular contributor to Spectrum, I find his<br>
views extreme.  ATS and its allies would like to define their beliefs as<br>
being mainstream/orthodox, and define everyone else as unorthodox<br>
(certainly including those wicked people at Spectrum).  Maxwell has<br>
studied enough denominational history to know that the church has<br>
changed many of its positions over time (including the trinity,<br>
rejection of the shut door, etc.).  He is right that the church changed<br>
emphasis in the 1950's--away from perfectionism and toward a more<br>
orthodox view of salvation by grace.  It is debatable that this change<br>
was a bad one (attacks on "Questions on Doctrine" and charges of "new<br>
theology").  What ever happened to the concept of "Present Truth"?  Even<br>
though my aesthetic sensibilites are offended by Celebration-type<br>
worship I don't think a judgmental attitude (they're unconverted) is at<br>
all helpful.<br>
<p>
This whole current discussion (including the NAD response) raises the<br>
issue of the role of a free press in the SDA church.  I do think that<br>
it's important to have some sources of information that are not<br>
controlled by church entities (perhaps this list serves some of that<br>
purpose?).  However, it also raises the problems of divisiveness and<br>
spreading of incorrect information (which is not impossible in the<br>
"official" press).  In any case, we need to read critically.  Many in<br>
the church have difficulty doing this.  <br>
<p>
As president of a local club, I know some of the problems in running a<br>
voluntary organization.  It's simply not always possible to get<br>
consensus.  We have members who are mad that we have our orchid show at<br>
a nuclear plant.  One won't come to the show, another quit the club<br>
entirely.  You can't please everyone all the time.  It's best to<br>
emphasize what we have in common rather than our differences.  At least<br>
in the Anglo church in North America, we have a multi-polar situation.<br>
It isn't simply conservatives vs. liberals.  As I noted above, I<br>
strongly agree with Maxwell on some issues and just as strongly disagree<br>
on others.  Another person would agree or disagree on other issues.  <br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(Internet:  brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
