<title>Mar_1993: RE: Religion as Minority status</title>
<h1>RE: Religion as Minority status</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 93 19:13:05 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#141">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#141">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#141">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#141">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0142.html">Richard Mazzaferri: "Australlian elections on Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0140.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Australlian elections on Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;In fact, the position of freedom of religion in law  has been gradually</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;eroded by the Supreme court over the last couple of years.  But I was not</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;aware that we had the protection of Civil Rights law to start with.</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;The First Amendment rights of free exercise of religion are different from</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;the civil rights afforded to minority groups.</i><br>
<p>
As for civil rights protection, the civil rights laws of both the <br>
federal and state<br>
governments _do_ protect people from private acts of discrimination based<br>
upon their religious affiliation.  Section 2000a of Title 42, United <br>
States Code,<br>
prohibits discrimination in places of pubic accommodation, not only on the<br>
basis of "race, color, and national origin," but also on the basis of <br>
"religion."<br>
Section 2000e of the same title prohibits discrimination on the basis <br>
of religion<br>
as an unlawful employment practice.  The federal Fair Housing Act, in Section<br>
3602 of Title 42, United States Code, prohibits discrimination in the sale or<br>
rental of housing on the basis of religion, in addition to forbidding <br>
discrimination<br>
on the basis of race, color, sex, familial status, handicap, or <br>
national origin.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;Civil rights are not only to protect minorities.  Witness women, who</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;are a majority, still needing civil protection.  What these people</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;may be trying to suggest is "Churches are not victims of society."</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;For that I would say that civil rights should not be limited to victims.</i><br>
<p>
Actually they are arguing that many religious groups are claiming victimization<br>
by society (ie. civil rights requirements, equal employment opportunity <br>
programs,<br>
liability charges based on doctrines taught, and it's effect on social <br>
structure),<br>
thus sanctioning the legislation of religion as protection for <br>
religious groups.<br>
I for one on the one hand believe, to a degree, that *some* religious groups<br>
_are_ victimized by "society", and on the other hand, other groups <br>
distort their<br>
victimization in order to misinterpret the spirit of the  First Amendment.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;There were enough religious killings in the early history of USA,</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;and are still enough going on elsewhere (Bosnia) to justify protection</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;against what might happen.</i><br>
<p>
I don't like killings period, but most religious killings where done by <br>
self-appointed<br>
religion police groups (ie. witch hunters, the offended by husbands who <br>
wife-kiss<br>
in public, murderers of *negro* loving Quakers, etc...).  The same ones who,<br>
themselves, fled Europe's religious police.  My understanding (and it might be<br>
wrong) is that the spirit of the law  is for no religion being sanctioned<br>
(above another) by government.  My biggest worry is knowing that somehow,<br>
my church - which I've been "born", and continually "choose" to be my church,<br>
won't be immune to the increased skepticism.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
