Forwarded message:<br>
Rick Behrens writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;      I heard on the radio yesterday that there will be elections in</i><br>
<i>&gt; Australia this Saturday.  Not only that, but voting is manditory</i><br>
<i>&gt; ($20 fine if you don't vote).  What do you think about voting on</i><br>
<i>&gt; Sabbath?  Also, perhaps someone down under could tell us whether</i><br>
<i>&gt; or not there is ample opportunity to do your voting during non-Sabbath</i><br>
<i>&gt; hours?</i><br>
<p>
As long as I can remember, elections have been on Saturdays in<br>
Australia.  There is a fine, and it's about $50, if you don't vote.<br>
<p>
There is plenty of opportunity for pre-poll voting, whether postal<br>
or in person, and one of the reasons that you can give for requiring<br>
a pre-poll vote is that of religious beliefs.<br>
<p>
Most (?)  Adventists cast pre-poll votes.  There is a pre-poll voting <br>
station every election it the Memorial Church in Cooranbong (the town <br>
that has Avondale College and the Sanitarium Health Food factory complex.)  <br>
This caters for the large number of Adventists who do not wish to vote on<br>
Sabbath.  Sometimes, depending on the time of year, the sun sets before<br>
pollig closes and Adventists vote then.<br>
<p>
Personally, I don't have any problem with voting on Sabbath - I believe<br>
that it is part of my duty to at least my fellow man, if not God.  I<br>
like to vote beforehand if possible just to save the hassle of going <br>
through the process on Sabbath.  It is usually faster to pre-poll vote <br>
(fewer people around - it took me about 30 minutes this Sabbath.)<br>
<p>
    Mazz.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
