<title>Mar_1993: Sabbath elections in aus.</title>
<h1>Sabbath elections in aus.</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>14 Mar 1993 10:09:46 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#150">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#150">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#150">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#150">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0151.html">a11111arne@attmail.com: "Re: Fire in Frederick, Maryland"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0149.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Unclean meats and Genesis 9"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0152.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Sabbath elections in aus."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Well I voted on the Monday before the election. Yes, voting is mandatory<br>
(unfortunately), and elections are *always* on Saturday, but it is<br>
absolutely no problem to get a pre-poll vote. You can either walk into<br>
an electoral office and vote, or apply for a postal vote. There are <br>
various things which can make a person eligible for a pre-poll vote, and<br>
one of them is "religious beliefs".<br>
<p>
In fact, at Cooranbong, where there is a very high density of SDAs, a<br>
special pre-poll voting booth is set up for a week at one of the local<br>
churches every election time. <br>
<p>
Unfortunately none of these things help improve the quality of the<br>
political candidates.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
