<title>Mar_1993: Wedding rings</title>
<h1>Wedding rings</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>14 Mar 1993 10:19:19 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#153">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#153">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#153">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#153">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0154.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Advice for a culturally deprived SDA"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0152.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Sabbath elections in aus."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0155.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Wedding rings"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Even in the more conservative circles in Australia, I don't think the<br>
wearing of wedding rings has ever been an issue. For the woman, that is.<br>
Until recently, SDA ministers were not permitted to perform double ring<br>
ceremonies. This has always seemed a little strange to us here, since<br>
most of the grass roots membership didn't feel in themselves that there was<br>
any real difference between a woman and a man wearing a ring. Perhaps that<br>
stance was a carry-over from the U.S., where it seems that wedding rings<br>
have been and are controversial. Anyhow, double-ring ceremonies are now<br>
the norm inside and outside of the SDA church. I know of no trend outside<br>
the church away from wearing wedding rings, either.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
