<title>Mar_1993: Re: Advice for a culturally deprived SDA</title>
<h1>Re: Advice for a culturally deprived SDA</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Mar 1993 11:16:09 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#154">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#154">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#154">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#154">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0155.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Wedding rings"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0153.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Wedding rings"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0116.html">Steven Timm: "Advice for a culturally deprived SDA"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
wedding band goes on left ring finger (next to little finger).  Goes way<br>
back to the time when no one knew much about anatomy, it was thought that<br>
there was a "heart channel" that connected the ring finger to the heart.<br>
Two rings, one plain or small stone, one large stone.  (engagement ring<br>
and wedding band).  Generaly, depending on the amount of money the groom has<br>
, the engagement ring will have  a small stone, and the wedding band may<br>
or may not have a stone.  Adventist guidlines are an unadorned  (plain<br>
wedding band).  Generaly it is "permitted" to wear a wedding band  in <br>
conditions where the culture demands it, or in a situation where there<br>
might be some mistake about ones marital status.  An example is a young<br>
married women in a secular college.  Most men automatically conclude that<br>
any woman not wearing a wedding or engagement band, is available.  It helps<br>
fend off unwanted advances.  There are other symbols in other conditions<br>
and cultures that serve the same purpose.  Rings on other fingers have no<br>
particular meaning, other than ornamentation or carrying wealth. (rings<br>
were originally conceived as a conveinient way to carry wealth without<br>
a major risk of losing it.).  When I got married, (to a nice adventist<br>
gal) neither one of use wanted a ring.  I would wear one, but my wife would<br>
not.  So, I wanted to get her a stone instead.  Just a plain un-mounted<br>
stone.  I *REALLY* wanted an alexanderite (fantastic, wonderful stone), but<br>
when I discovered that carrat for carrat it was nearly 2 times as expensive<br>
as diamond, I backed off.  Instead, she said that she wanted a cedar chest.<br>
I wound up buying an antique cedar wardrobe (which is much used and treasured)<br>
and a 1/2 Krugerand gold coin.  Turns out that she has felt guilty about<br>
owning the coin for years.  Something with EGW having said that we should not<br>
have silver and gold, but should sell them.  We still have the coin, but<br>
one day we probably will sell it.  It stays in a ring box, in a secure place.<br>
<p>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
<p>
woody@knapper.cactus.org
woody@chinacat.unicom.com (temporary) is forwareded to woody@knapper
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
