<title>Mar_1993: Re:  Wedding rings</title>
<h1>Re:  Wedding rings</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 14 Mar 1993 13:07:57 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#155">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#155">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#155">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#155">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0156.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Unclean meats and Genesis 9"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0154.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Advice for a culturally deprived SDA"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0153.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Wedding rings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0173.html">Woody Baker: "Re:  Wedding rings"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
When I spoke of the world "moving away from the wedding ring code just<br>
as the SDA church is embracing it", I refered to the trend that many<br>
women who are not married are now wearing wedding rings or similar-looking<br>
rings to make you think they are.  I certainly have not seen the abandonment<br>
of the ring anywhere.  And there are some women who wear so many rings<br>
you can't tell what they are all for.<br>
<p>
As long as we're on the subject, time was that male earrings, either one or<br>
both, conveyed a significant message.  But it seems that this code in the <br>
"world" may be breaking down as well.  Are male earrings supposed to mean<br>
anything anymore?  Will this be the next "non-ornamental piece of metal"<br>
we recognize now that the wedding ring has joined the broach, the stick-pin,<br>
the tie-tack, the cuff-link, and the gold watch as acceptable?  Has this<br>
trend reached the major salt shakers of Adventism as yet?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
