<title>Mar_1993: Re: Unclean meats and Genesis 9</title>
<h1>Re: Unclean meats and Genesis 9</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>14 Mar 1993 10:30:25 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#156">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#156">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#156">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#156">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0157.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Re Australian Elections"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0155.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Wedding rings"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0117.html">Steven Timm: "Unclean meats and Genesis 9"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Perhaps the clue to this is in Genesis 7:2,3. God speaking to Noah...<br>
"Take with you seven of every kind of clean animal, a male and its mate,<br>
and two of every kind of unclean animal, a male and its mate, ..."<br>
<p>
If this really is what God said to Noah, then clearly there was a distinction<br>
even then between different kinds of animal. Some were considered clean, and<br>
others unclean. Maybe it was unecessary for God to say,"Now, Noah, only eat<br>
the clean animals". Or maybe it just wasn't necessary for that to be <br>
recorded in the scripture.<br>
<p>
I don't know about you, but when I read Genesis the single biggest thing that<br>
strikes me is how much is not said. Particular as an SDA who has grown up<br>
with EGWs supplementation of the stories, and with Uncle Arthur's books, I<br>
am always surprised how little is actually there in the text. It is unlikely<br>
that a "watertight" case (pardon the pun) could be given regarding the diet<br>
given to Noah after the flood.<br>
<p>
Besides, surely something doesn't have to be "doctrine" for it to be good<br>
sense. Does it really matter whether the clean vs unclean is just a part<br>
of the ceremonial law, or something more? It seems to me that noone besides<br>
SDAs would be interested in the distinction anyway, since SDAs are part of<br>
a minority in the way they treat OT law. <br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
