<title>Mar_1993: Re Australian Elections</title>
<h1>Re Australian Elections</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@hunter.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 14 Mar 1993 11:41:34 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#157">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#157">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#157">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#157">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0158.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "SDAs and the military"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0156.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Unclean meats and Genesis 9"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To SDAnet<br>
<p>
The Australian Elections are held on Saturday (Sabbath) and it is<br>
compulsory to vote. There is ample opportunity for both postal <br>
voting and access to pre-election day polling booths. Near<br>
Avondale College polling booths are available for about 3 days<br>
prior to the election day. The same is true near the Sydney<br>
Adventist Hospital. Postal voting is available for approx<br>
three weeks before the poll.<br>
<p>
This has been available at least as long as I have lived in<br>
Australia (30 years) and I think that it is similar in New Zealand.<br>
<p>
I think that most SDAs are happy with the situation. I know that some<br>
folk refuse to vote, and this is accomplished by casting an invalid<br>
paper. Mind you it is easy to do an invalid paper for the senate<br>
where there is sometimes over 100 names, each of which has to be<br>
numbered if you are not voting for one of the major parties.<br>
<p>
Incidently, the Labor Party won another term yesterday.<br>
<p>
Regards<br>
Maurice Ashton<br>
Computer Science Lecturer<br>
Avondale College<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
