<title>Mar_1993: Re:  Pacifism and the church</title>
<h1>Re:  Pacifism and the church</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Mar 93 19:34:12 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#164">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#164">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#164">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#164">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0165.html">Paul Gates: "Switch back to Compuserve"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0163.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Spanish translator needed"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0125.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Pacifism and the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0289.html">DOWE001%TSU.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Re: Pacifism and the church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Terry L Anderson writes:<br>
<i>&gt;The non-combatant option is nearly unique to the US.  Elsewhere, the</i><br>
<i>&gt;variation runs from cases in which nearly every Adventist serves </i><br>
<i>&gt;as combatants to countries where the Church insists on conscientious</i><br>
<i>&gt;objection and nearly every Adventist (at least male) serves time in</i><br>
<i>&gt;prison for it.  Sometimes the position changes very quickly such as in</i><br>
<i>&gt;Korea, where until recently many SDAs served time in prison for</i><br>
<i>&gt;refusing to serve and then, in a very abrupt reversal, we now provide</i><br>
<i>&gt;military training with weapons on the campus of our college (we would</i><br>
<i>&gt;have lost government approval of the college if we refused to provide</i><br>
<i>&gt;training).</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;It seems that our position has often had less to do with any</i><br>
<i>&gt;principles and more to do with public acceptance/image and the</i><br>
<i>&gt;advantages vs disadvantages of government cooperation.  As the church</i><br>
<i>&gt;(in many countries) has become more mainstream, there has developed a</i><br>
<i>&gt;pressure to perserve (or create) a positive image and acceptance by</i><br>
<i>&gt;the public.  Where cooperation with the government has brought better</i><br>
<i>&gt;acceptance and sometimes other accommodations and where there has not</i><br>
<i>&gt;been a firm position based on universally accepted principles we seem</i><br>
<i>&gt;to have moved toward cooperation (on this as well as other issues).  </i><br>
<p>
This raises the question of how far to go in making compromises with<br>
governments or communities in order to stay legal or to have their favour.<br>
It is understandable to want to avoid trouble with the authorities --<br>
it is harder to run a church when you have to go underground: no premises,<br>
no official business, and everything has to be done covertly, like some<br>
cults do it, not to mention that it is harder to get converts or do<br>
evangelism. I bet when the really serious persecuition starts, a lot of<br>
Adventists will leave the church.<br>
	Still, how far should we go in compromising our principles or<br>
standards?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Since I do not look to my church to determine my position for me, such</i><br>
<i>&gt;changes don't bother me deeply, but I feel badly for others who have</i><br>
<i>&gt;felt compelled to pay a high personal price (prison, ...) for</i><br>
<i>&gt;maintaining the church's position and then have that abruptly change.</i><br>
<p>
Well, i feel quite bad for the Koreans who do not believe it right to<br>
serve as combattents and then find that the church organisation is not<br>
backing them up. It must be like trying to be a Sabbath keeper in a<br>
Sunday church. When i was facing difficulties in the army, i called up<br>
the pastor and he spoke to my officer to try to explain our stand and to<br>
tell him that i was not in fact a fanatic freak. I also got a lot of<br>
prayer support and moral encouragement from fellow church members. All<br>
that helped me a lot and kept me from freaking out under the stress.<br>
I wonder how it would be like if the church had not had the same stand<br>
as me. I would have felt a lot worse i'm sure.<br>
	Perhaps thats how the reformed SDA church split happened in Germany.<br>
<p>
-- Just some thoughts on the matter.<br>
<p>
- beng.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
