<title>Mar_1993: Switch back to Compuserve</title>
<h1>Switch back to Compuserve</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>14 Mar 93 23:30:10 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#165">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#165">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#165">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#165">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0166.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Donahue"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0164.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Pacifism and the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Thanks Steve for the switch back. Sorry for all the confusion. I did pick <br>
up most of the messages from AOL last evening. That is ok of course on the <br>
back messages.<br>
<p>
Wanted to share a couple of things with the net from messages that I have <br>
gleaned the last week or so.<br>
<p>
Wedding rings: I am not sure exactly about the tradition of wearing wedding <br>
rings on left hand.  I do know that the tradition is that there is a <br>
"nerve" ( I believe that is correct) that runs from that finger to the <br>
heart! I am not sure if it is still the "vogue" but it used to be if a <br>
woman was divorced and single she would wear her wedding rings on her right <br>
hand.<br>
<p>
Law: (Romans 6:14) Sometimes I think that we "nit-pick" on these "law" <br>
texts. Most of the time we can get at the context quite easily. In my <br>
reading of Romans 6 I have the idea that Paul was talking about the method <br>
of salvation. Keeping the law was not a method of salvation. The law does <br>
not save us or can it forgive sin. In my greek text the article "the" is <br>
not there. It's immaterial to try to figure out if Paul was talking about <br>
the moral law, ceremonial law, civil law, health laws. Paul is not <br>
referring to any law in particular but to law as a principle. We are under <br>
grace as a method of salvation.<br>
<p>
<p>
society seminary training is very necessary. Those ministers that slip <br>
through into the ministry without the seminary training are at a <br>
disadvantage. Sometimes they themselves cause their own problem. By this I <br>
mean that I have known of some  pastors without seminary training who never <br>
feel equal with pastors that have the sem. training. They feel insecure and <br>
are alway trying to measure up to the other ministers. I have know of at <br>
least one in Michigan that became a work-a-holic because he never felt he <br>
was doing enough and wanted to do everything by himself -- never could <br>
delegate anything -- He became sick mentally and physically serveral times <br>
in his ministry till he retired.<br>
<p>
Pacifists: I scanned over the messages on this subject. I hope that we are <br>
making a distinction between the  classifications of 1AO and 1O. Before I <br>
went into the service during the Korean war I had to "fight" to get my 1AO <br>
classification.  I was living in Miami, Fla at the time and in my draft <br>
board section there were a lot of Jehovah Witnesses that claimed to be <br>
ministers and thus were trying to get exempt from serving at all. I had to <br>
appear before the draft board in Miami and explain to the committee that as <br>
an SDA I was not objecting to serving in the service of my country but <br>
would like to serve in the Medics and save life rather than take it. I <br>
received the 1AO classification without any problem. I indicated to the <br>
committee that Adventists were Conscientious Cooperators really. We just <br>
would prefer not to carry arms.<br>
<p>
I received orders after my basic training at Ft. Meade, MD to serve as a <br>
typesetter ( civilian profession) on the Stars and Stripes newspaper in <br>
Tokyo, Japan. However, when I got to Japan there was such a need for medics <br>
and since I had that training my orders were changed and I landed up in <br>
Korea. I was attached to the 7th Division and in particular to a rifle <br>
company. I saw a lot of action and was awarded the Combat Medical Badge, <br>
Korean Service Medal with one Bronze Star, and the United Nations Service <br>
Medal. Our division was under the command of Gen. Douglas McArthur and <br>
fought our way up to the Yalu river just short of going into China at which <br>
time President Truman fired Gen. McArthur and we had to pull back to the <br>
38th Parallel. When I returned home I served in the reserves for 8 years. <br>
Just prior to the Desert Storm war I applied to get back into the service <br>
as a Chaplain but my request was denied because of my age. I considered <br>
myself a normal 7th-day Adventist and certainly would object very much to <br>
being classifed as a Pacifist!!<br>
<p>
It was a great honor to serve my country. While in Korea I advanced from a <br>
litter bearer to Chief Medical Aidman in my company. I had several 7th-day <br>
Adventists under my command. Some of them trained without weapons like I <br>
did while others trained with weapons. I always felt that it was their <br>
decision and respected them for it. To me to work as a medic in the field <br>
-- carrying a weapon was a nusiance when you were trying to patch up the <br>
wounded. It was a nusiance when you were trying to carry wounded back to <br>
the Aid station. A 45 cal. pistol was handier because you could carry that <br>
on your gun belt. However the range of a 45 was not that great!! I carried <br>
no weapons though.<br>
<p>
Any comments anybody concerning the above comments?<br>
<p>
.................Paul<br>
<p>
CompuServe: 70516.420<br>
Internet: Hamradi440@aol.com<br>
724 Mecklenburg Ave. <br>
Easton, MD 21601 (410)-820-8186<br>
<p>
THOUGHT FOR THIS WEEK: "A spirit of love and earnest prayer will not solve <br>
all problems,  not erase all differences, but it will favorably affect the <br>
outcome of any situation."<br>
