<title>Mar_1993: Re: Reformers and the Antichrist</title>
<h1>Re: Reformers and the Antichrist</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Mar 1993 23:23:10 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#169">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#169">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#169">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#169">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0170.html">Sue Oemcke: "Re  Australlian elections on Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0168.html">Russell Grau: "Re: Relevance of Prophecy"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0115.html">Steven Timm: "Reformers and the Antichrist"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0185.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Reformers and the Antichrist"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; In the ongoing discussions on the CHRISTIA list, Ruben Gonzalez</i><br>
<i>&gt; (who has been a big help on our side) has brought up the point that</i><br>
<i>&gt; what SDA's say about the Catholic church is no different than what</i><br>
<i>&gt; the various reformers have said, and brought out a various list</i><br>
<i>&gt; of reformers who referred to the pope as Antichrist, including Luther,</i><br>
<i>&gt; Wesley, and others.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; I have heard this many times, but don't know where to find the reference</i><br>
<i>&gt; on such.  Can anyone help?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
See Froom's "Movement of Destiny" for an exaustive account<br>
<p>
I think you may also find some stuff in (the sometimes, but not always useful <br>
book) Questions on Doctrine, and I'm not sure if Mervin Maxwell also mentions<br>
as few in His books "Daniel" and "Revelation".<br>
<p>
Also please help out on the CHRISTIA list, I've spent too much time<br>
on there all ready and need to get some work done of my own.<br>
<p>
[I would say that the discussion has died down on the CHRISTIA list<br>
and we probably don't need to stir it up again.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<p>
For those of you who are unaware of what *YOU* are all being accused of here<br>
is a little sample. [these are excepts from may, very long anti-SDA postings]<br>
<p>
(Just to stir some of you up)<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<p>
--------------<br>
This has been a very light touch on the Seventh-day Adventist church.  I<br>
hope it has answered some questions and has helped you see the kind of<br>
group the Branch Dividians came from.  The Dividians are extreme, but they<br>
came from a church of extremes, and come by their strangeness honestly.  If<br>
you know a Seventh-day Adventist, pray they will be set free from their<br>
bondage of legalism and health reform strictures.<br>
<p>
The entire Seventh-day Adventist church is founded on legalism and<br>
legalistic aspects.  If you take that away, and remove their errant beliefs<br>
regarding the final judgment and 1844, there is no reason whatever for that<br>
church to exist.<br>
 <br>
It is true that other churches do spawn cults like the Dividians, but you<br>
generally find the rabid cults coming from the rabid and cultish churches,<br>
not the mainline Protestant nor the Roman Catholic churches.  (Remember,<br>
this is a general statement, not meant to be completely accurate.)<br>
 <br>
Now, the real legalism of the Seventh-day Adventists comes through.  They<br>
teach that keeping of the Sabbath will not effect salvation.  They also<br>
teach that the saved person will keep the law, hence, they will keep the<br>
Sabbath.  A bit of reverse logic will show us that they also teach that if<br>
you don't keep the Sabbath, it is a sign that you are not saved, or are<br>
ignorant.  They don't often state that negative, but I have heard it from<br>
at least five Adventist pulpits, and it is said in so many words in many of<br>
the writings of their so-called prophet, Ellen White.<br>
<p>
First of all, there is no link between a high fat diet and cardiovascular<br>
disease.  A brand new Harvard Medical School study of 90,000  nurses showed<br>
that dietary fat intake and heart disease were unrelated.<br>
 <br>
The SDA church insists that the Roman Catholic church changed the day of<br>
worship from Saturday to Sunday, this is pure bunk.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
If you say that Christ is keeping the OT law in the believer, then it is<br>
still legalism, a terribly insidious form of legalism, and just as wrong as<br>
overt legalizm.<br>
 <br>
White declared that many things were sins, and here is a partial list:<br>
  - Dancing,<br>
  - Theatre,<br>
  - Card playing,<br>
  - Tabacco,<br>
  - Alcohol, all forms,<br>
  - Coffee, tea, Leviticus 11 unclean meats,<br>
  - Immodest clothing, (never clearly defined),<br>
  - Excessive marital relations, (never devined at all),<br>
  - Sattath breaking,<br>
  - forgetting things, (yup, you read right),<br>
  - Being sick,<br>
  - Having doubts,<br>
<p>
Their health programs stil revolve on the writings of White.  Many of those<br>
writings were copied from health reformers of the mid ninteenth century.<br>
Many of them are just plain wrong, but the SDA church holds to them with<br>
great tenacity.<br>
<p>
 They believe the Old<br>
Testament law is still in force and is binding on Christians. <br>
<p>
Adventist theologians will say loudly they believe in salvation by grace<br>
alone, but when the rubber meets the road, their prophet insists that the<br>
Sabbath must be kept, or the indivisual is lost.  The theologians try to<br>
get around this, but the church leadership will not let them, so they are<br>
hamstrung by ellen White's 100,000 pages of false prophecy.<br>
 <br>
Why do I say they are a dangerous cult?  Because they claim to have the<br>
gospel and don't even know what the gospel is.  They believe they are in<br>
the last days of Earth's history and insist that salvation is by grace, but<br>
insist on works to prove that grace. <br>
<p>
In 1888, a couple of men barnstormed the church with the doctrine of<br>
"Righteousness by Faith."  This issue is still a diving teaching in the<br>
church today.  What these men, mainly Waggoner and Jones, taught was a<br>
confusion of Protestand and Catholic theology, foreign to both, and<br>
friendly to none.<br>
<p>
The thing that is most noticable about SEventh-day Adventist doctrine is<br>
their legalism.  They are fanatic about keeping the Sabbath.  While many<br>
will eat out on Sabbath, many won'e ewven cook food, rather preparing it<br>
the day before, as their prophetess, Ellen White, instructed.<br>
 <br>
The SDA church has a very strong subculture, much like the Latter Day<br>
Saints and the Jehovah's Wittnesses. <br>
<p>
This division of the moral from the ceremonial law is one of the basic<br>
errors of the Seventh-day Adventist doctrinal structure.  That posting was<br>
very good, lots of texts, but it proves nothing.  I once wrote up a chart<br>
such as that, and even had more texts, but it was wrong, dead wrong.<br>
 <br>
Again, as in the health reform issue, the keeping of a Sabbath day holy is<br>
for control, not worship.  The church thinks it is for worship, but it is<br>
not.  It is easy to build a subculture around such stringent doctine.  it<br>
is easy to identify the "insiders" of the group by their behavior, this is<br>
at the base of the keeping of the "Moral" law by the Seventh-day<br>
Adventists.<br>
 <br>
How can you say the Seventh-day Adventist body of doctrine is not<br>
legalistic when the very name of the church embodyes the keeping of the<br>
fourth commandment?<br>
 <br>
The main body of the SDA church is legalistic.  They will not work on<br>
Sabbath, they generally will not go to the movies, nor drink any alcohol,<br>
nor drink coffee, nor smoke.  If asked, they will say these things are<br>
sins.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
