<title>Mar_1993: Unclean Meats</title>
<h1>Unclean Meats</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Mar 1993 17:18:16 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#171">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#171">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#171">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#171">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0172.html">Steven Timm: "Donahue &amp; Waco Stuff"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0170.html">Sue Oemcke: "Re  Australlian elections on Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This is in response to Ian Brown's question about work being done here<br>
at Andrews on unclean meats.  One of the doctoral students informs me<br>
that Jiri Moskala, a doctoral student from the Czech Republic, is<br>
working on Lev. 11 under Gerhard Hasel's direction.  However, this<br>
student is currently in the Czech Republic.<br>
<p>
The reference to the journal article is as follows, "The Distinction<br>
Between Clean and Unclean Animals in Lev 11:  Is It Still Relevant,"<br>
_Journal of the Adventist Theological Society_ (Autumn 1991, vol. 2,<br>
number 2, pp. 91-125).  That's more theology than I intend to read this<br>
afternoon!  It does not appear to refer to Gen. 9.  The conclusion<br>
follows:<br>
<p>
"The results of our study indicate the following: (1) The dietary law of<br>
Leviticus 11:2-23, 41-45 (Deut. 14:3-20) is part of the universal law<br>
provided in the Old Testament which is independent of the<br>
ceremonial/ritual law.  (2) Its placement in Leviticus 11 is due to<br>
"catchwords" and alrger literary and compositional patterns and thematic<br>
concerns within its immediate and larger pentateuchal contexts.  (3) Its<br>
linkages with the creation account and the flood narrative within the<br>
context of the universalism of Genesis 1-11 is assured in terminological<br>
and thematic grounds.  (4) The special language of "clean/unclean,"<br>
"detestable," and "abomination" and their relationships join it to<br>
universally valid divine law.  (5) The contextually explicit rationale<br>
of "holiness" and "redemption" joins the dietary law to the "holy<br>
nation" theme upheld in the New Testament for all true believers who are<br>
the spiritual "holy nation" that is separated unto God to be "holy . . .<br>
in all your conduct" (1 Pet. 1:15).  Holiness manifests itself in holy<br>
conduct.  It reveals itself among many things in a continuous<br>
distinction of what God has designated to be proper for human<br>
consumption.  In consuming foold appropriate for God's "holy" people,<br>
the church constantly manifests its Lord in an ongoing _imitatio dei_.<br>
In the Bible God is the ground for ethics, and God's true people live a<br>
life of godliness, a life of holiness, because they are a "holy people"<br>
(Exod. 19:6; 1 Pet. 2:9).<br>
<p>
I should let the thing speak for itself.  However, let me add several<br>
facts, which may or may not be relevant.  Hasel's major theme in his<br>
study is the "remnant."  He is the former dean of the seminary, who was<br>
removed by the board at the request of the president.  I cannot remember<br>
any public reasons being given for this, although it was widely believed<br>
that his actions promoting a "conservative agenda" played a major role<br>
in this.  He has been very active in the Adventist Theological Society,<br>
and this is from their journal.  As I pointed out in a previous post,<br>
this organization split from the general organization of SDA religious<br>
academics.  Membership is only by invitation and after swearing fealty<br>
to a rigid set of beliefs.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
