<title>Mar_1993: Donahue &amp; Waco Stuff</title>
<h1>Donahue &amp; Waco Stuff</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 15 Mar 1993 23:29:04 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#172">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#172">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#172">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#172">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0173.html">Woody Baker: "Re:  Wedding rings"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0171.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Unclean Meats"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnetters,<br>
<p>
I wrote--<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I was saddened by the former member of our SDA church.  He attended LLU</i><br>
as a religion major hoping to become a minister.  However, because he is<br>
blind, the hierarchy (at LLU?) told him that he would NOT be an<br>
effective minister, so he left the church.<br>
<p>
Marcus Responded--<br>
<i>&gt;&gt; I didn't see the show, but unlike Michael, I'm not saddened _by_ the</i><br>
former member of the church, I'm saddened _FOR_ him.  Right now, I feel<br>
empathy for him, his anger and pain, which he might have felt when<br>
treated so *UN*Christlike, by a church which prides itself for its<br>
doctrines and "the truth".  Just shows that we must turn our eyes from<br>
the church and set them on Jesus ALONE.<br>
<p>
My rebuttal--<br>
I'm sorry that I didn't correctly read through my editing, but as they<br>
say, Haste Makes Waste.  What I meant when I said that I was saddened,<br>
was that I was saddened by the fact that we have such hypocritical people in<br>
the church which I was born into and have known all my life to be the<br>
only church that I should believe!  (Now I wonder if I should believe in<br>
a church where there are hypocrites galore!) I have always known that<br>
there will<br>
be hypocrites in every church, but I never really knew that they would be<br>
so high UP (in the administration of the church)!  When I heard that<br>
those people around him said that he would not make a good preacher, it<br>
turned my stomach!  Sure, he may be blind, but he felt that GOD called<br>
him, and that the Holy Spirit was leading him, and that he did not get<br>
his calling from some two-bit fortune cookie or secret decoder ring from a<br>
Cracker-Jack box.  And then to be turned down, by people you believe are<br>
not supposed to be biased, that just made me burn up with anger! <br>
I feel that a person who is "called" to preach, should be allowed<br>
to do so, regardless of age, sex, or even physical "advantages"!  This<br>
just shows how much our church needs to learn before we can even<br>
consider calling ourselves the "remnant" of God's chosen people.  There<br>
are TOO many people who will not practice what they preach in our church<br>
and I for one am tired of hearing one thing from the Pulpit and beyond<br>
(the administration), yet seeing something totally different going on.<br>
Obviously, these people in our church need to evaluate what in the world<br>
they believe and why.  They need to quit talking about Jesus and act<br>
more like Him.<br>
<p>
Now that I have gotten off my soap box, I hope that I have made myself<br>
clear.<br>
<p>
Wishing You all the Best in Life,<br>
Michael B. Merginio<br>
merginim@andrews.edu<br>
<p>
James White Library, Berrien Springs, MI 49104-1300, (616) 471-6344<br>
=====================================================================<br>
I believe that in our world, this is one rule that everyone<br>
	should follow, and that is - TELL IT LIKE IT IS!!!!!<br>
	The truth may hurt, but lies, or withholding the truth <br>
	makes it hurt even more.    --M.B. Merginio <br>
=====================================================================<br>
