<title>Mar_1993: How to answer a CB</title>
<h1>How to answer a CB</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>15 Mar 1993 12:00:26 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#174">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#174">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#174">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#174">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0175.html">Steven Timm: "SDA-L: Welcome, new members"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0173.html">Woody Baker: "Re:  Wedding rings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Just a thought I had recently...<br>
<p>
We have lots of literature on "how to answer a JW" and "how to answer a<br>
mormon", discussing the differences in interpretation between SDAs and these<br>
other groups. Personally, I would benefit from a similar publication<br>
entitled "How to answer a CB". (Just in case CB is a purely Australian term,<br>
it means Concerned Brethren, and has come to stand for the hard-line<br>
conservative SDAs in the church here.)<br>
<p>
If, as Maxwell said in his letter, there are a large number of "new<br>
theology" adherents employed in the church administration and its<br>
educational institutions, then perhaps some of them could get together<br>
and produce a publication aimed specifically at the differences between<br>
their interpretation and that of the "old theology". I personally would<br>
not be at all concerned if the references to Great Controversy etc were<br>
few and far between, but all points would need to have strong scriptural<br>
support.<br>
<p>
Of course, the first step would be to clear up whether or not there is<br>
indeed a "new theology" at all. Maxwell says there is, and I am inclined<br>
to agree. But some are reluctant to discuss the issue. Bill Shea visited<br>
Australia last year, and I attended a meeting where he spoke on "Schism<br>
in the Adventist church". I was a little surprised when he didn't refer<br>
at all to the current "crisis" during his address. I was even more <br>
surprised when he ducked a direct question from the floor, to the effect<br>
of "There are currently two distinctly separate theological groups within<br>
the SDA church. Do you consider that this could result in some kind of<br>
schism?" Shea's reply was that there are far more than just two groups, <br>
and many of the groups can't agree, but that he didn't think it was any<br>
big deal. What he said was true, but in my opinion it showed a reluctance<br>
to face up to the situation.<br>
<p>
I am a believer in the concept of present truth, and I believe that there<br>
is always room for growth and development. Although I have never heard<br>
anybody define what the "new theology" is, from what I can gather I think<br>
it describes my understanding of God. But I do need some help when it<br>
comes to "answering the CBs"! <br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
