<title>Mar_1993: How to answer a CB</title>
<h1>How to answer a CB</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Mar 1993 22:13:46 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#188">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#188">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#188">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#188">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0189.html">Steven Timm: ""A Physicist can do anything""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0187.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: How to answer a CB"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0187.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: How to answer a CB"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am not surprised that Bill Shea thought that there is no danger of imminent<br>
schism in the SDA church.  He has expressed the same sentiments to me in <br>
small group conversation.  I understood him to say that the various groups,<br>
the right-wing ones specifically, are parasitic on the main church, and if <br>
they were to destroy their host, they could not survive.  <br>
<p>
The essential problem that has to be conquered in dealing with these people<br>
is one of communication.  We must first of all realize that the discourses<br>
in such magazines as Our Firm Foundation were at one point the major form<br>
of communication that existed in the church, and the alligator-skinned<br>
SDA's of that era were used to it.  Alden Thompson in his book "Inspiration"<br>
shows how various SDA literature of the 20's and 30's promoted the concept<br>
of verbal inspiration of the Bible and Ellen G. White, in direct<br>
contradiction to what EGW said.  The fundamentalist tendency in Adventism<br>
arose in parallel to the rise of fundamentalism in America.  To many people<br>
verbal inspiration is still the way to treat the inspired writings, and <br>
most critics of EGW are those who, having exploded the verbal inspiration <br>
myth, conclude that there is no inspiration there at all.<br>
<p>
So, on one side we have the DADs (Do As Demanded) who apply the doctrine <br>
of creeping inspiration:  Mr. X. says you should believe such a way,<br>
and Ellen G. White said he was right, and since I agree with Mr. X,<br>
therefore my will is the word of the Lord and you are going to burn a<br>
few minutes longer in hell.  <br>
<p>
On the other side we have the MOMs  (Mirror Of Me) who also refer to<br>
inspiration in an absolute sense, but reject and fight it in such a way<br>
as to exclude any other interpretation.  "Ellen G. White ate meat once<br>
so she didn't practice what she preached and I can do what I want."<br>
<p>
There is little common terminology between the two groups.  The recent<br>
flashpoint issue (since 1957) has been the nature of Christ.  One group <br>
argues that Christ had a sinful nature, the other that He did not.<br>
 Neither side knows what they mean by the term "nature", nor does either<br>
side mean the same thing by it.  the "CB's" find it incomprehensible <br>
that Christ could be in any way different from the humans of His day<br>
"This would give Him an unfair advantage."  Their opponents think<br>
that for Christ to have a "sinful nature" would be impossible because<br>
"then He would have had to sin."  They never stop to think that both <br>
positions could be wrong, and that by extension, any blending of the <br>
two answers is also wrong.   <br>
<p>
So I think that the first key is to show respect, if not concurrence,<br>
with whatever view of authority the person may have.  The second key<br>
is to make sure that your terms are defined similarly.  The third<br>
is to not get so tied into binary logic to ignore other possible solutions.<br>
<p>
"Faith and love" can be turned into legalism if one is not careful.<br>
I will always remember a gentleman in a church I went to who emphasized<br>
with a scowl "The only important thing is to show the love of Jesus Christ."<br>
This is the same person who told me "if the visiting young people are<br>
going to take the seats of the old ladies who have had them for years,<br>
then they <br>
shouldn't come at all."  It is, however, a measure of my conservative<br>
communication credentials that he was telling me all this thinking I might<br>
be a sympathetic ear, not realizing that I had organized the youth rally<br>
that had so ticked him off.  Having been through 22 years of Michigan<br>
Adventism,<br>
I can always speak the conservative language even in the modern age when <br>
God isn't a Republican anymore.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
  <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
