<title>Mar_1993: "A Physicist can do anything"</title>
<h1>"A Physicist can do anything"</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 16 Mar 1993 23:23:18 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#189">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#189">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#189">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#189">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0190.html">Cam Litvin: "Re: Are you trustworthy?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0188.html">Steven Timm: "How to answer a CB"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0197.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: "A Physicist can do anything""</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm associated daily with Fermilab.  Fermilab's organizational chart is <br>
different from a typical organizational chart in that prestige and <br>
power is derived not so much from what you say or the office you hold,<br>
but the type of physics you do.  Fermilab's goal is to do high-energy<br>
physics.  Most of the top-level people they hire are physicists because<br>
they are needed and because it's easier to justify budget for physicists<br>
than some other kinds of employees.<br>
<p>
This leaves us with a laboratory where physicists are in charge of<br>
everything.  A physicist in charge of directing the digging of water<br>
and sewer lines.  A physicist  (many, in fact) in charge of computing.<br>
A physicist as assistant director for finance.  Another physicst as<br>
assistant director for construction.  You get the idea--if the job can<br>
be performed<br>
by a physicist, it is performed by a physicist, and sometimes even when <br>
this job assignment is not optimal, for instance, assigning a physicist like<br>
myself to do electronics debugging.<br>
<p>
I think the point is clear, and the analogy to the SDA church and<br>
the job placement of pastors is a one-to-one mapping.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
