<title>Mar_1993: The Nature of Christ (Was How to answer a CB)</title>
<h1>The Nature of Christ (Was How to answer a CB)</h1>
<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 17 Mar 93 13:00:38 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#192">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#192">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#192">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#192">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0193.html">Rob Barnhurst: "Bio"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0191.html">Floyd Poenitz: "Re: SDA-L: Welcome, new members"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Religions of Christendom have erred on both sides of the question<br>
of the nature of Christ.<br>
<p>
 1) Those, such as the JW and Mormons who see less than full<br>
    divinity in Christ.  Some, for example, finding Jesus to<br>
    be the created or birthed brother of Lucifer.<br>
<p>
 2) Those, such as the Catholics, who in various different ways<br>
    have their various versions of the immaculate conception.<br>
    The Catholics claim this through His "perfect" mother Mary.<br>
    The Protestants claiming, without scripture, that Jesus<br>
    was born with a nature that was better off than Adam before<br>
    he fell.<br>
<p>
1) Uriah Smith is said to have subscribed to some of the first type<br>
   of error.  So, there were and probably are SDAs who err on that side.<br>
<p>
2) Much more common are the SDAs who claim the preAdam position.<br>
<p>
1) There are lots of folks out there who are quick to insist that<br>
   any church that falls short on the divinity of Jesus is a Cult.<br>
<p>
2) But many of these same people insist that it was utterly impossible<br>
   for Jesus to have failed in His mission, that is to have sinned.<br>
   Is this not "denying the power", is this not denying that Jesus<br>
   was tempted in ALL points?<br>
<p>
What about the texts that say that those who deny that Jesus came<br>
in the flesh are Antichrist?  It seems incredible to me that John,<br>
when he penned those texts, would have endorsed the preAdam position.<br>
I find it incredible that John could have seen Jesus as having<br>
benefited by advantages greater than Adam's and yet said that<br>
those who deny that Jesus came in the flesh are Antichrist.<br>
<p>
1) So, on one hand, churches that fall short on the divinity of Christ<br>
   are considered Cults.<br>
<p>
2) But 1 John and 2 John make clear that those who deny the humanity<br>
   of Jesus are Antichrist.  That sounds worse than Cult to me.<br>
<p>
In our church's eagerness to escape the "cult" stigma, have we rushed<br>
over to the other side?  Yes!  Has that improved our doctrine? NO!<br>
<p>
Perhaps one of the problems is our definition of sin.  Prebe, of<br>
Amazing Facts, clarifies the issue.  The source of the issue comes<br>
from Catholic doctrine that defines temptation to be sin even before<br>
a baby is old enough to understand what a temptation is.  By this<br>
definition, the only possible way by which Jesus could be sinless<br>
was for Jesus to be born of an immaculate (sinless) Mary.  But if<br>
sin only comes when a person understands right and wrong and is<br>
tempted and then yields to the temptation, then Jesus need not, by<br>
definition, have been birthed by either of the two forms of immaculate<br>
conception.  If we insist that temptation == human nature == sin<br>
then "He was tempted in all points like as we are" is an incredibly<br>
mistaken text for a Bible writer to pen.  If temptation == sin<br>
then Jesus sinned on all points like as we are.  If we accept that<br>
Jesus did not sin.  If we accept that Jesus was tempted like as<br>
we are.  Then clearly  Temptation =/= sin.  Sin can only be in<br>
the yielding to that temptation.  And so it is possible for Jesus<br>
to have our human nature, to have emptied Himself of His divinity,<br>
to be tempted just like we are.  And yet not have sinned.<br>
<p>
A favorite rebutal at this point is EGW's statement about Jesus<br>
not having any propensity to sin.  I have a Webster's dictionary<br>
that was published (a re-print) while EGW was still alive.  Propensity<br>
is used as a religious term that would fit well with the gansters<br>
of Miami Florida drug running fame.  Paul says often enough that<br>
"in Christ we cannot sin".  Jesus was constantly close to His<br>
father, never stepping out on His own.  As long as Jesus was "in"<br>
His Father, He could not sin.  If Jesus had stepped out on His own,<br>
as He could have done, then He would have been just as vulnerable<br>
as we are when we go it alone.  Consider the enormous struggle<br>
He went through in the garden of Gethsemene, to the point of<br>
drops of blood dripping from His forhead.  Can we contemplate<br>
that scene and insist that He was not tempted to abandone us,<br>
to abandone His ficcle disciples who did not seem even to care.<br>
Gethsemene is clearly a scene of Jesus human nature, of victory<br>
over temptation.<br>
<p>
It is interresting that "Issues" says the human nature of Christ<br>
is a "moot" issue.  And yet when Walter Martin confronted Adventism<br>
he saw things quite differently.  After having studied us at great<br>
length he made it clear to the SDA delegation that he was willing<br>
to leave us out of his upcoming cult book in spite of our belief<br>
in the Sabbath, the state-of-the-dead, and a lot of other things.<br>
But he came down strong on his point that we went in his cult book<br>
if we held to the human nature of Christ.  Read his "Kingdom of<br>
the Cults" and you see this confirmed.  He puts SDAs in the appendix<br>
of his book explaining why he did not write us up as a cult in spite<br>
of the Sabbath, the State-of-the-dead, . . . . . .  And explaining<br>
that while certain SDAs (that our leadership refer to as the lunatic<br>
fringe) insist on Jesus human nature, sanctuary, etc doctrines<br>
that the SDA leadership has come around to his position.<br>
<p>
So, "issues" is quite wrong to insist that this is a "moot" issue.<br>
They may be correct to say that leadership and laity are divided on<br>
this.  But it is a mistake to say its "moot".  Saying that anyone<br>
who makes an issue of it is divisive.<br>
<p>
What is interresting is the virtual unanimity of SDA writers on the<br>
nature of Christ before Walter Martin came on the scene.  And how<br>
that now our official church position is that its divided and "moot".<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
