<title>Mar_1993: Re:  The nature of Christ</title>
<h1>Re:  The nature of Christ</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 17 Mar 1993 23:06:40 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#196">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#196">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#196">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#196">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0197.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: "A Physicist can do anything""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0195.html">Woody Baker: "Re: "anti" posts on christia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[My apologies to longtime SDAnet readers who endured a discussion similar<br>
to this in fall of '90.  SCT]<br>
Dave points out one of the most important points to remember in discussing<br>
the nature of Christ.  Namely, His constant connection to the Father.<br>
Were Christ to drop that connection, then His human nature might have<br>
succumbed to the temptations and we would all be done for.<br>
<p>
The key paradox within the discussion of this issue to me is this.<br>
<p>
1)  Christ was somehow more than a man, otherwise any man could have been<br>
the Messiah and died for our sins.  Yet...<br>
<p>
2)  The Bible says that Christ was "tempted in all points like as we are,<br>
yet without sin."  <br>
<p>
What reconciles these two positions?  The connection (relationship) to <br>
God is something that Christ had from birth which we do not.  That is <br>
the idea of being "born in sin."  Yet this is not an "unfair advantage"<br>
because the same power which He has He offers to us, so we can also overcome.<br>
<p>
If I understand the arguments of the two sides correctly, this should make<br>
both of them mad.<br>
<p>
The second important idea is that a "sinful nature" does not necessarily <br>
mean that one cannot help but sin.  Some would say that sin is defined <br>
only by action.  I'm not sure about that, but I don't think one sins just <br>
by the act of being born.  There are many alcoholics who haven't had <br>
a drink in years.  Alcoholism is just one tendency (which some evidence<br>
indicates is inherited) that can be overcome through God's grace.  <br>
What about becoming "recovering sinners?"<br>
<p>
Anyway, one needs to be aware that different people define sin differently.<br>
Also consider the background of the theologians who thought up the ideas<br>
of immaculate conception and original sin.  These were celibate men who <br>
believed the sex act itself was sinful, in fact the original first sin.<br>
Therefore any conception would be sinful (and the pregnancy a "punishment"<br>
for the woman) unless there were some intervention by God, as in the case <br>
of Mary.  Even Catholic writers such as Aquinas argued against such a view.<br>
Such a doctrine of original sin leads directly to infant baptism,<br>
the idea that the soul is supplied at fertilization of the egg, and the <br>
militant Catholic anti-abortion stance.  There's more information on this<br>
in Peter DeRosa's book "Vicars of Christ"  (He's a former Catholic priest.)<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
