<!-- body="start" -->
Steven Timm writes:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
[ ... ]<br>
<i>&gt;This leaves us with a laboratory where physicists are in charge of</i><br>
<i>&gt;everything.  A physicist in charge of directing the digging of water</i><br>
<i>&gt;and sewer lines.  A physicist  (many, in fact) in charge of computing.</i><br>
<i>&gt;A physicist as assistant director for finance.  Another physicst as</i><br>
<i>&gt;assistant director for construction.  You get the idea--if the job can</i><br>
<i>&gt;be performed</i><br>
<i>&gt;by a physicist, it is performed by a physicist, and sometimes even when </i><br>
<i>&gt;this job assignment is not optimal, for instance, assigning a physicist like</i><br>
<i>&gt;myself to do electronics debugging.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I think the point is clear, and the analogy to the SDA church and</i><br>
<i>&gt;the job placement of pastors is a one-to-one mapping.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
But do you get the situation where, for instance, the division treasurer<br>
gets ordained because it's policy to have an ordained person as<br>
division treasurer?  (Would you give your accountant an honorary degree<br>
in physics so that he would be acceptable as assistant director for<br>
finance?)<br>
<p>
Of course, (in the church) this is probably a pragmatic approach to the<br>
problem of finding a suitably qualified person for jobs such as this<br>
without changing the policy book.  But it does have some drawbacks, such<br>
as automatically excluding women from the top positions.<br>
<p>
<p>
Malcolm Butler<br>
<pre>
-- 
Switched Networks Research Centre,
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia
</pre>
