<title>Mar_1993: In the presence of alcohol consumption</title>
<h1>In the presence of alcohol consumption</h1>
<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>19 Mar 1993 11:38:56 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#200">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#200">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#200">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#200">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0201.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: "A Physicist can do anything""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0199.html">Steven Timm: "Happy St. Patrick's Day"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0207.html">Steven Timm: "Re: In the presence of alcohol consumption"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I was going through some old SDAnet mail that had especially interested me<br>
at the time and found the following, written by Woody:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;It is important however, that you stand up for your principles.  Let me give</i><br>
<i>&gt;you an example.  I worked for 18 months selling computers and laser printers</i><br>
<i>&gt;for a store here in town.  I told my boss up front, that I would NOT be doing</i><br>
<i>&gt;any show duty from sundown Fri. thru sundown Sat.  Additionaly, I told him that</i><br>
<i>&gt;I absolutly would not attend any function for any reason where alcholic drinks</i><br>
<i>&gt;were served or consumed.  I was sucessfully able to maintain this in spite</i><br>
<i>&gt;of some pressure.  I found that he was accommodating.  I did attend a christmas</i><br>
<i>&gt;party once.  He arranged to have the happy hour/cocktail bar open about 30 to</i><br>
<i>&gt;45 minutes late, so I would be able to enjoy some of the food.  when the bar</i><br>
<i>&gt;opened, I left.  </i><br>
<p>
I can't say I'd ever thought of this stance! I am obviously in a different<br>
position to you as I am a mere student and not a salesperson or other<br>
professional of the suited variety. I have gone to the bar and to their BBQs<br>
and socialized with friends at Uni, I have eaten with them in a pub while we <br>
were attending a conference in Melbourne, and at the same conference I stood <br>
beside a poster of my research project at a poster session (drinking orange <br>
juice) while most others were over-indulging in free beer. It is true that I <br>
have never been with them in any serious drinking sessions but I have found<br>
it interesting to hear some of them "confessing" to me when they drank too<br>
much and saying they really shouldn't, and others saying that I'm really not<br>
missing anything.<br>
<p>
I can't imagine being able to avoid such situations, feeling that a label of<br>
"antisocial" could be given to me which may be worse as far as presenting<br>
Christianity in a positive light goes. But that is just my decision or<br>
impressions of the moment.<br>
<p>
Why did you decide, Woody, to take this position? When you did so, did you<br>
know others who had done the same thing? I'd also be interested to know how<br>
others enjoy(?!) interaction with non-SDAs when the social mode so often<br>
involves a glass of wine/can of beer.<br>
<p>
Thanx.<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
---*---<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
