<!-- body="start" -->
I finally got to look at Ruben's copy of that anti-SDA posting on CHRISTIA.<br>
I guess one man's chains is another man's liberation. <br>
<p>
The writer obviously either had a bad experience with SDAs or has never<br>
really met one from the other side of the fence. If there's such a thing<br>
as a moderate liberal in a conservative organization, I guess you can<br>
put me in that category. <br>
<p>
Call me brainwashed, but I don't see the Law as restrictive. What we do<br>
as a group to codify the law (i.e. no smoking, no drinking, etc), however,<br>
could be construed as restrictive. I think that is the case with the <br>
writer. I am not bothered by what "everyone" says I have to do on my<br>
Sabbath. I'd be more concerned by what Jesus says I could be doing on<br>
that day.<br>
<p>
I may not agree with some of the do's and don'ts of the church, but I still<br>
feel at home with the theological thrust of our group. And I agree with<br>
Woody that, although we should de-emphasize EGWhite's role as a prophetess,<br>
we should not put aside her counsels and her role in the formative years of<br>
the church. The only problem in de-emphasizing her role as a messenger<br>
is that it potentially undermines the SDA's claim of a latter-day messenger<br>
as outlined in prophecy. So much for the pieces falling into place.<br>
<p>
The way I see it, there are Pharisees in every mainstream church. I<br>
just don't believe that they represent the majority in this church. They<br>
sometimes have the loudest voices, with unfortunate results.<br>
<p>
--stan macasieb (macasib@degas.rtsg.mot.com)<br>
  Systems Engineer, Motorola, Arlington Hts, IL, USA<br>
  Comm Sec'y, North Shore SDA Church, Chicago, IL, USA<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
