<title>Mar_1993: Re: In the presence of alcohol consumption</title>
<h1>Re: In the presence of alcohol consumption</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Mar 1993 21:18:39 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#207">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#207">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#207">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#207">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0208.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Wedding rings"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0206.html">Steven Timm: "Ron Wyatt"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0200.html">CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "In the presence of alcohol consumption"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
If I were to avoid all places at which alcohol is served I'm afraid I <br>
wouldn't socialize much at all.  For example, at Fermilab, wine is served<br>
before every Friday afternoon seminar, which is usually the most important <br>
seminar of the week.  All work social functions involve the serving of<br>
alcohol.  Many of the parties likewise.  <br>
<p>
I find, however, that I am not usually the only person who is sober at <br>
such gatherings, and I have met some very interesting people this way.<br>
<p>
I am well acquainted with the type of philosophy that avoids alcohol<br>
totally, though, because my parents followed this philosophy while I was<br>
growing up. <br>
When I was young they would never go even to a restaurant that served alcohol.<br>
<p>
(In places like Europe this would be impossible, even Burger King serves<br>
beer, but I digress).<br>
<p>
Now they may attend such restaurants, but they would still never drink.<br>
There are several instances of alcoholism on my dad's side of the family, and<br>
he has done well to stay as far away as possible from it.  He took his<br>
no-drinking stance long before he became SDA.  In fact, his Lutheran <br>
pastor used to tell him that he ought not to drink.  Also, his dad would <br>
let him drive the family home from the various parties and weddings if he<br>
was sober.  <br>
<p>
I have found in several instances that I have been a help to my friends<br>
by offering to be the "designated driver" at some of the wilder parties.<br>
Surely my example of socializing, not drinking, yet not condemning has<br>
been noticed.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
