<title>Mar_1993: salvation</title>
<h1>salvation</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Mar 93 12:47:18 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#209">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#209">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#209">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#209">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0210.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Sabataran Patrick (was Happy St. Patrick's Day)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0208.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Wedding rings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
You write:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Christ was somehow more than a man, otherwise any man could have been</i><br>
the Messiah and died for our sins.  Yet...<br>
<p>
My response:<br>
<p>
Christ was somehow more than a man.  He also had a divine nature which<br>
we do not.  This made it possible for him to be our Saviour.  But<br>
we are discussing His humanity.  So the issue of the humanity of<br>
Christ is independent from the possibility of His being our Savior.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
