<title>Mar_1993: Sabataran Patrick (was Happy St. Patrick's Day)</title>
<h1>Sabataran Patrick (was Happy St. Patrick's Day)</h1>
<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i><br>
<i>Thu, 18 Mar 93 06:13:57 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#210">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#210">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#210">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#210">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0211.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Happy St. Patrick's Day"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0209.html">David Plaisted: "salvation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Someplace I heard that St. Patrick was one of the early Christians</i><br>
<i>&gt;in the British Isles who insisted on keeping the Sabbath.  Whether</i><br>
<i>&gt;or not that is true, I offer this reading, written by Richard Harris</i><br>
<i>&gt;and popularized by Wintley Phipps in SDA circles.  </i><br>
<p>
Jim Arrabito died in a plane crash several months ago.  He was traveling<br>
the world with his video camera documenting early AD Sabbath keeping<br>
in Australia, England, India, Ireland, Russia, China, etc.  Yes, he<br>
did come up with documentation that shows that people in that area<br>
and time in history were Sabatarian.  As I recall, I don't think there<br>
was direct proof that St. Patrick was a Sabbath keeping.  But that<br>
by inference it was highly likely.<br>
<p>
On the radio yesterday, on my way home, commercial newstalk radio,<br>
someone had called in to say that the Catholic church had sent in<br>
500 sword carrying priests to bring St. Patrick and his church into<br>
line because some of his clergy were married.  Some of what I've<br>
heard about St. Patrick, it would seem that he was a "heretic" by<br>
Rome's standards, but somehow became sainted after his death.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
