<title>Mar_1993: Re: Happy St. Patrick's Day</title>
<h1>Re: Happy St. Patrick's Day</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Mar 93 9:52:25 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#211">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#211">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#211">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#211">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0212.html">Malachi Robertson: "John and his writings"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0210.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Sabataran Patrick (was Happy St. Patrick's Day)"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0199.html">Steven Timm: "Happy St. Patrick's Day"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Someplace I heard that St. Patrick was one of the early Christians</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the British Isles who insisted on keeping the Sabbath.</i><br>
<p>
Eric B Hare, in one his Junior devotionals, for Mar 17, makes this claim.<br>
Out of curiosity, my wife and I dug into this some.  Wylie's "History<br>
of the Reformation" spends a couple of pages on Patrick.  Winston Churchhill,<br>
in his "History of the English Speaking People", also gives some insight<br>
into Patrick's background.  I won't delve into those details here, as I<br>
hope to motivate SDAnetters into reading these excellent books.  Suffice<br>
it to say that his parents belonged to a group of believers (their base was<br>
in what is now called Lyons, France), established by the apostles, who are<br>
known to have been Sabbath keepers.<br>
<p>
I don't have any scholarly references, but Lois Parker (and maybe someone<br>
else) has done her homework pretty thoroughly and has put out books<br>
aimed at junior aged youth.  One is entitled "Duncan, Son of Malcolm"<br>
(Wylie, Churchill, et al, verify that it was during Duncan's time that<br>
Catholocism came to Scotland) and the other title escapes my memory<br>
(maybe "A Sword Unsheathed"?).  Both mention Sabbath keepers in the<br>
British Isles.  Still available at the ABC.<br>
<p>
An older title is "They Took John's Torch".  There is mention of the<br>
apostolic group in France of which Patrick's family.  In general,<br>
the book treats the early Christian church in the British Isles and<br>
the persecution it faced from pagans and then prelates.  Probably only<br>
possible to find thru used book sellers such as Leaves of Autumn.<br>
<p>
I believe the late James Arrabito also produced some relevant materials,<br>
perhaps available from his widow.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
