<title>Mar_1993: John and his writings</title>
<h1>John and his writings</h1>
Malachi Robertson (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 18 Mar 93 17:30:03 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#212">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#212">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#212">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#212">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0213.html">David Plaisted: "Syracuse New York"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0211.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Happy St. Patrick's Day"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0240.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Re: John and his writings"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It was my understanding that the epistles of John and even the Gospel of<br>
John have elements within them that are a reaction against gnostic<br>
influences that were creeping into Christianity.  I believe that part of<br>
the heresy of the time was to put aside the humanity of Jesus and see him<br>
as a purely spiritual being.  As I write this, however, I keep thinking I<br>
am forgetting something.<br>
<p>
Ian.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
