<title>Mar_1993: Re: NAC C 47 10</title>
<h1>Re: NAC C 47 10</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 20 Mar 1993 21:21:55 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#217">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#217">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#217">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#217">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0218.html">Steven Timm: "Re: NAC C 47 10"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0216.html">Steven Timm: "Bob Gentry  was Re: Ron Wyatt"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0218.html">Steven Timm: "Re: NAC C 47 10"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I was reading the March 11 review today, and<br>
came across something that to me, is profoundly disturbing.  I quote it<br>
here, wondering if I am not reading it correctly, or if others may point<br>
out whether or not I am wrong:<br>
<p>
p.22<br>
<p>
Denominational Status for Seventh-day Adventist Organizations Criteria.<br>
<p>
VOTED: To adopt a new policy NAD C 47 10 Organizational Structure,<br>
Governance and Operations to read as follows:<br>
<p>
C 47 10 Organizational Structure, Bovernance and Operation: Organizations<br>
included in the "Seventh-day Adventist Yearbook" ((quotes indicate italics))<br>
must be affiliated with, and subject to, the general supervison or<br>
control fo the Seventh-day Adventist Chruch and must comply with the following<br>
requirements to hold denominational status:<br>
<p>
	1. Governing decuments:  The governing documents of the organization<br>
(i.e. articles of incorporation, constitution, bylaws, articles of associatein<br>
trusts, etc). shall provide for the following:<br>
<p>
	a.	Relation to denomination:The organization shall be affilliated<br>
with and/or be an integeral part of the Sevendth-day Adventist Church, and<br>
it's primary purpose shall be in harmony with, and supportive of, the mission<br>
of the church.<br>
<p>
	b.	Corporate membership:  All persons who serve as corporate <br>
	members, members  of the constituency, or shareholders of the <br>
	organization shall be members of the Seventh-day Adventist Church.  <br>
	Not less than a majority of the corporate membership, constituency,<br>
	or shareholders shall be comprised of persons who are members of <br>
	specific denominational constituencies, board, or executive committes <br>
	of organizations that are listed in the Seventh-day Adventist <br>
	yearbook.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;This is the one that REALLY concerns me.</i><br>
<p>
	My reading of this indicates that since a church is listed in the<br>
	yearbook, you can't form a church unless over 50% of your members<br>
	are already Seventh-day Adventists.  Either denominational <br>
	employees, or members serving on conference sponsored committees.<br>
	This makes no sense what-so ever.  It seems to be an attempt to<br>
	supress disident groups from forming.  There is no definition of<br>
	"specific denominational constituencies"<br>
&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;<br>
	<br>
	c.	Board: The board of directors or trustees (or comparable <br>
		governing body if not a corporation) shall serve by <br>
		appointment of the corporate membership, constituency, or <br>
		shareholders, who shall have the right to elect, appoint, <br>
		or remove any member of the board.  A majority of the board<br>
		shall be members of the Seventh-day Adventist Church, <br>
		although the corporate membership, constituency, or <br>
		shareholders may make an exception in unusual, limited <br>
		cases where it can be assured that the best interests of <br>
		the organization and the mission of the Seventh-day <br>
		nAdventist Church can be protected and served.<br>
		<br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</i><br>
	This seems to equate corporate membership, and constituency with <br>
	the membership in general.<br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</i><br>
<p>
	d.	Dissolution:  In the case of dissolution, the net owned <br>
		assets of the organization shall be transferred to an <br>
		organization holding Seventh-day Adventist denominatinal <br>
		status, which qualifies as a tax-exempt organization <br>
		described in Section 501 (c) (3) of the IRS code or sectino <br>
		149.1 of the Canadian Income Tax act, consistent with state <br>
		or prvidecial law.<br>
		<br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;</i><br>
	This sounds like a confiscatory grab by the church.  Suppose a<br>
	group formed a church that was qualified and listed under these<br>
	guidelines.  Further suppose the group decides to dis-band, and<br>
	owns property.  This prohibits them from selling said property<br>
	and useing the money to perhaps purchase another piece of property.<br>
	<br>
	Lets take an example.  Take a self-supporting institution such as<br>
	say, Pine Forrest.  It is owned by the Laymans Foundation.  I don't<br>
	know whether or not they are in the year book, but if they are, or<br>
	get listed, then they lose control over Pine Forrest.  Supposing<br>
	that a group decides to use the Pine Forrest campus (currently<br>
	it is unused) and forms a school that they ultimately desire to <br>
	be associated with the SDA church as a SDA church sponsored school.<br>
	(This has happened before).  The Church then obtains a de-facto<br>
	title to the intituion or land, because if it is dissolved, the<br>
	assets (the land) must be transfered to some other SDA entity.<br>
	I don't think that this is good at all.<br>
&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;<br>
<p>
<p>
	Now, if I am interpreting this wrong, please correct me, but don't<br>
	flame me. (my asbestos suit has been confiscated because it is a<br>
	cancer hazard... ;}  )<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
