<title>Mar_1993: Re: Ron Wyatt</title>
<h1>Re: Ron Wyatt</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 20 Mar 1993 21:41:44 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#220">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#220">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#220">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#220">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0221.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Wedding rings"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0219.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: bravery"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0206.html">Steven Timm: "Ron Wyatt"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0216.html">Steven Timm: "Bob Gentry  was Re: Ron Wyatt"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Robert Gentry's work on the surface builds a rather conclusive argument<br>
for an instantaneous creation.  Only if you dig deeper, and read through<br>
the opposing literature do you find that his experimental data are seriously<br>
flawed.  I have a lengthy article concerning this that was sent to me<br>
over the net.  Basically, Dr. Gentry has been studing radio-halos in mica<br>
and biotite. (one point of contention is that he mis-identified the material)<br>
from Pre-Cambrian gneiss and granites.  When a radio-active particle decays<br>
into lead, it goes through several transformations, emitting energy particles.<br>
These particles produce damage in the crystal matrix, and depending on thier<br>
energies, the damage allows one to identify the stages.  A more energetic<br>
particle will produce a longer track in the crystal.  The net result, is<br>
that if you section the rock at the neuclear site, you will find a series<br>
of rings or halos, corresponding to the diffrent particles emitted, and<br>
identifiable by thier width.  It turns out that certain isotopes in the<br>
decay chain have a very short half-life, and others have tremenously<br>
long half-lifes.  One of the short half-life particles is a Po isotope.<br>
I don't remember which one.  Gentry's claim is that he has found<br>
elemental (priomordial) sites in the crystal matrix where there are only<br>
a very few halos, and those start with this short half-life (I think<br>
37 seconds) isotope.  This of course implies that the matrix would have<br>
to have crystalized very rapidly to capture a primordial particle of this<br>
particular Po isotope, otherwise there would be parent decay halos, or<br>
no halo (the isotope would have decayed before the capture.)  He further<br>
asserts that the occurance of these is uniform throughout the pre-cambrian<br>
granites.  This implies that the entire pre-cambrian granites would have had<br>
to solidify vertually instantly.  He further states that his samples were<br>
taken from several continents.  In fact, his samples ALL came from the<br>
same uranium mine up in Canada, (which he never mentions).  He further<br>
ignores the fact that crystals form in layers, and indeed, if there were<br>
primordial Po particles is suspension in the melted matrix, there would be<br>
occasions when the crystalization could indeed trap them at the crystalization<br>
barrier. (Note these suckers are microscopic).<br>
<p>
Where he got into real trouble however, was his assertion that the first <br>
person to produce granite in the lab, and prove it to him, would invalidate<br>
his thesis, (or something along that line).<br>
<p>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
