<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;thing.  It wasn't quite what I believe but it came close.  My only mental</i><br>
<i>&gt;difficulty of late is trying to see how this scapegoat view (where Satan</i><br>
<i>&gt;gets to bear the sins of the cleansed) fits with the notion of Jesus</i><br>
<i>&gt;taking the wrath of God upon Himself.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Ian.</i><br>
<p>
Well, i don't know if this is correct, but i sort of thought that Jesus<br>
took the punishment that we deserve, paid our fine for us, and is our<br>
substitute. He paid the penalty for the sins of the world.<br>
	The devil i thought, will be punished for his part in tempting<br>
the "cleansed" to sin and causing them to fall. Jesus paid for their<br>
part of the blame, for they chose to go along with Satan in sin and so<br>
are guilty also. As such, Jesus bears the sins of the cleansed, and<br>
Satan bears his own sins, which include his part in aiding and abetting them<br>
to sin.<br>
	- beng<br>
