Gilbert Bailey writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;As I grew up in the church I was told that I must wait to be baptized</i><br>
<i>&gt;in order to 'fully understand' the significance of the bread and wine</i><br>
<i>&gt;before participating.  What is the relationship between Baptism and</i><br>
<i>&gt;the 'Lord's Supper'?</i><br>
<p>
I don't know. At my church, they have open communion, and *anybody* can<br>
join in the Lord's foot washing and supper, if they want to. The pastor<br>
always explains the meaning of the ceremony so they'll know whats going on.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Well, I'll stop now with the above list.  I'm sure all of you can think</i><br>
<i>&gt;of more questions/answers.  Just as a side note, my 5yr old son, asks </i><br>
<i>&gt;deeper questions than some 'mature' Christians, and based upon his later</i><br>
<i>&gt;comments he has a rather firm grasp on principles involved after I've</i><br>
<p>
Well, children sometimes see things clearer than adults. The thing is that<br>
a lot of adults don't know this and they appear to think that children<br>
are stupid or something.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;explained an answer(s) to his question(s).  He also seems to put into</i><br>
<i>&gt;practice the things he learns much more readily than his 'more mature'</i><br>
<i>&gt;counterparts.</i><br>
<p>
I guess we should do like Jesus said and be like children.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
