<title>Mar_1993: Re:  Things</title>
<h1>Re:  Things</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 21 Mar 93 04:02:47 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#238">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#238">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#238">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#238">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0239.html">Russell Grau: "Re: scapegoat"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0237.html">Steven Timm: "Bitnet is slow"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0203.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Things"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0249.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Things"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;The list is long!! (about 52k) So I won't post it. I will email it</i><br>
<i>&gt;to those who are interested. About 80% of the verses have some attached</i><br>
<i>&gt;comments highlighting the ommissions / modifications.</i><br>
<p>
I'm interested! Ruben, please send me a copy. Thanks.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Here is a sampling of what its like. (as they say try before you buy)</i><br>
<i>&gt;....</i><br>
<i>&gt;1 John 4:3 </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;KJV	And every spirit that confesseth not that Jesus Christ is come_in_</i><br>
<i>&gt;	the_flesh_is_not_of_God: and this is that spirit of antichrist,</i><br>
<i>&gt;	whereof ye have heard that it should come; and even now already is</i><br>
<i>&gt;	it in the world. </i><br>
<i>&gt;NIV	but every spirit that does not acknowledge Jesus ****************</i><br>
<i>&gt;	********* is not from God. This is the spirit of the antichrist, </i><br>
<i>&gt;	which you have heard is coming and even now is already </i><br>
<i>&gt;	in the world.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;ASV	and every spirit that confesseth not Jesus *********************</i><br>
<i>&gt;	********* is not of God: and this is the (spirit) of the antichrist, </i><br>
<i>&gt;	whereof ye have heard that it cometh; and now it is in the </i><br>
<i>&gt;	world already.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Now the spirit of ANTIChrist is  that which says Jesus did not come IN THE </i><br>
<i>&gt;FLESH ! however these modern bibles testify against themselves that they </i><br>
<i>&gt;are from antichrist because they deny (by omission) that Jesus came IN THE</i><br>
<i>&gt;FLESH !!!!</i><br>
<p>
Well, i personally like the NIV best amongst the English translations. The<br>
Elezebethen English of the KJV is sometimes a little hard to understand in<br>
some places, for me. Anyway, i find that although the RSV proports to be a<br>
revision of the KJV, the NIV is actually much closer to the KJV than the<br>
RSV, so that if someone is reading the KJV, i can follow in the NIV and<br>
get the same understanding. As to 1 jn 4:3, if you read it in context in the<br>
NIV, you still get the same meaning as in the KJV:<br>
<p>
1 Jn 4:2-3  This is how you can recognize the Spirit of God: Every spirit<br>
 that acknowledges that Jesus Christ has come in the flesh is from God,<br>
 3 but every spirit that does not acknowledge Jesus is not from God. This<br>
 is the spirit of the antichrist, which you have heard is coming and even<br>
 now is already in the world. (NIV) <br>
<p>
The reading in the RSV is similar, so it shouldn't be a problem. Anyway,<br>
i'm not sure that the KJV is a more accurate translation than the others.<br>
The SDA bible commentary on the KJV says on this verse: "Important textual<br>
evidence may be cited for the omission of "Christ" and of the phrase "is<br>
come in the flesh." The phrase then reads, "every spirit that confesseth<br>
not Jesus," and places emphasis upon the confession of a person rather than<br>
a creed. The textual variants make no significant change in the meaning of<br>
the passage, for both renderings refer to the teachers who fail to glorify<br>
the divine-human Jesus." -- page 661 Vol. 7<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;--------------------------------------</i><br>
<i>&gt;1 Tim 3:16 </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;KJV	And without controversy great is the mystery of godliness: God was</i><br>
<i>&gt;	manifest_in_the_flesh, justified in the Spirit, seen of angels,</i><br>
<i>&gt;	preached unto the Gentiles, believed on in the world, received up</i><br>
<i>&gt;	into glory.</i><br>
<i>&gt;NIV	Beyond all question, the mystery of godliness is great: He appeared</i><br>
<i>&gt;	in a body ****, was vindicated by the Spirit, was seen by angels, was</i><br>
<i>&gt;	preached among the nations, was believed on in the world, was taken</i><br>
<i>&gt;	up in glory.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Yep once again the NIV denies that Jesus came in the FLESH.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Why does Satan hate this doctrine ??</i><br>
<p>
Well, isn't "appeared in a body" the same as "manifest in the flesh"?<br>
Anyway, the NIV does have footnotes, and the one here says "16 Or in the<br>
flesh." I am not yet convinced that the NIV is Satanic.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;--------------------------------------</i><br>
<i>&gt;Acts 2:30 </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;KJV	Therefore being a prophet, and knowing that God had sworn with an</i><br>
<i>&gt;	oath to him, that of the fruit of his loins, according_to_the_flesh,</i><br>
<i>&gt;	he would raise up Christ to sit on his throne;  </i><br>
<i>&gt;NIV	But he was a prophet and knew that God had promised him on oath that</i><br>
<i>&gt;	he would place one of his descendants **************************</i><br>
<i>&gt;	************** on his throne.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;ASV	Being therefore a prophet, and knowing that God had sworn with an</i><br>
<i>&gt;	oath to him, that of the fruit of his loins *********************</i><br>
<i>&gt;	he would set (one) ******* upon his throne;  </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Not only is that fact that Jesus would come according to the flesh discarded</i><br>
<i>&gt;but even Christs' identitification here is removed. IS this  the spirit of</i><br>
<i>&gt;anitchrist or what?</i><br>
<p>
While it is true that the NIV omits "Christ" and "..flesh.." if you read the<br>
context of the verse in question, it becomes apparent that Christ the<br>
Messiah is referred to here in the NIV. And if the NIV is from antichrist,<br>
then so is the SDA bible commentary, because it has this to say on this<br>
verse:    "_According to the flesh_- Textual evidence favours the omission<br>
of the words "according to the flesh, he would raise up Christ," so that the<br>
passage would read, "God swore to him with an oath to place upon his throne<br>
one, of the fruit of his loins." This would agree more closely with Psalm.<br>
132:11" -- Vol. 6 page 146<br>
	So it seems, at least according to the SDA bible commentary, that<br>
the NIV is more accurately translated textually, than the KJV.<br>
<p>
	Well, Ruben, heres another verse to compare, and one which i like to<br>
use to compare translations: Isa 8:20<br>
<p>
Isa 8:20 To the law and to the testimony: if they speak not according to<br>
         this word, it is because there is no light in them.(KJV)<br>
<p>
Isa 8:20 To the law and to the testimony! If they do not speak according<br>
         to this word, they have no light of dawn. (NIV)<br>
<p>
Esaie 8:20 A la loi et au temoignage! Si l'on ne parle pas ainsi, Il n'y<br>
           aura point d'aurore pour le peuple. (French Revised Version)<br>
(rough translation: "To the law and to the testimony! If they speak not<br>
 thus/not in this way, there will not be any dawn at all for the people.")<br>
<p>
Isa 8:20 To the teaching and to the testimony! Surely for this word which<br>
         they speak there is no dawn. (RSV)<br>
<p>
Isa 8:20 You are to answer them, "Listen to what the LORD is teaching you!<br>
         Don't listen to mediums -- what they tell you will do you no good."<br>
         (Good News Bible, footnote to V.20 says: Verse 20 in Hebrew is<br>
         unclear.")<br>
<p>
Well, unlike the Goodnews bible, the SDA bible commentary does not note any<br>
difficulty with the Hebrew here, and you can see that the NIV is closer than<br>
the RSV here, to the KJV (The Hebrew reads "Torah"). If you want to read<br>
some good science-fiction, try Gen 6:1-4 in the Goodnews bible, its far out!<br>
(The gist of it is: Supernatural beings take beautiful girls born to men,<br>
then God limits man's lifespan and the Supernatural beings bear giants...-<br>
like an ET story or something eh?)<br>
	Personally, i think the GNB is better than no bible at all, but<br>
you have to take it with a pinch of salt.<br>
<p>
	Well, no offense intended to anybody, just some thoughts on bible<br>
translations.<br>
<p>
	regards,<br>
		beng.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
