<title>Mar_1993: Re: scapegoat</title>
<h1>Re: scapegoat</h1>
Russell Grau (<i>reg@ctshp.celtech.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 19 Mar 1993 08:23:01 -0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#239">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#239">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#239">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#239">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0240.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Re: John and his writings"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0238.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Things"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Regarding the scapegoat:<br>
<p>
It is my understanding that Satan DOES NOT bear our sins.  He bears his portion<br>
of responsability for our sins.  While he may not be physically responsible for<br>
our sins, he is the "father of all lies".  As such HE bears a responsability<br>
for causing the angels to fall, for causing the fallen angels to tempt other<br>
men and angels, who in turn tempt men of every age.<br>
<p>
I would also liken this to a captain on the ship.  He is responsible for every<br>
member's activity while on the ship.  Satan has made his own ship and is <br>
responsible for bringing the people on the ship.  That is the only type of<br>
responsability that he bears.<br>
<p>
Jesus bore our sins on the cross.  He is our saviour.  Satan will bear the<br>
responsability for his sins and his part in our sins.  <br>
<p>
Viewpoint, in this instance, makes a big difference.<br>
<p>
Russell E. Grau<br>
reg@celtech.com  &lt;&lt;-- work<br>
russellgen@aol.com  &lt;&lt;-- play  8-)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
