<title>Mar_1993: Re: John and his writings</title>
<h1>Re: John and his writings</h1>
<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 19 Mar 93 06:31:59 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#240">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#240">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#240">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#240">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0241.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Bible Translations"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0239.html">Russell Grau: "Re: scapegoat"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0212.html">Malachi Robertson: "John and his writings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;It was my understanding that the epistles of John and even the Gospel of</i><br>
<i>&gt;John have elements within them that are a reaction against gnostic</i><br>
<i>&gt;influences that were creeping into Christianity.  I believe that part of</i><br>
<i>&gt;the heresy of the time was to put aside the humanity of Jesus and see him</i><br>
<i>&gt;as a purely spiritual being.  As I write this, however, I keep thinking I</i><br>
<i>&gt;am forgetting something.</i><br>
<p>
The Gnostics had a lot of mystical theology including denial of the<br>
human nature of Christ.  Also, Antinomian -- God's law is done away with.<br>
The theory that the manuscripts from which the NIV and other modern<br>
translations translate; the theory that these were Gnostic versions;<br>
seems to have substance when the translations and the Gnostic theology<br>
are compared.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
