<title>Mar_1993: "Discovered--Noah's Ark"</title>
<h1>"Discovered--Noah's Ark"</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 30 Jun 1992 15:12:19 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#242">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#242">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#242">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#242">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0243.html">callen roy: "Re:  "Discovered--Noah's Ark""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0241.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Bible Translations"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0243.html">callen roy: "Re:  "Discovered--Noah's Ark""</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Now that I have your attention:<br>
I noticed a rather unfavorable review of this book in the latest issue<br>
of the newsletter of the Association of Adventist Physicists.  The book<br>
was authored by Ron Wyatt, whom I last encountered at the Friendship<br>
Camporee<br>
in Pennsylvania, teaching this to Pathfinders.  Wyatt is an anesthetist<br>
from Madison, Tennesee.<br>
<p>
Henry Pearl, the reviewer, claims (and rightly so) that Wyatt has<br>
misunderstood the geomagnetic field reversal data to mean actual<br>
flipping over of the earth, confusing celestial poles with magnetic<br>
poles.<br>
(Note that Pearl himself subscribes to the idea of a flood, as well.)<br>
<p>
I find it distressing that there are those who go off half-cocked<br>
claiming this or that piece of evidence proves the flood when in fact<br>
they don't understand such a piece of evidence.  On the other hand, it's<br>
not wise to attribute to deceit what can be explained by stupidity.<br>
<p>
For those who would rather strengthen their faith than know the truth, <br>
this book may be obtained from <br>
<p>
Ron Wyatt<br>
P.O. Box 5931<br>
Madison, TN  37116<br>
<p>
I understand Wyatt has embarked on other such expeditions in the past,<br>
including claiming to know where the Ark of the Covenant is.  If anyone has<br>
further information on his track record, let me know.  SDA physicists<br>
are still doing damage control in the wake of Bob Gentry, and now this<br>
has come up.  What next?  Are there any studies that show SDA's to be<br>
more gullible than the average population?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<p>
<p>
[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Henry Pearl, the reviewer, claims (and rightly so) that Wyatt has</i><br>
<i>&gt; misunderstood the geomagnetic field reversal data to mean actual</i><br>
<i>&gt; flipping over of the earth, confusing celestial poles with magnetic poles.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I find it distressing that there are those who go off half-cocked</i><br>
<i>&gt; claiming this or that piece of evidence proves the flood when in fact</i><br>
<i>&gt; they don't understand such a piece of evidence.  On the other hand, it's</i><br>
<i>&gt; not wise to attribute to deceit what can be explained by stupidity.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; If anyone has further information on his track record, let me know.</i><br>
<p>
About 2 years ago, a supporter of Wyatt's showed a videotape of Wyatt's<br>
work to a rather large crowd in Gladstone, OR.  Mostly how he found what<br>
he did, vignettes on other folks' searches, and whether what he had found<br>
was really Noah's ark (he believes so).  There were some interviews with<br>
SDA geologists/paleontologists (whatever those guys are) voicing their<br>
opinions.  The trend seemed to be supportive in the clips; however the<br>
supporter showing the tape acknowledged that his conversations with some<br>
of those interviewed yielded pretty neutral to somewhat skeptical opinions.<br>
<p>
Discussion afterwards was nuked by some strange character repeatedly raising<br>
spurious objections, such as: "What sort of strange doctrine are you trying<br>
to introduce into the church?  You're wanting us to sacrifice goats!"  What<br>
actually happened was that the video opened with a scene where Turkish folk<br>
are getting ready to build a tourist center at Wyatt's find and the opening<br>
festivities involve killing a goat.  The voice-over was quite clear as to<br>
what was happening.  It was the individual who mistook this and many others.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; SDA physicists are still doing damage control in the wake of Bob Gentry.</i><br>
<p>
Can you explain further?  I recall George Vandeman talking about Gentry's<br>
work maybe 20, 21 years ago.  I don't remember details nor what became<br>
of Gentry's ideas.  Remember that he wouldn't be the first to have an idea<br>
and then have it go down the drain.  Note how the State of Utah is spending<br>
big bucks on this cold fusion stuff.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What next?</i><br>
<p>
Wyatt is not the first.  Check out the French guy, Navarra.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Are there any studies that show SDA's to be more gullible than the</i><br>
<i>&gt; average population?</i><br>
<p>
Careful; you're looking at a very narrow slice of human behavior.  Note<br>
that this aspect of credulity is not limited to SDAs.  Take eschatology for<br>
example.  Consider Hal Lindsay's early works and the great following that that<br>
engendered!  Folk are still reading his stuff and hoping, despite the abject<br>
failure of his earlier predictions.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  For I know the thoughts that I have toward you, says the Lord, thoughts of
    peace and not evil, to give you hope and a future (Jer 29:11).
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
