<title>Mar_1993: Christ's humanity</title>
<h1>Christ's humanity</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>19 Mar 1993 14:51:09 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#247">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#247">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#247">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#247">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0248.html">Gilbert Bailey: "Lord's Supper"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0246.html">Russell Grau: "Re: In the presence of alcohol consumption"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
----&gt;<br>
Christ was somehow more than a man.  He also had a divine nature which<br>
we do not.  This made it possible for him to be our Saviour.  But<br>
we are discussing His humanity.  So the issue of the humanity of<br>
Christ is independent from the possibility of His being our Savior.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Well, let's discuss Adam's humanity. Was Adam created fully human, or did<br>
it take the destruction of his relationship with God to complete his<br>
humanity?<br>
<p>
I think those who say Christ had a "sinful nature" and those who say he<br>
had a "sinless nature", at least in the SDA church, are agreed about what<br>
Christ was. What is not agreed is what sin is.<br>
<p>
Position a:<br>
<p>
Sin = transgression of the law = actions/cherished thoughts/whatever<br>
Sinful nature = human body degraded by thousands of years of the effects<br>
                of sin, which we all agree Christ had.<br>
<p>
Position b:<br>
<p>
Sin = transgression of the law +<br>
      broken relationship with God <br>
Sinful nature = the state in which we are born, ie, with a broken relationship<br>
      with God, inherited from Adam<br>
Sinless nature (of Christ) = complete relationship with God, but still with<br>
      the same "sinful" body that the rest of us have.<br>
<p>
<p>
Disclaimer: this is far from a good exposition of both points of view, but<br>
I think it summarizes the way the two definitions of sinful/sinless differ.<br>
<p>
So my questions on "how to answer a cb" would include "what do you say to a<br>
person who says that transgression of law is the only definition of sin".<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
