On Mar 18,  4:23pm, Ruben Gonzalez wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Things</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 1 John 4:3</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; KJV	And every spirit that confesseth not that Jesus Christ is come_in_</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	the_flesh_is_not_of_God: and this is that spirit of antichrist,</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	whereof ye have heard that it should come; and even now already is</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	it in the world.</i><br>
<i>&gt; NIV	but every spirit that does not acknowledge Jesus ****************</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	********* is not from God. This is the spirit of the antichrist,</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	which you have heard is coming and even now is already</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	in the world.</i><br>
<i>&gt; ASV	and every spirit that confesseth not Jesus *********************</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	********* is not of God: and this is the (spirit) of the antichrist,</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	whereof ye have heard that it cometh; and now it is in the</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	world already.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Now the spirit of ANTIChrist is  that which says Jesus did not come IN THE</i><br>
<i>&gt; FLESH ! however these modern bibles testify against themselves that they</i><br>
<i>&gt; are from antichrist because they deny (by omission) that Jesus came IN THE</i><br>
<i>&gt; FLESH !!!!</i><br>
<p>
This is SUCH a short sighted conclusion I can't believe you would even post<br>
such a statement.  You REALLY believe that the NIV compilers, translators, etc<br>
really deny that Jesus came in the flesh to this world and died?  Any body<br>
reading the gospels in the NIV will see that to be a false statement.<br>
 Remember, you don't hang doctrine on one text or even two, but on the<br>
proponderence of evidence stated in the Bible.  To me, to "acknowledge" Jesus<br>
means to accept that He existed, that He came and lived and died on this earth<br>
for our sins.  That is what I read in my NIV.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; --------------------------------------</i><br>
<i>&gt; 1 Tim 3:16</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; KJV	And without controversy great is the mystery of godliness: God was</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	manifest_in_the_flesh, justified in the Spirit, seen of angels,</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	preached unto the Gentiles, believed on in the world, received up</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	into glory.</i><br>
<i>&gt; NIV	Beyond all question, the mystery of godliness is great: He appeared</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	in a body ****, was vindicated by the Spirit, was seen by angels, was</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	preached among the nations, was believed on in the world, was taken</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	up in glory.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Yep once again the NIV denies that Jesus came in the FLESH.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Why does Satan hate this doctrine ??</i><br>
<p>
<p>
What is "in the flesh" mean if not having a body.  How would you translate "in<br>
the flesh" using today's terminology?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; --------------------------------------</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Acts 2:30</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; KJV	Therefore being a prophet, and knowing that God had sworn with an</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	oath to him, that of the fruit of his loins, according_to_the_flesh,</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	he would raise up Christ to sit on his throne;</i><br>
<i>&gt; NIV	But he was a prophet and knew that God had promised him on oath that</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	he would place one of his descendants **************************</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	************** on his throne.</i><br>
<i>&gt; ASV	Being therefore a prophet, and knowing that God had sworn with an</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	oath to him, that of the fruit of his loins *********************</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	he would set (one) ******* upon his throne;</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Not only is that fact that Jesus would come according to the flesh discarded</i><br>
<i>&gt; but even Christs' identitification here is removed. IS this  the spirit of</i><br>
<i>&gt; anitchrist or what?</i><br>
<p>
You are brazenly suggesting that those reading the NIV are reading material<br>
written in the spirit of the antichrist.  Dream on...I believe there will be a<br>
lot of folks saved and in heaven who only knew and read the NIV or ASV, or<br>
even the Living Bible (should I guess it's too heretical to even mention).<br>
 God can speak to people in many ways, including through His written word.<br>
 The KJV has mistakes as well.  That doesn't mean we should throw the baby out<br>
with the bath water.  I think it good to read several versions and cross<br>
reference their meanings, but for everyday reading, I find I gain alot more<br>
from the NIV over the old english of the KJV.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
