<title>Mar_1993: Gentry's halos</title>
<h1>Gentry's halos</h1>
<i>ben@orion.lasierra.edu</i><br>
<i>Mon, 22 Mar 1993 10:39:03 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#251">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#251">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#251">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#251">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0252.html">Cam Litvin: "RE: Ron Wyatt"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0250.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: In the presence of alcohol consumption"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0266.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Gentry's halos"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It would be nice to have conclusive "proof" of a recent creation and a world<br>
wide flood. Unfortunately, the incontrovertible proofs of historical geology<br>
for either long ages or short ages are about as good as the historical<br>
reconstructions found in court trials. Sometimes the evidence is pretty good,<br>
but there's always more than one side. <br>
<p>
I know of two reviews on Robert Gentry's book that provide another side:<br>
---Origins, v.15, n.1, p.32-38, "Examining Radiohalos," reviewed by R.H.Brown,<br>
H.G.Coffin, L.J.Gibson, A.A.Roth, and C.L.Webster (1988).<br>
---Spectrum, v.20, n.1, p.56-57, "Adventist Scientists &amp; Robert Gentry's<br>
Pleochroic Halos," reviewed by S.C.Rowland, R.E.Kingman, and M.V.Anderson<br>
(1989). <br>
<p>
If someone is interested, send your US postal address. I can photocopy the<br>
articles and send them to you. (That's assuming there aren't too many<br>
requests.) <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
