<title>Mar_1993: Translations</title>
<h1>Translations</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@hunter.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 23 Mar 1993 15:12:01 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#255">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#255">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#255">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#255">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0256.html">CHURMS@nacdh4.nac.ac.za: "Re: Addresses of fellow SDA academics in the US"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0254.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: In the presence of alcohol consumption"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The discussion on Bible translations in recent SDAnet<br>
messages brings to mind a discussion I had with one of the local<br>
OT linguistic scholars. He said:<br>
<p>
"The facts are that by the time of Christ there were at least<br>
three Hebrew resencions or variant textual copies. The Greek<br>
translation which became the (OT) bible of the New Testament world<br>
was amde from one of them by Jews living in Alexandria in Egypt.<br>
In Jeremiah that text was 20% shorter and more reliable than the <br>
longer text used for our English Bibles.<br>
<p>
"God Breathed" But like the 1611 edition of the KJV, that included<br>
the apocryphal books and others. Well, even though not everything<br>
in them was correct, Paul and John for example, still used those<br>
books. So what was there view of inspiration. It certainly<br>
wouldn't be verbal."<br>
<p>
The inspiration of scripture must surely transend any individual<br>
translation. I find comparisons of translations interesting,<br>
not because one is more inspired than another, but<br>
because it reflects on what others think is important.<br>
<p>
An interesting exercise to try and rewrite a piece of scripture<br>
in your own words. The result may not be inspired but it can <br>
be inspiring.<br>
<p>
Maurice Ashton<br>
Avondale College<br>
   .-_|\<br>
  /     \<br>
  \._--_/<br>
       V<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
