<title>Mar_1993: Re: Gentry's halos</title>
<h1>Re: Gentry's halos</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 24 Mar 1993 23:40:25 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#266">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#266">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#266">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#266">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0267.html">DOWE001%TSU.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Re: Battle Creek Aventist Hospital"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0265.html">Sherman Cox: "Spectrum"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0251.html">ben@orion.lasierra.edu: "Gentry's halos"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0272.html">Gary W Burdick: "Re: Creation Research Institute"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My family has been watching a series of creation videos.<br>
A few points worth mentioning.<br>
<p>
* First landing on the moon.  Recall the big pads on the langer and<br>
  large wheels on the rover.  Scientists had calculated that space<br>
  dust would have built up to a softly packed depth of 45 to 600<br>
  feet (my numbers may be off a bit).  There was only about 1/4 inch<br>
  which adds up to about 6,000 years.<br>
<p>
* Population growth models back up to about 4,500 years ago and not<br>
  millions of years ago.<br>
<p>
* The earth's magnetism has a half life of 1400 years.  That works<br>
  back nicely a few thousand years but not millions of years.<br>
<p>
* The large flying dinosaurs could not have flown in our atmosphere.<br>
  Atmosphere must have been over X2 density.<br>
<p>
* Dinosaur cardiovascular system could not have supported much activity<br>
  in our atmosphere.  Must have had X2+ density and more oxygen.<br>
<p>
* Plants and animals lower in the column have counterparts that are<br>
  similar or same as today -- club moss today 6 to 8 inches and<br>
  club moss back then 60 to 80 ft.  A superior atmosphere would<br>
  explain it.<br>
<p>
* Hospitals today that have hyperbaric chambers -- X2+ pressure and<br>
  higher oxygen -- result in much faster healing rates.<br>
<p>
* Skipping a lot of the detail, anyway, explains how pre-flood man<br>
  could live 800, 900 years in the pre-flood context.  Well, one<br>
  example of a Japanese scientist growing a giant tomato that has<br>
  lived 7+ years, over 30 ft tall, a few thousand tomatoes on it.<br>
<p>
* They are trying to get funding to build a hyperbaric biosphere<br>
  in which to experiment.<br>
<p>
* Scientists documenting that light slows ("gets tired") and red shifts.  <br>
  Method of calculating stars way out there millions of light years,<br>
  by red shift theory, appears to be flawed.  Accounting for this<br>
  new red shift theory, stars are not as far away as previously<br>
  calculated.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<p>
[I can't complain about these creation posts, because I started this thread.<br>
I don't like to destroy people's faith, but also I don't like to see them<br>
build their faith on the rubbish of charlatans.  In particular the <br>
"speed of light decay" stuff is the most contrived set of figures you have <br>
seen.  The work of the professor has been repudiated even by several <br>
of the creationist think tanks.  It involves going back to the earliest<br>
measurements in the 1600's with higher errors and slightly higher values,<br>
and fitting an incredulous function with no knowledge of the parameters<br>
that would make it significant.  Those creation advocates who insist on<br>
spouting discredited arguments are their own worst enemies.  I do not<br>
mean<br>
to say that all the arguments given above are spurious, some of them are not.<br>
But I do believe there is a great need for integrity of scientific method <br>
in the work of creation research.  The SDA Geoscience Research Institute<br>
has been more cautious than most in this regard, and it seems that they <br>
are making a genuine effort to support real scientific research nowadays.<br>
Two of their scientists are members of SDAnet.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
