<title>Mar_1993: RE: In the presence of alcohol consumption</title>
<h1>RE: In the presence of alcohol consumption</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 23 Mar 93 22:11:43 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#270">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#270">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#270">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#270">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0271.html">CHURMS@nacdh4.nac.ac.za: "Is shaky evidence good enough?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0269.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Maxwell"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	Terry Anderson writes:<br>
<p>
<i>	&gt;This perpetuates the common SDA fallacy that there is nothing between</i><br>
<i>	&gt;total abstinence and being in a drunken stupor.</i><br>
<p>
Thanks Terry for your viewpoint.  I tend to be on this end of the scale <br>
in a general<br>
social setting.  Socializing with people where there is alcohol is not <br>
the same as<br>
showing up in bars with them.<br>
<p>
Funny thing, a few Saturday nights ago, I went out - for the first time <br>
- with a particular<br>
set of friends who are not Christian, GASP.  After watching a movie <br>
which dealt with a<br>
day in late winter, a crazy guy and a prairie animal... achem, said <br>
friends and I were<br>
deciding on a nice place to sit and chat.  One friend rattle off about <br>
the closest bars in<br>
the area.  They both obviously had done the bars.  I cringed at the <br>
thought...<br>
"Someone'll see me there!  There's _got_ to be some other place, we can <br>
talk the<br>
hours away."<br>
<p>
And there was.  Just as I was gearing to set the limits as to where we <br>
were going to<br>
drink and talk, the other friend spoke up that a bar wouldn't be a good <br>
place.<br>
The reasoning?  Not because of the smoke, or severely inebriated people, but<br>
because of Marcus.  This friend said that we should meet at a place <br>
which fit my<br>
lifestyle.  I've seen it happen over and over, as I socialize with <br>
people and show them<br>
that people who don't drink, smoke, or do drugs, aren't just little old <br>
ladies with scarves<br>
on their silver-haired heads.<br>
<p>
In addition, I learn that not all people who drink alcohol are addicts. <br>
 But I've not included<br>
this (light drinking) into my list of "optionals", regarding serious <br>
dates, and future spouse.<br>
Any of you married types felt the same when you were single?<br>
<p>
Marcuss@microsoft<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
