<title>Mar_1993: Is shaky evidence good enough?</title>
<h1>Is shaky evidence good enough?</h1>
<i>CHURMS@nacdh4.nac.ac.za</i><br>
<i>25 Mar 1993 09:31:29 +0200</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#271">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#271">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#271">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#271">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0272.html">Gary W Burdick: "Re: Creation Research Institute"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0270.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: In the presence of alcohol consumption"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Steve<br>
<p>
I was glad to read your comments about the caution we should show with respect<br>
to the quality of the evidence we cite as supporting our beliefs.  I have<br>
unfortunately often been embarrassed when listening to evidence cited to<br>
support theories in which I believe, but which I know are not based on sound<br>
scientific (or hermaneutic) principles.<br>
<p>
One GOOD piece of evidence is worth one hundred shaky ones.<br>
<p>
One shaky piece of evidence can do untold harm in discrediting all the good<br>
evidence with which it is associated.<br>
<p>
Maranatha<br>
<p>
Cecil<br>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
