<title>Mar_1993: Re: Creation Research Institute</title>
<h1>Re: Creation Research Institute</h1>
Gary W Burdick (<i>burdick@hkuxa.hku.hk</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 25 Mar 93 14:41:38 WST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#272">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#272">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#272">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#272">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0273.html">Woody Baker: "Re: In the presence of alcohol consumption"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0271.html">CHURMS@nacdh4.nac.ac.za: "Is shaky evidence good enough?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0266.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Gentry's halos"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0274.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Re: Gentry's halos"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
DaveB writes: <br>
<i>&gt; My family has been watching a series of creation videos.</i><br>
<i>&gt; A few points worth mentioning.</i><br>
<p>
I have seen these videos, too.  I have the feeling that they make a<br>
number of valid points supporting creation.  However, any valid<br>
information seems to be well hidden amongst the speculation and<br>
fallacious reasoning.  For instance,<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; * Population growth models back up to about 4,500 years ago and not</i><br>
<i>&gt;   millions of years ago.</i><br>
<p>
Extrapolating population growth models back many thousands of years is<br>
valid only if you assume that ALL the other variables remain constant,<br>
such as political conditions, environmental conditions, birth rates,<br>
mortality rates, etc.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; * The earth's magnetism has a half life of 1400 years.  That works</i><br>
<i>&gt;   back nicely a few thousand years but not millions of years.</i><br>
<p>
They totally ignore evidences for multiple reversals of the earth's<br>
magnetic field, implying that the earth's magnetism varies cyclicly<br>
rather than as an exponential decay.<br>
<p>
The arguments regarding the hyperbaric biosphere seem intriguing, but<br>
I am not qualified to judge whether they are valid.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Gary W. Burdick (burdick@hkuxa.hku.hk)
Department of Physics, University of Hong Kong, Pokfulam Rd, HONG KONG
Phone: (852) 859 2369 or 859 2360 Fax: (852) 559 9152 Telex: 71919 CEREB HX
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
