<title>Mar_1993: Re: Gentry's halos</title>
<h1>Re: Gentry's halos</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 25 Mar 93 12:35:58 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#276">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#276">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#276">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#276">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0277.html">Sherman Cox: "Maxwell"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0275.html">Bill Allen: "LSU presidential search"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0251.html">ben@orion.lasierra.edu: "Gentry's halos"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0303.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Gentry's halos"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Subject: Re: Gentry's halos </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; My family has been watching a series of creation videos.</i><br>
<i>&gt; A few points worth mentioning.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; * First landing on the moon.  Recall the big pads on the langer and</i><br>
<i>&gt;   large wheels on the rover.  Scientists had calculated that space</i><br>
<i>&gt;   dust would have built up to a softly packed depth of 45 to 600</i><br>
<i>&gt;   feet (my numbers may be off a bit).  There was only about 1/4 inch</i><br>
<i>&gt;   which adds up to about 6,000 years.</i><br>
<p>
Other scientists thought otherwise, the "dust sea" idea wasn't expected<br>
to be highly likely even before the first Apollo landings (and Surveyor<br>
hadn't sank, either, on landing).<br>
<p>
One thing that most hadn't banked on before the landings was vacuum<br>
welding...many things brought in contact in vacuum eventually weld together.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; * Population growth models back up to about 4,500 years ago and not</i><br>
<i>&gt;   millions of years ago.</i><br>
<p>
Assumes constant growth rates...isn't this a form of uniformitarianism<br>
that creationists have railed against?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; * The earth's magnetism has a half life of 1400 years.  That works</i><br>
<i>&gt;   back nicely a few thousand years but not millions of years.</i><br>
<p>
I'd like to see the reference for this one.  (Other evidence suggests that<br>
the magnetic field periodically reverses itself.)  Extrapolating current<br>
trends too far?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; * The large flying dinosaurs could not have flown in our atmosphere.</i><br>
<i>&gt;   Atmosphere must have been over X2 density.</i><br>
<p>
Why not?  The biggest ones were about the size of a good-performing hang<br>
glider.  They seem to fly pretty well, without *any* power input from the<br>
pilot, given reasonable wind conditions.  I'd want a reference on this<br>
one, too.<br>
<p>
Paul MacReady (sp), whose team built the first successful man-powered aircraft,<br>
built (and flew) a radio-controlled pterodactyl for the Smithsonian a couple of<br>
years back.  It used some wing-flapping, but otherwise wasn't powered...come to<br>
think of it, I'm not absolutely sure about the flapping.  But it did perform<br>
adequately.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; * Scientists documenting that light slows ("gets tired") and red shifts.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;   Method of calculating stars way out there millions of light years,</i><br>
<i>&gt;   by red shift theory, appears to be flawed.  Accounting for this</i><br>
<i>&gt;   new red shift theory, stars are not as far away as previously</i><br>
<i>&gt;   calculated.</i><br>
<p>
I thought that "tired light" was on pretty shakey grounds...<br>
<p>
It's too easy to make a video tape with all sorts of claims on it,<br>
but I'd like to see a *lot* better evidence that the claims have merit.<br>
<p>
sorry.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
