<title>Mar_1993: Why the SDA church needs liberals</title>
<h1>Why the SDA church needs liberals</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 25 Mar 1993 22:38:57 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#282">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#282">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#282">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#282">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0283.html">Woody Baker: "RE: In the presence of alcohol consumption"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0281.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Adventist thought"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0288.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Re: Why the SDA church needs liberals"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In the ongoing discussion on the CHRISTIA list, I find it amazing that <br>
none of the SDA's who were posting, (including myself, Ruben, Tony,<br>
and Noe Torres, who just joined the net) flamed each other, although<br>
we were really expressing rather divergent points of view.  <br>
<p>
It's interesting that although the critics on the liberal side have <br>
been loud and vocal, no liberal offshoot has emerged, and there is no <br>
immediate threat of one.  Nor do church administrators seem to take<br>
this threat anywhere near as seriously as the threat of a conservative<br>
offshoot.  In fact, people such as Desmond Ford and Walter Rea still <br>
hold membership in the SDA church, though they are by no means active.<br>
<p>
I think this has to do with the nature of the liberal arguments<br>
than anything else.  Whoever it was that suggested the beasts of Daniel 7<br>
were social ills didn't say "This is the One True Interpretation<br>
and those who disagree are Antichrist."  They merely suggested that this <br>
is another idea that can be drawn from that passage.  This is the <br>
way many of these arguments are made, not negating the other argument,<br>
but just putting out an alternative interpretation.  Desmond Ford was<br>
an exception to this in that he said not only his new theory, but<br>
also that the SDA doctrine was wrong.  <br>
<p>
The liberal arguments force us to think about what would we do if the <br>
knowledge we base our beliefs on were shown to be wrong.  If carried to <br>
the extreme, it forces us to look at the bare bones of our faith to see<br>
what are the really necessary things for belief.  Often when attacks<br>
on the faith come, we defend on a line of defense that is inaccurate<br>
or indefensible.  I am impressed by those who are able to yield almost<br>
every point put forth by the liberals, and yet maintain their faith.<br>
<p>
I am not comfortable making some of the liberal arguments myself, so I <br>
tend to find a group that is liberal enough so that I can be a conservative.<br>
Fortunately these groups are in large supply.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
