<title>Mar_1993: RE: In the presence of alcohol consumption</title>
<h1>RE: In the presence of alcohol consumption</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 25 Mar 1993 08:36:50 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#283">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#283">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#283">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#283">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0284.html">Steven Timm: "Baptism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0282.html">Steven Timm: "Why the SDA church needs liberals"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
DONT INCLUDE (light drinking).  If you don't drink, make SURE your<br>
mate doesn't also.  From my experience there are several major issues that <br>
you absolutly have to have resolved.  Make SURE that you are both settled<br>
as to whether you want kids or don't.  I don't want anything to do with<br>
kids.  Have never really wanted anything to do with kids. My wife desperately<br>
wants kids.  Before we got married, we decided that we would adopt after<br>
7 years.  Well it is nearly 10 years, and I still don't want kids.  Over<br>
the years of dealing with my sister-in-law and her kids, I have come to the<br>
conclusion that kids just don't fit with my lifestyle.  This is an underlying<br>
stress in our marriage, though it has not caused any major problems.  I <br>
suspect that we will be adopting in the next couple of years, but it will be<br>
a 6 to 9 year old.  I have many and varied reasons, some of which include<br>
the state of the current world.  (I feel it is morally wrong to add another<br>
mouth to the worlds burden, and bring up a kid in this current enviorment).<br>
To me, it is also the ultimate act of selfishness, when there are lots of <br>
kids who don't have a home or family, to bring a child into the world.  There<br>
are other considerations also, such as the fact that I have a low tolerance<br>
to stupid people.  If I created anything less than a above average IQ child<br>
I would really have problems.  A birthdefect would really sink me.  I could<br>
not handle it.  <br>
<p>
Another thing to get straight (it is critical) is how money is handled, and<br>
how decisions are handled.  In our marriage, Marilyn and I have decided that the<br>
person most affected has the final word in decisions.  This goes for purchasing<br>
decisions as well as other ones.  This model works well. <br>
<p>
Additionaly, resolve who fixes the pineapple. ???????????!!!!!!!!!!1??????????<br>
<p>
Yep, think about this.  This is a true story.  We got married in 1983 and<br>
moved to Austin shortly thereafter.  I went to work for Motorola as thier<br>
first software application engineer.  We were starting out, and so to make<br>
the budget stretch, we furnished our house from flea-markets and garage-sales.<br>
(I LOVE flea-markets).  Anyway, we found a really great deal on dead-ripe<br>
pinapples one day.  .50 each.  I bought 6 of them.  We lined them up on the<br>
kitchen counter.  And that is where they sat.  one spoiled, and got thrown<br>
away. Another one spoiled and got thrown away. and so on.  Finaly there were<br>
2 left, at which time I exploded. Periodicaly I would say, "why don't we<br>
have a pinapple tonight" to which Marilyn would say "that sounds good."<br>
During my explosion I demanded to know why she was just letting the pinapples<br>
rot down, and why SHE had not fixed them.  I was informed in a pleasant tone<br>
that peeling the pineapples was MY job. ??????????!!!!!!!!!<br>
It turns out that in my family my MOTHER always peeled and prepared the pine-<br>
apples, and in Marilyn's family her father always peeled and prepared the<br>
pineapples.  So here we were, waiting around for the other one to fix the<br>
pinapples, and they were rotting down.<br>
<p>
I got busy and fixed the pineapples.  However, the underlying core of this<br>
is people have differing role models, and you need to clearly define them<br>
and explore them first.<br>
<p>
Try to get to an engaged encounter or marriage enrichment seminar.  It will<br>
be worth your time.  Another thing that we did, was to pay a SDA marriage<br>
councilor many visits and much money (grin, the best 450.00 or so I've<br>
ever spent).  We went there with some minor problems to deal with, and<br>
discovered that there were some major ones we did not know about.  The man<br>
was invaluable in helping us deal with them, and work through them and<br>
without his help we never would have gotten married.  We are quite happily<br>
married, and have a much better than average relationship.<br>
<p>
Gotta go now, but perhaps I'll try to post our question list. For the first<br>
several years we set aside an hour or two every sunday to write down the<br>
answers to a list of 45 or so questions, then exchanged our answers and<br>
discussed them with each other.  It headed off blowups, pressures, etc. <br>
<p>
the habit slipped and we don't, do it any more. I think we are going<br>
to start doing it again.  It makes things go SO much easier...<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
<p>
woody@knapper.cactus.org
woody@chinacat.unicom.com (temporary) is forwareded to woody@knapper
</pre>
