<title>Mar_1993: SDA: Creation Science</title>
<h1>SDA: Creation Science</h1>
Brian Hartman (<i>hartbr@wwc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 26 Mar 93 10:10:26 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#285">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#285">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#285">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#285">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0286.html">Terry L Anderson 908-580-4428: "Adventist thought &amp; Spectrum"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0284.html">Steven Timm: "Baptism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Pre script:<br>
Could everyone put a "SDA:" in front of their subject headings?  I get<br>
upwards of 50 mail messages a day and I (and I would guess others feel<br>
the same) would love to be able to identify SDANet mail traffic by looking<br>
at the subject heading.<br>
<p>
<p>
I would like to comment on the creation video that people have been<br>
discussing.<br>
<p>
I feel that the creation cause is really lacking in the way of good scientific<br>
evidence.  This video attempts to show that creation is really a scientific<br>
theory and that there are hosts of good data sets to back it up.  I have<br>
a real problem with saying something is science just because it sounds<br>
good.  The video made alot of claims, very few of which were backed up<br>
by published scientific papers. <br>
<p>
I am a biology student at Walla Walla<br>
College and I just finished a class called Philosophy of Origins and<br>
Speciation.  In that class we came upon less than ten, I repeat, less<br>
than ten published scientific papers that came to bear upon the current<br>
understanding of a scientific view of creation.  Perhaps there are thousands<br>
more papers that we did not see, but I would dare say that there are not<br>
very many scientific papers that support a short-term chronology.<br>
<p>
<p>
Creationists CANNOT claim that they have a "scientific" theory on the basis <br>
of ten or even 20 papers.  I think that we need to be honest with our<br>
evolutionist friends that science has not really been good to the creation<br>
cause.  This may simply be because there have been at least 10,000 times as<br>
many evolution researchers than creation researchers, or because the money<br>
spent on evolution research is probably at a ratio of  100,000 dollars to<br>
every one dollar spent on creation research.  BUT, that still does not give<br>
us as creationists the right to claim that we have as much scientific <br>
evidence as the evolutionists.  Creationists sometimes tend to speculate<br>
and then call that speculation science.<br>
<p>
I feel that creation must be taken on faith.  Sure, there is currently some<br>
scientific evidence for a young earth, but WE ARE NOT GOING TO BRING PEOPLE<br>
INTO THE SDA CHURCH BY "PROVING" TO THEM THAT GOD CREATED THE EARTH.  That<br>
we have to take by faith.  God and his miracles do not fit into science.  <br>
Science only operates on what we can see and our perceptions may be flawed.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Brian Hartman<br>
Walla Walla College<br>
email: hartbr@wwc.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
