<title>Mar_1993: Adventist thought &amp; Spectrum</title>
<h1>Adventist thought &amp; Spectrum</h1>
Terry L Anderson 908-580-4428 (<i>tla@mozart.att.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 26 Mar 93 08:44:34 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#286">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#286">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#286">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#286">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0287.html">Steven Timm: "Why the SDA church needs conservatives"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0285.html">Brian Hartman: "SDA: Creation Science"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0281.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Adventist thought"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
    He talked about the magazine Spectrum.  I have heard of it, but he talked of <br>
    that magazine writing the view that the beasts were social ills and that<br>
    the remnant were social activists.  Does anyone know about this.  I have<br>
    never subscribed to the magazine.  Does it routinely print such things that <br>
    are so far out of adventist thought?<br>
<p>
Since no one else familiar with Spectrum has replied to this let me<br>
try.  I read Spectrum regularly and am listed on the "Spectrum<br>
Advisory Board" or some such title - this means I contribute to it<br>
financially on a regular basis - not that I have anything to do with<br>
setting editorial direction.  Although I confess I sometimes get<br>
behind in my reading and cannot claim to have read every article, I do<br>
not recall any recent article advocating the views you meantion.<br>
<p>
But one thing should be kept in mind about Spectrum -- Spectrum is<br>
published by the Association of Adventist Forums, a group of SDA<br>
members but the organization has no official connection to the church<br>
organization.  And unlike most journals published by the church,<br>
Spectrum has no mission to get teach or push a particular point of<br>
view.  It does solicit some of its articles in order to cluster<br>
articles reflecting a number of viewpoints on a single subject into<br>
one issue, but most of the articles are contributed unsolicited.  Its<br>
mission is to provide a forum (hence the name of the organization) for<br>
discussion of various viewpoints.  It tries to include both<br>
traditional viewpoints as well as those that challange traditional<br>
views.  Most authors are sympathetic to SDA tradition and strong<br>
believers in the SDA church but think that we do not have all the<br>
truth yet and must keep seeking better understanding by considering<br>
and reconsidering the details of our belief - not the fundamentals but<br>
the details (of course not all can agree on the separation of<br>
fundamentals and details).<br>
<p>
But my main point is that NO article or viewpoint reflects a position<br>
of the journal.  Its mission is to air many viewpoints, so it has no<br>
single consistent viewpoint.  There may occationally be an article<br>
that you would consider "far out of adventist thought" -- this<br>
challanges us to defend our traditions and often the same issue will<br>
contain other articles doing precisely that.<br>
<p>
<p>
			     --	Terry L Anderson<br>
				AT&amp;T Bell Laboratories, RM 3D-481<br>
				600 Mountain Av, Murray Hill, NJ 07974<br>
				UUCP:	...!att!mozart!tla<br>
