<title>Mar_1993: pitfalls to avoid</title>
<h1>pitfalls to avoid</h1>
<i>ben@orion.lasierra.edu</i><br>
<i>Fri, 26 Mar 1993 11:06:17 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#295">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#295">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#295">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#295">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0296.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Things"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0294.html">Sherman Cox: "Adventist Believe"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
At the recent field conferences that the Geoscience Research Institute held in<br>
Australia and New Zealand, we included one lecture on pitfalls to avoid.<br>
Included in that were: pleochroic halos, change in the speed of light, claims<br>
for discovery of Noah's ark, and Paluxy River footprints. The lecture was split<br>
up between three of us. We completely agree with Cecil's comment that "One<br>
shaky piece of evidence can do untold harm in discrediting all the good<br>
evidence with which it is associated." <br>
<p>
-------------------------------------- <br>
<p>
comments on: Decay in the Speed of Light suggested by Trevor Norman and<br>
Barry Setterfield. This has been discussed at length by several conservative<br>
creation groups that would like this evidence, but don't find it convincing.<br>
<p>
---Gerald E. Aardsma, "Has the Speed of Light Decayed?", Institute for Creation<br>
Research, Impact No. 179 (May 1988).<br>
---D. Russell Humphreys, "Has the Speed of Light Decayed Recently?", Creation<br>
Research Society Quarterly, vol. 25, p.40-45 (June 1988).<br>
---Maurie G. Evered / Alan Montgomery / Trevor Norman, (several articles),<br>
Creation ex Nihilo Technical Journal, vol. 5 (part 2), p. 94-122 (1991).<br>
<p>
They make several points:<br>
(1)	Setterfield made a least squares fit to the data, but not weighted by<br>
the errors for each point. Weighting the oldest data points by their large<br>
errors would significantly decrease their importance. <br>
(2)	Setterfield corrected some of the old data; however, other old data<br>
that fit his theory were not corrected. <br>
(3)	It has been noted in general that scientific measurements done over<br>
many years do approach today's accepted value from one side. This is just due<br>
to psychology - scientists don't want their new measurements to be too much<br>
different from the previous measurements. <br>
(4)	According to Setterfield, not only is the speed of light decaying, but<br>
in addition, the rate of decay has been decreasing. "Fortuitously," this rate<br>
of decrease has only recently become too small to measure, when technically it<br>
would be possible. A quote from Humphreys, "Why should the rate of change of c<br>
diminish in direct proportion to our ability to measure c more accurately?" <br>
<p>
-------------------------<br>
<p>
comments on decay of earth's magnetic field:<br>
--- note the following abstract<br>
<p>
	The earth has possessed a magnetic field for most of its history. It is<br>
therefore strange that the present-day field is changing so rapidly: at the<br>
recent rate of decay the magnetic field will be removed altogether in the next<br>
1500 years.If this fall persists, as seems likely, our future magnetic<br>
environment would be quite different from that of today. A long term program of<br>
observation and development of theory for the origin of the magnetic field are<br>
needed in order to understand the processes influencing the magnetic field. <br>
---David Gubbins, "Geomagnetism: the next millenium," Palaeogeography,<br>
Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology (Global and Planetary Change Section), 89<br>
(1990) 255-262. {published by Elsevier}<br>
<p>
However, this type of evidence shouldn't be used to prove a recent creation as<br>
noted by <br>
---Ivan E. Rouse, "Paleomagnetism II," Origins, v.10, n.2, p.66-89 (1983).<br>
He notes three problems for Barnes free decay model:<br>
(1)	Magnetic age dating is more rigidly uniformitarian than the<br>
uniformitarianism of conventional geologists.<br>
(2)	Paleomagnetic intensity measurements indicate that the<br>
earth's magnetic field has been decreasing in intensity only in the last<br>
2800 years and more rapidly only in the last 800 years. {note the only}<br>
(3)	The equation developed for predicting past inensities of the earth's<br>
magnetic field is entirely arbitrary.<br>
<p>
------------------------<br>
<p>
I don't believe that the scientific evidence is overwhelming for a recent<br>
creation of life or Noah's world wide flood. However, much evidence can be fit<br>
into either a short-age or a long-age model and some evidence appears to fit<br>
better into a short time scale. For me, the GOOD evidence is sufficient to<br>
be comfortable with a short time scale for life on earth, without using the<br>
eye-catching "proofs" that people are so anxious for.<br>
<p>
------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
Someone asked about GRI scientists:<br>
<p>
Ariel Roth, Director --- Ph.D. in biology from University of Michigan, with<br>
additional coursework in geology from University of California, Riverside /<br>
his research interest is coral reefs and coral growth rates.<br>
<p>
Ben Clausen --- Ph.D. in physics from University of Colorado / research in<br>
nuclear structure done at a number of US and foreign accelerators / SDAnet<br>
member <br>
<p>
Jim Gibson --- Ph.D. in biology from Loma Linda University / research interest<br>
in biogeography<br>
<p>
Elaine Kennedy --- Ph.D. in geology from University of Southern California /<br>
research interest in sedimentology / SDAnet member<br>
<p>
Clyde Webster --- Ph.D. in geochemistry from Colorado State University /<br>
research on uranium roll-front deposits and geochemistry of volcanic deposits<br>
at the Yellowstone Fossil Forests<br>
<p>
------------------------<br>
<p>
Ben Clausen<br>
Geoscience Research Institute<br>
Loma Linda University<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
