<!-- body="start" -->
On Mar 23,  3:32pm, Ruben Gonzalez wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re: Things</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; You are brazenly suggesting that those reading the NIV are reading material</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; written in the spirit of the antichrist.  Dream on..</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Thats for you to decide, all I have done is presented a simple hypthesis.</i><br>
<p>
By not denying this you are agreeing with it.  I think it very sad that someone would<br>
actually discourage people from using the Bible, regardless of the version.  I think<br>
we as Christians should be strongly encouraging Bible usage by all and not be<br>
concerned with whether this version or that is used just because the wording in a few<br>
places of one version doesn't say it the same way another version you prefer does.<br>
<p>
The examples you cited were trivial (IMHO) in that the wording was changed to clear<br>
up some old english.  But the main meaning was still there and unchanged when taken<br>
in context of the passages.  The phrases that you accused of being removed were<br>
removed because it is a phrase not used in today's english language...at least where<br>
I live.<br>
<p>
So if, for example, "in the flesh" is to be taken out due to its old english, what<br>
would you put in its place if YOU were re-writing the Bible text in question?  Any<br>
thing you state in reply I could accuse as being anti-christ because you have changed<br>
the all inportant phrase "in the flesh" to something else...but I won't.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt;.I believe there will be a</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; lot of folks saved and in heaven who only knew and read the NIV or ASV, or</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; even the Living Bible (should I guess it's too heretical to even mention).</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Hey many will be saved who have kept Sunday all their lives too.</i><br>
<p>
Are you catagorizing those who read the NIV with those who are ignorant of and don't<br>
keep the Sabbath?  I am sorry but even my KJV does not say "thou shalt not read the<br>
NIV".  Reading the NIV is not equal to keeping Sunday in my mind.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; You know sometimes you need to make really shocking statments like Jesus did</i><br>
<i>&gt; (eat my flesh, drink my blood) in order to get people to look behind the</i><br>
<i>&gt; superficials. Of couse whenever you do some will always write you off and</i><br>
<i>&gt; have nothing to do with you any more, but I suppose thats the cost.</i><br>
<p>
In spite of the pompous words, I still believe the NIV is just fine for people to<br>
read...(as is the KJV and the ASB and the RSV and the original Greek).  If they work<br>
for you then read them.<br>
<p>
How about spending your bandwidth time building up people's faith in the Word of God<br>
instead of trying to tear it down.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
