<i>&gt; Hallo Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt; I need for another time your help. </i><br>
<i>&gt; I need the email address of the OFFICE OF GLOBAL MISSION </i><br>
<i>&gt; in Silver Spring (if they are connected to a net).</i><br>
<i>&gt; Thousand thanks for your help.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Siegmar</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I just returned from a trip to Washington, DC, and while there paid a<br>
visit to the GC.  I'll report on issues related to the net later when<br>
I've caught up a bit.  Among other things, I picked up a so-called SDA<br>
E-Mail Directory (more on that later).  It appears to be mostly ATT Mail<br>
addresses (no Internet ones that I can see), and it is also in no<br>
discernible order.  The list is 4 pages long (I also got a<br>
machine-readable copy which I hope to be able to figure out a way to<br>
post to the list).  For GC Global Mission I see M.Ryan/H.Butler listed<br>
for Global Mission Portable Computer 1--A11111GLOBAL.  I also see one<br>
for Mike Ryan, GC Global Mission Coordinator--A11111GLOCOR.  For<br>
Internet access, I understand that one uses the ATT account (user ID)<br>
followed by @attmail.com.  I have used this for Carlos Medley at the<br>
Adventist Review, and it works.  It appears that the GC ATT accounts all<br>
start with A followed by 5 1's.  Next week I'll try to follow this up<br>
with the actual list, plus some discussion of some issues I see<br>
associated with this.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
[Harvey is correct, all AT+T accounts can be reached by sending to <br>
userid@attmail.com  The three issues I see are these:  (1), can Internet<br>
access be gotten by some cheaper means than attmail?  (2) If we put these <br>
GC officers on SDAnet and deluge their accounts with E-mail, might this<br>
turn them off from E-mail altogether?  (3)  If people knew that high<br>
General conference leadership was listening, would the character of SDAnet <br>
change into a gripefest?  SCT]<br>
