<title>Mar_1993: Re: Gentry's halos</title>
<h1>Re: Gentry's halos</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 26 Mar 1993 10:10:07 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#303">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#303">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#303">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#303">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0304.html">Malcolm Butler: "If the GC were on SDAnet"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0302.html">Paul Gates: "Why the SDA church needs conservatives"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0251.html">ben@orion.lasierra.edu: "Gentry's halos"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Several people have asked about my signature line.  I am a flint-knapper<br>
(one of my hobbies).  That means I make stone tools like the native americans.<br>
Arrowheads, knives, spearpoints etc.etc.  These are made by knocking flakes<br>
off flint, obsidian, chert, jasper, agate etc. (any silicious, non-crystalline<br>
elastic material).  Usualy I use copper billets (it is easier to get than<br>
good antler, and works nearly as well), but I do use a lot of moose antler<br>
batons/billets, and a hammerstone now and then.  I work the flakes or the<br>
core into stone tools with precussion and pressure flaking.  Bone or antler<br>
makes good pressure flakers, but once again I prefer copper.  (I use both).<br>
Doing this produces a good deal of *VERY* sharp edges and flakes, and you DO<br>
get cut.  It is unavoidable.<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
