<title>Mar_1993: If the GC were on SDAnet</title>
<h1>If the GC were on SDAnet</h1>
Malcolm Butler (<i>malb@boojum.ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 28 Mar 93 1:57:09 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#304">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#304">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#304">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#304">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0305.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "SDA: Recent creation &amp; God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0303.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Gentry's halos"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0290.html">Steven Timm: "Info (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steven Timm writes:<br>
<i>&gt; If we put these </i><br>
<i>&gt;GC officers on SDAnet and deluge their accounts with E-mail, might this</i><br>
<i>&gt;turn them off from E-mail altogether?  </i><br>
<p>
There are ways of controlling email access in a managable fashion.<br>
As an extreme example, I believe the White House is now attached to<br>
various email networks (including the Internet).  However, their<br>
connection operates by having a droid print each message and forward it<br>
through the normal paper channels inside the White House, so it doesn't<br>
give any particular advantage (except perhaps cost and ease of use) to<br>
the email user.  This isn't necessarily the best way to do it, the point<br>
is that just because someone uses email doesn't mean that the whole<br>
world has unfettered access to them.  (Apparently the White House is<br>
examining ways to streamline the situation.)<br>
<p>
At any rate, it seems to me that there are ways in which they could be<br>
provided with SDAnet access without getting deluged with regular email.<br>
In the worst case, they could resort to clumsy devices like receiving<br>
SDAnet mail under one alias, and posting from another.  Any mail can<br>
received at the posting address can be sent to /dev/null (or maybe to a<br>
secretary, the mail-person, or whoever).  Given good filtering tools, it<br>
should be able to set up a much better arrangement.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;(3)  If people knew that high</i><br>
<i>&gt;General conference leadership was listening, would the character of SDAnet </i><br>
<i>&gt;change into a gripefest?</i><br>
<p>
We need to decide what we want SDAnet to be: our "hotline" to the GC,<br>
or the general discussion forum that it is now.  I would like to think<br>
that it would remain a free and open forum in which (almost) anything<br>
can be discussed, and if the GC wants to be in on that, then by all<br>
means, plug them in.  The question is whether we get a "them-and-us"<br>
mentality, or if it's merely them joining in to what we are already<br>
doing.  (See? I'm already referring to it in those terms.)  This would be<br>
influenced as much by what the GC people say on SDAnet, as by what we<br>
say about them.<br>
<p>
One of the distinct advantages of email over other discussion forums is<br>
that it is possible to conduct discussions in parallel, so if you don't<br>
like one, you can ignore it and stick to the ones you do like.  If the<br>
flames get too much, there are technical means for separating the<br>
discussions.  If people want the chance to flame the GC, maybe there's<br>
scope for a separate mailing list for that purpose.  (Any takers?)<br>
However, used wisely, SDAnet is a unique opportunity for them to at<br>
least listen in on some of the "grassroots" of the church population.<br>
<p>
<p>
Malcolm<br>
<pre>
-- 
Switched Networks Research Centre,               malb@ee.uts.edu.au
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia            +61 2 330 2344
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
