<title>Mar_1993: SDA: Recent creation &amp; God</title>
<h1>SDA: Recent creation &amp; God</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>28 Mar 1993 11:02:29 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#305">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#305">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#305">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#305">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0306.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "SDA: Waggoner &amp; Jones"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0304.html">Malcolm Butler: "If the GC were on SDAnet"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As a Christian and a scientist, I too am a little disturbed by some of<br>
the "Creation Science" videos and publications that I see. Although I<br>
agree with most of what Brian said in his post, there is one small point<br>
I would like to comment on.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
I feel that creation must be taken on faith.  Sure, there is currently some<br>
scientific evidence for a young earth, but WE ARE NOT GOING TO BRING PEOPLE<br>
INTO THE SDA CHURCH BY "PROVING" TO THEM THAT GOD CREATED THE EARTH.  That<br>
&lt;---<br>
<p>
I may be wrong, but there seems to be an implicit assumption here that if<br>
God did indeed create the Earth, he did so by "recent creation", and that<br>
any other position denies the creatorship of God. Brian seems to have<br>
equated "young earth" with "creation" in this passage.<br>
<p>
I myself am *definitely* a creationist, but at this stage I find the<br>
evidence for a young earth very shaky. I don't see any inconsistency in<br>
my believing that God created everything, and at the same time my being<br>
unsure of the how, when, and how quickly. Forcing people to choose *between*<br>
positions that are not by nature mutually exclusive can have unfortunate<br>
results. (eg, was EG White inspired, or did she copy from other authors?)<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
