<title>Mar_1993: SDA: Waggoner &amp; Jones</title>
<h1>SDA: Waggoner &amp; Jones</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>28 Mar 1993 11:10:12 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#306">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#306">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#306">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#306">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0307.html">Cam Litvin: "Re: Baptism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0305.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "SDA: Recent creation &amp; God"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Whilst following some of the discussion on bit.listserv.christia, I noticed<br>
one remark which puzzled me somewhat. I quote:<br>
<p>
"In 1888, a couple of men barnstormed the church with the doctrine of<br>
Righteousness by Faith. This issue is still a diving (sic) teaching in the<br>
church today. What these men, mainly Waggoner and Jones, taught was a<br>
confusion of Protestant and Catholic theology, foreign to both, and friendly<br>
to none.<br>
<p>
They taught that man must still keep the OT law perfectly, but that Christ<br>
does it inside the believer. Some of you will agree with this, but it is<br>
folly and untrue"<br>
<p>
The main material I have read on 1888 is George Knight's book "From 1888 to<br>
Apostasy", along with some of the papers in the 1988 Ministry magazine issue.<br>
Does anyone know what this guy means by "a confusion of Protestant and <br>
Catholic theology" etc.? And was Waggoner &amp; Jones' message about law keeping?<br>
I got the impression that they were responding to a legalistic/perfectionistic<br>
swing within the church at that time, where people were getting their<br>
priorities a bit mixed up, focussing on law rather than on Christ.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
