<title>May_1993: re: female homosexuality in the bible?</title>
<h1>re: female homosexuality in the bible?</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 17 May 93 11:43:45 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#111">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#111">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#111">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#111">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0112.html">Marcus Stringer: "Thought..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0110.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Promises for Sabbath Problems"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0108.html">Steven Timm: "female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0122.html">Floyd Poenitz: "Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Again, I'm not "Bible scholar" but....<br>
<p>
Romans 1:26 says:<br>
	For this reason God gave them up to vile passions.<br>
	For even their women exchanged the natural use for<br>
	what is against nature.<br>
<p>
To get the full picture (context) we have to read all of chapter 1<br>
and on into chapter 3, where he crowns his thought with "there<br>
is non righteous, no, not one."(Rom 3:10)  In these chapters Paul<br>
seems to be painting a relationship between homosexual<br>
practices and idolatry (same as in OT).  Verses (26 and 27) come<br>
after a detailed description of a world  that "exchanged the truth of<br>
God for a lie, and worshiped and served created things rather<br>
than the Creator."  Again, as in the OT, the main issues seem to be<br>
lust, "unnaturalness," and, in verse 28, a desire to avoid<br>
acknowledgment of God.<br>
<p>
These verses, and in fact the entire Bible says nothing about<br>
the assumption that same-sex relationships can be "natural".<br>
So the Hawaii Marriage issue is too advanced.  Assumptions and facts<br>
at square ONE must fist be resolved.  I trust that all would agree that<br>
"homosexuals" (for the sake of this discussion) do not own the market<br>
on "exchanging the truths of God for a lie, or worshiping and serving<br>
created things rather than the Creator."  Paul seems to be headed in a<br>
different direction than "homosexual activity is sin, and that's that."<br>
<p>
I'm not prepared to say that all "homosexuals" are trying to avoid<br>
acknowledging God, through continuance of "unnatural" sexual<br>
activity.  Furthermore, I'm no more prepared to separate their sexual<br>
activity from their overall "personhood", than I am to do the same for<br>
"heterosexuals."  As our sexualities are only a part of our Whole Self<br>
(spiritual, mental, physical).  And since I don't know the whole story<br>
behind each "homosexual" person, I an not in position to judge.<br>
The "Church" which has traditionally done the least in the area of<br>
understanding, repeatedly seems the most poised to judge.<br>
<p>
The Church has practiced two approaches in its judgment of<br>
"homosexuals."  It has either tried to change them (see: Quest Learning<br>
Center/Colin Cook) or it has disfellowshiped them.  Granted that this<br>
is far less bloody than the pronouncement Leviticus places on them...<br>
but of course gay-bashing in the street has no connection to that coming<br>
from the pulpit - DOES it?<br>
<p>
Marcus (displaced Social Wkr....) Stringer<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
