<!-- received="Wed Apr 28 12:44:05 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Wed, 28 Apr 1993 12:44:05 -0400 (EDT)" -->
<!-- name="Harvey Brenneise" -->
<!-- email="brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Playboy, the James White Library and Censorship" -->
<!-- id="9304281644.AA02253@edmund.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>May_1993: Playboy, the James White Library and Censorship</title>
<h1>Playboy, the James White Library and Censorship</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Apr 1993 12:44:05 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#1">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#1">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#1">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#1">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0002.html">(no name): "Re: $100/500 million question"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0000.html">Dan Drazen: "Re: Has anyone heard of NLP?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It's interesting how persistent the rumor of the James White Library<br>
subscribing to _Playboy_ has been.  That rumor was around when I was a<br>
student in the early '70's.  In fact, when as a graduate student I had<br>
access to what was then the closed portion of the periodical stacks<br>
(spending hours reading microfilmed music reviews of the Metropolitan<br>
Opera), I spent some time (to no avail) seeing if I could fine said<br>
magazines.<br>
<p>
I have only learned a bit more of this story since coming back to the<br>
library as one of the librarians.  The James White Library does not now,<br>
nor has it ever subscribed to _Playboy_.  It is true that _Playboy_ has<br>
information in it that is not pornographic which might be useful in<br>
doing research.  It was because a specific student needed some of this<br>
information that the library obtained one (or possibly a few) rolls of<br>
the back issues of this magazine on microfilm much as we would obtain<br>
information on interlibrary loan.  This was never added to the<br>
collection.  It was made available to that student and kept in a<br>
non-public area.  At a much later date when there was evidence that it<br>
may have been viewed after hours (probably by a night watchman) it was<br>
discarded.<br>
<p>
The mission of the library supports the mission of the university.  One<br>
part of that mission is to make research materials available to the<br>
university community.  This was one way to accomplish that.  Another<br>
would have been interlibrary loan.  In the words of one of my esteemed<br>
library school professors (Lester Asheim), libraries should select<br>
materials that meet their mission rather than censor materials that<br>
might offend some users.  In the university working policy is a<br>
statement that the library supports the Library Bill of Rights of the<br>
American Library Association.  Part of that bill of rights is that we do<br>
not censor materials which we do not agree with.<br>
<p>
Because of that, the library owns many items which the library, the<br>
university, the church as an institution or individual church members<br>
might not agree with.  Not only does the library need to select (but not<br>
censor), but each individual needs to select materials appropriate for<br>
themselves without expecting that the library will censor (for everyone<br>
else) what they do not approve of.  The library owns materials on a wide<br>
variety of topics (religion, science, social issues, etc.) that some<br>
users don't agree with, and might even find offensive.  Users have the<br>
right to not use what they find distasteful, but not to censor it for<br>
others.  The library also does not act "in loco parentis."  Parents are<br>
responsible for what their children see or borrow.  A university library<br>
by definition has to take such a stance.  Too many Adventists appear to<br>
have gotten into a habit of "groupthink" where the group (or some<br>
members of the group) makes selection about what is appropriate, leaving<br>
the individual with little responsibility for their own selections.<br>
This applies to music, reading, cinema and other areas.  The library<br>
simply cannot operate this way.<br>
<p>
Now, lest anyone think we've got all kinds of wild things in the<br>
collection, our collection development policy specifically requires that<br>
the curricula of the schools drive the purchasing decisions.  We don't<br>
have a research interest in pornography, so don't need such magazines as<br>
_Playboy_.  It's also not indexed in the periodical indexes that our<br>
students commonly use.  We do have access to needed information it, or<br>
other magazines (e.g. _Rolling Stone_) as mentioned above.  _Playboy_ is<br>
and should be in other libraries that have other missions.  <br>
<p>
In closing, we emphasize the positive in selection rather than trying to<br>
find the negative (which is censorship).  I hope we don't get to the<br>
situation that exists at Brigham Young University, where members of the<br>
community come in an censor things themselves, even going to the lengths<br>
of cutting out individual microform frames.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
