<title>May_1993: Re: Has anyone heard of NLP?</title>
<h1>Re: Has anyone heard of NLP?</h1>
Dan Drazen (<i>drazen@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 2 May 1993 14:43:12 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#0">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#0">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#0">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#0">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Playboy, the James White Library and Censorship"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;    Has anyone heard of NLP (Neural-Linguistic Programming)?  I've just</i><br>
<i>&gt; heard a bit about it and would like to know if any of you have more </i><br>
<i>&gt; information about it?  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; --John (jash@eecs.wsu.edu)</i><br>
<i>&gt; KB7ONG</i><br>
<p>
John:<br>
<p>
Depending on who you talk to, neurolinguistic programming (NLP for<br>
short) is either a) a merely descriptive term for how information is<br>
processed on the individual level, or b) proof positive that "Adventist<br>
pastors have been trained to use hypnosis in their visitations and<br>
counseling...transferring their knowledge to unsuspecting lay<br>
volunteers."  Those who hold to the latter view tend to belong to the<br>
GC-basher crowd; a recent John Osborne pamphlet alluded to the sinister<br>
uses of NLP on its cover.  Clearly, we're talking heavy stuff here.<br>
<p>
The plain, prosaic truth of the matter is this: Back in the 1970's, LEAD<br>
Consultants (an interdenominational training group) put together a<br>
pastoral visitation training manual with the title "A Laboratory School<br>
on Skills for Calling and Caring Ministries."  Since this didn't exactly<br>
flow off the tongue, the manual was referred to as "Lab I" for short.<br>
(Yes, there is a Lab II -- it's the instructor training manual).<br>
<p>
Since the denomination had no comparable material, some SDA ministers<br>
began using Lab I.  It was useful in that its emphasis was on helping<br>
discouraged ex-members -- those who had dropped out because of crises<br>
such as unemployment, death in the family, etc. -- return to church.<br>
The emphasis was not on doctrinal matters, an area where the<br>
denomination IS well-equipped.<br>
<p>
Buried within the 14 interpersonal listening skills presented was<br>
information on neurolinguistic programming.  The material was technical<br>
in  nature and dealt with the processing of information by individuals,<br>
and how each individual handles information flow.<br>
<p>
While this all sounds innocent enough, it set off alarms in certain<br>
quarters.  Part of the problem is that some organizations have claimed<br>
NLP is a cure-all that can cure entrenched habits in a single session.<br>
It didn't help that some groups espousing NLP are New Age groups who, by<br>
definition, will try anything once.<br>
<p>
Most serious of all, though, is the allegation that NLP is really<br>
another name for hypnosis, against which SDA's have been strictly warned<br>
by the Spirit of Prophecy.  Those already disposed to call the<br>
leadership of the church Laodicean (if not Babylonian) thus found a<br>
stick with which to beat the General Conference.<br>
<p>
NLP, however, has nothing to do with hypnosis or even hypnotherapy.<br>
Having worked for a time in the library of the American Association of<br>
Nurse Anesthetists I was able to read several books and journal articles<br>
on hypnotherapy, which bears no resemblance to NLP or to the stagecraft<br>
mumbo-jumbo that was called "hypnotism" back in the days of vaudeville.<br>
<p>
But back to NLP.  Of the 78 pages in the Lab I manual, only one covered<br>
NLP.  Some ministers, conscious of the ambiguous nature of the subject,<br>
simply removed the page in question.  LEAD, however, has recently<br>
sponsored NLP certification classes, and as you discovered, there are<br>
still Lab I manuals floating around.  All this has fed the rumor mill<br>
about pastors practicing hypnotism under the guise of NLP.  Even though<br>
no proof has even been offered that actual harm has been done by the use<br>
of NLP in a pastoral counseling session.  But since when have<br>
rumor-mongers relied on solid information?<br>
<p>
For more information on the controversy, see the following:<br>
"Are Adventist pastors teaching hypnotism?" by Monte Sahlin, _Ministry_,<br>
June 1992, pp. 18-20.<br>
"The Facts about NLP" by William G. Johnsson. _Adventist Review_,<br>
February 20, 1992, p. 4. <br>
<p>
Daniel J. Drazen<br>
Editor, SDA Periodical Index<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
