<!-- body="start" -->
Hi, this is my first post on SDAnet, although I have been reading for<br>
the past three or four weeks.  Let me introduce myself before entering<br>
into the main discussion.<br>
<p>
I am an assistant professor in the Department of Physics and Computer<br>
Science at Pacific Union College.  I began teaching here during winter<br>
quarter 1990.  My area of expertise is atomic physics.  I have taught<br>
physics and engineering courses, but so far I have not taught any<br>
CS courses.  I was raised Roman Catholic by my parents, but rejected<br>
RC teachings as a teenager.  I first became aware of the SDA church<br>
during the summer between college graduation and the beginning of<br>
graduate school, and was baptized two years later.  My wife is an RN<br>
at St. Helena Hospital and Health Center which is an SDA facility<br>
located four miles from the college.  We have a six-year-old son who<br>
attends kindergarten at PUC Elementary.<br>
<p>
And now to the issue at hand:<br>
<p>
Steve asked about archeological sites that have been identified as<br>
Sodom and Gomorrah.  I recently attended a weekend series or seminars<br>
by Ron Wyatt who claims to have discovered not only Sodom and Gomorrah<br>
but the other cities of the plain as well.  I purchased a copy of a<br>
video in which he documents his findings.  The most interesting<br>
evidence may be summarized as follows:<br>
<p>
  (1) The sites contain powdery sulfur balls imbedded in extensive<br>
      ashen structures.<br>
<p>
  (2) These structures are consistent with the ruins of cities,<br>
      whereas the rock formations in surrounding areas are not.<br>
<p>
  (3) The sites extend from Zoar (Bela) and Sodom located south<br>
      of the Dead Sea to  Gomorrah which is located below Masada<br>
      on the western shore of the Dead Sea to Admah and Zeboiim<br>
      which are located *north* of the Dead Sea, far from the<br>
      traditional sites.<br>
<p>
Anyone interested in obtaining the video may send me email and I will<br>
dig out the necessary information.  (I do not have it with me at work.)<br>
<p>
Some of you may be familiar with Ron Wyatt.  He has written a book<br>
entitled _Discovered:_Noah's_Ark_ in which he claims to have found<br>
not only Noah's ark, but also remains of chariots at the bottom of<br>
the Gulf of Aqaba (sp?), Mount Sinai, the mechanism for raising stones<br>
for the construction of pyramids, and most incredibly, the Ark of<br>
the Covenant!  Some of his claims are absolutely incredible, however,<br>
he is very convincing in person.  He is either telling the truth or<br>
he is the world's best liar.  On the other hand, some of his statements<br>
seem entirely reasonable, such as regarding the mechanism for building<br>
pyramids and his method of analyzing the site he claims to be the<br>
remains of Noah's ark.<br>
<p>
I will let you be the judge for yourself.<br>
<p>
<p>
Daniel Crowe<br>
dcrowe@puc.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
