<title>May_1993: Internet news etc</title>
<h1>Internet news etc</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>03 May 1993 09:25:05 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#5">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#5">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#5">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#5">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Has anyone heard of NLP?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0004.html">Healy, Tammy R: "Shepherd's Rod"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
At most universities in Australia undergraduates are denied access<br>
to any internet facilities, due mainly to alleged resource limitations.<br>
Postgraduates are supposed to be too busy to waste time on trivia, so<br>
in theory no Australian student would read any of those newsgroups<br>
anyway!<br>
<p>
I don't know much about usenet, so this idea may not be practical. But<br>
the best policy for any institution would seem to be to subscribe to<br>
what is needed and no more. The computing resources are not there to<br>
provide trivial reading material for staff and students, they are<br>
there to be used for specific purposes. This way if anyone does wish<br>
to read alt.satanism, alt.tasteless or whatever, they would need to<br>
put forward a worthwhile case for doing so. I don't see this is<br>
"censorship", just as a wise use of resources.<br>
<p>
What I do strongly object to is an institution covertly monitoring<br>
the behaviour of individuals. This is an invasion of privacy. In this<br>
day and age of information sharing and global data access, we need to<br>
be very careful to preserve what privacy we have left!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
ps I sent a message the other day to st0o+SDA@andrew.cmu.edu...did<br>
this get through? Is that the address we're supposed to be using now?<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
