In message &lt;9304301233.AA17979@orion.cc.andrews.edu. cc.andrews.edu&gt;, hamstra@o<br>
rion.cc.andrews.edu writes:<br>
<i>&gt;Another issue has also surfaced here at Andrews.  We have a number of</i><br>
<i>&gt;Academy students who either use or are interested in using the Internet. </i><br>
<i>&gt;We also have a group of non SDA students from local high schools who come</i><br>
<i>&gt;onto campus to use our facilities in Math and Sciences (including Computer</i><br>
<i>&gt;Science).  Many of these individuals are "minors."  There is a lot of</i><br>
<i>&gt;"adult" material available via Internet: newsgroups, pictures, "dirty"</i><br>
<i>&gt;games, jokes etc.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;The question is this:</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Should these individuals be restricted in their access to these off campus</i><br>
<i>&gt;resources?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;dan hamstra</i><br>
<i>&gt;hamstra@andrews.edu</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
I'm at a secular university, we don't restrict access to the internet,<br>
but we do have strong policies on displaying pictures etc on students<br>
terminal screens. Naturally we are not always around to police such<br>
things. There is a strong emphasis here, that use of the computing<br>
facilities shouldn't be offensive to anyone, hence the restrictions.<br>
<p>
Not sure if this helps. We've found that less restrictions usually<br>
brings out the best in the students, of course there are always<br>
exceptions. I guess the logic is that if something is allowed, then it<br>
no longer has the added spice of being forbidden, therefore its not such<br>
a thrill to do it.<br>
<p>
	Sue<br>
