<title>May_1993: Re: Sodom and Gomorrah</title>
<h1>Re: Sodom and Gomorrah</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 3 May 1993 12:11:04 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#8">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#8">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#8">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#8">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0009.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Thought..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Has anyone heard of NLP?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I remember about a year ago hearing a very interesting lecture by Dr. </i><br>
<i>&gt; Bill Shea that included information about several archeological sites on </i><br>
<i>&gt; the east side of the Dead Sea.  These cities appear at a suitable</i><br>
<i>&gt; archeological layer to have been destroyed by fire, and it is now thought</i><br>
<i>&gt; that they may be the cities of Sodom and Gomorrah.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Does anyone know where print documentation may be had for this discovery.</i><br>
<i>&gt; I would assume in the Biblical Archaeology Review, to which I have wanted</i><br>
<i>&gt; to subscribe for years but never found the subscription address.  Any </i><br>
<i>&gt; SDAnet members can help us out on this?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
In searching our CD-ROM of the Religion Index (American Theological<br>
Library Association), I find these two citations:<br>
<p>
Steinberg, David, and others, "On the New Site Identifications for Sodom<br>
and Gomorrah," _Biblical Archaeology Review_ v7 No 1, p. 18+,<br>
January-February 1981.<br>
<p>
Hattem, Willem C. van, "Once again: Sodom and Gomorrah," _The Biblical<br>
Archaeologist_ v44, p. 87-92, Spring 1981.  ABSTRACT:  The location of<br>
Sodom and Gomorrah has been an itneresting--and elusive--problem in<br>
historical research for a very long time.  Different interpretations of<br>
the biblical and archaeological evidence have produced various theories<br>
regarding the location of the famous cities.  More recent evidence,<br>
however, has challenged some of the old ideas and has produced new and<br>
enlightening information about the missing "Cities of the Plain."<br>
<p>
Unfortunately, this database is only updated once a year and we haven't<br>
yet received the 1992 index, so anything more recent than 1991 won't be<br>
covered.  The good news is that this index is one which we are in the<br>
advanced states of implementing on our online catalog.  It will soon be<br>
available on the campus network.  I am not sure when (or how) it will be<br>
made available off campus (depends on licensing agreements not ye<br>
signed).  We hope this will be something that we can share with other<br>
church entities (and individuals?).<br>
<p>
The address of the Biblical Arachaeology Review is (at least for<br>
subscriptions) PO Box 7026, Red Oak, IA  51591.  The number is 1-800-678-5555.  The subscription price is $24 (6/year).  If you need the editorial<br>
office (which is in Washington, DC), I can supply that.<br>
<p>
As usual, this information is easily available from almost any library<br>
(we do have directories of periodicals), including those who don't<br>
subsribe to a journal.  Articles are available through Interlibrary Loan<br>
(or let me know, and we can have our ILL office send them out).  This is<br>
a fairly routine type of reference question.  However, I don't mind<br>
being your online reference librarian!<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head REference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
