<title>May_1993: Re: WWC and Internet News</title>
<h1>Re: WWC and Internet News</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 3 May 93 16:18:14 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#11">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#11">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#11">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#11">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Ron Vyhmeister: "Re: Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Edward W. Fargusson: "Re: Mark Martin in Arizona"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hello,<br>
<p>
[Healy, Tammy R writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; I am a student at WWC and I think that Internet shouldn't be policed.  If</i><br>
<i>&gt; they start with alt.sex, will they later decide to ban alt.vampyres or</i><br>
<i>&gt; alt.pagan, too.  I admit some of it is morally incorrect, but I figure</i><br>
<i>&gt; we're old enough now to make decisions on what we read.</i><br>
<p>
The fact that the service was decided on, provided and administered by the college<br>
administration for the benefit of the students suggests to me that they indeed have<br>
the right and the obligation to make sure that what is allowed through the net into<br>
the school should be filtered at their discretion.<br>
<p>
We are not talking about a service that is available to students via some off-campus<br>
network or bulletin board  where students can dial up with a modem and access all the<br>
garbage they want.  The difference here is that the choice is theirs and only theirs<br>
(the college has no part of that decision).  But in this case where the decision to<br>
allow Internet on campus and provide it for the students is made by the college,<br>
 then they (those that decided to allow it) are responsible for what comes through it<br>
to the students.<br>
<p>
I liked the example someone used of the campus bookstore...they don't provide<br>
Playboy, etc for the students because the store is run by the college.  Yes the<br>
magazine can be had from other local stores but the real issue is that something that<br>
is provided and sponsored by the college should uphold and conform to the morals that<br>
the college teaches.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Bruce G. Holm               503-685-1350      email:  bruceh@wv.mentorg.com
Mentor Graphics Corp.       503-685-7000
8005 SW Boeckman Rd.
Wilsonville, OR 97070-7777     Disclaimer:  Opinions expressed are my own!
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
