<title>May_1993: Sodom and Gomorrah</title>
<h1>Sodom and Gomorrah</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 4 May 1993 13:33:12 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#21">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#21">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#21">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#21">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Woody Baker: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0020.html">ben@orion.lasierra.edu: "RE: Sodom and Gomorrah"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0017.html">Dan Crowe: "Re: Sodom and Gomorrah"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
By happenstance, shortly after I posted to the list about Sodom and<br>
Gomorrah, who should walk into the library but Bill Shea.  Of course I<br>
asked him for further guidance on archaeology of the area.  His<br>
information is as follows.  There has been a long series of<br>
archaeological expeditions to the southeast Dead Sea Region, beginning<br>
in the 1970s, and the latest season being 1990.  The principal<br>
archaeologists involved are Walater Rast and R. Thomas Schaub.  These<br>
expeditions have been reported in detail in a number of publications of<br>
the American Schools of Oriental Research (ASOR) [their bulletin and<br>
excavation reports) as well as in some of the more popular archaeology<br>
publications (e.g. Biblical Archaeology Review).  They have dug at<br>
various sites, most notably Bab Edh-Dhra, as well as more recently at<br>
Numeirah (1990).  It usually takes several years for scientific reports<br>
of such expeditions to appear.<br>
<p>
In searching our online catalog (telnet library.libr.andrews.edu; login<br>
library), I find 8 publications by Rast, 3 by Schaub and 2 that mention<br>
Bab Edh-Dhra.  In the _Religion Index_ CD-ROM, I find 1 reference to<br>
Numeirah, 28 to Bab Edh-Dhra, 36 to Rast, and I forgot to write down how<br>
many to Schaub.  If I weren't so busy doing such things as trying to get<br>
the _Religion Index_ loaded into our online catalog (not to mention<br>
recovering from the second disc crash of our DEC 5000 in 2 months!) I<br>
might spend more time figuring out how to forward these to you<br>
electronically.  But then, I don't really know how interested you are in<br>
reading technical archaeological publications anyway.<br>
<p>
Incidentally, I mentioned that the _Playboy_ rumor was long-standing<br>
because not only do I remember it from my college days, but it keeps<br>
cropping up here from time to time (as, indeed, it did on the list)!<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
