<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I think we need to remember that the issue of News is not only a matter</i><br>
<i>&gt; of principal.  It is a matter of cost to the organization giving access</i><br>
<i>&gt; to news.  The question then also becomes:  should an SDA school be</i><br>
<i>&gt; paying money in order to give students access to materials which are</i><br>
<i>&gt; definitely against the principles of the institution?</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; From a stewardship standpoint, I do not believe that we should fund</i><br>
<i>&gt; activities which go contrary to our principles.  If students wish to</i><br>
<i>&gt; access the information, that is their choice, but let them do it</i><br>
<i>&gt; at their own expense.</i><br>
<p>
Now this brings up something that students at CUC are a little sensitive about.<br>
 It is tuition money that pays for the school.  So the students should have<br>
some say in how the money is spent.  I don't think it is valid to argue this on<br>
the basis of money since the students actually pay for the connection anyway.<br>
<p>
Short story:  When I first started working here the Internet connection was<br>
being paid for by selling junk food to the adult evening students.  We made<br>
just enough to pay for the connection.  Since we move to the science building<br>
the school has been paying for the connection.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
