<title>May_1993: Midrash and the Jesus Generation</title>
<h1>Midrash and the Jesus Generation</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  4 May 1993 19:31:49 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#23">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#23">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#23">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#23">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0024.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Midrash and the Jesus Generation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Woody Baker: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0024.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Midrash and the Jesus Generation"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As one who plays theologian on the net, I understand the term _Midrash_<br>
to be a Hebrew term which refers to reinterpreting inspired writings in <br>
light of new realities.  One example in the Bible of such would be <br>
1st Chronicles, where the case is made that the covenant was really <br>
with David and not so much with Abraham.  Most of the gory details of David's<br>
career are absent in 1 Chronicles as compared to II Samuel.<br>
<p>
It seems to me that the last 15 years or so have seen a lot of Midrash<br>
within the Seventh-day Adventist Church  (much before that I was too young<br>
to observe much).  A recent article referred to the young people currently <br>
growing up within our church as the "Jesus generation," pointing out<br>
correctly that the current crop of teens is experiencing much less<br>
legalism<br>
than ever before, and that the emphasis on salvation by faith within the<br>
church has never been higher.<br>
<p>
To a certain extent, the church is still reacting to the emphasis on<br>
salvation by faith that really started getting shouted loudly in the<br>
1970's.<br>
The various groups in whatever debate all in their own way have to address<br>
the question:  "Given that some of the elements of the SDA culture are not <br>
absolutely essential for salvation, should we still cling to them?"<br>
<p>
Desmond Ford and his crowd answered that question firmly "no."  Many of <br>
the books written since then have been trying to explain why the answer is <br>
"yes."  In a broad sense I am thinking of the work of George Knight, <br>
Martin Weber, and others here.  I think this work is valuable and would like<br>
to join it (if SDAnet hasn't ruined my writing style for life !:)  perhaps<br>
I am doomed to forever write in sound bites).<br>
<p>
In the process of Midrash we can discover new and better motivations to <br>
do the right things we have always done.  And hopefully we can move more <br>
members from motivations of fear to motivations of love.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
