<title>May_1993: Re: WWC and Internet News</title>
<h1>Re: WWC and Internet News</h1>
Bill Nickless (<i>nickless@mcs.anl.gov</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 04 May 1993 22:23:55 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Koresh."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Religio-moral issues aside, there are concerns about the appropriateness of<br>
providing access to materials of an, um, disquieting nature.<br>
<p>
There is a legal concept called "common carrier."  This is how the telephone<br>
company can't be held liable for damages if someone plots a criminal act<br>
against you over the 'phone.  Or commits one, using a modem, or whatever.<br>
<p>
This principle rests on the idea that the telephone company disclaims any<br>
control over the content of the information and will simply move signals from<br>
one point to another for anyone who will pay the bills.<br>
<p>
This principle has *NOT* yet been generally extended to computer data<br>
networks.  And, if any controls or selection processes are in place, it<br>
becomes even more difficult to claim common carrier protection.  People have<br>
been arrested and thrown into jail because someome uploaded child pornography<br>
to their bulletin boards.  Literally.<br>
<p>
A topic of some concern to for-profit, moral-judgement-free network providers<br>
now is the move to put K-12 schools on the internet.  Will the network<br>
providers be held liable for legally obscene materials that these high school<br>
and grade school students access?  Legally, there is no clear answer at all.<br>
<p>
I don't intend this note as support for an incredibly fascist Internet policy.<br>
Far from it.  Rather, it's a call for an up-front understanding and concensus<br>
of acceptable use of the shared resource that WWC is putting into place.<br>
Prurient material is but one area of concern.  Others include pirated software<br>
packages, huge sound files, use of college computers as launching points for<br>
remote system attacks, poorly-designed, high-volume network generating<br>
applications of many sorts, electronic mail harassment of all sorts, and the<br>
list goes on.  And on.  And on.<br>
<p>
In short, don't address the problem from a "what will we prohibit"<br>
perspective, but from the viewpoint of "what are we using this for."  Don't<br>
put the fascist technical controls into place, but try to develop<br>
self-disclipling based on well-established principles.  Remeber: it's always<br>
better to solve the human problems in a humane way than to try to solve the<br>
human problems technically.  (If you want more support for that last<br>
statement, let me know....)<br>
<pre>
---
Bill Nickless  System Support Group  &lt;nickless@mcs.anl.gov&gt;  +1 708 252 7390
<p>
(System Support Group, in my case, includes network traffic analysis and
security enforcing duties, among many others.)
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
