<title>May_1993: Re: Re: WWC and Internet News</title>
<h1>Re: Re: WWC and Internet News</h1>
Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473 (<i>jwiley@law.usc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 5 May 93 09:11:06 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#32">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#32">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#32">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#32">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Ralf Simonsson: "God responsible"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0055.html">Archau: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Regarding tution's paying for the school. . .<br>
<p>
First, I doubt seriously that tution pays the full costs of running<br>
CUC.  Are there no church subsidies for capital or operating?  Are there<br>
no donors who gave largely because of the priciples CUC espoused?  Are<br>
there no endowments?  Thus, folks besides the tution-paying students<br>
may have interests in the institution.  If money is the determinent,<br>
then the question of the multimillion dollar donor from a week or 10<br>
days ago should be reviewed.<br>
<p>
Secondly,  if one elects to join an organization knowing its standards,<br>
e.g., a private club, then one presumably has agreed to abide by the<br>
institution's [club's] rules and adhere to its principles.  Surely,<br>
one can work from the inside to change the standards, but merely<br>
saying, "I pay my dues [tuition]" isn't persuasive that the institution<br>
should change its rules.  Indeed, one of the constant tensions in<br>
private education is the tension between money and the right to set the<br>
standards.  <br>
<p>
A few years ago, we at the law school gave back a $2,000,000 gift<br>
because the donor felt that the gift had implied terms that were<br>
not in harmony with its express terms, and that although we were in<br>
harmony with the documents executed with the acceptance of the<br>
gift, we were not in harmony with the implied terms that the donor<br>
felt all understood [we didn't "hear" what he/they thought was said].<br>
We were recognizing the donor's right to spend money in harmony with<br>
his desires, and our right to abide by the principles of academic<br>
freedom.  If students want to have access to materials the college<br>
finds out of harmony with its principles/standards, then the student<br>
may 1)spend her/his tuition dollars elsewhere; 2)get the information<br>
through other means at her/his expense, or 3)try to change the rules/<br>
standards of the institution through internal processes.<br>
<p>
--Jerry<br>
USC Law Center<br>
<p>
P.S. Was it Groucho Marx who said, "I don't want to belong to any club<br>
that would have me as a member"?  Standrads for membership often result<br>
in scarcity which creates its own market.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
