<title>May_1993: In practical terms...</title>
<h1>In practical terms...</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>05 May 1993 09:56:49 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#39">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#39">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#39">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#39">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Dan Drazen: "Re: Midrash and the Jesus Generation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Ron Vyhmeister: "Prayers Answered"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One question which remains in my mind is: What are the real, practical<br>
implications of the nature of sin/nature of Christ debate? There must be <br>
some quite substantial ones, otherwise there would be no motivation for <br>
this debate.<br>
<p>
I think I understand the motivation for one side. Let me summarize:<br>
Sinful acts do not need to be a part of the life of a Christian. In fact<br>
they _should_ not be. Christ has demonstrated for us how to live in an<br>
evil world without participating in its corruption. He is now willing and<br>
able to work in us against evil, as well as forgiving us for our sinful<br>
past. We are Christ's witnesses both to our fellow humans and to the<br>
entire universe. As such, it is our responsibility to accept what Christ<br>
offers us, make the decision to break the shackles of evil, and progress<br>
towards a victorious Christian life.<br>
<p>
This makes sense to me. With or without the concept of original sin I<br>
can agree with that. (I suppose I have phrased it such a way that I<br>
can!)<br>
<p>
What I would like to know is, why do the others find it important to<br>
make statements like this one from Noe:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
The more clearly we define our terms, the more room for agreement I find<br>
in your positions, especially with regard to the sanctified life.  The<br>
statement you've quoted several times, where EGW says that if we say we<br>
cannot keep the law perfectly we are accusing God of being unjust, is very<br>
good.  What it means is that we ***can*** keep God's law perfectly by<br>
accepting the perfect righteousness of Christ.  Christ kept the law<br>
perfectly and his perfection is credited to our account.  We can add<br>
nothing to the transaction.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
What drives this debate? A skeptic would say that a statement such as the<br>
above only serves to absolve the Christian from the responsibility to<br>
avoid evil in the here and now. That a continued emphasis on this aspect<br>
of the gospel is made because the Christian does not really wish to live<br>
as a disciple of Christ should.<br>
<p>
I am sure this is not the real reason for this emphasis. Could Noe, or<br>
anyone else who represents this side of the issue, provide a couple<br>
of paragraphs explaining why you feel it is important to provide this<br>
emphasis? And also what implications you see this having for the <br>
Christian?<br>
<p>
Thanks,<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
