On May 4,  5:30pm, Alan Fargusson wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re: Re: WWC and Internet News</i><br>
...<br>
<i>&gt; Now this brings up something that students at CUC are a little sensitive</i><br>
about.<br>
<i>&gt;  It is tuition money that pays for the school.  So the students should have</i><br>
<i>&gt; some say in how the money is spent.  I don't think it is valid to argue this</i><br>
on<br>
<i>&gt; the basis of money since the students actually pay for the connection anyway.</i><br>
<p>
Yes, I see your point, but I do believe that parents and students pay good<br>
tuition money for the privalege of attending a Christian institution that<br>
teaches and upholds the SDA doctrines, beliefs, and ethics.  If you didn't value<br>
that, why would you then pay such high prices to attend.  Therefore, the school<br>
is under obligation and charter to fulfill this role for those willing to pay<br>
for it.  Then why should they compromise or be expected to change their role for<br>
the sake of providing access to a service that communicates information that is<br>
contrary to these beliefs?  This is not an issue of _what_ on Usenet is good or<br>
bad but an issue of whether the college has the right to filter or not.  I<br>
believe they are, as expressed in hard earned dollars paid to the college that<br>
are "voting" that they want the college to uphold standards and to provide a<br>
quality and consistent Christian education.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
