<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;to observe much).  A recent article referred to the young people currently</i><br>
<i>&gt;growing up within our church as the "Jesus generation," pointing out</i><br>
<i>&gt;correctly that the current crop of teens is experiencing much less legalism</i><br>
<i>&gt;than ever before, and that the emphasis on salvation by faith within the</i><br>
<i>&gt;church has never been higher.</i><br>
<p>
I see no conflict at all, between the doctrine of salvation by grace,<br>
through faith, and that of keeping the law. They are complimentary and one<br>
needs to understand the one to fully comprehend the other. That is also the<br>
view of most of the other young people in my church i think.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;The various groups in whatever debate all in their own way have to address</i><br>
<i>&gt;the question: "Given that some of the elements of the SDA culture are not</i><br>
<i>&gt;absolutely essential for salvation, should we still cling to them?"</i><br>
<p>
Is "salvation" all that we are after? Is the only reason that we choose to<br>
be Christians the fact that we hope to be saved thereby? Perhaps the<br>
question should be rephrased. Actually i'm not sure what is meant by "SDA<br>
culture", but i don't think any kind of culture is going to save anybody,<br>
only God can save the sinner. Culture is not something to cling to for its<br>
own sake. In fact, some SDA customs are not found in the bible, and some<br>
that are in the bible do not appear to be popular with SDAs at all.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
