<title>May_1993: Re: Midrash and the Jesus Generation</title>
<h1>Re: Midrash and the Jesus Generation</h1>
Dan Drazen (<i>drazen@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 6 May 1993 08:34:49 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#40">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#40">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#40">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#40">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0041.html">Fred Christiansen: "(Re) Introducing myself to SDAnetters"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0039.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "In practical terms..."</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0023.html">Steven Timm: "Midrash and the Jesus Generation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; As one who plays theologian on the net, I understand the term _Midrash_</i><br>
<i>&gt; to be a Hebrew term which refers to reinterpreting inspired writings in </i><br>
<i>&gt; light of new realities.... </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; It seems to me that the last 15 years or so have seen a lot of Midrash</i><br>
<i>&gt; within the Seventh-day Adventist Church  (much before that I was too young</i><br>
<i>&gt; to observe much).... </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; In the process of Midrash we can discover new and better motivations to </i><br>
<i>&gt; do the right things we have always done.  And hopefully we can move more </i><br>
<i>&gt; members from motivations of fear to motivations of love.</i><br>
<p>
Steve:<br>
<p>
In a sense, Midrash is reinterpretation of sacred texts.  But it is a<br>
limited sense.  My working definition of the term comes from the essay<br>
"Midrash" by Barry W. Holtz, which appears in Holtz (ed.)<br>
_Back To The Sources: Reading The Classic Jewish Texts_ (New York:<br>
Summit, 1984, ch. 3):<br>
<p>
"[W]e can see the central issue behind the emergence of Midrash as the<br>
need to deal with the presence of cultural or religious tension or<br>
discontinuity.  Where there are questions that demand answers, and where<br>
there are new cultural and intellectual pressures that must be<br>
addressed, Midrash comes into play...<br>
   The Bible is loath to tell us the motivations, feelings, or thoughts<br>
of characters.  Rarely giving us descriptive details either of people<br>
or places, it is composed in a stark, uncompromising style.<br>
   Hence in the laconic style of the Bible, we find one significant cause<br>
for the necessity of Midrash.  Midrash comes to fill in the gaps, to<br>
tell us the details that the Bible teasingly leaves out: what did Isaac<br>
think as his father took him to be sacrificed?  The Bible doesn't tell<br>
us, but Midrash fills it in...Why did Cain kill Abel?  Once again the<br>
Bible is silent, but Midrash is filled with explanation.  How tall was<br>
Adam as he walked in the Garden?  Look to the midrashic material, not to<br>
the Bible, for such details.  The human mind desires answers,<br>
motivations, explanations.  Where the Bible is mysterious and silent,<br>
Midrash comes to unravel the mystery." (pp. 179-180).<br>
<p>
This definition has the interesting side-effect of classifying Spirit of<br>
Prophecy writings as being midrashic.  By the same token, Lois<br>
Erickson's biblical novels (e.g., _Leah_) might also be considered to be<br>
in the tradition of Midrash.<br>
<p>
I hadn't intended to solve anything with this reply; just to throw<br>
something into the stew pot.<br>
<p>
Daniel J. Drazen<br>
Editor, SDA Periodical Index<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
