Steve,<br>
    I thought you might like this for the SDA net.<br>
<p>
*********************************************************<br>
<p>
On the front page of the 5-03-93 edition of the Wall Street Journal,<br>
there is an article (in the column known as the A column) titled "Can<br>
Texaco Win A Battle if the Lord Is on the Other Side? -- Gas Station<br>
Owner Says God Calls for Sabbath Closing, Despite Company's Rules."<br>
<p>
In Salem Oregon, there is a Christian fundamentalist (he puts the fun in<br>
fun-damentalist) named Barry Davis who refuses to operate his gas<br>
station from Friday sundown to Saturday sundown.  The article says that<br>
he isn't SDA but the SDA church is legally defending him saying that he<br>
shouldn't be forced to operate against his religious beliefs.<br>
<p>
There's lots of interesting stuff here.  Apparantly Mr. Davis operates<br>
some of the most successful gas stations in the country.  His take home<br>
pay last year was almost $470,000.  Texaco has given him commendations<br>
and other awards asking him about what made him so successful.  In<br>
January he started to close on Saturdays (fri. sundown to sat. sundown)<br>
putting out a sign "Closed for Sabbath."  Texaco estimates that they<br>
lost 26% percent of sales due to this action by Mr. Davis.  Davis,<br>
claims that he can more than make up for the closing during the week. <br>
The ACLU says that Davis doesn't have a legal leg to stand on because it<br>
isn't an employer employee relationship, but a contract.  "In the eyes<br>
of the law he might as well be general Motors" says Lewis Maltby legal<br>
director of the ACLU.<br>
<p>
It gets better.  Davis claims to have direct communication with God.<br>
When Texaco suggested that his profits from Saturday's operations be<br>
donated to his favorite religious cause, Davis responed by saying that<br>
he asked God and God found it unacceptable.  <br>
<p>
At a lunch with Texaco officials last year he "revealed" his secret for<br>
success.  "I told them God takes care of me and mine.  Everything I've<br>
asked for I've gotten."  In an earlier discussion with Texaco officials<br>
he told them that "God once appeared in a green cloud, along with<br>
thunder and lightning."  <br>
<p>
The article ends with a quote from Davis: "For years I was a hero, now<br>
suddenly they're treating me like the wacko from Waco."<br>
<p>
--Trevor<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
