<title>May_1993: Re: Waco</title>
<h1>Re: Waco</h1>
<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 07 May 93 12:44:24 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#48">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#48">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#48">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#48">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0049.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Ee's poetry"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Scott  Bechtel: "SDA Court"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0037.html">David Plaisted: "Waco"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Dave Plaisted writes]<br>
<i>&gt;I think that the church is partly responsible for some of its</i><br>
<i>&gt;serious members being drawn off into Waco type things.  People</i><br>
<i>&gt;are hungry for some serious prophetic exposition which isn't</i><br>
<i>&gt;found in the church today as much as it used to be.  They are</i><br>
<i>&gt;also sensitive to our failures to live up to the light we have</i><br>
<i>&gt;been given.  So it's easy for someone else to claim he has the</i><br>
<i>&gt;true church which is more faithful than we are.</i><br>
<p>
A strong undercurrent that I am seeing, especially in confrontations<br>
with "independent ministries" is conference officers insisting on<br>
submission to their authority while insisting that their confrontation<br>
has nothing to do with theology.  So, members get disfellowshiped<br>
and churches disbanded over the issue of authority while carefully<br>
setting asside theology.  And so I find more and more SDA members<br>
who want to align themselves with the church who more and more<br>
insist on a sort of blind obedience to their pastor and to church<br>
officers.  And so the stage is set.  Let some of these folks who<br>
are blindly obedient to church officers "have their eyes opened"<br>
such that their "blind obedience" evaporates.  But their mind set<br>
is that of blind obedience.  And so they align themselves with the<br>
leadership of those who "opened" their eyes.  And so I think that<br>
conference pressure for membership obedience is lending itself to<br>
more Wacos rather than solving the problem.<br>
<p>
The apostle Paul writes about how glad he is that he had not<br>
baptised very many people because some of the other evangelists<br>
were developing quite a following -- some saying I am a follower<br>
of Apolos and others saying I am a disciple of . . . .  Paul's<br>
point being that we should rather be disciples of Jesus and not<br>
of Paul or of Apolos.  And so, if a conference pastor comes<br>
preaching the truth, as confirmed as the Bereans would, then I'm<br>
eager to go listen to that preacher.  And if an indepent ministry<br>
preacher has truth to preach then I'm going to listen to his<br>
sermons as well.  If I find a preacher is out of touch with the<br>
Bible, then I don't care if that preacher is of the conference or<br>
an indepent, I frankly don't care to continue to listen to him/her.<br>
Also, I don't pledge my alegiance to any particular ministry or<br>
conference.  I am not a disciple of . . . . . or of . . . . .<br>
I am a disciple of Jesus.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
