<title>May_1993: Possible new services of SDAnet</title>
<h1>Possible new services of SDAnet</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun,  9 May 1993 21:29:33 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#45">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#45">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#45">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#45">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0046.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Authoritarian leadership"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0044.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Des Ford and firm no"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The possibility is strong that new software will soon be acquired to <br>
manage SDAnet.  We have been using it for communications among our board<br>
members, with mostly good results.  If we make the move, it will be sometime<br>
in June.  It will be possible for us to have a wide variety of services <br>
that are now impossible.  I would like your opinions about which of these<br>
might be useful to you:<br>
<p>
1)  Daily digest:  SDAnet traffic arrives as one message per day.<br>
    Disadvantage:  harder to reply to each individual message<br>
    Advantage:  Less clutter in mailbox<br>
<p>
2)  Elm rules:   (I know, I have promised these for a month.  They're<br>
coming.)  These can show you how to split SDAnet mail into a sub-mailbox.<br>
<p>
3)  On-line ftp'able archive<br>
<p>
4)  Software understands LISTSERV commands for subscribe, unsubscribe<br>
    and nomail (but there will still be a human who understands English<br>
    as well).<br>
<p>
5)  Shorter headers<br>
<p>
6)  an SDAnet information center on Gopher/WWW<br>
<p>
What I would like to have but which would take some real work and will <br>
not be accomplished by just a software change is a digest that really <br>
is a digest in which discussion topics are grouped together and some<br>
extraneous posts and headers and included text are edited out.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0046.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Authoritarian leadership"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0044.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Des Ford and firm no"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
