<title>May_1993: SDA-L: The SDA-L link to SDAnet</title>
<h1>SDA-L: The SDA-L link to SDAnet</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+%ANDREW.CMU.EDU%CMU.EDU@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>09 May 1993 21:51:11 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#50">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#50">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#50">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#50">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0051.html">Steven Timm: ""Christianity in the life of the young professional""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0049.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Ee's poetry"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
For the last two years, every message produced by SDA-L (all 50 of them<br>
or so) has been echoed to the readership of SDAnet.  SDAnet is currently<br>
exploring a LISTSERV-like software (which if successful, could also<br>
be used to move SDA-L to lasierra.edu).  It would be convenient<br>
to break the SDA-L link at this time, although not absolutely necessary.<br>
<p>
SDAnet readers would notice almost no effect from this.  But such an<br>
action could serve to revitalize SDA-L.  The core of subscribers which<br>
remain subscribed to SDA-L but not SDAnet shows that there is a market<br>
for a lower-traffic unmoderated list.  Many who can't take the high<br>
volume of SDAnet messages could stand to subcribe to a list with 20-30<br>
messages a month.  Also it would mean that anyone who wanted to read this<br>
traffic would have to go out and subscribe for him/herself.<br>
<p>
The reason why I have insisted on maintaining the link up until now<br>
is to have some guard against cross-posting.  If there were two totally<br>
independent nets and the same article were posted to both, then people<br>
who subscribe to both would get double copies.  Currently we assure that<br>
all SDAnet members are also SDA-L members so that cannot happen.<br>
Some guard against cross-posts would have to be maintained if this action<br>
were to happen.<br>
<p>
Before such a step is undertaken, SDA-L would need to find a slightly<br>
larger niche.  Ideally there should be some topics that are meant for<br>
SDA-L and not for SDAnet.  This can be done by picking from the many<br>
areas and types of traffic that SDAnet never covers.  If you see a topic<br>
that's mentioned only rarely on SDAnet, post to SDA-L and try it out.<br>
<p>
(SDAnet members, remember I will forward your post to SDA-L if it<br>
has SDA-L in the subject line.)<br>
<p>
I would appreciate any comments on this issue<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
