I once had a pastor here in Austin, who shall remain nameless, but was a<br>
prime example.  The current conference leadership was up for nomination.  There<br>
was a STRONG undercurrent of discontent with the confrenece president, and I<br>
was a delegate to the constituency meeting.  In the church board meeting just<br>
before the constituency meeting, he looked at me, and said something to the<br>
effect of "you do your job so I can do mine"  When I questioned him as to what<br>
he ment he plainly told me straight out that I was to vote FOR the confrence<br>
president.  I needless to say was appalled.  I voted the way I was going to<br>
(against ).  I was told later that he was furious at me, and publicly stated<br>
that as long as he was pastor here, I would never hold a board position agian<br>
<p>
after he left a couple of years later.  A year after that, I had my old<br>
board position back.  <br>
<p>
I find it hard to believe.  The pastor before that, was a businessman type<br>
and considered members in terms of dollars and cents.  I literaly overheard<br>
him in a board meeting, make the statement that it wasn't cost effective to<br>
have an evangilistic effort, as the it cost to much per person in relation to<br>
what they would be worth in dollars to the church.  Just blew me away.<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
<p>
