<!-- body="start" -->
This is a response to Tammy's post about students paying for internet.<br>
<p>
Two points. First, students pay a significant, but not by any means the <br>
whole of the cost of the services provided by the college. Part of the cost <br>
is also paid by the church members through the Union Conference, part by <br>
various private donors, part by various agency grants. In the case of <br>
internet, it was my understanding that it  is partly funded by an NSF <br>
grant.  So  while the views of students clearly must be considered, the <br>
administration has to make a judgement that goes beyond the students' views <br>
only, and surely must consider whether what it supports or makes available <br>
to students corresponds with the mission of the college.<br>
<p>
Second, even if the students were paying it all, that translates to parents <br>
as well.  The fact is, although the students are no longer (in most cases) <br>
minors, the money they pay is often not theirs but their parents' and was <br>
paid based on their parents' judgement about what they are exposed to at <br>
college. It would seem that by that argument, the parents also deserve a <br>
vote. Further, even if it were students' funds (minus parents), these are <br>
often government guaranteed loans, and the government clearly reserves <br>
certain rights when it guarantees money.  Of course, the government does <br>
not concern itself with the issue at hand, but it does have a say in <br>
various aspects of school policy so long as the college receives funds that <br>
it guarantees.<br>
<p>
The point I am making is that although the voice of the student must be <br>
heard in matters which affect them, that voice is only one of many <br>
competing interests and is not by any means determinative.<br>
<p>
Austin Archer<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
