<title>May_1993: Authoritarian leadership</title>
<h1>Authoritarian leadership</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>10 May 1993 11:52:37 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#46">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#46">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#46">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#46">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Scott  Bechtel: "SDA Court"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Steven Timm: "Possible new services of SDAnet"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0059.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: Authoritarian leadership"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Just how common is this authoritarian, "do what we say", church leadership<br>
which is referred to from time to time on the net? I myself have rarely<br>
encountered it from the institution as such. Certainly individuals within<br>
the institution can be authoritarian - but they would be like that regardless<br>
of who they work for.<br>
<p>
One instance which does come to mind is a recent conference session, where the<br>
delegates from my church were reprimanded for discussing their views amongst<br>
themselves prior to the nominating committee meeting. This, apparently,<br>
constituted "lobbying" and was deemed to be prohibited. I found this incident<br>
quite incredible, but the fact was that the reprimand came from a very<br>
authoritarian individual whose conference employment was "on the line" at that<br>
particular meeting.<br>
<p>
My point is that I don't think church leadership as a whole expects "blind<br>
obedience". From my experience, there are many church members who wish that<br>
they could blindly follow, but the leadership will not oblige them!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
