</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I enjoyed reading Tony's post.  To be honest, I agree with him in general,<br>
the SDA church does have a leadership which tries with varying degrees of<br>
success to listen to members concerns as long as the challenge does not come<br>
into certain "erroneous zones".<br>
<p>
What I have observed is not that the majority of SDA leaders are<br>
authoritarian instead of consensus builders, but rather the system has no<br>
checks or balances requiring consensus building by leadership.  It is<br>
possible for leaders to excercise almost absolute power toward their<br>
subordinates as long as they have the patronage of their superiors.  This<br>
system works as well as it does because most members of the system truly do<br>
have the good of the organization and the spread of God's word as their goal.<br>
 This allows persons who feel aggrieved to allow God to work in the system<br>
rather than pursue a more political resolution of grievances and it also<br>
keeps Godly leaders from excercising arbitrary power.  Unfortunately however,<br>
from my perspective, the system is not set up to require consensus building. <br>
This leaves leaders open to the corrupting effects of power.  Remember the<br>
adage: "Power corrupts, absolute power corrupts absolutely!"<br>
<p>
My opinions are based upon observations of several battles within the church,<br>
most of them involving the church's medical care institutions, both here and<br>
in the mission field.  <br>
<p>
I would be interested in hearing your opinions on how the church should<br>
organize its corporate structure to require consensus building in<br>
organizational decisions.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
