<title>May_1993: Authoritarian Leadership</title>
<h1>Authoritarian Leadership</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 11 May 1993 21:37:42 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#60">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#60">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#60">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#60">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Authoritarian leadership"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0059.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: Authoritarian leadership"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0065.html">David Plaisted: "Re: Authoritarian Leadership"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think the issue of authoritarian leadership runs deeper than any <br>
individual administrator.  Anyone acquainted with the president of the <br>
Illinois Conference, B.J. Christensen, (soon may be heading for Southern<br>
California), knows he is one of the ultimate peacemakers and consensus<br>
builders.  But it takes more than one to build consensus, and you will find<br>
that Illinois has its quota or more of ex-pastors as a result.  Not<br>
necessarily as a function of the conference leadership or the pastors<br>
themselves, but as a result of a system that lets anyone thumping a Bible<br>
or Ellen G. White demand an authoritarian application of that particular<br>
point.  I think if we were to examine the situation closely we would<br>
find that authoritarianism is deeply rooted in the church membership,<br>
and we have <br>
a system that allows each individual church member to be an authoritarian.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<p>
<p>
Seventh-day Adventist:  (n) Member of church who reveres Ellen G. White<br>
as a prophet, admirably suited to the needs of his neighbor.  :)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
