<title>May_1993: Sabbath Observance</title>
<h1>Sabbath Observance</h1>
John Ash - CS (<i>jash@eecs.wsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 11 May 93 23:44:04 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#70">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#70">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#70">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#70">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0071.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "Plato's Soul and Biblical Death (Posted to s.r.c.)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0069.html">Terry L Anderson 908-582-7013: "The Branch Davidians &amp; Events at Waco"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0079.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Sabbath Observance"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
THE QUESTIONS:<br>
<p>
   1.  How should the hours of the Sabbath be kept?<br>
   <br>
   2.  Can I justify my position (on Sabbath keeping) from the Bible?<br>
<p>
-----<br>
<p>
   The first question is simple enough, but I've found that the answer is <br>
anything but straightforward.  The second question is what prompted this post<br>
to SDAnet.<br>
<p>
   Reasons.  Reasons?  Reasons!  Why must one have reasons for doing the <br>
things one does?  If a person focused on having a close enough relationship <br>
with God, then wouldn't s/he be convicted of what was right/wrong?  Why then <br>
must one have physical, concrete reasons?  Does one's Christian walk have to <br>
be REASONable? or can we rely on tradition and/or convictions (feelings?).<br>
<p>
   I am an Engineer, and thus prefer to have well-defined beliefs.  Although<br>
I don't need to have formulas as such, nevertheless I try to have definite,<br>
well defined principles for the things I do (and don't do).  This way, I <br>
can keep from adopting the hypocritical tendencies which Jesus denounced<br>
(Matt 23:25, many other texts).<br>
<p>
   I believe that the Bible should be our main source of truth.  This isn't<br>
to say that the writings of Ellen White and other books are irrelevent.  On<br>
the contrary!  I often gain many spiritual blessings from the writings of EGW, <br>
and believe that her writings are very relevent and appropriate today.  I just<br>
believe that when it comes to defining beliefs, then we should base our <br>
decisions fully on God's word.<br>
<p>
   OK, ok, enough of defining positions.  The meat of the question is:  Show<br>
me from the Bible, some simple, quality principles for how we should spend our <br>
time on Sabbath.  Simple enough?  Not really!  I have come to the conclusion <br>
that either my standards are needlessly high, or most members of the SDA <br>
church are hypocrites when it comes to Sabbath observance.<br>
<p>
<p>
EXAMPLES -- EXAMPLES -- EXAMPLES -- EXAMPLES -- EXAMPLES -- EXAMPLES <br>
<p>
Sabbath Afternoon Activities???<br>
-------------------------------<br>
<p>
Rock-climbing with ropes and gear <br>
An exertive hike (scrambling) up a mountain<br>
A leisurely stroll through the woods <br>
Sitting around the living room, talking<br>
<p>
Playing a competitive game of basketball or soccer<br>
Shooting baskets for the fun of it<br>
Playing "catch" with a base-ball or throwing a frisbee<br>
Skipping rocks across a lake<br>
Playing a game of charades or Bible trivia<br>
<p>
Studying for classes, doing homework<br>
Doing only homework for Bible classes<br>
Watching a nature special on the Discovery Channel<br>
Reading National Geographics<br>
<p>
Sleeping through Sabbath School<br>
Sleeping most of the afternoon  <br>
<p>
Sabbath afternoon discussions:<br>
   Discussing Adventist doctrines<br>
   Secular things<br>
   Gossipping<br>
   Normal socializing (not necessarily religious in nature)<br>
<p>
Leaf-raking for the elderly (non-SDA's)<br>
   This was quite a controvertial one on WWC campus.  The Bible clearly <br>
   states that no work should be done on the Sabbath (Ex 20:8, Heb. 4:9,10),<br>
   but Jesus also said it is lawful to do good on the Sabbath (Matt 12:12).<br>
<p>
NOTE:  Even though these examples might sound very legalistic in nature,<br>
====   what I'm trying to find are the driving principles behind these <br>
       situations.<br>
<p>
<p>
TEXTS -- TEXTS -- TEXTS -- TEXTS -- TEXTS -- TEXTS<br>
<p>
   From what I could find in the concordance on Sabbath keeping, most of<br>
the texts deal with refraining from work on the Sabbath  (Ex 20:8; 35:2).<br>
Other texts require that it not be "desecrated" (Isa 56:2,6), and that it<br>
be kept as a sign between us and God (Eze 20:20).<br>
<p>
   How did Jesus spend the Sabbath hours?  Preaching, teaching, healing, <br>
and arguing doctrines with the Pharisees (Matt 12:1-13; Luke 13:10-16).<br>
Notice that he went out of his way *NOT* to stop healing on the Sabbath.<br>
(Wasn't he being a stumbling block to the Pharisees?)<br>
<p>
   Now for the troubling text:  "If you keep... from doing as you please<br>
on my holy day, if you call the Sabbath a delight... if you honor it by <br>
not going your own way, doing as you please, or speaking idle words, <br>
then you will find your joy in the Lord..."  Isa 58:13-14<br>
<p>
   How can I keep from doing as I please, yet be expected to call the <br>
Sabbath a delight?  Does this text mean I can't do anything fun on<br>
Sabbath?  What exactly constitutes "doing as one pleases?"<br>
<p>
<p>
***********************<br>
***  Your Turn Now  ***<br>
***********************<br>
<p>
   Well, I've done quite enough talking thus far.  Now I would like to<br>
hear from you.  Do you have specific suggestions about:<br>
<p>
  -- Answers to some of the questions above?<br>
  -- Guiding principles for appropriate Sabbath activities?<br>
  -- Bible texts to support those principles?<br>
<p>
   Thanks.<br>
<p>
--John Ash (jash@eecs.wsu.edu)<br>
KB7ONG <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
