<title>May_1993: Adult Children Of God</title>
<h1>Adult Children Of God</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 12 May 1993 00:43:49 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">John Gaskins: "Re: SDA-L topics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Authoritarian leadership"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0074.html">CHURMS@nacdh4.nac.ac.za: "Re: Adult Children Of God"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I recently attended an alumni reunion where one of the honored alumni<br>
was said to have "two adult children."  In the current climate with the<br>
popularity of the group "Adult Children Of Alcoholics", I thought <br>
to myself, "this guy must have done something wrong."<br>
<p>
But then I thought, well what about God?  With all the dysfunctional<br>
relationships that occur with God, there must be some people who have<br>
failed to grow up and are now "adult children"<br>
<p>
If there were a support group for "Adult Children of God", what would <br>
it's twelve steps be?  Is our church already a support group of sorts <br>
for these type of people?  What would characterize such people?  Would<br>
it be the aversion to any type of authority?  Would it be a tendency to <br>
downplay or attack the law to build up the gospel?  Or perhaps a behavior<br>
to pigeonhole God into a particular "sweet loving Jesus" box or  "big<br>
bad God" box?<br>
<p>
<p>
Inquiring minds want to know.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
