<!-- body="start" -->
Style of leadership assumes "style."<br>
<p>
As for evangelistic efforts, I'd be very interested in how you think<br>
those of us who are charged with the responsibility for allocation of<br>
church resources [I am a layperson who has often been a part of the<br>
governance structure, e.g., conference committee, college/university<br>
trustee] should evaluate the value of varying types of evangelism.  For<br>
example, suppose we discovered that evangelistic efforts cost us<br>
$1,000 per "recruit" [baptism], but programs in schools cost us<br>
$500 per "recruit"?  Or that efforts in Spanish-speaking groups cost<br>
us $500 per baptism, but in one of the Asian languages the cost was<br>
$10,000 per baptism?  What if the Anglo effort cost $25,000 per baptism,<br>
but running health clinics in the local church cost us $1,250 per<br>
baptism?  Would that information be relevant?  <br>
<p>
What are appropriate measures for performance in a church setting?<br>
<p>
[All numbers are purely hypothetical!!!]  Is baptism a proper surrogate<br>
for "success"?  Do the gospels speak of the number of baptisms Christ<br>
achieved?<br>
<p>
--Jerry Wiley<br>
USC, LSU, So. Calif. Conf., Alhambra SDA Church<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
