<title>May_1993: Re: Authoritarian Leadership</title>
<h1>Re: Authoritarian Leadership</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 12 May 93 14:03:47 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#65">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#65">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#65">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#65">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Adult Children Of God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Steven Timm: "Uniformity and success"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0060.html">Steven Timm: "Authoritarian Leadership"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It's interesting that Ellen White recommended a non-authoritarian<br>
system of church government with 3 or 4 gc presidents around the<br>
world.  I suppose one for each world division, and no one above<br>
them.  Like the 12 apostles with only Christ above them.  It would<br>
give the church a less centralized system.  But her suggestions were<br>
rejected by the GC -- the vote was 60 to 20 or something -- in<br>
1901 or 1903, I don't remember which.  She was crushed and wrote<br>
about it being the greatest disappointment of her life.  The<br>
leaders rejected her explicit counsel;  one of them even said,<br>
It's OK to have a central president, as long as he respects the<br>
counsels of the Lord through Sister White.  At the same time as<br>
they were rejecting her counsel.<br>
<p>
The church leaders are human like us all and the human tendency<br>
is to centralize power more and more.  I think Folkenberg is trying<br>
to reverse this.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
