<title>May_1993: Uniformity and success</title>
<h1>Uniformity and success</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 12 May 1993 23:58:27 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">David Plaisted: "Re: Authoritarian Leadership"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">John Gaskins: "Re: SDA-L topics"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0081.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: Uniformity and success"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The organization began in a small building in Southern California, in<br>
the early 1950's.  From the beginning their focus was on serving people.<br>
 The <br>
people whom they served always thought they were treated fairly and enjoyed<br>
the service.  One of the suppliers of the organization came to visit and was<br>
amazed at the amount of equipment they needed for their food service.  He <br>
soon bought the entire organization and began opening branches, first across<br>
America, then around the world.<br>
<p>
As the organization spread out, they maintained a strict uniformity in their<br>
service.  The same product was served all over the world, with few if any <br>
variations permitted.  Patrons were urged to take what was served and<br>
not ask for substitutions.  Often raw materials for the products were<br>
imported <br>
from America.  This organization became a symbol of America all over the <br>
world and was known by American travelers abroad as a place where English<br>
would always be spoken.  Despite this rigidity, or perhaps because of it,<br>
the organization has always been very profitable, and currently faces the <br>
crisis of altering its signs because they can only show "99 BILLION SERVED"<br>
and they have now served more than that.  I speak, of course, of McDonald's.<br>
<p>
What can the SDA church learn from McDonald's about rigidity and its effects?<br>
Since the vegetarians of Berrien Springs, MI have made that McDonalds one of <br>
the few in the USA to offer a vegetarian sandwich at a discount, we know that<br>
even McDonalds (which admits to throwing all customer suggestions in the<br>
trash heap) can bend with time.  Should the SDA church do the same?<br>
<p>
What is the core of our business and what is the cultural wrapping it<br>
comes in?  Is our church training all our new converts overseas to be<br>
Seventh-day<br>
Americans? Is Jesus the sushi of life and the tortilla of life as well <br>
as the bread of life?  Can we separate the gospel from the rugged<br>
individualism that Americans of all denominations attach to it?  I<br>
believe that we can and must.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<p>
  <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
