<title>May_1993: Re:  Adult Children Of God</title>
<h1>Re:  Adult Children Of God</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 13 May 1993 00:57:22 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#75">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#75">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#75">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#75">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0076.html">John Gaskins: "Re: SDA-L:  Oakwood Re: SDA-L topics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0074.html">CHURMS@nacdh4.nac.ac.za: "Re: Adult Children Of God"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0062.html">Steven Timm: "Adult Children Of God"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Responding to two questions:  <br>
<p>
1)  Why do we attract the "odd people"?  <br>
<p>
Although I am not at all sure that this statement is quantitatively true,<br>
we do have our share.  Quantitative surveys are always frustrated because<br>
it's hard to know whether or not to count oneself into the total.<br>
<p>
Several factors contribute:<br>
    a)  SDA churches are generally metropolitan churches, not community<br>
        churches.  Thus there is no selection effect due to location.<br>
        An SDA church is more likely to draw from all socioeconomic strata.<br>
    <br>
    b)  The common ground of forming an SDA church is doctrinally based,<br>
        not a group of people with common goals and interests.  To join <br>
        the SDA church one must inherently be a nonconformist.<br>
<p>
    c)  The SDA church preaches exclusivism.  Few ministers say we are the<br>
        only way to get to heaven anymore, but most still say we are the<br>
             best. (and well they should.)  For those who turn to<br>
religion <br>
        seeking internal security (the vast majority), an exclusive<br>
        advantage is very appealing.<br>
<p>
    d)  The SDA church has more than our share of saintly persons who take<br>
        an interest in these "odd people" and get them involved in coming<br>
        to church and learning about the SDA message.<br>
<p>
Church wouldn't be church without them.  I have been to churches that <br>
were on purpose constructed 30 miles out of downtown in a ritzy suburb,<br>
thus using transportation to screen out the inner-city people and the <br>
disabled and handicapped.  It feels so artificial there.  Church isn't<br>
meant to be a collection of people just like me, and I hope everyone<br>
is grateful for that.<br>
<p>
<p>
2)  Did I "slip off the fence", or nearly so, as Marcus suggested?<br>
<p>
Well, maybe I didn't explain myself as well as I could have.  "Adult<br>
Children Of God" is not a precise enough term to cover all the different<br>
behaviors<br>
I was mentioning, and besides, the Bible says that we are and will always <br>
be children of God.  Perhaps "Recovering legalists", "Co-legalists",<br>
and "adult children of legalists" are more descriptive terms for the<br>
behaviors I'm trying to describe.  All three of these groups have in common<br>
the behavior of ignoring or explaining away scriptural evidence that doesn't<br>
fit their rigid pictures of God and how to relate to Him.<br>
<p>
I see the "recovering legalist" as one who says the right words about <br>
how salvation happens, but between every sentence adds a caveat from the <br>
book of James.  <br>
<p>
The "co-legalist" is not a legalist at all, in fact is the opposite.<br>
When pressed the co-legalist will say that one does need to obey God.<br>
But the rest of the time is spent beating the rubber chicken of legalism<br>
wherever it is found and many places that it is not.  The "co-legalist"<br>
is co-dependent on the legalist in the sense that if there were no legalism<br>
to attack, he would have nothing to say.  <br>
<p>
The "Adult Children of Legalists" are often those who had bad experiences<br>
with church rules and regulations while growing up.  But instead of<br>
recognizing that the rules were simply misapplied, they conclude that <br>
the rules and regulations, and the church that made them, are wrong.<br>
Often, however, they will attack the rules and rule-makers using the same<br>
intolerant attitude and narrow-mindedness that was used on them.<br>
<p>
All three of these groups can be distinguished in conversation because<br>
they will often agree in words to the point being discussed but yet<br>
the extraneous things they add to the conversation will tell you that <br>
there is another issue which is emotionally much more important to them.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
