<title>May_1993: Re: Sabbath Observance</title>
<h1>Re: Sabbath Observance</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 13 May 93 10:42:41 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#79">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#79">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#79">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#79">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0080.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Adult Children Of God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Fred Christiansen: "Info on James Arrabito's productions"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0070.html">John Ash - CS: "Sabbath Observance"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0116.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Re: Sabbath Observance"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[John Ash - CS writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; [.. lots of things ..]</i><br>
<i>&gt;    Now for the troubling text:  "If you keep... from doing as you please</i><br>
<i>&gt; on my holy day, if you call the Sabbath a delight... if you honor it by </i><br>
<i>&gt; not going your own way, doing as you please, or speaking idle words, </i><br>
<i>&gt; then you will find your joy in the Lord..."  Isa 58:13-14</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;    How can I keep from doing as I please, yet be expected to call the </i><br>
<i>&gt; Sabbath a delight?  Does this text mean I can't do anything fun on</i><br>
<i>&gt; Sabbath?  What exactly constitutes "doing as one pleases?"</i><br>
<p>
I shan't address everything in John's message, raising some excellent<br>
points for tho't, but I did want to respond to the above since I've been<br>
thinking on this lately.<br>
<p>
Recently, a certain pastor discussed the above text, and made some<br>
observations and conclusions.  I found myself in disagreement with<br>
his observations, making his conclusions worthy of question.  His observation<br>
had to do with the word "pleasure".  He claimed that in olden times,<br>
when you entered a pub, the waiter asked you, "What is your pleasure?"<br>
You would answer "plumber" or "accountant" (to use today's terms) and be<br>
shown to a table of your fellows.  He observed then, that the verse<br>
meant simply you should not work for gain on the Sabbath.  Altho I had never<br>
encountered this alleged denotation in old English (e.g., Shakespeare), I<br>
could not deny it.  Hence it seemed worthwhile investigating the underlying<br>
Hebrew to see if it supported this concept.<br>
<p>
The Strong's number for "pleasure" herein, if memory serves, is 2656;<br>
the Hebrew is "chephets" (khay-phets), meaning delight, pleasure, that<br>
which delights or pleases you, etc.  Hence, the Hebrew does not support<br>
the notion that "pleasure" here means "work".<br>
<p>
Moreover, in the classic Hebrew manner of expressing parallel tho'ts,<br>
the phrase is in context with:<br>
    not doing thine own ways,<br>
    nor finding thine own pleasure,<br>
    nor speaking thine own words: (Is 58:13c)<br>
<p>
I submit that this is contrasting honoring God by doing what pleases Him<br>
versus pleasing ourselves, i.e., doing whatever we please, doing whatever<br>
we want (the essence of rebellion and selfishness).  I believe that the<br>
prior phrases support this.  Notice:<br>
    and call the sabbath a delight,<br>
    the holy of the LORD, honourable;<br>
    and shalt honour him, (Is 58:13b)<br>
<p>
When we understand the contrast, that helps us understand what John finds<br>
troubling:<br>
    If thou turn away thy foot from the sabbath,<br>
    from doing thy pleasure on my holy day; (Is 58:13a)<br>
<p>
The contrast of "pleasing God" versus "pleasing myself" is repeated numerous<br>
times in Scripture.  Deut 12:8, 13:18: Judges 17:6, 21:25; and throughout<br>
Kings and Chronicles as a description of a king's reign, e.g., 2 Chr 14:2.<br>
Also note Proverbs:<br>
    PRO 12:15 The way of a fool is right in his own eyes: but he that<br>
    hearkeneth unto counsel is wise.<br>
    PRO 21:2 Every way of a man is right in his own eyes: but the LORD<br>
    pondereth the hearts.<br>
<p>
But, one may say, it still sounds like I can't have fun on the Sabbath!<br>
Well, perhaps it depends upon how we have developed our tastes.  Let's<br>
note some more contrasts simply where the word pleasure is used, let<br>
alone joy (Neh 8:10) and many others we could also refer to:<br>
    PSA 16:11 Thou wilt shew me the path of life: in thy presence is<br>
    fulness of JOY; at thy right hand there are PLEASURES for evermore.<br>
    PSA 36:8 They shall be abundantly satisfied with the fatness of thy house;<br>
    and thou shalt make them drink of the river of thy PLEASURES.<br>
    PSA 111:2 The works of the LORD are great, sought out of all them that<br>
    have pleasure therein.<br>
    PHI 2:13 For it is God which worketh in you both to will and to do of<br>
    his good pleasure.<br>
<p>
    PRO 21:17 He that loveth pleasure shall be a poor man: he that<br>
    loveth wine and oil shall not be rich.<br>
    ECC 2:1 I said in mine heart, Go to now, I will prove thee with mirth,<br>
    therefore enjoy pleasure: and, behold, this also is vanity.<br>
    ISA 47:8 Therefore hear now this, thou that art given to pleasures, that<br>
    dwellest carelessly, that sayest in thine heart, I am, and none else<br>
    beside me;<br>
    LUK 8:14 And that which fell among thorns are they, which, when they<br>
    have heard, go forth, and are choked with cares and riches and pleasures<br>
    of this life, and bring no fruit to perfection.<br>
    ROM 1:32 Who knowing the judgment of God, that they which commit such<br>
    things are worthy of death, not only do the same, but have pleasure in<br>
    them that do them.<br>
    TH2 2:12 That they all might be damned who believed not the truth, but<br>
    had pleasure in unrighteousness.<br>
    PE2 2:13 And shall receive the reward of unrighteousness, as they that<br>
    count it pleasure to riot in the day time. Spots they are and blemishes,<br>
    sporting themselves with their own deceivings while they feast with you;<br>
    HEB 11:25 Choosing rather to suffer affliction with the people of God,<br>
    than to enjoy the PLEASURES OF SIN for a season;<br>
<p>
We see clearly contrasted the pleasures of God versus the pleasures of sin.<br>
These are parallel with, may I suggest identical to, the contrasts preceding.<br>
<p>
When we are willing to accept God's premise that the Sabbath is a delight<br>
made for us (Mar 2:27), to be found when we desire His pleasures instead<br>
of our own carnal ones, when we desire His ways above ours (Isa ch 55),<br>
when we desire to speak His words (Isa 6:1-8), then we shall experience<br>
the promised rewards:<br>
    ISA 58:14 Then shalt thou delight thyself in the LORD; and I will cause<br>
    thee to ride upon the high places of the earth, and feed thee with the<br>
    heritage of Jacob thy father: for the mouth of the LORD hath spoken it.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
