<!-- body="start" -->
Steven Timm writes:<br>
[ ... about the Golden Arches Family Restaurant ... ]<br>
<i>&gt;What is the core of our business and what is the cultural wrapping it</i><br>
<i>&gt;comes in?  Is our church training all our new converts overseas to be</i><br>
<i>&gt;Seventh-day Americans?</i><br>
<p>
I don't think even the most ardent McDonald's supporter would suggest<br>
that you should eat there exclusively.  There is plenty of scope for<br>
filling out your other culinary needs (whether nutritional or<br>
aesthetic) from other institutions.<br>
<p>
Are we as accomodating in the church?  To some extent we are, but we do<br>
seem to have some difficulty deciding which bits we will allow<br>
ourselves to disagree on.  Ironically, many of these things are, in<br>
fact, things that people disagree about.  Many of the "hot potatoes"<br>
are more or less accepted in some parts of the world: e.g. the<br>
ordination of women, or worship styles.  In the list of Sabbath<br>
afternoon activities given in another posting, many would be acceptable<br>
in some cultures but not in others.<br>
<p>
This must mean we either _are_ able to cope with cultural variations,<br>
and are just not (completely) admitting it, or we haven't been totally<br>
successful at impressing one particular culture on the whole of the<br>
church body.<br>
<p>
Malcolm<br>
disclaimer:  Given the oportunity, I am perfectly willing to avoid<br>
eating at McDonald's.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
