<title>May_1993: Re: E-mail addresses</title>
<h1>Re: E-mail addresses</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 14 May 1993 00:58:59 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#82">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#82">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#82">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#82">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0083.html">TANG BENG YONG: "female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0081.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: Uniformity and success"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0072.html">Steven Timm: "E-mail addresses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0093.html">Woody Baker: "Re: E-mail addresses"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm glad that e-mail address lists are not released to non-subscribers<br>
of SDAnet, but I'd also like to suggest that e-mail mailing lists not be<br>
released to ANYONE without each individual's express permission.  I feel<br>
that just because I belong to a mailing list (e-mail, Snail mail, or<br>
otherwise) does not mean that my address should be distributed to<br>
others.  I feel that people should have the right to choose who gets<br>
information about them.<br>
<p>
I know that some will say that this is "public" information - that it<br>
could be gotten simply from passwd files on computer systems, etc.  But<br>
The analogy is sometimes made to "public" listings of names and<br>
addresses in phone books.....  But my argument is that just because<br>
something has been "public" information - like phone books - does not<br>
mean that it is the same issue when it is in machine readable form, a<br>
form that makes it very easily distributable and searchable by all kinds<br>
of people.  I think that this issue needs to be addressed by the<br>
computing/information community and given very serious thought.  I think<br>
it is being badly neglected in the discussions of today.<br>
<p>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Dan Turk     Computer Science &amp; Information Systems     Andrews University<br>
Berrien Springs, MI          turk@andrews.edu               (616) 471-3426<br>
==========================================================================<br>
[It is SDAnet policy that whoever wishes to be anonymous in the directory<br>
may remain anonymous.  But an explicit "no" is required, not an explicit<br>
yes.  Also, the list as we give it out is really not machine-readable<br>
without a great deal of work.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
