<title>May_1993: Divorce in the SDA church</title>
<h1>Divorce in the SDA church</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 14 May 1993 01:24:46 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#87">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#87">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#87">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#87">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0088.html">Steven Timm: "Re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0086.html">a11111arne@attmail.com: "Re: SDAnet news release"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Time was when a divorce meant a death sentence for a pastor's career in <br>
the SDA church.  It seems that this is no longer the case.  Is this <br>
another case of trying so hard to avoid the past mistake of condemnation<br>
that we have fallen into the opposite trap of being morally struck mute?<br>
Or worse yet, have we moved from condemners to enablers, becoming void<br>
of spiritual authority?<br>
<p>
I am not saying that a divorce ought necessarily to end a pastor's career.<br>
Nor do I know any divorced pastors still serving who are guilty of adultery.<br>
But the state of families in church leadership as well as membership is <br>
certainly endangered today, and I would like to see a way for the church <br>
to support family unity.  Any ideas?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0088.html">Steven Timm: "Re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0086.html">a11111arne@attmail.com: "Re: SDAnet news release"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
