<title>May_1993: Re: female homosexuality in the bible?</title>
<h1>Re: female homosexuality in the bible?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 14 May 1993 01:40:39 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#88">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#88">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#88">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#88">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re: SDA-L topics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">Steven Timm: "Divorce in the SDA church"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0083.html">TANG BENG YONG: "female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dan Crowe: "Re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
We've had a few posts on the issue that seemed to disappear into the <br>
bit bucket and gather no responses.  <br>
<p>
The central question here is:  "Is whatever that is not expressly forbidden<br>
by the Bible allowed?"  <br>
<p>
There are two slippery slopes of Bible interpretation that one can fall <br>
down in this instance, and I find myself arguing for balance, which worries me.<br>
<p>
Slippery slope number 1:  We argue that some of the verses in the NT are<br>
culturally conditioned.  (Particularly those dealing with women.)  But the<br>
verses dealing with women and those dealing with homosexuality are in close<br>
juxtaposition, and it is hard to reject one set without rejecting the <br>
other as well.<br>
<p>
Slippery slope number 2:  We hold the Mosaic laws against homosexuality<br>
and bestiality to be still binding.  But then it is difficult to say why <br>
the others should not be valid still as well.  Furthermore, if we wish <br>
to establish God's ideal for sexual intimacy, we must return to the <br>
Genesis account of the creation of Adam and Eve.  If initimacy is viewed<br>
as the ultimate expression of the image of God, then not only homosexuality<br>
but perhaps other sexual variants even between marriage partners, and birth <br>
control, can be called into question.  In short, I fail to see how one <br>
can pursue this line of thought and not wind up with the Catholic view<br>
of procreation.  People have tried to convince me otherwise on SDAnet<br>
and hopefully they will try again.  But I find it strange that most groups<br>
who deliver Bible studies on this issue come up with a position that <br>
declares to be "all right" what they are already doing.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
