<title>May_1993: re: female homosexuality in the bible?</title>
<h1>re: female homosexuality in the bible?</h1>
<i>beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com</i><br>
<i>Fri, 14 May 93 08:58:53 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#104">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#104">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#104">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#104">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0105.html">Susan Harrington: "Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0103.html">beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com: "Egocentric exegesis"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0108.html">Steven Timm: "female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0105.html">Susan Harrington: "Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To answer the original poster's question: the apostle Paul<br>
mentions what can be reasonably interpreted as female homosexuality<br>
in Romans 1:26, lumping it together with its male analogue in<br>
the next verse.<br>
<p>
Regarding slippery slope #1: I've also wondered if the NT condemnation<br>
of homosexuality could possibly be culturally conditioned, as some of<br>
the verses dealing with women are thought to be (though perhaps<br>
properly understood the latter are not as controversial as they appear<br>
taken at face value).  What helped convince me that this is probably<br>
*not* the case are the corresponding Mosiac prohibitions against<br>
homosexuality.  The culture of the early Christians in Rome was<br>
substantially different than that of the Israelites in the wilderness.<br>
Yet homosexual relations are a sin in both cultures.  To me this is a<br>
sign of something normative.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Slippery slope number 2:  We hold the Mosaic laws against homosexuality</i><br>
<i>&gt; and bestiality to be still binding.  But then it is difficult to say why </i><br>
<i>&gt; the others should not be valid still as well.  Furthermore, if we wish </i><br>
<p>
If by "others" you mean other parts of the Levitical code, there are<br>
indeed other parts which are still binding on Christians (e.g. the<br>
definitions of unclean meats which are not to be considered as food).<br>
For myself, it helps to (1) try to understand the principle behind<br>
the original regulation (2) decide if the principle is still valid<br>
and (3) if the principle is still valid, decide if the regulation is<br>
still a valid application of that principle.<br>
<p>
For passover and the sacrificial system, I don't think the principle of<br>
pointing forward to Christ is valid anymore.  They've been superseded.<br>
(e.g., by the Lord's Supper, which shows the Lord's death until He<br>
returns). <br>
<p>
For unclean meats, the NT principle of my body as the temple of God<br>
is still valid today.  Given that the composition of unclean meats<br>
and the human body's reaction to consuming them is not any better today<br>
than in OT times, it seems logical that (3) holds and the regulation is<br>
still applicable. <br>
<p>
Gary Beihl (gary.beihl@columbiasc.ncr.com)<br>
