<title>May_1993: Re: Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re: Sabbath</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>14 May 1993 09:51:23 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#85">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#85">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#85">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#85">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0086.html">a11111arne@attmail.com: "Re: SDAnet news release"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The Branch Davidians &amp; Events at Waco"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I find it interesting to read the whole of Isaiah 58 rather than<br>
just the last two or three texts. If you consider the days of <br>
fasting as similar to the Sabbath, then this may provide more<br>
illumination on the topic of doing good on the Sabbath. Whether<br>
or not this is good exegesis is another question!<br>
<p>
As for "refraining from doing as you please", I don't think<br>
anybody reads that as "don't do anything you enjoy", rather "don't<br>
just do any old thing". Treat the day as distinctly separate from<br>
your everyday existence.<br>
<p>
And the phrase "do no work"? I would like to hear from one of our<br>
ancient languages experts as to just what this phrase could mean.<br>
I doubt that the "work" referred to hear is the same definition of<br>
work that a ten year old would use, or even that a modern Western<br>
adult would use.<br>
<p>
It's also interesting to carefully look at Jesus' Sabbath miracles.<br>
In each and every case the healing was a non-urgent, non-life-<br>
threatening situation; well, those that are recorded in the gospels<br>
anyway. Each time He made a point of it, rather than just healing<br>
the person quietly. I have often wondered what Jesus would do in<br>
the late twentieth century to shock Seventh-day Adventists into<br>
viewing the Sabbath differently!<br>
<p>
Lastly...<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
   I believe that the Bible should be our main source of truth.  This isn't<br>
to say that the writings of Ellen White and other books are irrelevent.  On<br>
the contrary!  I often gain many spiritual blessings from the writings of EGW, <br>
and believe that her writings are very relevent and appropriate today.  I just<br>
believe that when it comes to defining beliefs, then we should base our <br>
decisions fully on God's word.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
To the writer of this paragraph, what major difference do you perceive between<br>
the word of God given through Ellen White and that given through the prophets<br>
of old? Given, of course, that every prophet was a "modern day" prophet at<br>
some point in history.<br>
<p>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
