<title>May_1993: Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?</title>
<h1>Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?</h1>
Susan Harrington (<i>sue@cuc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 14 May 93 11:35:42 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#105">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#105">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#105">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#105">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0106.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "The White Lie, golf at PUC, Newbury Park shopping mall"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0104.html">beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com: "re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0108.html">Steven Timm: "female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0107.html">Dan Crowe : "Re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Beng writes:  "no true SDA would ever be taken in by them (arguments for<br>
biblical non-condemnation of homosexuality)."<br>
<p>
I believe that a true SDA can surely believe in non-condemnation of<br>
homosexuality.  I am one of them.  <br>
<p>
You probably won't find anything about lesbians in the scriptures.  At least<br>
I haven't found anything but then that is hardly a surprise.  In the scriptures<br>
women are talked about only as a function of males.  <br>
<p>
Beng wrties:  "it is illegal to have sex with children or with members of the<br>
same sex".  <br>
<p>
To equate sexual abuse of children with sexual acts between consenting<br>
adults is to minimize a horrible act of domination.  <br>
<p>
We, none of us, know why a person is a gay, lesbian or a straight person.  We<br>
can, however, observe how difficult it is in our society for a person who is gay or lesbian.  We, as friends of the Divine One, could perhaps ease this pain by<br>
providing acceptance and love.  We have been told not to judge--when we<br>
condemn persons different from us we are judging.<br>
<p>
You might talk with a person who is struggling with who they are (e.g. with their sexual orientation) before you make blanket statements of condemnation.  <br>
I cannot believe that we are acting as co-workers with the Holy One when we<br>
alienate persons who are different from us.<br>
<p>
Sue Harrington<br>
Computer Science<br>
Columbia Union College<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
