<title>May_1993: Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?</title>
<h1>Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 16 May 93 12:09:07 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#94">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#94">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#94">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#94">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0095.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Sabbath Observance"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0093.html">Woody Baker: "Re: E-mail addresses"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0108.html">Steven Timm: "female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0104.html">beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com: "re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Sue Harrington writes:<br>
<i>&gt;We, none of us, know why a person is a gay, lesbian or a straight person. </i><br>
<i>&gt;We can, however, observe how difficult it is in our society for a person</i><br>
<i>&gt;who is gay or lesbian.  We, as friends of the Divine One, could perhaps ease</i><br>
<i>&gt;this pain by providing acceptance and love.  We have been told not to</i><br>
<i>&gt;judge--when we condemn persons different from us we are judging.</i><br>
<p>
It is true that homosexuals have a hard time in society, and that we should<br>
definitely provide everyone, including them, with acceptance and love, but<br>
that does not mean that we okay homosexuality any more than we do any other<br>
form of sex perversion (eg: heterosexual adultery etc).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;You might talk with a person who is struggling with who they are (e.g.</i><br>
<i>&gt;with their sexual orientation) before you make blanket statements of</i><br>
<i>&gt;condemnation.  I cannot believe that we are acting as co-workers with the</i><br>
<i>&gt;Holy One when we alienate persons who are different from us.</i><br>
<p>
Well, are not all Christians struggling with self? It is not our business to<br>
condemn individuals, but we are to call sin by its right name. "Straight"<br>
people perhaps have to struggle with various other temptations too, and we<br>
don't condemn them as people, neither do we tell them it is okay to sin, we<br>
should treat homosexuals the same. What i am really against is the promotion<br>
of sin as a way of life, which is what some of these gay and lesbian<br>
activists seem to be doing.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
