<title>May_1993: The White Lie, golf at PUC, Newbury Park shopping mall</title>
<h1>The White Lie, golf at PUC, Newbury Park shopping mall</h1>
<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>16 May 1993 15:43:16 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#106">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#106">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#106">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#106">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0107.html">Dan Crowe : "Re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0105.html">Susan Harrington: "Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
1. If you have access to a copy of the White Lie, read it -- it is a<br>
fascinating volume and well-documented.  I could only wish that Wlater<br>
(oops, Walter) Rey (or is it Ray?) had been less vitriolic and more<br>
even-tempered in between his scholarly documentations of EGW's borrowing<br>
of material.  He has side by side comparisons of chspaters in which<br>
nearly every word, plus chapter titles and illustrations have been<br>
taken from another book.  (Well, I can't type today -- chspaters=chapters!)<br>
<p>
2. Our PUC netter may have more up to date information, but I hear that<br>
the PUC golf course idea is not dead yet.  My brother sent me clippings<br>
from the St. Helena paper that include a discussion of various uses for<br>
some of the college's land: cemetery, retirement center, agricultural uses;<br>
however, the VP for financial affairs at PUC is quoted as saying that<br>
the administration thought those uses would not generate as much income<br>
as a golf course!  Well, now, if income is our goal, turn the college into<br>
a casino!  That would really bring in the bucks!<br>
<p>
3. Along the same lines, the Newbury Park church has decided to move<br>
their church, school, and senior citizens' housing to one end of their<br>
campus, and build a 30-acre shopping mall at the other end -- complete<br>
with a multiscreen theater, Price Club type warehouse, and other stores<br>
that would sell liquor and remain open through the weekend.  Adventist<br>
officials "in charge of the project angrily refute accusations that they<br>
are abandoning their religious principles for material gain.  Although they<br>
will shepherd the project through the Planning Commission and City Council<br>
over the next six months, the Adventists plan to sell the movie theater<br>
and perhaps the retail stores once the development gets under way, church<br>
leaders said."  Oh, well, that makes me feel better!  We are just getting<br>
it started, then selling, so we have no further responsibility!  Whatever<br>
happened to the "strangers within our gates" admonition?<br>
<p>
Regarding numbers 2 and 3, I think we would do well to read a little<br>
Faust now and again, just to remind us what happens to someone who sells<br>
their soul for earthly gain.  I mention Faust, because surely these good<br>
SDA people are not reading their Bibles and following the council they<br>
find there....<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
