<title>May_1993: Re: Sabbath Observance</title>
<h1>Re: Sabbath Observance</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 17 May 1993 09:57:37 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#116">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#116">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#116">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#116">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0117.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Request for prayer support"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0115.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Integrated Faith and Learning"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0070.html">John Ash - CS: "Sabbath Observance"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0136.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: Sabbath Observance"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The questions raised by John Ash about Sabbath observance are interesting<br>
and provide the basis for a very long discussion. The verses from the<br>
Bible regarding the detail of Sabbath observance range from condemnation<br>
of any work through to allowing necessary work.<br>
<p>
On the one hand we are told not to do our own pleasure, while on the other<br>
hand we are told that the Sabbath was made for man. We live in a complex<br>
society and it is impossible to shut down hospitals, power stations,<br>
blast furnaces etc for a variety of reasons. How then do we observe<br>
Sabbath?<br>
<p>
1.  Sabbath is a state of mind. We should do all in our power to make<br>
    the Sabbath a delight in the culture and environment we find ourselves<br>
    in.<br>
<p>
2.  The Sabbath was designed as a day of rest. It should be a change<br>
    from what we do for the rest of the week.<br>
<p>
3.  The Jews were condemned for the minute detail of law with which they<br>
    surrounded the Sabbath. They were not condemned for their celebration<br>
    of the Sabbath. It is celebrated as something special, like a birthday<br>
    party.<br>
<p>
4.  We are often too quick to condemn what we see as poor Sabbath observance<br>
    when really many of the differences are cultural. eg Australians don't<br>
    play sport on Sabbath (usually), Other cultures do. I don't think<br>
    either position is wrong.<br>
<p>
5.  The Bible is not a rule book for everything we do. It lays down some<br>
    good principles which we can apply. It says nothing about TV, cars<br>
    and computers, but that does not mean that we should not use them.<br>
    Similarly it only lays down some principles about Sabbath keeping.<br>
    It omits the detail and leaves us to decide that for ourselves.<br>
<p>
6.  An exact formula would be nice, but a heuristic allows us to express<br>
    our Sabbath observance in creative and inovative ways. God himself<br>
    is a creator and I think sometimes he expects us, his subjects to<br>
    be creative as well.<br>
<p>
Maurice Ashton<br>
mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au<br>
   .-_|\<br>
  /     \<br>
  \.--._/<br>
       V<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
