<title>May_1993: Integrated Faith and Learning</title>
<h1>Integrated Faith and Learning</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 17 May 1993 10:15:26 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#115">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#115">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#115">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#115">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Maurice George Ashton: "Re: Sabbath Observance"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0114.html">CHURMS@nacdh4.nac.ac.za: "Re: Homosexuality in the Bible"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A few year ago Humberto Rasi and George Akers from the GC came to<br>
Avondale to run a seminar on Integrated Faith and Learning (IFL).<br>
We had an intersting time and a number of points were raised which<br>
Hilighted the difference between American and Australian education<br>
systems.<br>
<p>
It was pointed out that integrating faith and learning was much easier<br>
in subjects such as literature, history and science, and much more<br>
difficult in subjects such as maths and computer science. It appeared<br>
that the more vocational a subject was, the less easy it was to include<br>
our faith in our teaching.<br>
<p>
As a computer science lecturer, I adopted the approach that in these<br>
subjects the content was less important and the pedagogy, the methods<br>
of how you taught the subject were more important when it comes to<br>
integrating Christian values.<br>
<p>
Since the SDAnet has a number of both educators and students of<br>
computer science among its members, I would be interested in hearing some<br>
dialog on IFL in the area of computer science. At the time of the workshop<br>
I wrote a paper about IFL in computer science and I would like to<br>
improve the paper now by hearing what others have to say about the subject.<br>
<p>
Maurice Ashton<br>
Avondale College<br>
mashton @moria.cs.su.oz.au<br>
   .-_|\<br>
  /     \<br>
  \.--._/<br>
       V <br>
