Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 17 May 1993 19:17:04 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#119">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#119">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#119">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#119">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Steven Timm: "Update on the organ search"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0118.html">Steven Timm: "Bargain time at the Den O'Thieves"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As I've shared before, my approach to this topic changed <br>
somewhat when a friend confided to me that she was <br>
a lesbian.  A lot of theories blow up in  ones face when <br>
faced with the task of practicality.<br>
<p>
Though I do not embrace or condone her behavior, neither <br>
do I condemn it, nor am I surprised by it.  Whatever ones<br>
opinion or belief may be concerning this, responses to it <br>
must come from reasoned calmness and a implicit assumption<br>
that the person is acting as he/she feels he/she must do.<br>
Responses based from fear are counterproductive.<br>
<p>
I feel the battle is too narrowly defined.  Many of the<br>
so-called "pro-family" forces are focusing all their energies<br>
on claiming the homosexual orientation is a choice and not<br>
an innate part of the person.  I would counter that there<br>
is just as much a genetic link to alcoholism as there is to <br>
homosexuality, perhaps more.  Genetic tendencies, even if they exist, do<br>
not excuse behavior.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
