<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Genetic tendencies, even if they exist, do not excuse behavior.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Steve Timm</i><br>
<p>
Correct, so the issue is the behavior, not the orientation?<br>
Is it the type of sex acts we imagine it to include (which many<br>
heterosexuals practice)?  What makes the difference, the genitalia<br>
of the partner (symbol)?  Is the act separate or void of other variables,<br>
"love", "care", "fidelity" - which we assume all heterosexual relations<br>
contain?<br>
<p>
These aren't easy questions to answer, at least the may make us<br>
uncomfortable and silent.  What would be the most important thing to<br>
know, how dinosaurs became extinct, or the reasons for and surety<br>
of accepting/rejecting a group of people which Christ lived and died<br>
for, and has a will and purpose for, as for all other sinners?<br>
<p>
Marcus Stringer<br>
@ Microsoft<br>
