<i>&gt; Mississippi" are situated in SDA institutions, with the fourth</i><br>
<i>&gt; (the largest) being in Crystal Cathedral?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Tony</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; [I'll defer to west coast colleges.  PUC's organ is large, but</i><br>
<i>&gt; I doubt it is that large.  Certainly in Pittsburgh alone there </i><br>
<i>&gt; are at least five organs bigger than those to be found at any SDA college.</i><br>
<i>&gt; I know there is one giant tracker organ in Seattle, WA at a nonSDA </i><br>
<i>&gt; institution, and the organ at Davies Hall in San Francisco is nothing </i><br>
<i>&gt; to sneeze at.  The absolute largest organ in the USA is at the </i><br>
<i>&gt; US Military Academy in West Point.  SCT]</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Let me start with the _Guinness Book of World Records_ (1992, p. 179),<br>
which doesn't help much.  It lists the largest and loudest (!) musical<br>
instrument ever built to be the Auditorium Organ in Atlantic City (now<br>
only partially functional).  The largest fully functional organ is at<br>
the Wanamaker Store in Philadelphia (in another state from Pittsburgh?).<br>
It lists the largest church organ at Passau, Germany with 16,000 pipes,<br>
but then lists the West Point organ at 18,200 pipes.  Go figure, I<br>
guess.<br>
<p>
At any rate, it really doesn't answer the question.  We can only surmise<br>
which the 3 organs might be, but probably Walla Walla, PUC and the Loma<br>
Linda University Church (leaving out an organ or two at La Sierra).<br>
What this sounds like is someone trying to make a point without really<br>
checking out the facts (I used to have a pastor like that--I'd go to the<br>
public library each week to see which facts had been mangled that week,<br>
but that's another story).  In addition to the organ of Davies Hall, in<br>
San Franciso surely one would note those in St. Mary's (Catholic) and<br>
Grace (Episcopalian) cathedrals.  I believe the one in Seattle is in St.<br>
Mark's Cathedral.  I don't know the organs of LA, but likely there are<br>
others there, not to mention San Diego, St. Louis, Denver, Texas, etc.,<br>
etc.  Probably the most egregious oversight in this list, however, is<br>
the monster in the Mormon Tabernacle in Salt Lake City (not to mention<br>
the nicer instrument in the Assembly Hall).  It might be interesting to<br>
do a review of Adventist pipe organs sometime, but that sounds more like<br>
a music review and is best left for another occasion.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
