<title>May_1993: Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?</title>
<h1>Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 18 May 93 10:24:59 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#134">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#134">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#134">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#134">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0135.html">Healy, Tammy R: "Re: The White Lie,"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0133.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Jesus and the homosexual"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On May 17,  6:35pm, Floyd Poenitz wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?</i><br>
<i>&gt; From: Susan Harrington  &lt;netmail!sue@cuc.edu&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; To:  &lt;med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg&gt;;  &lt;st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Date: Friday, May 14, 1993 11:35AM</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; I believe that a true SDA can surely believe in non-condemnation of</i><br>
<i>&gt; homosexuality.  I am one of them.</i><br>
<p>
I think people have a very hard time differentiating between the act of<br>
homosexuality and the person who commits the act.  God loves all people, but<br>
hates the sin.  Is it possible to love the homosexual but hate (not condone)<br>
their lifestyle?  I believe so.  But for many, they get their feelings and<br>
emotions wrapped up in the thought and can't seem to separate the two.<br>
<p>
If you have children, you can see how it is possible to hate, abhor, disapprove,<br>
etc, of their bad behavior, but you still love the child very much.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; You probably won't find anything about lesbians in the scriptures.  At least</i><br>
<i>&gt; I haven't found anything but then that is hardly a surprise.  In the</i><br>
<i>&gt; scriptures women are talked about only as a function of males.</i><br>
<p>
Texts have already been mentioned about women and men trading "natural"<br>
relations for "un-natural" ones.  I think that Sodom and Gamorah were guilty of<br>
homosexuality which led to their fiery destruction.  If that isn't an indication<br>
of God's displeasure, then what is?  I would have a hard time believing that<br>
only men were at fault here.  Besides, if "un-natural relations were wrong for<br>
men, would it not also apply for women?<br>
...<br>
<i>&gt; We, none of us, know why a person is a gay, lesbian or a straight person.  We</i><br>
<i>&gt; can, however, observe how difficult it is in our society for a person who is</i><br>
<i>&gt; gay or lesbian.  We, as friends of the Divine One, could perhaps ease this</i><br>
<i>&gt; pain by providing acceptance and love.  We have been told not to judge--when</i><br>
<i>&gt; we condemn persons different from us we are judging.</i><br>
<p>
Again, we must differentiate between the person and the action. We should be<br>
loving to these people, but we should in no way give the impression that we<br>
approve of their actions.  To do so is to approve of homosexuality, which is<br>
clearly stated in the Bible as being abhorant to God.  While we are not to<br>
judge, we are also told to call sin by its right name.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; You might talk with a person who is struggling with who they are (e.g. with</i><br>
<i>&gt; their sexual orientation) before you make blanket statements of condemnation.</i><br>
<i>&gt; I cannot believe that we are acting as co-workers with the Holy One when we</i><br>
<i>&gt; alienate persons who are different from us.</i><br>
<p>
Good point.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
