<title>May_1993: Anti-evangelism</title>
<h1>Anti-evangelism</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>18 May 1993 11:34:08 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#130">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#130">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#130">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#130">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0131.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: SDA world mission"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0129.html">Steve Hix: "Re: The Branch Davidians &amp; Events at Waco"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0146.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Anti-evangelism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Well I have just found out once again the difference in impact<br>
between public evangelism, "what we preach", and personal evangelism,<br>
"what we practice".<br>
<p>
Our conference hosted a basketball competition last Saturday night,<br>
with twenty-odd teams from around the place competing in a round-robin<br>
tournament. The matches were played at the local basketball stadium, the<br>
same one I play at twice a week in their regular competition.<br>
<p>
I regret to say that the prevailing spirit present was not one of <br>
a friendly social get-together. Although many of us did enjoy the night,<br>
a proportion of those competing exhibited behaviour considerably less<br>
than sporting. As an example (this may have been the worst case - I hope<br>
so), in one particular A-grade match the substitute players continually<br>
mouthed off at the referees, to the extent that a bench tech was given.<br>
This is quite a rare occurrence, even in the professional leagues where<br>
a lot more is at stake. Not to be deterred, the players continued with<br>
their abuse, and a second bench tech was given to the same individual.<br>
(Two personal techs were also given to on-court players during the course<br>
of the game). According to the rules, two techs on a single individual<br>
results in this individual having to leave the playing area. After the<br>
match was over, the team suggested to the referee that he may wish to<br>
accompany them outside to discuss the matter further.<br>
<p>
Dispute and bickering were present in some of the other matches as well,<br>
with both referees and players being the target of verbal abuse and some<br>
physical intimidation. Complaints were made about the fact that some of<br>
the refs were juniors (u/16). This was despite the fact that these were<br>
association refs, had come in especially on a Saturday night, and were<br>
being paid $5 per game as opposed to the $7.60 they receive for a regular<br>
social game on a weeknight. I could go on.<br>
<p>
The refs coordinator is a friend of mine, as I've done some refereeing for<br>
her in the past, and she gets to know a lot of the regular players. On the<br>
Sunday night when I turned up for another game she came over to talk to<br>
some friends and I about the previous evening's activities. (She knows I<br>
am ex-Avondale, and she had seen my friends and I at the competition).<br>
She didn't seem particularly angry, but she was certainly upset over some<br>
of the things that had happened. Some of her comments were,<br>
<p>
"It really wasn't a good night at all. For a bunch of Christians, they<br>
weren't very charitable. If they decide to do it again next year, they will<br>
have to find their own referees. We don't want to ruin our Saturday night<br>
just to get abused, especially for $5 a game."<br>
<p>
She had noticed every single thing that had happened, including the fact<br>
that one disgruntled team had stolen half the trophies when they didn't<br>
make it to the grand final.<br>
<p>
Now I'm no angel, and I have to admit that at times I get a bit hot-headed.<br>
The nature of a physical sport like basketball does predispose a player<br>
towards quick reactions, and sometimes actions and words precede thoughts.<br>
<p>
But I have to ask, why are SDA sporting competitions typified by aggression<br>
and argument? Why is it that a tournament between Christians can result in<br>
more tension in a single night than is usually seen in months of regular<br>
competition? Is avoiding competitive sport the answer? If so, it is <br>
disappointing that an activity which can be a lot of fun, and which can<br>
be enriching both socially, and physically, should need to be avoided.<br>
<p>
If nothing else, this experience has served to remind me once again that<br>
anyone who takes on the label "Christian" becomes a witness, like it or<br>
not. My life is under scrutiny, even when I'm not even aware of it. <br>
Our associates take much more notice of what we practice than of what<br>
we preach, and months of good can be ruined in a single moment. There<br>
isn't any theology in that, it's just bitter experience!!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
...my new sig file...<br>
#############################################################################<br>
#                                            #                              #<br>
#	Anthony J. Dyson                     #   phth1@cc.newcastle.edu.au  #<br>
#                                            #                              #<br>
#	Theoretical Surface Research Group   #   RS/6000 320 AIX3.1.5       #<br>
#	Department of Physics                #   (Waiting for the upgrade   #<br>
#	University of Newcastle              #    tapes...still waiting...  #<br>
#	Australia                            #    waiting some more...)     #<br>
#                                            #                              #<br>
#############################################################################<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
