<!-- body="start" -->
Steve, could you please post this (if you think it's appropriate) in <br>
response to all the e-mail notes you forwarded to me?  Thanks!  DG<br>
<p>
****<br>
<p>
It's going to be awhile before I get to personally thank everyone or write<br>
Thank you notes, so this e-mail will have to do in the meantime:<br>
<p>
THANKS for all the cards, visits, phone calls, and thoughts.<br>
<p>
The final story (without too many gory details) is that I developed an<br>
infection on one of the valves of my heart (a valve that I knew was <br>
prolapsed).  This happens to about 2-8% of people with prolapsed valves--I <br>
guess I'm lucky!  The infection evidently sent a clot to my abdomen, <br>
creating appendicitis-like symptoms, which got me into the hospital.  Then a <br>
2nd clot went to my arm (Thank God, not to my brain!), and they had to do <br>
surgery to restore the circulation to my arm.  Then finally, once they had <br>
pumped enough antibiotics into me, they went in and took out the infection <br>
and the affected valve and gave me an artificial valve.  So now, if you're <br>
in the right acoustical position, you can hear my 'click' as my heart <br>
pumps!  Long term, I and my 'click' should be just fine and carry on a <br>
normal life.  In the interim, it's lots of sleep, IV antibiotics three <br>
times a day, and trying not to sneeze or cough while my sternum heals.<br>
<p>
Again, thanks for everything.  I hope to talk to each of you soon.  DG<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
