<title>May_1993: Re: The White Lie,</title>
<h1>Re: The White Lie,</h1>
Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473 (<i>jwiley@law.usc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 18 May 93 18:11:34 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#152">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#152">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#152">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#152">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0153.html">David Plaisted: "Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0151.html">Bill Allen: "Re: SDA world mission"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The problem is not so much in the reliance on sources, but rather on the<br>
claims by church leaders, and to some extent by Mrs. White, that she<br>
did not rely on sources, and that her writings were the result of<br>
special revelation, not the kind of revelation available to the<br>
rest of humanity.  Thus, the plagarism is a minor theme compared<br>
to the unfair and untruthful claims that her millions of words<br>
came by direct revelation of God.  "I put it up on a high shelf<br>
that I might not be influenced by it. . ." is close to one EGW<br>
claim, but the text is so close to the original as to defy credibility.<br>
<p>
Rea really wants people to return to the gospel, and not to use<br>
Mrs. White as if she were "a part of the canon."<br>
<p>
--Jerry Wiley<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
