<title>May_1993: Church organs</title>
<h1>Church organs</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>19 May 1993 09:30:45 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#154">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#154">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#154">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#154">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0155.html">Bill Nickless: "Re: The Branch Davidians &amp; Events at Waco"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0153.html">David Plaisted: "Inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My original source for the statement was the technical guy who came out<br>
to Australia recently accompanying a drama group from La Sierra. I don't<br>
think he was trying to make a point as such, he and I were discussing <br>
various things to do with building acoustics, sound systems, music and so<br>
on, and the fact that at one stage our church was supposed to aquire a<br>
pipe organ. This project has since been "canned", because the donor pulled<br>
out. (More politics I fear!)<br>
<p>
It's great that organ music can point a person upwards to God. Of course,<br>
this isn't always the case, so the question must be: is the financial<br>
investment in such an instrument, along with the necessary acoustic<br>
modifications/design of the building, appropriate considering the mission<br>
of the church as a whole? Even in the local church situation, neglecting<br>
the worldwide church, any building optimized for organ (which it will be<br>
if someone has spent a huge sum of money putting one in), will necessarily<br>
be acoustically poor for many other functions, not the least of which<br>
being speech intelligibility.<br>
<p>
Disclaimer: I myself do enjoy organ music!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
