<title>May_1993: Re: The White Lie,</title>
<h1>Re: The White Lie,</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 19 May 93 16:34:45 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#142">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#142">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#142">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#142">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0143.html">Bruce Holm: "Re:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0141.html">UMBJTO%LLUVM.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Re: Century of Adventist Education in South Africa"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0135.html">Healy, Tammy R: "Re: The White Lie,"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0150.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The White Lie,"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
TAmmy wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I wouldn't recommend this book to anyone eho isn't an SDA.  It basically </i><br>
<i>&gt; makes E.G. White into a plagarist.  Maybe by today's legal standards, she </i><br>
<i>&gt; could be charged with plagarism, but back in the 19th century, you didn't </i><br>
<i>&gt; have to document your sources as thoughly as you do now.</i><br>
<i>&gt; If Sister White had broken any plagarism laws, she would've been brought </i><br>
<i>&gt; to trial, I'm sure.  Since she wasn't sued or ever accused of plagarism </i><br>
<i>&gt; by her detractors in her day, I'd have to say that Walter Rea was out to </i><br>
<i>&gt; smear Sister White, not to encourage the remnant church in the faith of </i><br>
<i>&gt; Jesus.</i><br>
<p>
It goes deeper than plagarism charges.  Some people attack Ellen White's<br>
inspiration by implying that if she was a prophet she would not quote<br>
from other sources.  I guess some would say that she could only quote from<br>
other inspired sources.  This, according to my understanding, is a misunderstanding<br>
of how inspiration works in some instances. Bible writers even did research<br>
and used sources.  At least some of them did.  Luke for example.  I believe<br>
it is proven that Ellen White could not be considered a plagiarist by the laws<br>
of her day.  Also people cannot attack her being a prophet solely on the<br>
premise that inspired writers do not quote or use uninspired sources.<br>
<p>
This question about how inspiration works is one that seems to periodically come up<br>
on the SDAnet.  We may get into it again.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
"Keep the Faith, Baby"  --  Adam Clayton Powell, Jr
"Keep Hope Alive"       --  Jesse Jackson
"We are Saved by Hope"  --  Paul
<p>
Sherman H. Cox, II       scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu
</pre>
