<title>May_1993: Re: The White Lie,</title>
<h1>Re: The White Lie,</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 19 May 1993 18:47:21 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#150">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#150">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#150">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#150">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0151.html">Bill Allen: "Re: SDA world mission"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0149.html">Steven Timm: "Southern College's Organ"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0142.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: The White Lie,"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0165.html">Gingerlei Tupito: "Re: The White Lie,"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am at somewhat of a disadvantage while moderating this discussion, because<br>
I have never read Walter Rea's book _The White Lie_ and am currently <br>
bibliographically disadvantaged (no good libraries and no place to buy.)<br>
I suspect that that book may well be out of print, however.  Does anyone<br>
know?  In the early 1980's in Michigan, Good Upstanding Adventist Youth<br>
such as myself didn't even discuss Rea, much less read him.  I might not<br>
have heard of such if not for the article in Time magazine that was <br>
printed at the time.<br>
<p>
To me it seems that there are certain basic questions:<br>
<p>
1)  Are Ellen White's writings in harmony with the Bible?  <br>
2)  What validity did she claim for her own writings?<br>
3)  Do the writings when used properly demonstrate this validity?<br>
4)  Are there any harmful effects that can come from properly applying the<br>
    writings?<br>
<p>
I understand the answers to the above questions to be 1) yes  <br>
2) she claimed to be the Lord's messenger 3) yes  4) no.<br>
<p>
Others have made much more detailed claims for her than she made for <br>
herself.  These needed to be countered.  But I don't think based on what<br>
I've heard that Walter Rea was in the business of doing that.  It seems<br>
that he started with a very narrow view of inspiration, and when the writings<br>
of Ellen White came in conflict with that, he decided to reject the writings<br>
rather than to correct his view.  If anyone has more information <br>
I would be glad to see it.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
