<!-- name="Steven Timm" -->
<!-- email="st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Southern College's Organ" -->
<!-- id="MfyfaT_00YUoI=O4hx@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>May_1993: Southern College's Organ</title>
<h1>Southern College's Organ</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 19 May 1993 18:50:07 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#149">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#149">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#149">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#149">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0150.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The White Lie,"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0148.html">Steven Timm: "Church Organ Size"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0169.html">David Plaisted: "Re: Southern College's Organ"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The largest tracker (mechanical) pipe organ built by an American<br>
organ builder is housed on the campus of Southern College. The<br>
Anton Heiller Memorial Organ was dedicated in approximately 1986<br>
from donations came from funds raised for the college. Much of the<br>
$390,000 came from physicians wanting to contribute to a special<br>
project which would not otherwise be able to exist. Today the<br>
organ is valued at $1.6 million, a good financial investment when<br>
you consider that electronic organs become obsolete in about a 20-year<br>
time frame. This organ will last many generations or perhaps as long<br>
as time will last. A tracker organ lasts for hundreds of years as<br>
those in European cathedrals testify.<br>
<p>
This organ is a fantastic investment for another reason as well:<br>
publicity generated for the college and for the church. This organ<br>
is well-known in America and Europe and is very famous because of<br>
the organ builder who built it. I attracts music lovers and organists<br>
from all over the world to our campus. An "open door" policy is<br>
maintained so other organists are welcome to play it. It is not locked<br>
up (as the pianos in the church are). <br>
<p>
Other reasons:<br>
1. Phillip Glass, a contemporary organist, has just recorded a CD<br>
to be released in August or Sept. The parent company (RCA) sent the<br>
recording team returning from California from recording the Grammies.<br>
This is the same team that records Lincoln Center and the Metropolitan<br>
Opera functions. This was a crew of six. When they saw the organ, the<br>
company sent another crew--a video crew--to film for 2-3 days to make<br>
a promotional for the CD. I doubt any of these people would set foot in<br>
an Adventist Church here otherwise.<br>
<p>
2. Services are broadcast on WSMC every Sabbath. The organ is a prominent<br>
feature and the service attracts people to visit our church to see and<br>
hear the music in person.<br>
<p>
3. Universities bring students here because of the organ.<br>
<p>
4. A very active Elderhostel program occurs at Southern. (Retirees attend<br>
classes at colleges and universities across the country.) These non-SDA<br>
people visit the campus and take courses, one of which is on the organ.<br>
<p>
5. There is a concert series every year.<br>
<p>
6. There is an organ workshop in the summer. These are attended by<br>
overwhelmingly non-SDA.<br>
<p>
7. Churches/schools in the market for purchasing an organ come to this<br>
campus to see and hear this organ.<br>
<p>
I was at another university in another state recently and when one of<br>
the university officials learned I was from Collegedale, he immediately<br>
told me he had visited our church on his honeymoon to hear and see the<br>
organ. He and his bride had heard a concert broadcast nationally on<br>
"Pipe Dreams" and had decided to stop on their way back home. He said<br>
a recording was in progress at the time and that they wanted to return.<br>
They don't play, but they love the music.<br>
<p>
This organ reaches segments of our culture that perhaps would never be<br>
touched or approached by an Adventist. Those detractors who complain<br>
about the money spent on the organ could never purchase the kind of<br>
coverage in any broadcast/mass communication medium for the amount of<br>
money spent. And I haven't even touched on the Southern College students<br>
who are trained here and go out into society as professional musicians<br>
in other churches and their own. Many of the organists in Chattanooga<br>
are Adventists, ministering to others who might never come in contact<br>
with an Adventist. <br>
<p>
When you're in Collegedale, make sure in addition to visiting the<br>
Little Debbie Thrift Store that you see and hear our magnificent organ.<br>
<p>
Pam Maize Harris<br>
Harrisp@utkvx.utk.edu<br>
<p>
[It's open for playing?  WOW!  See you tomorrow.  (I wish.)  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
