<title>May_1993: Church Organ Size</title>
<h1>Church Organ Size</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 19 May 1993 19:14:38 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#148">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#148">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#148">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#148">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0149.html">Steven Timm: "Southern College's Organ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0147.html">Tony Dyson: "Re: Sexual practices"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It seems to a great extent that a church views its pipe organ as an <br>
extension of its persona.  Although many organists are women, I would say<br>
speaking as a male organist that it is a great feeling of power to have<br>
control over such a large instrument, and I know several female organists<br>
who feel the same way.<br>
<p>
It has been suggested at various times both by our pastor and his various<br>
antagonists on the board that our church in Pittsburgh saw up our pipe organ<br>
for firewood.  Fortunately this has not happened.  But that organ is an <br>
example of how bigger is not necessarily better.  It has twice the size<br>
and twice the number of ranks of the tracker organ in Illinois on which <br>
I play my lessons.  Yet one voice of that tracker can outplay a combination<br>
of several on the other.  There are many situations where less is more<br>
in terms of organ playing.  <br>
<p>
Finally, the point was raised about church mission and "ought we to be<br>
spending $300000 on an organ that will last 200 years when the Lord<br>
is coming soon?"  (especially if the building that houses it will fall down <br>
in 50 yrs or so?)  The Global Mission people had the type of churches<br>
that can afford tracker organs in mind when they planned their material.<br>
The theory of North America as the "pocket" of the church is now openly <br>
in print.  The typical local SDA church exists to preserve itself, make<br>
its members comfortable, and give money so others will do outreach.    <br>
(Note I didn't say that it should be that way, only that it is.)  A <br>
tracker organ fits well into such a mission.<br>
<p>
Churches like that (which are the majority) are good because they separate<br>
the "movers" from the "shakers".  The "movers" get tired of playing games<br>
like the above and head for the mission field.  The "shakers" prefer to <br>
stay where they are in the salt-shaker that houses the salt of the earth.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
