<title>May_1993: Price gouging on veggie-meat?</title>
<h1>Price gouging on veggie-meat?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 19 May 1993 19:17:34 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#158">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#158">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#158">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#158">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0159.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "RE: Homosexuality"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0157.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: The White Lie,"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0164.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: Price gouging on veggie-meat?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Within the past couple years, Worthington Foods bought out its major <br>
competitor in the meat analog market, Loma Linda Foods, and became the <br>
predominant supplier of such.  Has anybody noticed that the price of <br>
various things has gone up considerably since that time?  It seems to <br>
be doing so.  If it is happening, is it because Worthington is just <br>
enjoying their monopoly or because sales are down and they need a higher<br>
margin on what they sell?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
