<title>May_1993: More thoughts on homosexuality</title>
<h1>More thoughts on homosexuality</h1>
Ray Mialki (<i>rm1g+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 19 May 1993 20:34:49 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#299">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#299">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#299">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#299">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0300.html">Darius A. Lecointe: "Verification"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0298.html">Bruce Holm: "RE: Biases"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have been following this thread on homosexuality, which started out<br>
questioning whether female homosexuality was mentioned in the<br>
Scriptures.  I think it has been pretty clear that the Scriptures do<br>
prohibit such acts.  But I would like to make some other comments on the<br>
subject.<br>
<p>
For several years, I have had a semi-ministry to homosexuals.  Unlike<br>
colin Cook's and others, who sought to help those who already were<br>
Christians, I decided to reach homosexuals who did not yet know Christ. <br>
One way I did this was to send Christian literature to personal ads in a<br>
local gay magazine.  So far I have only had one person actually come to<br>
Christ through this method.  And I did get several death threats, and<br>
some sincere inquiries.  (The death threats were the reason I used a<br>
post office box and no last name.)<br>
<p>
One thing that must be mentioned is that although the Scriptures call<br>
homosexuality an abomination, it is not the worst of all sins. Proverbs<br>
6 also calls lying tongues, and those that sow strife between brothers<br>
an abomination, also.  Having access to the Reformed Presbyterian<br>
Theological Seminary here in Pittsburgh, I was able to check the<br>
original Hebrew in both passages.  From this, I would imagine God views<br>
all of these types of sin with equal disgust.<br>
<p>
However, the Christian Church has historically treated homosexuality as<br>
a different sin.  A person could be addicted to three different<br>
narcotics, or could have ax murdered his parents, or been involved in<br>
any number of gross sins, and the Church's plea has always been, "Come<br>
to Christ, come into the fellowship of His Church, and we willhelp you<br>
deal with your problems."  But when it comes to homosexuality, the<br>
Church has usually said, "Straighten out your life first, and then come<br>
to Christ.  And after you do, you will be watched closely, and will<br>
never be trusted to lead the youth group, or be in ;the men's<br>
fellowship.  And you better get married soon, to prove that Christ<br>
really changed you and that you are truly repentant."<br>
<p>
Pity this jperson if he should ever fall back into the sin of<br>
homosexuality.  However, I know that I have told at least one lie since<br>
my conversion.  According to that passage in Proverbs, I have committed<br>
an abomination.<br>
<p>
Some posters talked about seperating the sin from the sinner.  That is<br>
really wishy washy, and I don't think God looks at it that way.  A<br>
person who steals is a thief.  A person who kills is a murderer.  A<br>
person who does not speak the truth is a liar.  A person who has sex<br>
with members of his own sex is a homosexual.  <br>
<p>
When Christ comes in judgment, these people will be destroyed.  God is<br>
holding these objects of his wrath until then.  (Read Romans 9)  When a<br>
thief is put in jail, the PERSON is put in jail, not his actions.  <br>
<p>
As a Church, we must learn to accept the homosexual, and his behaviour,<br>
but without approving of it.  Then when they are led to Christ, over<br>
time, as they renew and transform their minds, they will change.  And it<br>
does take time, and they will sometimes fall.  But that is what the<br>
Church is for, to bring them back.  <br>
<p>
Ray the kop<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
