<!-- received="Thu May 20 08:45:25 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Thu, 20 May 1993 08:45:25 CDT" -->
<!-- name="Woody Baker" -->
<!-- email="woody@knapper.cactus.org" -->
<!-- subject="questions" -->
<!-- id="2bfb8b7a.knapper@knapper.cactus.org" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>May_1993: questions</title>
<h1>questions</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 May 1993 08:45:25 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#239">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#239">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#239">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#239">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0240.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Guns, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0238.html">Marcus Stringer: "FW:  female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve, I have corrected some spelling errors, and expanded the list<br>
slightly.  Please post this over SDA net.<br>
<p>
<p>
	This is a partial list of questions.  I have been searching madly<br>
for the complete list of questions before posting this, but have had so <br>
many requests that I feel I need to get something out.  It has been most <br>
interesting, as I have found answer sheets dating back to the first year<br>
of our marriage.  The answers are really revealing, and I have been able to <br>
reconstruct some of the missing questions.  My wife and I started out doing<br>
54 or so questions every sunday.  That took 2 hours, and got to be a real <br>
drag.  Later we pared the list down to 19 or so.<br>
<p>
RULE #1:	ADHERE TO THE RULES, and INSTRUCTIONS<br>
<p>
INSTRUCTIONS:<br>
<p>
	Pick a time when you can devote a couple of hours to this <br>
excercise without interruption.  Each spouse is to take a copy of the <br>
questions, and write down the answers.  This should be done without <br>
interference from the other spouse.  Go to opposite sides of the room if <br>
you have to.  When you are finished, draw up 2 chairs facing one another.  <br>
Get them close enough so your knees touch (This is not super essential, you <br>
can sit on the couch, but be prepared for position changes.  You won't <br>
believe the body language that some of these questions can elicit. Before <br>
you answer or discuss these questions have a word of prayer together, <br>
praying for each other.  <br>
<p>
RULE #2 *********** IN THE CASE OF A SEVERE CONFLICT, SET A TIME, AND DATE <br>
		    A COUPLE OF DAYS INTO THE FUTURE TO SIT DOWN AND <br>
		    DISCUSS THE ISSUE.  THIS IS CRITICAL.  YOU *WILL* FIND <br>
		    THAT THIS EXCERCIZE CREATES (UNCOVERS HIDDEN) <br>
		    FRICTIONS.  THAT IS IT'S PURPOSE, TO GET THE UNDERLYING <br>
		    STUFF OUT IN THE OPEN TO BE DEALT WITH.  DO **NOT** GET<br>
		    EMOTIONAL!!!!!!!!<br>
		   <br>
I can't stress rule 2 strongly enough.  This must be agreed to by both <br>
parties BEFORE you start.  Conflict resolution is beyond the scope of this <br>
post, though you need to know that there are 3 basic ways of handling <br>
conflict.  Agreeing to dis-agree, capitulation (one of the parties) or <br>
compromise (both parties).  It helps to reveiw this when a conflict comes <br>
up, and discuss these things when you set your date for conflict <br>
resolution.<br>
<p>
<p>
RULE #3:<br>
	*****AVOID the following words. "always, never, all the time,"  <br>
	i.e. absolutes.  They are ALWAYS false, and are known as "fighting" <br>
	words.  Avoid them in your written answers and well as your verbal <br>
	ones.  <br>
	<br>
RULE #4:<br>
	Agree on an "ouch".  This makes good common sense all the time, not <br>
	just when you are answering questions.  What is an "ouch"?  Well <br>
	you pick a word or clue that BOTH spouses agree on, and what it <br>
	means is "that hurt...or that is a sensitive area, and we need to <br>
	discuss it, or your just embarassed me"  When ever and of those <br>
	things happens in day to day conversation, the verbal or visual <br>
	clue will let the spouse know that the other persons feelings have <br>
	been hurt, and/or they want to talk about it.<br>
	<br>
RULE #5:<br>
	Use "I percieve..." when talking about things with the otherm <br>
	spouse that your can't know.  You will note that I use the word in <br>
	the questions below.  It is not arbitrary.  It tells the other <br>
	person that you see things one way, but are willing to be <br>
	corrected.  Use it in every day speech.  "I percieve that"  is a <br>
	lot better than "You do".<br>
	<br>
	<br>
INSTRUCTIONS CONTINUED:<br>
<p>
	Once the questions have been answered, and you are comfortably <br>
	situated, exchange answer sheets, and take turns reading the <br>
	answers to the questions to each other.  Explore the other persons <br>
	answers with them, allowing them to elaborate as needed.<br>
	<br>
That is about it, except for brainstorming.<br>
<p>
	This will almost invariably uncover areas of common goals.  One of <br>
	the ways to zero in on things that can improve or aid the <br>
	achieveing of these goals is brain storming.  This is a rather <br>
	simple excercise.  Take a pad of paper, and designate one person to <br>
	be the recorder.  Each person takes turns giving a one or two word <br>
	phrase relating to the topic. If you can't think of any, then just <br>
	say pass. DO NOT ELABORATE AT THIS TIME.  When you have 10 or so <br>
	items down, stop and go back over them, combining the duplicates <br>
	(elaborate as needed).  Then rank order them from most important to <br>
	least important or most useful to least useful or most doable to <br>
	least doable.<br>
	<br>
	This will enable your to narrow down, and focus on solutions to <br>
	problems.  This proceedure can be used in any size group for any <br>
	kind of consensus seeking.<br>
<p>
Well I need to get back to work.  I will try to put more together later.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
NOTE:	Each of these questions can be expanded to include children<br>
	as well.  This was set up for just my wife and I.  You can select<br>
	a few of these questions to do with your children.  It will help <br>
	them to set goals, and discuss them.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
		GOAL SETTING<br>
<p>
What are my short term goals for me?<br>
What are my short term goals for us?<br>
What are my short term goals for you?<br>
<p>
What do I perceive to be your short term goals for you?<br>
What do I perceive to be your short term goals for me?<br>
What do I perceive to be your short term goals for us?<br>
<p>
What are my long term goals for me?<br>
What are my long term goals for us?<br>
What are my long term goals for you?<br>
<p>
What do I perceive to be your long term goals for you?<br>
What do I perceive to be your long term goals for me?<br>
What do I perceive to be your long term goals for us?<br>
<p>
What am I doing to interfere with your long term goals?<br>
What am I doing to interfere with your short term goals?<br>
<p>
What do I perceive that you are doing to interfere with my long term goals?<br>
What do I perceive that you are doing to interfere with my short term goals?<br>
<p>
What do I perceive that you are doing to interfere with your long term goals?<br>
What do I perceive that you are doing to interfere with your short term goals?<br>
<p>
What do I perceive that I am doing to interfere with my long term goals?<br>
What do I perceive that I am doing to interfere with my short term goals?<br>
<p>
What items do I feel that we need to aquire to further our goals?<br>
What items do I feel that we need to aquire to further my goals?<br>
What items do I feel that we need to aquire to further your goals?<br>
<p>
Where do I want us to be financially in 6 months?<br>
Where do I want us to be financially in 12 months?<br>
<p>
Where do I perceive that you want us to be financially in 6 months?<br>
Where do I perceive that you want us to be financially in 12 months?<br>
<p>
<p>
		RELATIONSHIPS<br>
		<br>
What do I perceive that makes you feel loved?<br>
What I can do that makes you feel loved?<br>
<p>
What makes me feel loved?<br>
What do I perceive that you can do that makes me feel loved?<br>
<p>
What actions of yours make me angry?<br>
What actions of mine make you angry?<br>
<p>
When you get angry, how do I want you to express that anger?<br>
When I get angry, how do I perceive that you want me to express that anger?<br>
<p>
Are there any troubles in our relationship?<br>
<p>
What can I do to relieve those troubles?<br>
What do I perceive that you can do to relieve those troubles?<br>
<p>
<p>
What do I appreciate most about you?<br>
What do I appreciate most about our relationship?<br>
<p>
<p>
.....Some real potential trouble questions, approach with care .....<br>
<p>
What do I like least about our relationship?<br>
What do I perceive that you like most about me?<br>
What do I percieve that you like most about our relationship?<br>
<p>
What is good about our sex life?<br>
What is not so good about our sex life?<br>
What could I do to improve it?<br>
What do I perceive that you could to to improve it?<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
		LEISURE TIME<br>
		<br>
What do I feel is missing in our leisure time?<br>
What do I like about the way we spend our leisure time?<br>
<p>
What do I perceive that you feel is missing in our leisure time?<br>
What do I perceive that you like about our leisure time?<br>
<p>
How could we improve our enjoyment of our leisure time?<br>
<p>
What would I like to do on our aniversary?<br>
What would I like to do on your birthday?<br>
What would I like to do on my birthday?<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
		FINANCES<br>
		<br>
What do I feel is good about the way we handle our finances?<br>
<p>
Have I made any financial decisions that negativly impact you?<br>
Have you made any financial decisions that negativly impact me?<br>
<p>
What do I feel is wrong with the way we handle our finances?<br>
What do I feel could be done to correct the problems?<br>
<p>
		<br>
I--------------------------------------------------------------------I<br>
<p>
		Some early questions, that need to be answered and<br>
		discussed BEFORE you get married!<br>
<p>
What is my model of handling finances?<br>
What do I percieve to be your model of handling finances?<br>
<p>
How should we handle finances?<br>
<p>
How should decisions be made?<br>
Who has the last word on important decisions?<br>
What is the dollar threshold above which a joint decision should be made<br>
  before spending money?<br>
  <br>
How important is having children to you?<br>
How important is having a child that is produced by us, to you?<br>
How many years should we wait to start a family?<br>
Would you be comfortable with adoption?<br>
Do you REALLY like kids?<br>
Are you willing to make the commitment to spend the $100,00.00 dollars or<br>
  so over the life of a child that it takes to raise one?<br>
  <br>
How important is religion in your life?<br>
How important is church attendance in your life?<br>
<p>
<p>
Who should work, and for how long?<br>
<p>
<p>
...And last but not least, "who fixes the pineapple?" (Grin, ask me <br>
sometime)...<br>
<p>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<p>
