<!-- body="start" -->
In response to the list of censored newsgroups at WWC, I am surprised<br>
they decided to cut alt.sexual.abuse.recovery.  I have never read<br>
this newsgroup (or any of the others, for that matter), but it<br>
doesn't sound like an immoral topic to me.  In fact, it sounds like<br>
it could be a valuable forum and information exchange for those who<br>
have suffered sexual abuse.<br>
<p>
Why was it excluded?  I can speculate on some possibilities:<br>
<p>
(1)  alt.sexual.abuse.recovery was censored because it has "sex" in<br>
its name and no one thought about it very carefully when constructing<br>
the list.<br>
<p>
(2) The newsgroup is not what its name would suggest, and the WWC<br>
administration knows that.<br>
<p>
(3) This is a deliberate attempt to sweep the problem of sexual abuse<br>
under the rug and squelch any discussion on the topic.  (Did any of<br>
you see the appalling letters written to the Adventist Review after<br>
they did a piece on sexual abuse?)<br>
<p>
Unless the real reason is number (2) above this decision should be<br>
changed.  Those at WWC who could benefit from such a newsgroup may<br>
be the last to speak out against it being censored, so its up to the<br>
rest of us to defend their rights.<br>
<p>
-- Rick Behrens<br>
   WWC alumnus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
