<title>May_1993: Collegedale Church organ</title>
<h1>Collegedale Church organ</h1>
Daniel Turk (<i>turk@isengard.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 May 1993 09:06:06 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#175">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#175">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#175">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#175">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0176.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0174.html">Gingerlei Tupito: "Spring Lectureship - All Nations Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I note the interest in organs but I don't know how the subject got</i><br>
<i>&gt; started.  One thing that I am quite certain of is this, that the organ</i><br>
<i>&gt; built during the 80's in the Collegedale, TN SDA church is the largest</i><br>
<i>&gt; tracker organ built in the U.S. in the 20th century.  It is both wonderful</i><br>
<i>&gt; to hear and a visual delight.  A second special tracker organ was built</i><br>
<i>&gt; for the music recital hall at Southern College and a third small tracker</i><br>
<i>&gt; for the studio of organist Judy Glass.  All three organs were build by</i><br>
<i>&gt; John Brombaugh (sp?).  All of these organs were built in the tracker (the</i><br>
<i>&gt; keys are mechanically attached to each pipe) style but with such modern</i><br>
<i>&gt; touches such as teflon bushings where tracks were attached to each other.  A</i><br>
<i>&gt; formal concert in the church is something not to be missed.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Good listening to all.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Bill Allen</i><br>
<p>
Just a clarification.  I was a student at Southern College when this<br>
organ was put in and I don't believe that the two organs in the Music<br>
building were specially built for the Music dept.  I do believe there<br>
are two organs there - one in the recital hall and one in Judy Glass's<br>
office - but one of these had been the church organ for a number of years <br>
before the new one was built.  When the new one was installed, the old<br>
one was moved to the Music building.<br>
<p>
And to confirm what Bill says, the new (I guess it's not new any more!)<br>
organ IS beautiful to see and hear!  My wife and I were married in the<br>
church and were the first ones to have the organ used for a wedding!<br>
John Brombaugh (sp?) was still working on it the day we were married!<br>
<p>
