<!-- received="Thu May 20 10:20:44 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Thu, 20 May 93 10:20:44 CDT" -->
<!-- name="Sherman Cox" -->
<!-- email="scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Re: Anti-evangelism" -->
<!-- id="9305201520.AA26404@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="9305190231.AA14594@europa.ee.uts.edu.au" -->
<title>May_1993: Re: Anti-evangelism</title>
<h1>Re: Anti-evangelism</h1>
Sherman Cox (<i>scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 May 93 10:20:44 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#185">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#185">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#185">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#185">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0186.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Censored Newsgroups @ WWC (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0184.html">Steve Hix: "Re: sdas and guns"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0146.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Anti-evangelism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0161.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Anti-evangelism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Ruben writes:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; But I have to ask, why are SDA sporting competitions typified by aggression</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; and argument? Why is it that a tournament between Christians can result in</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; more tension in a single night than is usually seen in months of regular</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; competition? Is avoiding competitive sport the answer? If so, it is </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; disappointing that an activity which can be a lot of fun, and which can</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; be enriching both socially, and physically, should need to be avoided.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Doesn't EGW clearly say that SDAs are not to engage in any form of </i><br>
<i>&gt; competitive sport ? And then people go off and wonder why she should </i><br>
<i>&gt; say sauch things.</i><br>
<p>
I have heard stories about people pulling guns at basketball games between<br>
adventist churches.  These tournements do not cause any problems, but they<br>
show us the problems that are deep within us.  In this country we are taught<br>
from birth that victory for someone means defeat for another.  We praise <br>
victory.  This leads us to the belief that winning is everything. Our whole<br>
economic system is built on using any edge that is possible to make more<br>
money for yourself.  We teach our young to cheer for the home team and <br>
boo the opposing team.  When our opponent makes a mistake we cheer.  Some of us<br>
even cheer when a player on the opposing team is injured.  It is now easier <br>
for your team to win.<br>
<p>
I believe something is wrong when we are happy at the mistakes of our opponents.<br>
Because we cannot conceive of a system that was not built on beating the other<br>
man we think that it is unnatural to have any other system but competitive.<br>
<p>
I believe something is wrong when we derive pleasure from the subjigation of<br>
an opponent.  The spirit of Jesus is to build up others.  To want the best for<br>
others.  To even give up your life for others.  Is the spirit of competition<br>
compatible with that?  I believe that is the question.<br>
<p>
To close I will put up my old sig.<br>
<p>
"Competition is the law of the jungle.<br>
 Cooperation is the law of civilization."  --  Eldridge Cleaver<br>
