<title>May_1993: Re: female homosexuality in the bible?</title>
<h1>Re: female homosexuality in the bible?</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 May 93 10:52:21 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#180">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#180">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#180">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#180">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0181.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Sexual practices"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0179.html">Steven Timm: "Competition"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0160.html">Steven Timm: "Re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0196.html">Marcus Stringer: "Re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[paul virgo writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; if ya were to take the Falwellian view--Christ should've jumped up, when</i><br>
<i>&gt; Mary Magdalene was wiping His feet,and said 'Get this whore away--she is an</i><br>
<i>&gt; abomination to me--I don't care WHAT she says about Me changing her life!</i><br>
<i>&gt; She practices a horrible lifestyle and is condemned to death and eternal</i><br>
<i>&gt; damnation!'</i><br>
<i>&gt; Doesn't quite sound like the Lord I know and love,does it????</i><br>
<p>
And what did the Lord, Who we know and love, say when she was caught?<br>
<p>
JOHN 8:4-11:  They say unto him, Master, this woman was taken in adultery,<br>
    in the very act.  Now Moses in the law commanded us, that such should be<br>
    stoned: but what sayest thou? This they said, tempting him, that they<br>
    might have to accuse him. But Jesus stooped down, and with his finger<br>
    wrote on the ground, as though he heard them not.  So when they continued<br>
    asking him, he lifted up himself, and said unto them, He that is without<br>
    sin among you, let him first cast a stone at her.  And again he stooped<br>
    down, and wrote on the ground.  And they which heard it, being convicted<br>
    by their own conscience, went out one by one, beginning at the eldest,<br>
    even unto the last: and Jesus was left alone, and the woman standing in<br>
    the midst.  When Jesus had lifted up himself, and saw none but the woman,<br>
    he said unto her, Woman, where are those thine accusers? hath no man<br>
    condemned thee?  She said, No man, Lord. And Jesus said unto her, NEITHER<br>
    DO I CONDEMN THEE: GO, AND SIN NO MORE.<br>
<p>
No approbation of her lifestyle, but hope and encouragement to live as a<br>
new creature in Christ.  Interestingly, Simon at whose feast Mary washed<br>
the feet of Jesus, was the very one who had earlier led Mary into adultery<br>
(whence into prostitution).  He felt that Jesus, if He were Christ, would<br>
not let her touch Him .. but He did.  So, what can we learn?<br>
<p>
0)  It is not clear, btw, that Mary was adulterous at the time she washed<br>
    His feet.  As to the past .. God remembers forgiven sins no more,<br>
    forever (Jer 31:34); we, unfortunately, tend to.<br>
<p>
1)  Jesus wants to save us from sin, not wanting any to perish (Jn 3:16-17).<br>
<p>
2)  Jesus cannot help those who think they have no need of Him (Luke 5:32,<br>
    18:10-14; Matt 5:3-9, 9:12; Rev 3:15-21).  Simon was self-righteous;<br>
    Mary *knew* she was messed up and needed help to escape her lifestyle.<br>
    Attitude (pride vs humility) is what makes the difference.<br>
<p>
3)  The Pharisees taught that there was no forgiveness for certain sins,<br>
    crushing the hopes of those who realized their folly and who wanted<br>
    to turn their lives around; Jesus taught that there was forgiveness<br>
    for the repentant (e.g., Mark 2:3-12; cf EGW comments thereon in DA).<br>
    The man with palsy found hope when he heard of God's goodness and love<br>
    (cf Matt 5:45, 1 Jn 4:19) towards all, healings, etc, and was led to<br>
    repentance (cf Rom 2:4).<br>
<p>
4)  There is no condemnation for those in Christ, who walk after the Spirit<br>
    (Rom 8:1); rather they become as dead to sin (e.g., read what EGW has to<br>
    say in P&amp;P about how Joseph in Egypt kept himself pure), continuing no<br>
    more (Rom 6:1-4):<br>
	What shall we say then? Shall we continue in sin, that grace may<br>
	abound? God forbid. How shall we, that are dead to sin, live any<br>
	longer therein? Know ye not, that so many of us as were baptized<br>
	into Jesus Christ were baptized into his death? Therefore we are<br>
	buried with him by baptism into death: that like as Christ was<br>
	raised up from the dead by the glory of the Father, even so we<br>
	also should walk in newness of life.<br>
<p>
5) Christ's robe of righteousness does not cover unconfessed and unforsaken<br>
   sin (1 Jn 1:9; cf EGW comments on these topics).<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
