<i>&gt; &gt;At one time, in Alaska, state law required that aircraft flying cross-country</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;carry a firearm of a minimum size.  This included, of course, the church-owned</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;aircraft.  It would not surprise me to learn that this requirement was still</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;in force.  And besides: in Alaska, that makes a lot of sense.</i><br>
<p>
beng responds:<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; I am not a pastor nor am i alsakan, but it seems to me that there is nothing</i><br>
<i>&gt; wrong with possessing weapons, for example, to protect oneself against wild</i><br>
<i>&gt; animals. However, as Christians, we are not to use them on people. The</i><br>
<i>&gt; Branch Davidians were not stockpiling a military arsenel to protect against</i><br>
<i>&gt; marauding bears or for sports shooting competitions.</i><br>
<p>
Exodus 20:13 - prohibition against murder.<br>
<p>
Exodus 22:2-3 - Use of lethal force allowed in some cases of self defense.<br>
<p>
Luke 22:35-36, 38 - This is no spiritual sword being discussed, implies to<br>
		    me that armed self defense is not immoral.<br>
<p>
There is a vast difference between the use of defensive and offensive force.<br>
<p>
If we are to "resist evil", I don't believe that we should resist only<br>
spiritual evil, and not necessarily refrain from physical resistance (which<br>
could, of course, involve non-violent forms of resistance...and should, if<br>
at all possible).<br>
<p>
I see nothing admirable in not resisting a rapist or other violent criminal,<br>
allowing him to go on to harm other innocents in the future.<br>
<p>
This, of course, is a course of action that must be left up to the conscience<br>
of each individual. I believe that coercion either way is wrong, too.<br>
<p>
	steve hix<br>
