<title>May_1993: Church organs</title>
<h1>Church organs</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 May 1993 11:46:17 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#172">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#172">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#172">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#172">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0173.html">Richard Behrens: "Re: Censored Newsgroups @ WWC"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0171.html">Harvey Brenneise: "The White Lie"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here are a few additional thoughts about church pipe organs.  At least<br>
in an educational environment, an organ such as this will be amortized<br>
over many thousands of hours of use, not only for services but for<br>
practice and lessons.  When I was a student here at Andrews, the<br>
practice schedule for the Casavant in the church was so full that some<br>
students (more dedicated than I) literally practiced in the middle of<br>
the night.  In the end, it's a matter of priorities.  A few years ago<br>
some of the science/technology faculty at Duke University were appalled<br>
when someone gave a fabulous new tracker organ (a Flentrop that I prefer<br>
to the Brumbaugh at SC because of its less severe sound) for the chapel.<br>
How much better the money would have been spent (so some thought) if it<br>
were used for scientific research, a new computer (which by now would<br>
have been long outdated and discarded), etc.  If it's true that organs<br>
are mainly for women (and I won't agree to that), is it possible that<br>
the "boys with the toys" just wanted a different toy (perhaps a new<br>
sound system or even a TV ministry)?<br>
<p>
When contemplating purchase of an "organ for the ages" one must also<br>
assume that there will be maintenance costs, sometimes significant ones<br>
(like rebuilding).  The pipework may tend to last, but many of the other<br>
mechanical things do not.  They wear out, as has happened here.  That<br>
heavy organ use has literally worn out the console.  Now there seems to<br>
be no money to replace it.  Those European organs that have survived<br>
hundreds of years (even through wars) have certainly not done so without<br>
maintenance and regular rebuilding.<br>
<p>
Tony is right in pointing out an acoustics problem.  However, it is a<br>
larger one than organs.  It is difficult to do anything musically in a<br>
dull acoustic.  Perhaps an improvement in church deportment is in order.<br>
One does not need to pad up a church (making it more like a bedroom than<br>
a place to worship God) in order to deaden noise that has not been made.<br>
Adventist churches, at least in North America, have become rather noisy<br>
places.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
