<title>May_1993: The White Lie</title>
<h1>The White Lie</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 May 1993 12:22:44 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#171">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#171">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#171">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#171">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0172.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Church organs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0170.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Homosexuality"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0193.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: The White Lie"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As a librarian, I am sorry to see Steve be bibliographically<br>
disadvantaged!  We wouldn't want to wish that on anybody.  Again let me<br>
remind you that (partly through the power of computers) libraries worldwide<br>
are tied together through interlibrary loan.  Even a small library can<br>
obtain specialized items of interest.  As long as we have adequate staff<br>
to support it, we even supply ILLs with no fees to SDA libraries and<br>
even other libraries if we are informed that the material is for an SDA<br>
(we feel that the church at large is "owner" of the university and of<br>
the James White Library).<br>
<p>
I cannot agree with those who argue for ignorance of important books<br>
that examine or even challenge traditional understandings.  Steve<br>
certainly could have read the book when he was here at Andrews, as it is<br>
(and was) available in the library and I believe in an open way (unlike<br>
the previous incident with Numbers' book).  I don't know if the book is<br>
still available or not.  It was privately published (Turlock, CA:  M &amp; R<br>
Publications, 1982) by the author.  I believe he still lives in that<br>
area (Patterson, possibly, I don't remember).  If you're really<br>
interested, we might be able to find something in the Adventist Heritage<br>
Center.  The name, BTW, is Walter T. Rea.  <br>
<p>
It's been a long time since I read the book, but my memory is of a lot<br>
of documentation but a bitter tone--one of betrayal.  Apparently he had<br>
been a real worshipper of Ellen White and thus tried to duplicate and<br>
read her personal library.  This was when he discovered the<br>
anacknowledged borrowings.  He then experienced cognitive dissonance<br>
with what he had believed, based on what the church (especially the<br>
White Estate) promoted--essentially an original author whose works are<br>
inerrant.  Jerry is right in noting that the biggest problem is not so<br>
much the borrowing as it is the way she is portrayed.  She had become an<br>
inerrant authority on everything, although this idea had already been<br>
thoroughly debunked by Numbers, Peterson, McAdams and others.  I think<br>
Rea expected the church to make an open admission of these problems and<br>
find a new hermeneutic of Ellen White.  He was also apparently unwilling<br>
or unable to work with the rather slow committee structure of the<br>
church.  While he uncovered much important information, he was not as<br>
careful as he should have been in interpreting it or using it.<br>
<p>
In the end, his work has probably not had much impact on the church as a<br>
whole because apparently there is little desire to change understandings<br>
and practices.  It is interesting that the relationship between the<br>
church leadership and a live Ellen White (much conflict, including an<br>
exile in Australia) is quite different than it is with a dead Ellen<br>
White (much easier to "control").  The historical role of the White<br>
Estate and its changing interpretations of her writing would be<br>
an interesting historical study.  On one thing, however, they never<br>
change--her authority (and theirs to interpret her).  My observation of<br>
the operation of the White Estate is that it's more a shrine than a<br>
place for serious historical study (although there are many important historical documents there).  It is interesting to note that on this campus that<br>
while the Ellen White Research Center is located in the James White<br>
Library (in recent years) it is not part of the library (as it is, sort<br>
of, at Loma Linda).  Their purpose and methods are quite different than<br>
ours.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
