<h1>Re: Price gouging on veggie-meat?</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 May 93 15:50:33 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#182">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#182">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#182">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#182">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0183.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Online Bible"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0181.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Sexual practices"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0166.html">Gingerlei Tupito: "Re: Price gouging on veggie-meat?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0237.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Price gouging on veggie-meat?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Gingerlei Tupito writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; But it is sad to know that our &gt; own SDA stores sell them so high ...</i><br>
<p>
We haven't comparison shopped the vege-food "health" foods (Loma Linda,<br>
et al) at any point; our local supermarket carries them, btw.  As we've<br>
been recently eating less refined products and making more of our own,<br>
we only rarely buy off-the-shelf [*].  However, I have noticed that foods<br>
considered "natural" or "health" are invariably premium priced, esp<br>
if you buy at a "health food" store.  Examples:<br>
* No-sugar-added corn flakes (by some company in Calif) at Hi-Health<br>
  (local chain) are considerably pricier than Kellogg's corn flakes,<br>
  let alone generic or store brand corn flakes.<br>
* Ezekiel bread at Hi-Health is steeper than Oroweat at the grocer's<br>
  (let alone Price Club, Costco, Sam's, whatever you have) which in<br>
  turn is steeper than Wonder (ghastly stuff).  To supplement what<br>
  we make at home, we get Weimar to drop ship us some (excellent!) at a<br>
  price between Ezekiel and Oroweat.<br>
* Granola packaged "healthy" and in the "natural" section is spendier<br>
  than "regular" brand granola (15 cents/oz), despite the contents being<br>
  nearly identical.  Bulk granola is sometimes 13c/oz.  We get ours from Weimar<br>
  (no sugar) at a price (even with shipping) competitive with brand name.<br>
<p>
So, I guess it's not over surprising that LL vegefoods are premium, if<br>
you think like a Harvard School of Business-type.<br>
<p>
[*] I have to confess 8-) that in Oregon, we would buy Garden Burgers, um-yum.<br>
    They're a local specialty.  Fortunately for my deprived taste buds,<br>
    we've found a recipe that's nearly as good.<br>
<pre>
-- 
