I'm not sure if this made it to you Steve:<br>
--------------------------------------<br>
Bruce, don't leave us up a creek without a boat on this one.<br>
<p>
HOW, exactly are we to love the sinner but hate the sin?  How, are we<br>
suppose to know when, I assume, "Godly love" for the 'sinner' should<br>
end, and condoning begin?  Can you, or anyone help in explaining<br>
this?  There are people who are out to make sure that homosexuals<br>
do not have jobs or homes... (especially if they are honest about who<br>
they are) where is the Bible on this, where is the Church on this?<br>
If they support this type of anti-gay work, why are they silent?<br>
If they reject it, why are they silent?  People are perishing, now isn't the<br>
time to be silent.<br>
<p>
The Sodom story isn't a good one to use against homosexuality.<br>
The Bible says that literally, ALL the men of Sodom were at Lot's<br>
house the night of the destruction.  This is a bit more than even 10%<br>
of the population...  Was Sodom an all-gay town?  If anything, the<br>
destruction of Sodom is due to committing homosexual [rape] on<br>
strangers if not angels.  Rape is more an issue of "power", self exalting,<br>
disrespect, contempt for the other persons, than an out of control lust.<br>
I understand that males raping males in ancient culture was an ultimate<br>
way to demean, and was used often to "crown" a victorious war.<br>
Couple this with the societal beliefs regarding gender status, and the<br>
assumed meaning for the destruction applies less fittingly.<br>
<p>
I once heard a Loma Linda U. professor speak about what some<br>
today call sexism, and gender-centric in the style of biblical writing<br>
(due to culture).  Maybe we should learn more background info behind<br>
some of the texts.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
