<title>May_1993: Re: Censored Newsgroups @ WWC</title>
<h1>Re: Censored Newsgroups @ WWC</h1>
John Ash - CS (<i>jash@eecs.wsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 May 93 19:24:29 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#199">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#199">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#199">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#199">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0200.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: The White Lie"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0198.html">Alvin Vitangcol: "Student Movement at Andrews University"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0145.html">Steven Timm: "Censored Newsgroups @ WWC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0227.html">Ted Ashton: "Re: Censored Newsgroups @ WWC"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
<p>
Post from Richard Behrens:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; In response to the list of censored newsgroups at WWC, I am surprised</i><br>
<i>&gt; they decided to cut alt.sexual.abuse.recovery.  I have never read</i><br>
<i>&gt; this newsgroup (or any of the others, for that matter), but it</i><br>
<i>&gt; doesn't sound like an immoral topic to me.  In fact, it sounds like</i><br>
<i>&gt; it could be a valuable forum and information exchange for those who</i><br>
<i>&gt; have suffered sexual abuse.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Why was it excluded?  I can speculate on some possibilities:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; (1)  alt.sexual.abuse.recovery was censored because it has "sex" in</i><br>
<i>&gt; its name and no one thought about it very carefully when constructing</i><br>
<i>&gt; the list.</i><br>
<p>
   I believe this was the reason.  From what I can see, the administration<br>
(upon hearing of such "evils") decided to take quick action by suspending<br>
all groups containing the word "sex"--as well as a few other groups.  Once <br>
this was done, a committee was formed to look into the situation<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; (2) The newsgroup is not what its name would suggest, and the WWC</i><br>
<i>&gt; administration knows that.</i><br>
<p>
   I spent a good deal of time perusing the groups mentioned and found this<br>
one (alt.sexual.abuse.recovery) to be especially nice.  I would highly<br>
recommend it to anyone who has had an abusive background.  Most of the posts<br>
go through some sort of a system to keep the posters anonymous, thus helping<br>
them to speak freely.  There is heartwarming support and encouragement in <br>
many of the posts.  Don't just take my word... go and see for yourself.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; (3) This is a deliberate attempt to sweep the problem of sexual abuse</i><br>
<i>&gt; under the rug and squelch any discussion on the topic.  (Did any of</i><br>
<i>&gt; you see the appalling letters written to the Adventist Review after</i><br>
<i>&gt; they did a piece on sexual abuse?)</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Unless the real reason is number (2) above this decision should be</i><br>
<i>&gt; changed.  Those at WWC who could benefit from such a newsgroup may</i><br>
<i>&gt; be the last to speak out against it being censored, so its up to the</i><br>
<i>&gt; rest of us to defend their rights.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; -- Rick Behrens</i><br>
<i>&gt;    WWC alumnus</i><br>
<p>
   Agreed.  I believe the system does need to change.<br>
<p>
------------------------------<br>
<p>
   If any other WWC Alumni (or anyone else for that matter) want to voice<br>
your opinions on this subject, I'll compile your responses and see what I <br>
can do to get them to the committee.  Please do the following:<br>
<p>
SEND TO:  jash@eecs.wsu.edu<br>
<p>
KEEP IT SHORT:  A couple paragraphs &lt; 20 lines.  Summarize.<br>
<p>
SUBJECT:  Please put "TO_WWC" on the Subject line so I know it's not <br>
          regular SDAnet email.<br>
<p>
DISCUSS:  (just some ideas)<br>
<p>
  -- Do you think newsgroups should be removed?  Why or why not?<br>
  -- What principles do you think should govern which groups are removed?<br>
  -- What changes should be made to the list of suspended newsgroups?<br>
  -- Who should have a say in this?  Parents? Students? Alumni? Teachers? <br>
<p>
<p>
   Remember... a committee is gonna read what you write.  8-)   So make<br>
it convincing.  It might be helpful to back up what you say with sources.<br>
<p>
--John (jash@eecs.wsu.edu) <br>
KB7ONG  <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
