<title>May_1993: Competition</title>
<h1>Competition</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 May 1993 20:31:13 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#179">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#179">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#179">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#179">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0180.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0178.html">TANG BENG YONG: "sdas and guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0188.html">Ray Mialki: "Re: Competition"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The church has fallen into a trap with regards to several conflicts between<br>
our principles and the ambient culture.  Kids are raised to believe <br>
"Good Adventists don't do ....." (play pro sports, grow up to be policemen,<br>
get involved in politics, you name it...)  The "doctor nurse preacher <br>
teacher dentist lawyer" set of careers was clearly defined in my day.<br>
<p>
Perhaps this stance ought not to have any credibility to start with.  But<br>
it rapidly loses whatever credibility it had when the SDA church lionizes<br>
its people who succeed in areas that we were always told "Good SDA's<br>
don't do."  Maybe this is just an extension of the "love the sinner,<br>
hate the <br>
sin" philosophy, but I think it is rather a publicity-starved church<br>
trying to play to a church full of people suffering from individual and <br>
collective inferiority complexes.  We crave vicarious fame. "Vicarious<br>
Famous Athlete" is our new beast.  <br>
<p>
This argument doesn't happen in the Mormon church anymore because <br>
Brigham Young's teams win too much for it to be an issue.  Give Columbia<br>
Union a few years and it may be the same situation.  All the hoopla <br>
raised over Samson Kisekka a few years ago (while carefully not mentioning<br>
that he came to power in a coup) is another example.  Likewise Andrews<br>
Univ. granting a doctorate to Daniel Arap Moi while his own people are rising<br>
in revolt against him for human rights violations.<br>
<p>
A few years ago a Seventh-day Adventist pitcher actually made the big-league<br>
team of the Texas Rangers, but was hurt early in the season before he <br>
had a chance to pitch.  He's not been heard from since, but there will be<br>
others.  Once this happens, we can be sure the star-struck SDA church<br>
will be there as his groupies.<br>
<p>
By the way, if I remember correctly, Ellen White's comments about competitive<br>
sport and the roughness of it were based on seeing the performance at Battle<br>
Creek of a visiting Australian football team.  It seems some things never<br>
change.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
