<title>May_1993: Re: Price gouging on veggie-meat?</title>
<h1>Re: Price gouging on veggie-meat?</h1>
<i>a11111arne@attmail.com</i><br>
<i>20 May 93 23:42:31 GMT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#187">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#187">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#187">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#187">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0188.html">Ray Mialki: "Re: Competition"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0186.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Censored Newsgroups @ WWC (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0208.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Price gouging on veggie-meat?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dan:<br>
<p>
To answer your concern about the prices of VEGE food one has to consider many <br>
variables. Often supermarkets like Schraders choose to take a very small <br>
profit on some items and larger profits on others. For example Scraders has an<br>
extensive (authentic) meat section. There primary market is not Adventists. <br>
Therefore they can afford to price the VEGE meat lower in order to add new <br>
customers. Once those customers are in the store they will buy other staple <br>
items such as fruits, fresh vegetables, and paper products. These other <br>
products could have a  higher profit margin. <br>
<p>
I'm sure that Schraders would be glad to underprice AV in order to get SDAs.<br>
On the other hand. AV's main market is SDAs. The VEGE food is their meat and <br>
potatoes. They cannot afford to sell these items at large discounts. There's <br>
no other products to assign the costs to. Also AV has committed itself to a <br>
large, diversified inventory. If Schrader concentrates on just a few hot <br>
sellers there storage and overhead costs will be less. <br>
<p>
Understand that even with the high prices, AV is not making a lot of money.<br>
<p>
Carlos Medley<br>
Adventist Review<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
