<title>May_1993: Re: Competition</title>
<h1>Re: Competition</h1>
Tom Zirkle (<i>zirkle@act.sps.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 21 May 93 9:56:11 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#191">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#191">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#191">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#191">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0192.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: Sexual practices"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0190.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Competition"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0179.html">Steven Timm: "Competition"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0194.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Competition"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The church has fallen into a trap with regards to several conflicts between</i><br>
<i>&gt; our principles and the ambient culture.  Kids are raised to believe </i><br>
<i>&gt; "Good Adventists don't do ....." (play pro sports, grow up to be policemen,</i><br>
<i>&gt; get involved in politics, you name it...)  The "doctor nurse preacher </i><br>
<i>&gt; teacher dentist lawyer" set of careers was clearly defined in my day.</i><br>
<p>
I'm not sure that lawyer was on the traditional list.  However, the<br>
perceived slant toward the health, teaching, and ministerial fields is<br>
not as strong as it used to be.  Clearly, these professions afford some<br>
of the best opportunities to reach a large number of people, addressing<br>
their immediate needs.  They also include a great deal of self sacrifice <br>
and SERVICE to others (maybe not doctoring now, but that may change again).  <br>
If we really believe that we are to spread the word around the world quickly, <br>
then we should encourage (not demand) our youth into directions that <br>
would maximize their contact and influence among others.<br>
<p>
This does not mean that the SDA Church should be the church of doctors, <br>
teachers, and preachers only.  I certainly hope not, for I am only<br>
a lowly engineer!  We all, whatever our life work, should feel welcome<br>
in the church.  If we don't, I would say something is dreadfully wrong<br>
with our Church's spiritual health.  We all, if we are willing, can have<br>
a valuable place in the work.  Remember this, Jesus began His group <br>
not from the elite, but from a cross section of the common man of His day.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; ..., but I think it is rather a publicity-starved church</i><br>
<i>&gt; trying to play to a church full of people suffering from individual and </i><br>
<i>&gt; collective inferiority complexes.  We crave vicarious fame. "Vicarious</i><br>
<i>&gt; Famous Athlete" is our new beast.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; This argument doesn't happen in the Mormon church anymore because </i><br>
<i>&gt; Brigham Young's teams win too much for it to be an issue.  Give Columbia</i><br>
<i>&gt; Union a few years and it may be the same situation.  All the hoopla </i><br>
<i>&gt; raised over Samson Kisekka a few years ago (while carefully not mentioning</i><br>
<i>&gt; that he came to power in a coup) is another example.  Likewise Andrews</i><br>
<i>&gt; Univ. granting a doctorate to Daniel Arap Moi while his own people are rising</i><br>
<i>&gt; in revolt against him for human rights violations.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Do you really think that the members of the Church are publicity starved?<br>
If you are saying that for the good of the SDA Church that we encourage<br>
such activity so that we can get along to other things, I think we are<br>
in deep trouble, our focus being in the wrong place!!!<br>
<p>
tez...<br>
<p>
<pre>
--
