<title>May_1993: Re: sdas and guns</title>
<h1>Re: sdas and guns</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 21 May 93 09:45:09 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#209">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#209">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#209">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#209">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0210.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0208.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Price gouging on veggie-meat?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0178.html">TANG BENG YONG: "sdas and guns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0224.html">Raylene Dyson: "Re: sdas and guns"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On May 20, 11:57am, TANG BENG YONG wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: sdas and guns</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;At one time, in Alaska, state law required that aircraft flying cross-country</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;carry a firearm of a minimum size.  This included, of course, the</i><br>
church-owned<br>
<i>&gt; &gt;aircraft.  It would not surprise me to learn that this requirement was still</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;in force.  And besides: in Alaska, that makes a lot of sense.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Any former Alaskan pastors care to comment on that?  :)</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; I am not a pastor nor am i alsakan, but it seems to me that there is nothing</i><br>
<i>&gt; wrong with possessing weapons, for example, to protect oneself against wild</i><br>
<i>&gt; animals. However, as Christians, we are not to use them on people.</i><br>
                    ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
<p>
This may open a can of worms but...<br>
<p>
Where do you get this directive?<br>
Yes, the Bible says "Thou shalt not kill" but I think a strong case can be made<br>
that the type of killing referred to was not an across-the-board no taking of<br>
life under any circumstances definition.  I believe that offensive,<br>
premeditated, killing is definitely included.  But what about self defense,<br>
defense of your spouse and family?  I am not saying that they are ok, only<br>
asking the question to generate some views.<br>
<p>
There are cases in the Bible where people were stoned for this and that...false<br>
prophets for example.  Peter carried a knife or sword...the equivalent of<br>
carrying a gun today.  Yet Christ never told him to take it off and get rid of<br>
it.  Why?  He did tell Peter to put it away (not to use it) when Peter cut off<br>
the guys ear in the garden.  but that was because what was prophesied had to<br>
happen (no intervention allowed).<br>
<p>
If I were to come home some evening to find my wife and/or kids harmed, raped,<br>
 and/or killed by somebody and that somebody was still there, I'd be hard<br>
pressed not to use a gun to stop them in thier tracks, especially given the<br>
rediculous justince system we have in our country (USA).<br>
<p>
Or what if you are awakened at night to a noise.  You check it out and you find<br>
someone attempting to violate your home (harm someone or your property) and they<br>
have a weapon and plan to use it to get what they want.  Do you let them harm<br>
you or your family?<br>
<p>
As head of our household, I don't think that the "turning the other cheek"<br>
applies here.  If my life is definately threatened and its clear that its their<br>
life or mine and one of us won't be alive afterward, is it ok then to take a<br>
life?<br>
<p>
For me, I can see giving up my life so that they can still have a chance at<br>
salvation, but in the case where they have hurt or taken the lives of those I am<br>
responsible for protection, I'd have a very hard time with.<br>
<p>
I don't think guns are to be used for threatening someone  (outside the home) or<br>
for implementing justice for others (other than your family).  But what about as<br>
a last resort, self (family) protection device?<br>
<p>
What do you all think?  I would appreciate Bible texts that do apply to these<br>
thoughts.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Bruce G. Holm               503-685-1350      email:  bruceh@wv.mentorg.com
Mentor Graphics Corp.       503-685-7000
8005 SW Boeckman Rd.
Wilsonville, OR 97070-7777     Disclaimer:  Opinions expressed are my own!
</pre>
