<title>May_1993: Church organs etc</title>
<h1>Church organs etc</h1>
Tony Dyson (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>21 May 1993 09:45:20 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#177">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#177">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#177">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#177">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0178.html">TANG BENG YONG: "sdas and guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0176.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Thanks everyone for your comments on church organs and so on.<br>
I have never heard the "our organ is an evangelistic tool"<br>
argument before, so that one was definitely worthwhile.<br>
<p>
My preference would be to attend a church without a pipe organ,<br>
and visit a church that does have one. (As it is I don't have<br>
a choice, there are none handy to visit.) I don't enjoy being<br>
in acoustically super-live environments with a crowd of people,<br>
and trying to listen to a sermon or something. Our church is <br>
difficult enough at times, and it has carpet on the floor and<br>
padding on the seats! (More comfort for the shakers? No, just<br>
acoustical engineering...)<br>
<p>
Interestingly, at our last church business meeting the topic of<br>
stewardship was discussed. Some of the church leaders are trying<br>
to raise money for a few projects, and wished to send a letter<br>
to every family in the church encouraging budgeted giving. It<br>
was voted not to mention the new-electronic-organ project in the<br>
letter, in order not to deter otherwise willing givers! It seems<br>
some in our church feel that the organ is loud enough and played<br>
enough already, and that to buy a new one would only encourage<br>
"louder and longer" playing!<br>
<p>
So there you go. In our case, I think we're fortunate that the<br>
donor piked out. So, all you people at Southern College, continue<br>
to enjoy your recitals, music schools and so on. I assume the<br>
College students enjoy it just as much as all the distinguished<br>
non-SDA guests??<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
<p>
#############################################################################<br>
#                                            #                              #<br>
#	Anthony J. Dyson                     #   phth1@cc.newcastle.edu.au  #<br>
#                                            #                              #<br>
#	Theoretical Surface Research Group   #   RS/6000 320 AIX3.1.5       #<br>
