[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; The "doctor nurse preacher </i><br>
<i>&gt; teacher dentist lawyer" set of careers was clearly defined in my day.</i><br>
<p>
 From my experience, I might not state it quite as strongly; Andrews,<br>
after all, started up a trades/tech school around 1970.  However,<br>
I would agree that there has been and still is an attitude that<br>
people who work by the sweat of their brow and with their hands are<br>
somehow inferior to (at least less gifted than) "brain workers", which<br>
attitude I deplore.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; it rapidly loses whatever credibility it had when the SDA church lionizes its</i><br>
<i>&gt; people who succeed in areas that we were always told "Good SDA's don't do."</i><br>
<p>
A case of cognitive dissonance, indeed.  Perhaps it is the lionization which<br>
is sometimes unwise (wanting to be like the "other nations"? (1Sam 8:19,20)).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; All the hoopla </i><br>
<i>&gt; raised over Samson Kisekka a few years ago (while carefully not mentioning</i><br>
<i>&gt; that he came to power in a coup) is another example.</i><br>
<p>
Is Delbert Baker available for comment?  My recall is that Dr Kisekka<br>
got in trouble with Idi Amin (not a nice guy!), that he worked with those<br>
trying to bring better government to Uganda.  After the fall of Amin,<br>
things were pretty chaotic for some time (almost all wildlife was butchered),<br>
so it seems somewhat difficult to call what happened next a "coup"<br>
(I may be fuzzy on the sequence of governments), nor have I perceived<br>
a cover-up of any kind as to his involvement (viz Delbert Baker's book).<br>
Moreover, Dr Kisekka was invited to become Prime Minister; I do not recall<br>
him actively seeking that position nor fomenting riot and rebellion or even<br>
politicking to achieve any position.<br>
<p>
...Fred (who warmly remembers a wonderful Sabbath spent at Ishaka Hospital)<br>
