[Tony Dyson writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Whatever Judges 19:22 might be about, I can't believe that a homosexual</i><br>
<i>&gt; act between consenting partners is "worse" than the horrible scene depicted</i><br>
<i>&gt; in this verse. The fact that the man could treat his "virgin daughter" in</i><br>
<i>&gt; this way both astounds and disgusts me. Lets not allow our innate homophobia</i><br>
<i>&gt; obscure just how awful this "heterosexual" scene really is.</i><br>
<p>
The account of the sodomites in Gen 19 is similar. The Gay Pastor said that<br>
God was angry at the the people because of their violence and attempted rape<br>
of strangers, and not at their homosexual acts.  Actually, if you just take<br>
the few verses around there in total isolation, it is impossible to say for<br>
sure what in particular God didn't approve about their actions, but that is<br>
not how the bible should be studied. If you read the whole bible, you'll<br>
see that *all* of it was sinful: the violence, the attempt at violation of<br>
another's rights, and the sex perversion. Jude 1:7 makes it clear that their<br>
fornication was a sin.<br>
	As for the man offering them the women to abuse, that is indeed<br>
wrong, and depicts the ancient low estimate in which womanhood was held, but<br>
that does not change the fact that Sodomy is a sin too. In Lot's case, the<br>
angels thankfully prevented the plan going through, in the Levite case, the<br>
concubine was raped to death. That is certainly not viewed with favor with<br>
God.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
