<title>May_1993: Re: female homosexuality in the bible?</title>
<h1>Re: female homosexuality in the bible?</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 21 May 93 12:35:50 PDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#196">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#196">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#196">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#196">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0197.html">Bill Allen: "Re: The White Lie,"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0195.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Please redirect your email to me."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0108.html">Steven Timm: "female homosexuality in the bible?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
(talking about competition and pipe organs is definitely a LOT less work).<br>
************************<br>
Let's back-up in the story a bit... : )<br>
<p>
Paul Virgo seems to be commenting on the "He that is without<br>
sin among you, let him first cast a stone at her" section of John 8:4-11.<br>
You seem to bring out the "go and sin no more" section.  Maybe the two<br>
are coexistent, and do NOT cancel the other.<br>
<p>
If this is the case, we are back to the point of "why do some Christians,<br>
hetero and homosexual, believe that condemnation against homosexual<br>
orientation, and further, committed homosexual relationships can NOT be<br>
supported from the Bible (read with all contextual background in tact)?"<br>
If "go and sin no more" and "He that is without sin..." *DO* cancel each other,<br>
then why?  Must they?<br>
<p>
I'd really like to hear many and diverse responses to this.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0197.html">Bill Allen: "Re: The White Lie,"</a>
