<!-- received="Fri May 21 12:38:15 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Fri, 21 May 1993 12:38:15 -0500" -->
<!-- name="Stan Macasieb" -->
<!-- email="macasib@rtsg.mot.com" -->
<!-- subject="Re: Competition" -->
<!-- id="9305211738.AA15492@degas" -->
<!-- inreplyto="st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<title>May_1993: Re: Competition</title>
<h1>Re: Competition</h1>
Stan Macasieb (<i>macasib@rtsg.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 21 May 1993 12:38:15 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#190">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#190">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#190">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#190">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0191.html">Tom Zirkle: "Re: Competition"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0189.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Online Bible"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Competition is a basic component in our day-to-day existence. Whether<br>
it be work or play, it seems that the measurement for success is who<br>
came in first. No one remembers the Braves finishing second, or the <br>
Bills going to three straight Super Bowls. It would be tragic to say<br>
that the Bulls are not a great team if they don't three-peat this<br>
year. That's how long our measuring stick has become.<br>
<p>
I like playing basketball. Making myself a better player drives me to<br>
challenge myself against others who may be better than I am. However,<br>
I try to remind myself that it's still only a game and to enjoy it<br>
as long as my body can stand it. I tell that to my teammates when<br>
we are losing badly and are frustrated to a point where tempers could<br>
flare.<br>
<p>
Competition, ideally, drives all of us to be better, as<br>
long as we're driving toward the same goal and if we're willing to<br>
help our competitors finish, if not in first place. But as long as the<br>
goal is "first place, whatever it takes," the carnage, physically<br>
and spiritually, will be strewn by the wayside. Trashtalk and Little<br>
League parents are good examples.<br>
<p>
I observed a game where the team leading the ballgame late started to<br>
showboat. That was classless, I thought. Then a player from the opposite<br>
team gave a hard foul. The benches cleared, the fans in the stands spilled<br>
onto the court, and all I wanted was to get out of the gym, lest some<br>
gangbanger with a itchy trigger finger wanted to unload his .357 into<br>
the crowd. The officials called the game, giving the win to my HS alma<br>
mater.<br>
<p>
Bottom line: it's a matter of an attitude adjustment toward Christ.<br>
Then we can put competition in its proper role and let cooperation<br>
take us farther along.<br>
<p>
And now, back to your regularly scheduled program, "Cheers." Oops,<br>
sorry. It's a rerun.<br>
<p>
******************************************************************************<br>
--Stan Macasieb                              |  <br>
--Motorola, Arlington Heights, IL            | Reach out to someone:<br>
--  macasib@degas.rtsg.mot.com               | <br>
--  macasib@sand.rtsg.mot.com                |     Write email!<br>
--  stanleyne@aol.com                        | 	         <br>
