<!-- body="start" -->
In light of one of our current discussions, I saw a couple of<br>
interesting messages on another listserv which I'm forwarding as an<br>
interesting counterpoint.<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<p>
Forwarded message:<br>
<i>&gt; Date:         Wed, 19 May 1993 09:05:20 CDT</i><br>
<i>&gt; From: Gary Phillips &lt;phillips@AUSTEN.NOTIS.COM&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Subject:      Re: Bible and Homosexuality</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; A friend showed me an article titled The Bible and Homosexuality, by H.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Darrell Lance, in American Baptist Quarterly, vol. 8, 1989, pages 140-151,</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; which claims that the current issue of homosexuality is more a result of</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; our interest than a reflection of biblical priorities.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; It is not hell on wheels, but more in line with William Sloane Coffin's</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; thinking.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Terry, this is entirely correct. Not only is homosexuality a very tiny</i><br>
<i>&gt; issue in the bible, there are instances where gay relationships appear to</i><br>
<i>&gt; be accepted. Much of the furor over this issue among fundamentalist</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christians derives from mistranslation of a few specific verses. It's</i><br>
<i>&gt; a big deal with them because it has always been a "safe" position: who</i><br>
<i>&gt; would DARE contradict them on this one? Like the flurry of anti-gay</i><br>
<i>&gt; legislation we are seeing, this position arises because it is no longer</i><br>
<i>&gt; fashionable or acceptable to hate blacks or Jews or Russians. We have</i><br>
<i>&gt; become the safe target for bigotry and hatred.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Don't let anyone use Sodom and Gomorrah as an argument, the issue there</i><br>
<i>&gt; had nothing to do with sex and everything to do with hospitality toward</i><br>
<i>&gt; strangers. Likewise, the words used by Paul in his epistles that are</i><br>
<i>&gt; usually translated as "homosexual" or "effeminate" could just as easily</i><br>
<i>&gt; be translated as "coward" or "weakling." Quotes from Leviticus are the</i><br>
<i>&gt; most worthless of all: unless the person relying on Leviticus is also</i><br>
<i>&gt; willing to condemn wearing of mixed fiber garments, wet dreams, women who</i><br>
<i>&gt; wear red, and eating of shellfish or shrimp.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I come by these positions honorably: I have a degree in religious studies</i><br>
<i>&gt; and some additional seminary coursework. And I can read Greek, which is</i><br>
<i>&gt; often a claim that our detractors cannot make!</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<!-- body="end" -->
