<title>May_1993: Re: EGW question, reply to Tony Dyson</title>
<h1>Re: EGW question, reply to Tony Dyson</h1>
Ron Estrada (<i>72072.3367@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>22 May 93 01:52:23 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#236">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#236">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#236">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#236">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0237.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Price gouging on veggie-meat?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0235.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Censored Newsgroups @ WWC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My third-party reply:<br>
  I consider the Word of God to be infallible. I don't subscribe to the <br>
infallibility of the  Pope. <br>
Likewise I don't subscribe to the infallibility of EGW. What major <br>
difference do you  perceive <br>
between the infallibility of the Pope and the infallibility of EGW (which I <br>
 assume is your position <br>
as one who places the writings of EGW on a par with the Word of  God)?<br>
  Actually my position is that: to date, I haven't read in the Spirit of <br>
Prophecy anything that  "I" <br>
consider a failure of truth. There is much more of the SOP that I haven't <br>
read, so in no  way am I <br>
even eligible to declare it infallible. In another respect, I could never <br>
account my  own wisdom <br>
sufficient to ascribe any writings outside of the Word of God as <br>
infallible.  My faith in the Word of <br>
God as infallible is just that, God given faith; followed by many  <br>
convincing evidences of accuracy <br>
and fidelity. I certainly don't possess the same for the  SOP, though I do <br>
not dispute the possibility <br>
of it in fact being perfect.<br>
  My conclusion: Faith in the Word of God is definitely imperative to <br>
believers. As  important and <br>
beneficial as the SOP is, EGW herself said that if we held to Bible truth <br>
and  understanding as we <br>
should, her writings would not have been necessary. She "herself"  placed <br>
her writings in what <br>
must be taken to be its proper place, a position below the Word of God. If <br>
that text of her  writings <br>
was as inspired as the rest of her writings (which would be  good <br>
assumption), then let's not forget <br>
that, and let's not attempt to influence others to believe anything to the <br>
contrary.   Every member of <br>
God's kingdom is led by the Spirit of God, let's go ahead and permit the  <br>
Spirit to convince each <br>
man's heart.<br>
<p>
Ron Estrada<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
