<title>May_1993: Re: The White Lie</title>
<h1>Re: The White Lie</h1>
Bill Nickless (<i>nickless@mcs.anl.gov</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 23 May 1993 08:51:36 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#219">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#219">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#219">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#219">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0220.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Re: Bible and Homosexuality (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0218.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Bible and Homosexuality"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Should we then recommend that all SDAs should get out and read Kellogs</i><br>
<i>&gt; book "The living Sanctuary". Was EGW wrong in attempting to prohibit</i><br>
<i>&gt; its publication ?</i><br>
<p>
It was right for Ellen White to counsel against the publication of Kellogg's<br>
book _by_the_Review_&amp;_Herald_.  As I recall my church history, Kellogg's book<br>
was the last of many publications that R&amp;H accepted that were not in harmony<br>
with SDA doctrine.  (It actually wasn't printed; the plant burned down after<br>
the type was set but before the printing run--in a fire attributed to divine<br>
origin.)<br>
<p>
There is a big difference between attempting to prohibit the publication<br>
_at_all_ of a book, and prohibiting the publication _by_the_church_press_ of a<br>
book.  By church officials, the latter is good and proper, the former is<br>
wrong.  (Readers at Andrews: I interpret much of the biennial controversy over<br>
the Student Movement April 1st edition as a similar question of editorial<br>
control.  Is the SM ultimately being published by Andrews University, or by<br>
the Andrews University Student Association?)<br>
<p>
I must agree with Harvey Brenneise: to attack a book or other publication<br>
without at least starting to read it yourself puts you in a postition where<br>
you're merely repeating the prejudices and biases of others.  (Forgive me if I<br>
misunderstand your position....)  On the other hand, we need not recommend<br>
that "all SDAs" "get and read Kellogg's book" because not "all SDAs" have an<br>
interest in that time and place in church history.<br>
<p>
If you don't want to read a book because of what other people say about it,<br>
that's fine.  Freedom of choice in reading material includes freedom _not_ to<br>
have to read something.  But if you feel the need to condemn or praise a book,<br>
understand and communicate that your condemnation or praise is not based on<br>
personal knowledge, but on the understanding of somebody else.<br>
<p>
--Bill Nickless<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
