<title>May_1993: Guns, Guns</title>
<h1>Guns, Guns</h1>
Len Archer  (<i>LSARCHER@scifac.indstate.edu</i>)<br>
<i>23 May 93 10:11:25 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#215">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#215">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#215">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#215">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0216.html">Bill Nickless: "Re: sdas and guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0214.html">Steven Timm: "organs and synthesizers"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hello SDAnetters:<br>
<p>
What is it with the American obsession with guns?  Did any of you see<br>
the Nightline program last week, where Ted interviewed some folk on<br>
this subject?  If I am not mistaken, the statistics indicate that in<br>
the USA, tens of thousands of people die every year as a result of<br>
hand gun violence, whereas in Canada, Japan and Britain, less than<br>
70, (yes 7-0-) die a year.  Yet most Americans can see nothing<br>
unusual or catastrophic about those figures.<br>
<p>
The focus was based on the Japanese boy who was shot to death in<br>
Lousiana last year on Halloween night after knocking on a door to get<br>
instructions on how to find a Halloween party to which he was going.<br>
And the Lt. Gov of Louisiana sits with a straight face and suggests<br>
that this was an isolated incident.  Is human life worth so little to<br>
us that we argue about our right to bear arms?  In fact despite the<br>
ugly TV news, many more die at the hands of relatives or friends or<br>
by accident than by the drive-by shootings and violent crime we often<br>
use as an excuse for our need to protect ourselves.<br>
<p>
Maybe there is something else that I don't  understand being an<br>
immigrant of only 12 years.<br>
<p>
Len<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
