<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; I cannot agree with those who argue for ignorance of important books</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; that examine or even challenge traditional understandings.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Should we then recommend that all SDAs should get out and read Kellogs</i><br>
<i>&gt; book "The living Sanctuary". Was EGW wrong in attempting to prohibit</i><br>
<i>&gt; its publication ?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Ruben.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I really don't see that much connection between the two cases.  In any<br>
case, there's only one Book that I would recommend that ALL SDAs should<br>
read.  The controversy over "The Living Temple" was more a political<br>
power struggle in the church (viz. between the preachers/church leaders<br>
and the medical work, specifically Kellogg) than it was over theology.<br>
I have not read the book, but historians report that the charges of<br>
pantheism were overplayed.  It is hardly controversial today, and would<br>
be of interest to those who wish to understand the history of the church<br>
(as is "The White Lie").  Kellogg also wrote a very popular book about<br>
sex (actually several books that went through many editions--some of the<br>
titles are "Man, the Masterpiece," "Plain Facts About Sexual Life," and<br>
"Plain Facts for Old and Young").  Reading these might be helpful in<br>
understanding the mileau in which Ellen White wrote on similar topics.<br>
(Incidentally, Kellogg also seemed obsessed with colon hygiene, which I<br>
undertand is prominent in Boyle's new novel about Battle Creek).  It is<br>
also interesting that Ellen White condemned the writings of Thomas<br>
Paine, the reading of which is essential now for historians of the<br>
Revolutionary period (both in the US and France).<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
