<title>May_1993: organs and synthesizers</title>
<h1>organs and synthesizers</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 23 May 1993 23:00:24 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#214">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#214">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#214">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#214">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0215.html">Len Archer : "Guns, Guns"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0213.html">Len Archer : "Tang Beng's friend Caleb"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0226.html">Preacher: "Re: organs and synthesizers"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
At the risk of being considered uncultured by the purists, have you<br>
considered a synthesizer instead of an organ for your church, Steve?<br>
I know, I know, they aren't aesthetically pleasing to look at and they<br>
don't have all those wonderful pipes to put up front as a semi-shrine,<br>
but they are MUCH more versatile, at least according to my source.  My<br>
source is an organ professor here at Morehead State, who joined our<br>
church last year and moved in his Yamaha Electone and now provides us<br>
with the most beautiful music on Sabbaths!  In the hands of someone who<br>
knows what he or she is doing, that thing is really something -- as you<br>
see, words fail me to describe it...  While not being cheap, it is<br>
certainly much cheaper than a custom built tracker organ, or even an<br>
electronic organ.  You might be able to semi-satisfy both camps.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
[I wouldn't mind at all but I think our current worship style doesn't <br>
lend itself well to that.  And as for Elmhurst SDA, no one is suggesting<br>
a tracker.  We have neither the money nor the right space.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
