<!-- body="start" -->
The discussion on homosexuality in the Bible on SDAnet created a minor<br>
and rather amusing problem for me the other day. I wanted to demonstrate<br>
to my students doing the subject Operating Systems and Networks,<br>
the joys of email. Imagine their delight when they saw the well labelled<br>
SDAnet mail addressed to me on Female Homosexuality. Never mind<br>
excluding sex oriented news groups. I am sure the CBs of Australia<br>
would have a field day with SDAnet headers if they ever saw a list.<br>
<p>
I grew up on a farm where we kept a few hundered sheep. One of my<br>
jobs was to separate lambs from their tails, and if male, the scrotal<br>
sack as well. This job was carried out on balmy spring days in the<br>
beautiful green hills of North New Zealand. I remember once catching<br>
a lamb to perform this operation and finding that it had both male<br>
and female parts. In my youth this did not astound me greatly. I<br>
had seen preserved specimens of two headed calves at the local vets.<br>
<p>
If something can go wrong with the development of a new animal to the<br>
extent that it is born a hermaphrodite, then surely some of the<br>
brain chemistry can go wrong to the extent that someone is born<br>
homosexually oriented. Such people face identity problems through<br>
the whole of their lives and deserve our support and understanding.<br>
<p>
What I am concerned about is the evangelical zeal which some use to<br>
promote homosexuality as a way of life. When homosexuality becomes an<br>
excuse for selfish gratification, then it becomes wrong. In that sense<br>
it is just as wrong as someone who uses marriage as an excuse for<br>
selfish gratification.<br>
<p>
The condemnation of homosexuality which is given in the Bible is often<br>
given in the context of a number of other sins. I see no condemnation<br>
for homosexual orientation, or for people who suffer from birth defects.<br>
My problem is that I cannot tell the difference between those who have<br>
been born with the problem, and those who are doing it by considered<br>
choice.<br>
<p>
I do not know the answers. God asks us to love one another and that<br>
includes sinners, physically and mentally impaired, and even Australians.<br>
<p>
Regards<br>
Maurice Ashton<br>
Avondale College<br>
mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au<br>
   .-_|\<br>
